{"title_page": "Tuxedo Junction", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Tuxedo Junction (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Tuxedo Junction\n| cover      = Tuxedo Junction Glenn Miller Lewis Music 1940.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = 1940 sheet music cover for the Glenn Miller recording, Lewis Music, New York\n| type       =\n| artist     = Glenn Miller and His Orchestra\n| album      =\n| EP         =\n| written    =\n| published  =\n| released   = 1939\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Bluebird Records|RCA Bluebird]]\n| writer     = [[Buddy Feyne]] (vocal version)\n| composer   = [[Erskine Hawkins]], [[Bill Johnson (reed player)|Bill Johnson]], [[Julian Dash]]\n| lyricist   =\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\"'''Tuxedo Junction'''\" is a popular song written by [[Erskine Hawkins]], [[Bill Johnson (reed player)|Bill Johnson]], [[Julian Dash]] with lyrics by [[Buddy Feyne]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ascap.com/Home/ace-title-search/index.aspx | title = ASCAP ACE song search | accessdate = 2014-07-17}}</ref> The song was introduced by Erskine Hawkins & His Orchestra, a college dance band previously known as the [[Bama State Collegians]].<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|title=Erskine Hawkins & His Orchestra|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/erskine-hawkins-his-orchestra-mn0000206380/biography|website=AllMusic|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref> RCA released it in 1939 and it climbed to #7 on the American pop charts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/and-his-tuxedo-junction-orchestra-erskine-hawkins-vocalion-review-by-graham-l-flanagan.php|title=Erskine Hawkins reference|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> The song was a No. 1 hit for [[Glenn Miller]] & His Orchestra in 1940.\n\n==Background==\nIn the late 1930s Hawkins and his Orchestra were one of the house bands at the [[Savoy Ballroom]]. They alternated with the [[Chick Webb]] band and often used \"Tuxedo Junction\" as their sign-off song before the next band would take the stage so that the dancing would continue uninterrupted.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/face/Article.jsp?id=h-1365 |title=Erskine Hawkins |last=Wanser |first=Jeff |publisher=Alabama Humanities Foundation |date=8 October 2007 |website=Encyclopedia of Alabama |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nA live 6 1/2 minute version of the song by the Hawkins Orchestra exists, with extended solos from Hawkins on the trumpet, [[Paul Bascomb]] and [[Julian Dash]] on tenor saxophones, and [[Heywood Henry]] on the clarinet. It was recorded as an aircheck in the summer of 1942 at the Blue Room club in New York City.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes |title=Erskine Hawkins & his Orchestra vol. 2 : Holiday for Swing 1940/1948 |others=[[Erskine Hawkins]] |year=2000 |first=Jacques |last=Morgantini |last2=Waterhouse |first2=Joyce |type=booklet |publisher=EPM Musique |id=159762 |location=Paris}}</ref>\n\nThe song was written as an instrumental. When it was given to Lewis Music Publishing, they sent it to several prospective lyricists to see who could write the best words for the song. [[Buddy Feyne]] asked [[Erskine Hawkins]] why he titled it \"Tuxedo Junction.\" Erskine explained that the Junction was a whistle stop on the \"[[Chitlin' Circuit]]\". That information inspired Feyne's lyrics, which Hawkins preferred to the other submissions. Once the song had been published, \"white\" bands added it to their playlists.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://buddyfeyne.com/ftj.html | title = Buddy Feyne Tuxedo Junction history | accessdate = 2011-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==1940 Glenn Miller recording==\n\n[[Glenn Miller]] and His Orchestra had the most successful recording of the song (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' No. 1). Miller's arrangement slowed down the tempo and added trumpet fanfares.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc1633227/m1/#track/2 |title = Pop Chronicles 1940s Program #1|year = 1972}}</ref> The trumpet lick in the original recording was played by band member [[Johnny Best]]. The main soloists on that recording were Best and [[Bobby Hackett]]. The Glenn Miller recording sold 115,000 copies in the first week.<ref>Simon, George T. ''Glenn Miller and His Orchestra''. NY: Crowell, 1974.</ref> It was featured in the 1953 Glenn Miller biopic ''[[The Glenn Miller Story]]'' starring [[James Stewart]] and [[Harry Morgan]].\n\nThe Glenn Miller Orchestra recorded the song on February 5, 1940 in New York. The personnel on the Glenn Miller recording: Saxes: Hal McIntyre, Tex Beneke, Wilbur Schwartz, Jimmy Abato, Al Klink; Trumpets: Clyde Hurley, John Best, R. D. McMickle, Legh Knowles; Trombones: Glenn Miller, Tommy Mack, Paul Tanner, Frank D'Annolfo; Piano: Chummy MacGregor; String Bass: Rowland Bundock; Guitar: Richard Fisher; Drums: Moe Purtill.<ref>''The Essential Glenn Miller''. Recording Information, p. 30. BMG/RCA/Bluebird, 1995.</ref> The B side of the RCA Bluebird 78 single was \"Danny Boy (Londonderry Air)\".\n[[File:Tuxblu.jpg|thumb|left|The Glenn Miller single on Bluebird Records]]\n==Other recordings==\n\n\"Tuxedo Junction\" was covered by numerous bands and swing orchestras and solo artists, including [[The Andrews Sisters]], [[Ella Fitzgerald]], [[Duke Ellington]], [[Harry James]], [[Frankie Avalon]] and [[Joe Jackson (musician)|Joe Jackson]]. [[Stan Kenton]] included it on his 1961 ''Mellophonium Magic'' album. It became the theme song for [[The Manhattan Transfer]], first recorded on their album ''[[The Manhattan Transfer (album)|The Manhattan Transfer]]'' in 1975.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.manhattantransfer.net/main.html | title = Manhattan Transfer Discography | accessdate = 2011-01-24 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090928114121/http://www.manhattantransfer.net/main.html | archivedate = 2009-09-28 }}</ref> [[Bob Marley]] used this song as an inspiration for his hit \"Kaya\". It was also the inspiration for an all-girl disco group, entitled \"Tuxedo Junction\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://discofunkmusic70e80.blogspot.com/2010/12/tuxedo-junction-tuxedo-junction-1977.html | title = Disco Funk Music 70 & 80 Tuxedo Junction | accessdate = 2011-01-24}}</ref>\n\nThe song is about a [[jazz]] and [[blues]] club in the Birmingham, Alabama suburb of [[Ensley, Birmingham, Alabama|Ensley]]. The area is referred to as \"Tuxedo Junction\", though the building is called the \"Nixon Building\" (built in 1922). This is due to the location of a [[streetcar]] crossing at Tuxedo Park, hence \"Tuxedo Junction\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://united-service-associates-inc.birmingham.al.amfibi.business/us/c/18612478-united-service-associates-inc#company_full_details | title = United Service Associates Inc.| accessdate = 2017-03-27}}</ref> A punk rock venue bearing the same name operated near there briefly in the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.800alabama.com/alabama-attractions/tuxedo_junction.html | title = Tuxedo Junction | accessdate = 2011-01-24}}</ref>\n\nThe song was a used in the movies ''[[The Glenn Miller Story]]'', ''[[The Gene Krupa Story]]'', and the [[Woody Allen]] film ''[[The Curse of the Jade Scorpion]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://buddyfeyne.com/ffilmTV.html | title = Buddy Feyne Film | accessdate = 2011-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Glenn Miller}}\n{{Duane Eddy}}\n{{Frankie Avalon}}\n[[Category:1930s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:1939 songs]]\n[[Category:Glenn Miller songs]]\n[[Category:The Manhattan Transfer songs]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Buddy Feyne]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in B-flat major]]\n[[Category:Bluebird Records singles]]\n[[Category:Historically African-American theaters and music venues]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Tuxedo Junction (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Tuxedo Junction\n| cover      = Tuxedo Junction Glenn Miller Lewis Music 1940.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = 1940 sheet music cover for the Glenn Miller recording, Lewis Music, New York\n| type       =\n| artist     = Glenn Miller and His Orchestra\n| album      =\n| EP         =\n| written    =\n| published  =\n| released   = 1939\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Bluebird Records|RCA Bluebird]]\n| writer     = [[Buddy Feyne]] (vocal version)\n| composer   = [[Erskine Hawkins]], [[Bill Johnson (reed player)|Bill Johnson]], [[Julian Dash]]\n| lyricist   =\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\"'''Tuxedo Junction'''\" is a popular song written by [[Erskine Hawkins]], [[Bill Johnson (reed player)|Bill Johnson]], [[Julian Dash]] with lyrics by [[Buddy Feyne]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ascap.com/Home/ace-title-search/index.aspx | title = ASCAP ACE song search | accessdate = 2014-07-17}}</ref> The song was introduced by Erskine Hawkins & His Orchestra, a college dance band previously known as the [[Bama State Collegians]].<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|title=Erskine Hawkins & His Orchestra|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/erskine-hawkins-his-orchestra-mn0000206380/biography|website=AllMusic|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref> RCA released it in 1939 and it climbed to #7 on the American pop charts<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/and-his-tuxedo-junction-orchestra-erskine-hawkins-vocalion-review-by-graham-l-flanagan.php|title=Erskine Hawkins reference|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>. The song was a No. 1 hit for [[Glenn Miller]] & His Orchestra in 1940.\n\n==Background==\nIn the late 1930s Hawkins and his Orchestra were one of the house bands at the [[Savoy Ballroom]]. They alternated with the [[Chick Webb]] band and often used \"Tuxedo Junction\" as their sign-off song before the next band would take the stage so that the dancing would continue uninterrupted.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.encyclopediaofalabama.org/face/Article.jsp?id=h-1365 |title=Erskine Hawkins |last=Wanser |first=Jeff |publisher=Alabama Humanities Foundation |date=8 October 2007 |website=Encyclopedia of Alabama |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nA live 6 1/2 minute version of the song by the Hawkins Orchestra exists, with extended solos from Hawkins on the trumpet, [[Paul Bascomb]] and [[Julian Dash]] on tenor saxophones, and [[Heywood Henry]] on the clarinet. It was recorded as an aircheck in the summer of 1942 at the Blue Room club in New York City.<ref>{{Cite AV media notes |title=Erskine Hawkins & his Orchestra vol. 2 : Holiday for Swing 1940/1948 |others=[[Erskine Hawkins]] |year=2000 |first=Jacques |last=Morgantini |last2=Waterhouse |first2=Joyce |type=booklet |publisher=EPM Musique |id=159762 |location=Paris}}</ref>\n\nThe song was written as an instrumental. When it was given to Lewis Music Publishing, they sent it to several prospective lyricists to see who could write the best words for the song. [[Buddy Feyne]] asked [[Erskine Hawkins]] why he titled it \"Tuxedo Junction.\" Erskine explained that the Junction was a whistle stop on the \"[[Chitlin' Circuit]]\". That information inspired Feyne's lyrics, which Hawkins preferred to the other submissions. Once the song had been published, \"white\" bands added it to their playlists.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://buddyfeyne.com/ftj.html | title = Buddy Feyne Tuxedo Junction history | accessdate = 2011-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==1940 Glenn Miller recording==\n\n[[Glenn Miller]] and His Orchestra had the most successful recording of the song (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' No. 1). Miller's arrangement slowed down the tempo and added trumpet fanfares.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc1633227/m1/#track/2 |title = Pop Chronicles 1940s Program #1|year = 1972}}</ref> The trumpet lick in the original recording was played by band member [[Johnny Best]]. The main soloists on that recording were Best and [[Bobby Hackett]]. The Glenn Miller recording sold 115,000 copies in the first week.<ref>Simon, George T. ''Glenn Miller and His Orchestra''. NY: Crowell, 1974.</ref> It was featured in the 1953 Glenn Miller biopic ''[[The Glenn Miller Story]]'' starring [[James Stewart]] and [[Harry Morgan]].\n\nThe Glenn Miller Orchestra recorded the song on February 5, 1940 in New York. The personnel on the Glenn Miller recording: Saxes: Hal McIntyre, Tex Beneke, Wilbur Schwartz, Jimmy Abato, Al Klink; Trumpets: Clyde Hurley, John Best, R. D. McMickle, Legh Knowles; Trombones: Glenn Miller, Tommy Mack, Paul Tanner, Frank D'Annolfo; Piano: Chummy MacGregor; String Bass: Rowland Bundock; Guitar: Richard Fisher; Drums: Moe Purtill.<ref>''The Essential Glenn Miller''. Recording Information, p. 30. BMG/RCA/Bluebird, 1995.</ref> The B side of the RCA Bluebird 78 single was \"Danny Boy (Londonderry Air)\".\n[[File:Tuxblu.jpg|thumb|left|The Glenn Miller single on Bluebird Records]]\n==Other recordings==\n\n\"Tuxedo Junction\" was covered by numerous bands and swing orchestras and solo artists, including [[The Andrews Sisters]], [[Ella Fitzgerald]], [[Duke Ellington]], [[Harry James]], [[Frankie Avalon]] and [[Joe Jackson (musician)|Joe Jackson]]. [[Stan Kenton]] included it on his 1961 ''Mellophonium Magic'' album. It became the theme song for [[The Manhattan Transfer]], first recorded on their album ''[[The Manhattan Transfer (album)|The Manhattan Transfer]]'' in 1975.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.manhattantransfer.net/main.html | title = Manhattan Transfer Discography | accessdate = 2011-01-24 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090928114121/http://www.manhattantransfer.net/main.html | archivedate = 2009-09-28 }}</ref> [[Bob Marley]] used this song as an inspiration for his hit \"Kaya\". It was also the inspiration for an all-girl disco group, entitled \"Tuxedo Junction\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://discofunkmusic70e80.blogspot.com/2010/12/tuxedo-junction-tuxedo-junction-1977.html | title = Disco Funk Music 70 & 80 Tuxedo Junction | accessdate = 2011-01-24}}</ref>\n\nThe song is about a [[jazz]] and [[blues]] club in the Birmingham, Alabama suburb of [[Ensley, Birmingham, Alabama|Ensley]]. The area is referred to as \"Tuxedo Junction\", though the building is called the \"Nixon Building\" (built in 1922). This is due to the location of a [[streetcar]] crossing at Tuxedo Park, hence \"Tuxedo Junction\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://united-service-associates-inc.birmingham.al.amfibi.business/us/c/18612478-united-service-associates-inc#company_full_details | title = United Service Associates Inc.| accessdate = 2017-03-27}}</ref> A punk rock venue bearing the same name operated near there briefly in the mid-1980s.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.800alabama.com/alabama-attractions/tuxedo_junction.html | title = Tuxedo Junction | accessdate = 2011-01-24}}</ref>\n\nThe song was a used in the movies ''[[The Glenn Miller Story]]'', ''[[The Gene Krupa Story]]'', and the [[Woody Allen]] film ''[[The Curse of the Jade Scorpion]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://buddyfeyne.com/ffilmTV.html | title = Buddy Feyne Film | accessdate = 2011-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Glenn Miller}}\n{{Duane Eddy}}\n{{Frankie Avalon}}\n[[Category:1930s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:1939 songs]]\n[[Category:Glenn Miller songs]]\n[[Category:The Manhattan Transfer songs]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Buddy Feyne]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in B-flat major]]\n[[Category:Bluebird Records singles]]\n[[Category:Historically African-American theaters and music venues]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuxedo_Junction"}
{"title_page": "Turn on red", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2013}}\n{{inbox|In countries where one [[right- and left-hand traffic|drives on the left]], replace \"right turn\" with \"left turn\" and vice versa.<br>For left turn on red in right-side-drive countries, and right turn on red in left-side-drive countries, see [[#Left turn on red in countries with right hand traffic]] below.}}\n\n[[File:Turn right on red.JPG|thumb|French sign indicating to cyclists that they may treat the red light as a yield if turning right]]\n[[File:No Right Turn On Red Sign.JPG|thumb|\"No right turns on red light\" sign in [[Quebec City, Quebec]], Canada]]\n[[File:Rightonred.JPG|thumb|Turning right on red is forbidden in [[New York City]] unless this sign or similar is posted.<ref>{{cite web |title= Driver's Manual |work= New York State Department of Motor Vehicles |url= http://www.dmv.ny.gov/broch/MV21.pdf |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20101009003639/http://www.dmv.ny.gov/broch/MV21.pdf |url-status= dead |archivedate= 9 October 2010 }}</ref><br><!--In Broad Channel, there are similar signs for left turns.--> In the United States outside New York City, right turns are permitted on red (except for school buses and trucks carrying [[dangerous goods|hazardous materials]]) unless there is a \"No Turn on Red\" or a \"Right Turn Signal\" light indicating the same and controlling the right turn.]]\n[[File:Right turn on red Belgrade, Serbia.JPG|thumb|\"Right turn on red\" traffic light in [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]], right turn only after pedestrians and traffic pass from left.]]\n\nA '''turn on red''' is a principle of law permitting vehicles at a [[traffic light]] showing a red signal to turn into the direction of traffic nearer to them (almost always after a complete stop) when the way is clear, without having to wait for a green signal. It is intended to allow traffic to resume moving, with minimal risk provided that proper caution is observed.\n\nIt is commonly known as a '''right turn on red''' (or simply '''right on red''') in countries that [[Right- and left-hand traffic|drive on the right side]] of the road, or a '''left turn on red''' in [[List of countries with left-hand traffic|countries which drive on the left side]] of the road.\n\n==North America==\nRight turns on red are permitted in many regions of North America.  In the [[United States]], western [[US state|states]] have allowed it for more than 50 years,{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}} and eastern states amended their traffic laws to allow it in the 1970s as a fuel-saving measure in response to motor fuel shortages in [[1973 oil crisis|1973]]. The [[Energy Policy and Conservation Act]] of 1975 required in \u00a7362(c)(5) that in order for a state to receive federal assistance in developing mandated conservation programs, they must permit right turns on red lights.<ref>{{cite web | title = Energy Policy and Conservation Act | publisher= govtrack.us | url= https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/94/s622/text }}</ref>  All 50 states, the [[District of Columbia]], [[Guam]], and [[Puerto Rico]] have allowed right turns on red since 1980, except where prohibited by a sign or where right turns are controlled by dedicated [[traffic lights]]. (The last state with a right-on-red ban, Massachusetts, ended its ban on January 1, 1980<ref>{{cite news |last= Rabinovitz |first=Jonathan D |date=4 December 1979 |title=Right-On-Red Comes to Boston | url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1979/12/4/right-on-red-comes-to-boston-pwhen-it/ | work=The Harvard Crimson | accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref>) The few exceptions include [[New York City]],<ref>{{cite web |title= Right Turn on Red |work= Sustainable Streets Index |date= 2009 |publisher= New York City Department of Transportation |url= http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/ssi09_rightonred.pdf }}</ref> where right turns on red are prohibited, unless a sign indicates otherwise.\n\nIn some states, such as New York,<ref name=\"NYS DMV Driver's Manual - Chapter 4\">{{cite web |title= Chapter 4: Traffic Control |work= Online Driver's Manual and Study Guide |publisher= New York State Department of Motor Vehicles |url= http://dmv.ny.gov/dmanual/chapter04-manual.htm#tra-sig }}</ref> Virginia, North Carolina, Nebraska, Minnesota, and California, a right turn on red is prohibited when a red arrow is displayed.\n\nAt intersections where [[U-turn]]s are permitted and controlled by a U-turn arrow from the left-most lane, motorists turning right on red onto the same road must yield to those making U-turns before turning, as the motorists making U-turns have the [[right-of-way (traffic)|right of way]] and a [[traffic collision|collision]] could easily occur. At intersections where U-turns are prohibited in the same fashion, a green right turn arrow will sometimes appear for those turning right onto the road, allowing only traffic turning right to proceed without having to stop or yield to other vehicles or pedestrians. Some states such as California have \"No U-Turn\" signs posted at these intersections because of the green right turn arrow.\n\nMost [[Caribbean]] countries with [[Right- and left-hand traffic|right-hand traffic]], such as the [[Dominican Republic]], allow right turn on red unless a sign prohibits it. Some vehicles, such as those carrying [[Dangerous goods|hazardous materials]] and [[school buses]], are not allowed to turn on red under any circumstance and must wait for a green light or arrow.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nDuring 1982\u20131992, approximately 84 fatal crashes per year occurred in the U.S. where a vehicle was turning right at intersections where right turn on red was permitted.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} As of 1992, right turn on red is governed federally by {{UnitedStatesCode|42|6322}}(c) (\"Each proposed State energy conservation plan to be eligible for Federal assistance under this part shall include: ...(5) a traffic law or regulation which, to the maximum extent practicable consistent with safety, permits the operator of a motor vehicle to turn such vehicle right at a red stop light after stopping, and to turn such vehicle left from a one-way street onto a one-way street at a red light after stopping.\"). All turns on red are forbidden in [[New York City]] unless a sign is posted permitting it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/ssi09_projects/ssi09_rightonred.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304184841/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/ssi09_projects/ssi09_rightonred.pdf |url-status=dead |archivedate=4 March 2011 |title=Right Turn on Red |publisher=nyc.com |accessdate=22 January 2010 }}</ref>\n[[File:Qu\u00e9bec P-115-1-mtl.svg|right|200px]]\nThrough most of [[Canada]], a driver may turn right at a red light after coming to a complete stop unless a sign indicates otherwise. In the province of [[Quebec]], turning right on a red was illegal until a pilot study carried out in 2003 showed that the right turn on red manoeuvre did not result in significantly more accidents. Subsequent to the study, the Province of Quebec now allows right turns on red except where prohibited by a sign. However, like in New York City, it remains illegal to turn right on a red anywhere on the [[Island of Montreal]].<ref>{{cite web |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716214404/http://www.mtq.gouv.qc.ca/portal/page/portal/grand_public_en/vehicules_promenade/reseau_routier/signalisation/virage_droite_feu_rouge |website=mtq.gouv.qc.ca |archivedate=16 July 2011 |url=http://www.mtq.gouv.qc.ca/portal/page/portal/grand_public_en/vehicules_promenade/reseau_routier/signalisation/virage_droite_feu_rouge |title=Transports Qu\u00e9bec : Right Turn on Red |url-status=dead}}</ref> Motorists are reminded of this by large signs posted at the entrance to all bridges.\n\nIn [[Mexico]], right turns on red are generally allowed unless a sign indicates otherwise.<ref name=\"Reglamento de Transito del Edo de Mexico\">[http://ces.edomex.gob.mx/sites/ces.edomex.gob.mx/files/files/marco%20juridico/06%20Reglamentos/07%20Reglamento%20de%20Tr%C3%A1nsito%20del%20Estado%20de%20M%C3%A9xico.pdf Estado de Mexico] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085001/http://ces.edomex.gob.mx/sites/ces.edomex.gob.mx/files/files/marco%20juridico/06%20Reglamentos/07%20Reglamento%20de%20Tr%C3%A1nsito%20del%20Estado%20de%20M%C3%A9xico.pdf |date=4 March 2016 }}</ref> [[Mexico City]] has implemented a new transit law which prohibits right turns and motorists can be issued a citation for noncompliance.<ref name=\"Adi\u00f3s a la vuelta continua y multas por usar el tel\u00e9fono, as\u00ed el nuevo Reglamento de Tr\u00e1nsito del DF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animalpolitico.com/2015/08/adios-a-la-vuelta-continua-y-multas-por-uso-del-telefono-al-conducir-asi-el-nuevo-reglamento-de-transito-del-df/|title=Adi\u00f3s a la vuelta continua y multas por usar el tel\u00e9fono, as\u00ed el nuevo Reglamento de Tr\u00e1nsito del DF - Animal Pol\u00edtico|publisher=|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Left turn on red ====\n[[File:Legality of left turn on red in USA.svg|thumb|200px|'''Left turns on red for US states'''\n{{Legend-table|lang=en\n|#2262cf|Left turns on red '''from''' one-way and two-way streets '''into''' one-way streets permitted\n|#1fa3cf|Left turns on red '''from''' one-way streets '''into''' one-way streets permitted\n|#ce2a20|State prohibits left turns on red\n}}\n]]\nIn the U.S., 38 states allow left turns on red only if both the origin and destination streets are [[one-way traffic|one way]] as of December, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/12/26/bill-in-missouri-legislature-would-let-drivers-turn-left-during-red-light/|title=Bill in Missouri Legislature would let drivers turn left during red light|last=|first=|date=2018-12-26|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-25|quote=The bill would allow for left turns during a red light when the vehicle is in the left-most lane on a one-way street turning onto another one-way street. Thirty-eight states currently permit the move.}}</ref>\n\nFive states, namely [[Alaska]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legis.state.ak.us/basis/folioproxy.asp?url=http://wwwjnu01.legis.state.ak.us/cgi-bin/folioisa.dll/aac/query=%5BJUMP:%2713+aac+02!2E010%27%5D/doc/{@1}?firsthit|title=DOC Frame Page|date=|publisher=Legis.state.ak.us|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>, [[Idaho]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legislature.idaho.gov/idstat/Title49/T49CH8SECT49-802.htm|title=Idaho State Legislature|last=Offices|first=Legislative|publisher=|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>, [[Michigan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legislature.mi.gov/doc.aspx?mcl-257-612|title=Michigan Legislature - Section 257.612|publisher=|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>, [[Oregon]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/2015/10/turn_left_on_red_the_devils_in.html|title=Turn left on red? The devil's in the details (Commuting Q&A)|last=Njus|first=Elliot|date=2015-10-22|website=oregonlive|language=en|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> and [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=46.61.055|title=RCW 46.61.055: Traffic control signal legend.|publisher=|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>, allow left turns on red into a one-way street from either a one-way or a two-way street. \n\nAs of December 2018, the following states and territories ban left turns on red: [[Connecticut]], [[Maine]], [[Missouri]], [[New Hampshire]], [[New Jersey]], [[North Carolina]], [[South Dakota]] (unless permitted by local ordinance), the [[District of Columbia]], and [[Guam]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/12/26/bill-in-missouri-legislature-would-let-drivers-turn-left-during-red-light/|title=Bill in Missouri Legislature would let drivers turn left during red light|date=2018-12-26|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> [[New York City]] prohibits left turn on red unless a sign indicates otherwise.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn Canada, left turn on red light from a one-way road into a one-way road is permitted except in some areas of [[Quebec]], [[New Brunswick]], and [[Prince Edward Island]]. Left turn on red light from a two-way road into a one-way road is permitted in [[British Columbia]]<ref name=\"BC Motor Vehicle Act, Sec 129\">[http://www.bclaws.ca/EPLibraries/bclaws_new/document/ID/freeside/96318_05#section129 BC Motor Vehicle Act] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920003926/http://www.bclaws.ca/EPLibraries/bclaws_new/document/ID/freeside/96318_05#section129|date=20 September 2016}}, Section 129</ref> after yielding to pedestrians and cross traffic.\n\n==Central America==\n\nIn [[Costa Rica]], right turns on red are allowed in general, but a sign can forbid them.\n\n==South America==\n[[File:Chile road sign RA-2.svg|thumb|150px|[[Chile]]an right turn on red permitted sign]]\nIn [[Chile]], right turns on red are only allowed when a sign permitting it is shown.\n\nIn [[Paraguay]], right turns on red are allowed in some towns.\n\nIn [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Colombia]], [[Peru]] and [[Uruguay]], right turns on red are not allowed.\n\n==Europe==\n[[File:Zeichen 720 - Gr\u00fcnpfeil, StVO 1994.svg|thumb|left|[[Germany|German]] right turn on red permission sign]]\n\nIn [[Europe]]an countries in general, it is illegal to turn on a red light, unless it is indicated otherwise, for example by a green arrow on a red light, a flashing amber arrow with a red light or a permanent green board next to the red light.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nIn [[Poland]], right turns on red are permitted, only if an additional green arrow light (apart from the main signal light) is present and lit. However, the regulations require drivers to stop completely, as their paths intersect with other vehicles or pedestrians in at least one direction. Green arrow light can be also directed left (the same regulations apply).<ref name=\"Rozporz\u0105dzenie Ministr\u00f3w Infrastruktury oraz Spraw Wewn\u0119trznych i Administracji z dnia 31 lipca 2002 r. w sprawie znak\u00f3w i sygna\u0142\u00f3w drogowych\">[http://isap.sejm.gov.pl/DetailsServlet?id=WDU20021701393 Rozporz\u0105dzenie Ministr\u00f3w Infrastruktury oraz Spraw Wewn\u0119trznych i Administracji z dnia 31 lipca 2002 r. w sprawie znak\u00f3w i sygna\u0142\u00f3w drogowych] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330114324/http://isap.sejm.gov.pl/DetailsServlet?id=WDU20021701393 |date=30 March 2016 }}, \u00a7 96.1. and 96.3.</ref>\n\nIn [[Germany]], right turns on red are only permitted when a sign is present at the traffic light, after a complete stop. This rule was first introduced in 1978 in [[East Germany]]. It was derided as the \"socialist right turn\" in West Germany, which planned to eliminate it after [[German reunification]] in 1990.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fisher |first1=Marc |title=Anxiety Spreads in East |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1990/10/01/anxiety-spreads-in-east/c7b64473-38b1-4f24-ab3c-98916c40e85c/ |work=Washington Post |date=1 October 1990}}</ref> However, a public backlash put an end to the plans, and the practice spread to the rest of Germany in 1994. Half of the 5,000 turn-on-red intersections that existed in 2002 were located in the former [[West Germany]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn [[Russia]], turns on red are prohibited unless a separate arrow-shaped green light allows it; drivers must give way to any vehicle coming from a different direction. When the arrow is not lit, turns in the arrow direction are prohibited. However, in some cities, they have allowed turns on right provided there is a fixed green arrow with the writing below saying \"Give way to everyone, you can turn on right\".<ref name=\"\u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0432\u0438\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\">[http://base.garant.ru/1305770/#p_188074 \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0432\u0438\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113214310/http://base.garant.ru/1305770/#p_188074 |date=13 November 2016 }}, \u043f.6.3</ref>\n[[File:Feux avec passage.svg|thumb|[[France|French]] Right turn (or others) on red permission sign]]\n\nIn the [[Netherlands]], bicycles are occasionally allowed to turn right on a red light (assuming that the design of the junction is such that the light is even applicable to right turning cyclists, which it often is not in the Netherlands). Wherever this is the case, a sign \"''rechtsaf voor fietsers vrij''\" (right turn free for cyclists) or \"''rechtsaf voor (brom)fietsers vrij''\" (right turn free for cyclists and mopeds) is present.\n\nIn [[France]] a right turn on red without stopping is allowed when a separate arrow-shaped amber light flashes, but drivers do not have priority.  They must check if any pedestrians are crossing before turning and must give way to vehicles coming from other directions.<ref>Arr\u00eat\u00e9 du 24 novembre 1967 relatif \u00e0 la signalisation des routes et des autoroutes - Article 7 {{cite web|url=http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexteArticle.do;jsessionid=8EE36C429C78C3EFCB06EDB0F10FDA60.tpdila10v_2?idArticle%3DLEGIARTI000025705490%26cidTexte%3DJORFTEXT000000829916%26categorieLien%3Did%26dateTexte%3D |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412185700/https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexteArticle.do%3Bjsessionid%3D8EE36C429C78C3EFCB06EDB0F10FDA60.tpdila10v_2?idArticle=LEGIARTI000025705490&cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000829916&categorieLien=id&dateTexte= |archivedate=12 April 2016 }}, [[Legifrance]], accessdate=2 October 2015</ref>{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}. In France, cyclists are permitted to turn right on red if a sign indicates it.\n\nIn [[Belgium]], road signs that allow cyclists to turn right on a red light have been added to traffic law in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ejustice.just.fgov.be/cgi_loi/loi_a1.pl?language=nl&la=N&cn=2012081512&table_name=wet&&caller=list&N&fromtab=wet&tri=dd+AS+RANK&rech=1&numero=1&sql=%28text+contains+%28%27%27%29%29|title=Wet tot wijziging van artikel 6.3 van het koninklijk besluit van 1 december 1975 houdende algemeen reglement op de politie van het wegverkeer en van het gebruik van de openbare weg teneinde te voorzien in een afwijking op het algemene voorrangsbeginsel voor de verkeerslichten, in geval van verkeersborden die voorrang verlenen aan de fietsers}}</ref> Such roads signs have been placed on intersections in the [[Brussels Capital Region]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Brussel plaatst 100 extra borden waar fietser door het rood mogen rijden|url=http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/957/Binnenland/article/detail/1887620/2014/05/15/Brussel-plaatst-100-extra-borden-waar-fietsers-door-het-rood-mogen-rijden.dhtml|work=Het Laatste Nieuws|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nLike in the Netherlands, Belgium and France have a road sign that allows cyclists to turn right on a red light. The French and Belgian signs consist of a yield sign with a yellow bike and arrow inside. Such signs are placed under traffic lights.<ref>{{cite web|last=Trotignon|first=Jean-Michel|title=Tourne \u00e0 droite au feu rouge: il manque juste le panneau|url=http://www.fubicy.org/IMG/pdf/VC109_PANNEAU_TOURNE_A_DROITE.pdf|work=V\u00e9locit\u00e9|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise des Usagers de la Bicyclette|accessdate=16 July 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Panneau tourne \u00e0 droite.jpg|thumbnail|right|Sign allowing cyclists to turn right on red in France and Belgium.]]\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], which [[drives on the left]], left turn on red is prohibited, but at some junctions there is a separate left arrow-shaped green \"filter\" light which, when lit, allows left-hand turns but conflicting traffic will always have a red signal.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Highway Code: Using the road (rule 177)|url=https://www.gov.uk/using-the-road-159-to-203/road-junctions-170-to-183|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref> Other non conflicting traffic movements may have their own left or right arrow-shaped green light. Sometimes there are specific lanes without signals for turning left, separated from the through traffic signalled traffic by traffic islands, but give way signs are installed.\n\nIn the [[Republic of Ireland]], which drives on the left, left turns on red are prohibited.\n\nIn [[Lithuania]], drivers are allowed to turn right on red when a particular sign with a green arrow on a white background is mounted beside the red light of the traffic signal. However, on 10 November 2014, national traffic rules were altered meaning that this sign will be valid only until 31 December 2019 at the latest, by which time all such signs will have been eliminated. These changes for reasons of road safety.<ref>{{cite web|title=Changes of Lithuanian Traffic rules on 3 October 2014 - valid from 10 October 2014 |language=Lithuanian|url=http://www3.lrs.lt/pls/inter3/dokpaieska.showdoc_l?p_id=484529&p_tr2=2|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141123221243/http://www3.lrs.lt/pls/inter3/dokpaieska.showdoc_l?p_id=484529&p_tr2=2|url-status=dead|archivedate=23 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia]] right turns on red are allowed only when there is a lit green arrow present (called S 5 in Czech Republic and S 10 in Slovakia). Also in this case the car turning on red must give way to ongoing traffic, to pedestrians and other road users. (According to Czech law \u00a770 of decree 30/2001 of Law Codex; and Slovak law \u00a79, part 3g, decree 9/2009 of Law Codex)\n\nIn [[Romania]], right turns on red are prohibited, except when there is a small green flashing light with a right turn arrow. Drivers must yield to pedestrians and oncoming vehicles from their left. In some one-way junctions, the same rule applies for left on red (such as [[Cluj-Napoca]] [[Avram Iancu Square, Cluj-Napoca|Avram Iancu Square]]).\n\nIn [[Bulgaria]], right turns on red are prohibited.\n\nIn [[Spain]], right turns are allowed only if there's either a flashing amber or lit green arrow-shaped traffic light. Flashing amber arrow allows turning without priority (turn must be done exercising caution, giving way to any other vehicles and pedestrians that may cross the path), while a lit green arrow grants priority. If just a regular set of traffic lights is present (no light arrows), then turning on red is prohibited.\n\nIn [[Iceland]], right turn on red is allowed only when the \"H\u00e6gri Kveiktu \u00e1 Rau\u00f0um\" sign is displayed at the traffic junction. The driver will have to stop at the red light first and give way to pedestrians and oncoming vehicles from their left before turning.\n\n==Asia==\n\nAs in the former United Kingdom British Colony of Hong Kong Overseas British Territories, left turn on red is always prohibited in [[Hong Kong]]. At some junctions, however, there may be separate sets of signals for left turns, or specific lanes for turning left separating from the through traffic by [[traffic island]]s and [[give way sign]]s are installed. One such example is at the junction of [[Queen's Road East]] and [[Morrison Hill Road]].\n\nIn [[China]], a right turn on red is generally permitted, unless there is a red arrow pointing to the right. However, certain cities such as [[Shantou]] prohibited right turn on red.\n\nIn [[India]], which drives on the left, a \"free left turn\" is generally prohibited.<ref>{{Citation|last=Adhiraj Joglekar|title=Driving in India: At Red Lights There are no Free Left Turns|date=8 May 2007|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VQblcMUL8jg|accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiastudychannel.com/resources/83838-Common-Traffic-Rules.aspx|title=Common Traffic Rules|date=30 August 2009|newspaper=India Study Channel|accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref> However, some cities specifically permit turning left on a red signal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/for-a-change-its-a-hasslefree-ride/article8030897.ece|title=For a change, it's a hassle-free ride|last=Ramu|first=Marri|date=26 December 2015|newspaper=The Hindu|issn=0971-751X|accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chandigarhtrafficpolice.org/directions.php|title=Chandigarh traffic police, promoting road safety, traffic safety, India road signs & rules, safe responsible driving, first aid India.|website=www.chandigarhtrafficpolice.org|accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref> An explicit green or blinking orange left signal also permits a turn on red, which usually means that conflicting traffic is not permitted to enter the same road.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.team-bhp.com/forum/street-experiences/104328-did-govt-change-no-free-left-rule-off-late-2.html|title=Did govt change the \"No Free Left\" Rule, off late - Team-BHP|newspaper=Team-BHP.com|accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Japan]], which drives on the left, the left turn on a red light requires either a green left arrow signal along with the red light, or a white road sign with a blue left arrow (not to be confused with the one way sign).\n\nIn [[Malaysia]], left turn on red can only be observed in [[Sarawak]] since 1960s and [[Putrajaya]] since mid-2000s. The road sign by the traffic lights in Sarawak may state \"Turn Left when Exit is Clear\", as English, Malay and Chinese are used for road signage. The practice is not implemented nationwide. \n\nAs in the former United Kingdom British Colony Straits of Singapore Overseas British Territories and which drives on the left, left turn on red is always prohibited at the traffic junction in [[Singapore]]. The driver must stop at the red light and wait for green lights to turn left only on green lights on. At most junctions, however, there may be separate sets of signals for left turns, or specific lanes for turning left separating from the through traffic by [[traffic island]]s and [[give way sign]]s are installed.\n\nIn [[Taiwan]], right turn on red is always prohibited, except when there is a green arrow along with the red light.\n\nIn [[Thailand]], which drives on the left, left turn on red is allowed unless a sign prohibits it.\n\nIn [[Saudi Arabia]], right turn on red is generally permitted, unless there is a dedicated slip lane for right turn.\n\nIn [[Lebanon]], unless sign or a red arrow prohibits it, right turning on red is permitted after coming to a full stop to give way to oncoming traffic and pedestrians.\n\n==Oceania==\n[[File:Left Turn on Red sign Australia.jpg|thumb|150px|Australian \"left turn on red\" sign at traffic lights]]\nIn [[Australia]], which drives on the left, left turns on red are not permitted unless a sign indicating otherwise exists at the intersection. At such intersections, a sign generally reads \"left turn on red permitted after stopping,\" meaning a vehicle can make a left turn only after coming to a complete stop first and giving way to approaching traffic and any crossing pedestrians or cyclists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/roads/safety-rules/road-rules/traffic-lights.html|title=Traffic lights and road markings - Safety & Rules|work=Roads and Maritime Services|accessdate=14 October 2016|url-status=live|archivedate=14 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161014042212/http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/roads/safety-rules/road-rules/traffic-lights.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/traffic-transport/traffic-management/left-turn-red-project|title=Left Turn on Red project|work=Brisbane City Council|accessdate=14 October 2016|archivedate=14 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161014042829/https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/traffic-transport/traffic-management/left-turn-red-project}}</ref> Such signs are only in limited locations in the states of [[New South Wales]], [[Queensland]], [[South Australia]] (six locations as of 2016<ref name=\"ABCau\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-07-24/allow-left-hand-turns-on-red-lights-in-sa-opposition-says/7656180|title=Call to allow left-hand turns on red lights in SA|date=24 July 2016|accessdate=14 October 2016|work=ABC News}}</ref>) as well as the [[Northern Territory]] and [[Australian Capital Territory]] and are banned in other states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/queensland/left-turns-at-red-lights-to-be-allowed-in-new-traffic-trial/story-fnii5v6w-1226763320721|title= Left turns at red lights to be allowed in new traffic trial |date=19 October 2013|first=Peta|last=Fuller|work=news.com.au|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref> In New South Wales, a number of tests to the intersection must be met before a turn on red will be permitted, including pedestrian volume, bus stop locations, geometry of the intersection, and the amount of lane changing at the intersection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/business-industry/partners-and-suppliers/guidelines/complementary-traffic-material/tsdappendixev1-2.pdf|title=Traffic Signal Design: Appendix E Left Turn on Red|work=NSW Government Roads and Maritime Services|date=14 July 2016}}</ref> There are conflicting views on the policy of left turns on red, with supporters pointing to lower vehicle emission and time savings, while opponents cite safety concerns.<ref name=\"ABCau\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/wa/a/23004026/turn-left-on-red-possible-solution/#page1|title=Turn left on red possible solution|first=Kent|last=Acott|work=The West Australian|date=27 April 2014|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[New Zealand]], which drives on the left, left turns on red are not permitted. However, there is usually a fork before the traffic lights with a giveway sign on busy intersections.\n\nIn [[Samoa]], which drives on the left, left turns on red are permitted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.samoa.travel/travel-info/driving-in-samoa/road-rules/|title=Samoa Road Rules}}</ref> Samoa used to drive on the right and basically follow the US rules of American Samoa, and this rule remained after switching to driving on the left on 7 September 2009.\n\n==Pedestrian and bicyclist safety==\nA 1981 US Department of Transportation study determined that the frequency of motor vehicle collisions with bicyclists and pedestrians when the vehicle was turning right increased significantly after the adoption of \"Western RTOR\". According to that study \"Estimates of the magnitude of the increases ranged from 43% to 107% for pedestrian accidents and 72% to 123% for bicyclist accidents.\"<ref>{{cite report |authors=D. F. Preusser, W. A. Leaf, K. B. DeBartolo, R. D. Blomberg |date=October 1981 |title=The Effect of Right-Turn-On-Red on Pedestrian and Bicyclist Accidents |url=https://rosap.ntl.bts.gov/view/dot/1322/dot_1322_DS1.pdf? |publisher=US.Department of Transportation National Highway Traffic Safety Administration |page=vii |accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> A 1984 study found that where RTOR was allowed \"all right-turning crashes increase by about 23%, pedestrian crashes by about 60%, and bicyclist crashes by about 100%.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zador |first1=Paul |date=August 1984 |title=Right-turn-on-red laws and motor vehicle crashes: A review of the literature |journal=Accident Analysis & Prevention |volume= 16|issue=4 |pages=241\u2013245 |doi= 10.1016/0001-4575(84)90019-8}}</ref> A 1993 study also concluded that RTOR increased crashes for pedestrians and cyclists, by 44% and 59% respectively.<ref>{{cite conference|title=Safety Effects of Right Turn on Red: A Meta Analysis |last1=Dussault |first1=Claude |date=14\u201316 June 1993 |location=Saskatoon, Saskatchewan |conference=Proceedings of the Canadian Multidisciplinary Road Safety Conference VIIII}}</ref> However, a 2002 study brought those results into question, while agreeing that \"No-Turn-on-Red restrictions are desirable where high volumes of pedestrian and conflicting vehicular traffic exist.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleck |first1=Jack |last2=Yee |first2=Bond |title=Safety Evaluation of Right Turn on Red |url=https://archives.sfmta.com/cms/rhomepd/documents/DPT_right_turn_on_red.pdf |accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Vienna Convention on Road Signs and Signals]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/people/outreach/traftech/1995/TT086.htm The Safety Impact Of Right Turn On Red: Report To Congress], [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] ''Traffic Tech''\n* Sarkar, van Houten, and Moffatt, [http://trrjournalonline.trb.org/doi/10.3141/1674-07 Using License Manuals To Increase Awareness About Pedestrian Hazards at Intersections]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sarkar|first=Sheila|last2=Van Houten|first2=Ron|last3=Moffatt|first3=John|date=1 January 1999|title=Using License Manuals To Increase Awareness About Pedestrian Hazards at Intersections. Missed Opportunity for Educating Drivers|url=|journal=Transportation Research Record: Journal of the Transportation Research Board|volume=1674|pages=49\u201356|doi=10.3141/1674-07|issn=0361-1981}}</ref>, ''Transportation Research Record'' 1674.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091027100909/http://geocities.com/jusjih/trafficlightsignals.html Traffic Light Signals and Red Light Cameras: Turning on Red Light (US)], by Justin JIH.\n\n{{Traffic law}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Right Turn On Red}}\n[[Category:Traffic law]]\n[[Category:Traffic signals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2013}}\n{{inbox|In countries where one [[right- and left-hand traffic|drives on the left]], replace \"right turn\" with \"left turn\" and vice versa.<br>For left turn on red in right-side-drive countries, and right turn on red in left-side-drive countries, see [[#Left turn on red in countries with right hand traffic]] below.}}\n\n[[File:Turn right on red.JPG|thumb|French sign indicating to cyclists that they may treat the red light as a yield if turning right]]\n[[File:No Right Turn On Red Sign.JPG|thumb|\"No right turns on red light\" sign in [[Quebec City, Quebec]], Canada]]\n[[File:Rightonred.JPG|thumb|Turning right on red is forbidden in [[New York City]] unless this sign or similar is posted.<ref>{{cite web |title= Driver's Manual |work= New York State Department of Motor Vehicles |url= http://www.dmv.ny.gov/broch/MV21.pdf |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20101009003639/http://www.dmv.ny.gov/broch/MV21.pdf |url-status= dead |archivedate= 9 October 2010 }}</ref><br><!--In Broad Channel, there are similar signs for left turns.--> In the United States outside New York City, right turns are permitted on red (except for school buses and trucks carrying [[dangerous goods|hazardous materials]]) unless there is a \"No Turn on Red\" or a \"Right Turn Signal\" light indicating the same and controlling the right turn.]]\n[[File:Right turn on red Belgrade, Serbia.JPG|thumb|\"Right turn on red\" traffic light in [[Belgrade]], [[Serbia]], right turn only after pedestrians and traffic pass from left.]]\n\nA '''turn on red''' is a principle of law permitting vehicles at a [[traffic light]] showing a red signal to turn into the direction of traffic nearer to them (almost always after a complete stop) when the way is clear, without having to wait for a green signal. It is intended to allow traffic to resume moving, with minimal risk provided that proper caution is observed.\n\nIt is commonly known as a '''right turn on red''' (or simply '''right on red''') in countries that [[Right- and left-hand traffic|drive on the right side]] of the road, or a '''left turn on red''' in [[List of countries with left-hand traffic|countries which drive on the left side]] of the road.\n\n==North America==\nRight turns on red are permitted in many regions of North America.  In the [[United States]], western [[US state|states]] have allowed it for more than 50 years,{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}} and eastern states amended their traffic laws to allow it in the 1970s as a fuel-saving measure in response to motor fuel shortages in [[1973 oil crisis|1973]]. The [[Energy Policy and Conservation Act]] of 1975 required in \u00a7362(c)(5) that in order for a state to receive federal assistance in developing mandated conservation programs, they must permit right turns on red lights.<ref>{{cite web | title = Energy Policy and Conservation Act | publisher= govtrack.us | url= https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/94/s622/text }}</ref>  All 50 states, the [[District of Columbia]], [[Guam]], and [[Puerto Rico]] have allowed right turns on red since 1980, except where prohibited by a sign or where right turns are controlled by dedicated [[traffic lights]]. (The last state with a right-on-red ban, Massachusetts, ended its ban on January 1, 1980<ref>{{cite news |last= Rabinovitz |first=Jonathan D |date=4 December 1979 |title=Right-On-Red Comes to Boston | url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1979/12/4/right-on-red-comes-to-boston-pwhen-it/ | work=The Harvard Crimson | accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref>) The few exceptions include [[New York City]],<ref>{{cite web |title= Right Turn on Red |work= Sustainable Streets Index |date= 2009 |publisher= New York City Department of Transportation |url= http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/ssi09_rightonred.pdf }}</ref> where right turns on red are prohibited, unless a sign indicates otherwise.\n\nIn some states, such as New York,<ref name=\"NYS DMV Driver's Manual - Chapter 4\">{{cite web |title= Chapter 4: Traffic Control |work= Online Driver's Manual and Study Guide |publisher= New York State Department of Motor Vehicles |url= http://dmv.ny.gov/dmanual/chapter04-manual.htm#tra-sig }}</ref> Virginia, North Carolina, Nebraska, Minnesota, and California, a right turn on red is prohibited when a red arrow is displayed.\n\nAt intersections where [[U-turn]]s are permitted and controlled by a U-turn arrow from the left-most lane, motorists turning right on red onto the same road must yield to those making U-turns before turning, as the motorists making U-turns have the [[right-of-way (traffic)|right of way]] and a [[traffic collision|collision]] could easily occur. At intersections where U-turns are prohibited in the same fashion, a green right turn arrow will sometimes appear for those turning right onto the road, allowing only traffic turning right to proceed without having to stop or yield to other vehicles or pedestrians. Some states such as California have \"No U-Turn\" signs posted at these intersections because of the green right turn arrow.\n\nMost [[Caribbean]] countries with [[Right- and left-hand traffic|right-hand traffic]], such as the [[Dominican Republic]], allow right turn on red unless a sign prohibits it. Some vehicles, such as those carrying [[Dangerous goods|hazardous materials]] and [[school buses]], are not allowed to turn on red under any circumstance and must wait for a green light or arrow.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nDuring 1982\u20131992, approximately 84 fatal crashes per year occurred in the U.S. where a vehicle was turning right at intersections where right turn on red was permitted.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} As of 1992, right turn on red is governed federally by {{UnitedStatesCode|42|6322}}(c) (\"Each proposed State energy conservation plan to be eligible for Federal assistance under this part shall include: ...(5) a traffic law or regulation which, to the maximum extent practicable consistent with safety, permits the operator of a motor vehicle to turn such vehicle right at a red stop light after stopping, and to turn such vehicle left from a one-way street onto a one-way street at a red light after stopping.\"). All turns on red are forbidden in [[New York City]] unless a sign is posted permitting it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/ssi09_projects/ssi09_rightonred.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304184841/http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/ssi09_projects/ssi09_rightonred.pdf |url-status=dead |archivedate=4 March 2011 |title=Right Turn on Red |publisher=nyc.com |accessdate=22 January 2010 }}</ref>\n[[File:Qu\u00e9bec P-115-1-mtl.svg|right|200px]]\nThrough most of [[Canada]], a driver may turn right at a red light after coming to a complete stop unless a sign indicates otherwise. In the province of [[Quebec]], turning right on a red was illegal until a pilot study carried out in 2003 showed that the right turn on red manoeuvre did not result in significantly more accidents. Subsequent to the study, the Province of Quebec now allows right turns on red except where prohibited by a sign. However, like in New York City, it remains illegal to turn right on a red anywhere on the [[Island of Montreal]].<ref>{{cite web |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716214404/http://www.mtq.gouv.qc.ca/portal/page/portal/grand_public_en/vehicules_promenade/reseau_routier/signalisation/virage_droite_feu_rouge |website=mtq.gouv.qc.ca |archivedate=16 July 2011 |url=http://www.mtq.gouv.qc.ca/portal/page/portal/grand_public_en/vehicules_promenade/reseau_routier/signalisation/virage_droite_feu_rouge |title=Transports Qu\u00e9bec : Right Turn on Red |url-status=dead}}</ref> Motorists are reminded of this by large signs posted at the entrance to all bridges.\n\nIn [[Mexico]], right turns on red are generally allowed unless a sign indicates otherwise.<ref name=\"Reglamento de Transito del Edo de Mexico\">[http://ces.edomex.gob.mx/sites/ces.edomex.gob.mx/files/files/marco%20juridico/06%20Reglamentos/07%20Reglamento%20de%20Tr%C3%A1nsito%20del%20Estado%20de%20M%C3%A9xico.pdf Estado de Mexico] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085001/http://ces.edomex.gob.mx/sites/ces.edomex.gob.mx/files/files/marco%20juridico/06%20Reglamentos/07%20Reglamento%20de%20Tr%C3%A1nsito%20del%20Estado%20de%20M%C3%A9xico.pdf |date=4 March 2016 }}</ref> [[Mexico City]] has implemented a new transit law which prohibits right turns and motorists can be issued a citation for noncompliance.<ref name=\"Adi\u00f3s a la vuelta continua y multas por usar el tel\u00e9fono, as\u00ed el nuevo Reglamento de Tr\u00e1nsito del DF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animalpolitico.com/2015/08/adios-a-la-vuelta-continua-y-multas-por-uso-del-telefono-al-conducir-asi-el-nuevo-reglamento-de-transito-del-df/|title=Adi\u00f3s a la vuelta continua y multas por usar el tel\u00e9fono, as\u00ed el nuevo Reglamento de Tr\u00e1nsito del DF - Animal Pol\u00edtico|publisher=|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Left turn on red ====\n[[File:Legality of left turn on red in USA.svg|thumb|200px|'''Left turns on red for US states'''\n{{Legend-table|lang=en\n|#2262cf|Left turns on red '''from''' one-way and two-way streets '''into''' one-way streets permitted\n|#1fa3cf|Left turns on red '''from''' one-way streets '''into''' one-way streets permitted\n|#ce2a20|State prohibits left turns on red\n}}\n]]\nIn the U.S., 38 states allow left turns on red only if both the origin and destination streets are [[one-way traffic|one way]] as of December, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/12/26/bill-in-missouri-legislature-would-let-drivers-turn-left-during-red-light/|title=Bill in Missouri Legislature would let drivers turn left during red light|last=|first=|date=2018-12-26|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-25|quote=The bill would allow for left turns during a red light when the vehicle is in the left-most lane on a one-way street turning onto another one-way street. Thirty-eight states currently permit the move.}}</ref>\n\nFive states, namely [[Alaska]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legis.state.ak.us/basis/folioproxy.asp?url=http://wwwjnu01.legis.state.ak.us/cgi-bin/folioisa.dll/aac/query=%5BJUMP:%2713+aac+02!2E010%27%5D/doc/{@1}?firsthit|title=DOC Frame Page|date=|publisher=Legis.state.ak.us|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>, [[Idaho]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legislature.idaho.gov/idstat/Title49/T49CH8SECT49-802.htm|title=Idaho State Legislature|last=Offices|first=Legislative|publisher=|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>, [[Michigan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legislature.mi.gov/doc.aspx?mcl-257-612|title=Michigan Legislature - Section 257.612|publisher=|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>, [[Oregon]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/2015/10/turn_left_on_red_the_devils_in.html|title=Turn left on red? The devil's in the details (Commuting Q&A)|last=Njus|first=Elliot|date=2015-10-22|website=oregonlive|language=en|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> and [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps.leg.wa.gov/RCW/default.aspx?cite=46.61.055|title=RCW 46.61.055: Traffic control signal legend.|publisher=|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref>, allow left turns on red into a one-way street from either a one-way or a two-way street. \n\nAs of December 2018, the following states and territories ban left turns on red: [[Connecticut]], [[Maine]], [[Missouri]], [[New Hampshire]], [[New Jersey]], [[North Carolina]], [[South Dakota]] (unless permitted by local ordinance), the [[District of Columbia]], and [[Guam]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2018/12/26/bill-in-missouri-legislature-would-let-drivers-turn-left-during-red-light/|title=Bill in Missouri Legislature would let drivers turn left during red light|date=2018-12-26|website=Missourinet|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> [[New York City]] prohibits left turn on red unless a sign indicates otherwise.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn Canada, left turn on red light from a one-way road into a one-way road is permitted except in some areas of [[Quebec]], [[New Brunswick]], and [[Prince Edward Island]]. Left turn on red light from a two-way road into a one-way road is permitted in [[British Columbia]]<ref name=\"BC Motor Vehicle Act, Sec 129\">[http://www.bclaws.ca/EPLibraries/bclaws_new/document/ID/freeside/96318_05#section129 BC Motor Vehicle Act] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920003926/http://www.bclaws.ca/EPLibraries/bclaws_new/document/ID/freeside/96318_05#section129|date=20 September 2016}}, Section 129</ref> after yielding to pedestrians and cross traffic.\n\n==Central America==\n\nIn [[Costa Rica]], right turns on red are allowed in general, but a sign can forbid them.\n\n==South America==\n[[File:Chile road sign RA-2.svg|thumb|150px|[[Chile]]an right turn on red permitted sign]]\nIn [[Chile]], right turns on red are only allowed when a sign permitting it is shown.\n\nIn [[Paraguay]], right turns on red are allowed in some towns.\n\nIn [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Colombia]], [[Peru]] and [[Uruguay]], right turns on red are not allowed.\n\n==Europe==\n[[File:Zeichen 720 - Gr\u00fcnpfeil, StVO 1994.svg|thumb|left|[[Germany|German]] right turn on red permission sign]]\n\nIn [[Europe]]an countries in general, it is illegal to turn on a red light, unless it is indicated otherwise, for example by a green arrow on a red light, a flashing amber arrow with a red light or a permanent green board next to the red light.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nIn [[Poland]], right turns on red are permitted, only if an additional green arrow light (apart from the main signal light) is present and lit. However, the regulations require drivers to stop completely, as their paths intersect with other vehicles or pedestrians in at least one direction. Green arrow light can be also directed left (the same regulations apply).<ref name=\"Rozporz\u0105dzenie Ministr\u00f3w Infrastruktury oraz Spraw Wewn\u0119trznych i Administracji z dnia 31 lipca 2002 r. w sprawie znak\u00f3w i sygna\u0142\u00f3w drogowych\">[http://isap.sejm.gov.pl/DetailsServlet?id=WDU20021701393 Rozporz\u0105dzenie Ministr\u00f3w Infrastruktury oraz Spraw Wewn\u0119trznych i Administracji z dnia 31 lipca 2002 r. w sprawie znak\u00f3w i sygna\u0142\u00f3w drogowych] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330114324/http://isap.sejm.gov.pl/DetailsServlet?id=WDU20021701393 |date=30 March 2016 }}, \u00a7 96.1. and 96.3.</ref>\n\nIn [[Germany]], right turns on red are only permitted when a sign is present at the traffic light, after a complete stop. This rule was first introduced in 1978 in [[East Germany]]. It was derided as the \"socialist right turn\" in West Germany, which planned to eliminate it after [[German reunification]] in 1990.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fisher |first1=Marc |title=Anxiety Spreads in East |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1990/10/01/anxiety-spreads-in-east/c7b64473-38b1-4f24-ab3c-98916c40e85c/ |work=Washington Post |date=1 October 1990}}</ref> However, a public backlash put an end to the plans, and the practice spread to the rest of Germany in 1994. Half of the 5,000 turn-on-red intersections that existed in 2002 were located in the former [[West Germany]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn [[Russia]], turns on red are prohibited unless a separate arrow-shaped green light allows it; drivers must give way to any vehicle coming from a different direction. When the arrow is not lit, turns in the arrow direction are prohibited. However, in some cities, they have allowed turns on right provided there is a fixed green arrow with the writing below saying \"Give way to everyone, you can turn on right\".<ref name=\"\u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0432\u0438\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438\">[http://base.garant.ru/1305770/#p_188074 \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0432\u0438\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113214310/http://base.garant.ru/1305770/#p_188074 |date=13 November 2016 }}, \u043f.6.3</ref>\n[[File:Feux avec passage.svg|thumb|[[France|French]] Right turn (or others) on red permission sign]]\n\nIn the [[Netherlands]], bicycles are occasionally allowed to turn right on a red light (assuming that the design of the junction is such that the light is even applicable to right turning cyclists, which it often is not in the Netherlands). Wherever this is the case, a sign \"''rechtsaf voor fietsers vrij''\" (right turn free for cyclists) or \"''rechtsaf voor (brom)fietsers vrij''\" (right turn free for cyclists and mopeds) is present.\n\nIn [[France]] a right turn on red without stopping is allowed when a separate arrow-shaped amber light flashes, but drivers do not have priority.  They must check if any pedestrians are crossing before turning and must give way to vehicles coming from other directions.<ref>Arr\u00eat\u00e9 du 24 novembre 1967 relatif \u00e0 la signalisation des routes et des autoroutes - Article 7 {{cite web|url=http://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexteArticle.do;jsessionid=8EE36C429C78C3EFCB06EDB0F10FDA60.tpdila10v_2?idArticle%3DLEGIARTI000025705490%26cidTexte%3DJORFTEXT000000829916%26categorieLien%3Did%26dateTexte%3D |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412185700/https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexteArticle.do%3Bjsessionid%3D8EE36C429C78C3EFCB06EDB0F10FDA60.tpdila10v_2?idArticle=LEGIARTI000025705490&cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000829916&categorieLien=id&dateTexte= |archivedate=12 April 2016 }}, [[Legifrance]], accessdate=2 October 2015</ref>{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}. In France, cyclists are permitted to turn right on red if a sign indicates it.\n\nIn [[Belgium]], road signs that allow cyclists to turn right on a red light have been added to traffic law in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ejustice.just.fgov.be/cgi_loi/loi_a1.pl?language=nl&la=N&cn=2012081512&table_name=wet&&caller=list&N&fromtab=wet&tri=dd+AS+RANK&rech=1&numero=1&sql=%28text+contains+%28%27%27%29%29|title=Wet tot wijziging van artikel 6.3 van het koninklijk besluit van 1 december 1975 houdende algemeen reglement op de politie van het wegverkeer en van het gebruik van de openbare weg teneinde te voorzien in een afwijking op het algemene voorrangsbeginsel voor de verkeerslichten, in geval van verkeersborden die voorrang verlenen aan de fietsers}}</ref> Such roads signs have been placed on intersections in the [[Brussels Capital Region]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Brussel plaatst 100 extra borden waar fietser door het rood mogen rijden|url=http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/957/Binnenland/article/detail/1887620/2014/05/15/Brussel-plaatst-100-extra-borden-waar-fietsers-door-het-rood-mogen-rijden.dhtml|work=Het Laatste Nieuws|accessdate=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nLike in the Netherlands, Belgium and France have a road sign that allows cyclists to turn right on a red light. The French and Belgian signs consist of a yield sign with a yellow bike and arrow inside. Such signs are placed under traffic lights.<ref>{{cite web|last=Trotignon|first=Jean-Michel|title=Tourne \u00e0 droite au feu rouge: il manque juste le panneau|url=http://www.fubicy.org/IMG/pdf/VC109_PANNEAU_TOURNE_A_DROITE.pdf|work=V\u00e9locit\u00e9|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration fran\u00e7aise des Usagers de la Bicyclette|accessdate=16 July 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Panneau tourne \u00e0 droite.jpg|thumbnail|right|Sign allowing cyclists to turn right on red in France and Belgium.]]\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], which [[drives on the left]], left turn on red is prohibited, but at some junctions there is a separate left arrow-shaped green \"filter\" light which, when lit, allows left-hand turns but conflicting traffic will always have a red signal.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Highway Code: Using the road (rule 177)|url=https://www.gov.uk/using-the-road-159-to-203/road-junctions-170-to-183|accessdate=26 June 2015}}</ref> Other non conflicting traffic movements may have their own left or right arrow-shaped green light. Sometimes there are specific lanes without signals for turning left, separated from the through traffic signalled traffic by traffic islands, but give way signs are installed.\n\nIn the [[Republic of Ireland]], which drives on the left, left turns on red are prohibited.\n\nIn [[Lithuania]], drivers are allowed to turn right on red when a particular sign with a green arrow on a white background is mounted beside the red light of the traffic signal. However, on 10 November 2014, national traffic rules were altered meaning that this sign will be valid only until 31 December 2019 at the latest, by which time all such signs will have been eliminated. These changes for reasons of road safety.<ref>{{cite web|title=Changes of Lithuanian Traffic rules on 3 October 2014 - valid from 10 October 2014 |language=Lithuanian|url=http://www3.lrs.lt/pls/inter3/dokpaieska.showdoc_l?p_id=484529&p_tr2=2|archive-url=https://archive.is/20141123221243/http://www3.lrs.lt/pls/inter3/dokpaieska.showdoc_l?p_id=484529&p_tr2=2|url-status=dead|archivedate=23 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia]] right turns on red are allowed only when there is a lit green arrow present (called S 5 in Czech Republic and S 10 in Slovakia). Also in this case the car turning on red must give way to ongoing traffic, to pedestrians and other road users. (According to Czech law \u00a770 of decree 30/2001 of Law Codex; and Slovak law \u00a79, part 3g, decree 9/2009 of Law Codex)\n\nIn [[Romania]], right turns on red are prohibited, except when there is a small green flashing light with a right turn arrow. Drivers must yield to pedestrians and oncoming vehicles from their left. In some one-way junctions, the same rule applies for left on red (such as [[Cluj-Napoca]] [[Avram Iancu Square, Cluj-Napoca|Avram Iancu Square]]).\n\nIn [[Bulgaria]], right turns on red are prohibited.\n\nIn [[Spain]], right turns are allowed only if there's either a flashing amber or lit green arrow-shaped traffic light. Flashing amber arrow allows turning without priority (turn must be done exercising caution, giving way to any other vehicles and pedestrians that may cross the path), while a lit green arrow grants priority. If just a regular set of traffic lights is present (no light arrows), then turning on red is prohibited.\n\nIn [[Iceland]], right turn on red is allowed only when the \"H\u00e6gri Kveiktu \u00e1 Rau\u00f0um\" sign is displayed at the traffic junction. The driver will have to stop at the red light first and give way to pedestrians and oncoming vehicles from their left before turning.\n\n==Asia==\n\nAs in the former United Kingdom British Colony of Hong Kong Overseas British Territories, left turn on red is always prohibited in [[Hong Kong]]. At some junctions, however, there may be separate sets of signals for left turns, or specific lanes for turning left separating from the through traffic by [[traffic island]]s and [[give way sign]]s are installed. One such example is at the junction of [[Queen's Road East]] and [[Morrison Hill Road]].\n\nIn [[China]], a right turn on red is generally permitted, unless there is a red arrow pointing to the right. However, certain cities such as [[Shantou]] prohibited right turn on red.\n\nIn [[India]], which drives on the left, a \"free left turn\" is generally prohibited.<ref>{{Citation|last=Adhiraj Joglekar|title=Driving in India: At Red Lights There are no Free Left Turns|date=8 May 2007|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VQblcMUL8jg|accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiastudychannel.com/resources/83838-Common-Traffic-Rules.aspx|title=Common Traffic Rules|date=30 August 2009|newspaper=India Study Channel|accessdate=4 November 2016}}</ref> However, some cities specifically permit turning left on a red signal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/for-a-change-its-a-hasslefree-ride/article8030897.ece|title=For a change, it's a hassle-free ride|last=Ramu|first=Marri|date=26 December 2015|newspaper=The Hindu|issn=0971-751X|accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chandigarhtrafficpolice.org/directions.php|title=Chandigarh traffic police, promoting road safety, traffic safety, India road signs & rules, safe responsible driving, first aid India.|website=www.chandigarhtrafficpolice.org|accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref> An explicit green or blinking orange left signal also permits a turn on red, which usually means that conflicting traffic is not permitted to enter the same road.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.team-bhp.com/forum/street-experiences/104328-did-govt-change-no-free-left-rule-off-late-2.html|title=Did govt change the \"No Free Left\" Rule, off late - Team-BHP|newspaper=Team-BHP.com|accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Japan]], which drives on the left, the left turn on a red light requires either a green left arrow signal along with the red light, or a white road sign with a blue left arrow (not to be confused with the one way sign).\n\nIn [[Malaysia]], left turn on red can only be observed in [[Sarawak]] since 1960s and [[Putrajaya]] since mid-2000s. The road sign by the traffic lights in Sarawak may state \"Turn Left when Exit is Clear\", as English, Malay and Chinese are used for road signage. The practice is not implemented nationwide. \n\nAs in the former United Kingdom British Colony Straits of Singapore Overseas British Territories and which drives on the left, left turn on red is always prohibited at the traffic junction in [[Singapore]]. The driver must stop at the red light and wait for green lights to turn left only on green lights on. At most junctions, however, there may be separate sets of signals for left turns, or specific lanes for turning left separating from the through traffic by [[traffic island]]s and [[give way sign]]s are installed.\n\nIn [[Taiwan]], right turn on red is always prohibited, except when there is a green arrow along with the red light.\n\nIn [[Thailand]], which drives on the left, left turn on red is allowed unless a sign prohibits it.\n\nIn [[Saudi Arabia]], right turn on red is generally permitted, unless there is a dedicated slip lane for right turn.\n\nIn [[Lebanon]], unless sign or a red arrow prohibits it, right turning on red is permitted after coming to a full stop to give way to oncoming traffic and pedestrians.\n\n==Oceania==\n[[File:Left Turn on Red sign Australia.jpg|thumb|150px|Australian \"left turn on red\" sign at traffic lights]]\nIn [[Australia]], which drives on the left, left turns on red are not permitted unless a sign indicating otherwise exists at the intersection. At such intersections, a sign generally reads \"left turn on red permitted after stopping,\" meaning a vehicle can make a left turn only after coming to a complete stop first and giving way to approaching traffic and any crossing pedestrians or cyclists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/roads/safety-rules/road-rules/traffic-lights.html|title=Traffic lights and road markings - Safety & Rules|work=Roads and Maritime Services|accessdate=14 October 2016|url-status=live|archivedate=14 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161014042212/http://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/roads/safety-rules/road-rules/traffic-lights.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/traffic-transport/traffic-management/left-turn-red-project|title=Left Turn on Red project|work=Brisbane City Council|accessdate=14 October 2016|archivedate=14 October 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161014042829/https://www.brisbane.qld.gov.au/traffic-transport/traffic-management/left-turn-red-project}}</ref> Such signs are only in limited locations in the states of [[New South Wales]], [[Queensland]], [[South Australia]] (six locations as of 2016<ref name=\"ABCau\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-07-24/allow-left-hand-turns-on-red-lights-in-sa-opposition-says/7656180|title=Call to allow left-hand turns on red lights in SA|date=24 July 2016|accessdate=14 October 2016|work=ABC News}}</ref>) as well as the [[Northern Territory]] and [[Australian Capital Territory]] and are banned in other states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/queensland/left-turns-at-red-lights-to-be-allowed-in-new-traffic-trial/story-fnii5v6w-1226763320721|title= Left turns at red lights to be allowed in new traffic trial |date=19 October 2013|first=Peta|last=Fuller|work=news.com.au|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref> In New South Wales, a number of tests to the intersection must be met before a turn on red will be permitted, including pedestrian volume, bus stop locations, geometry of the intersection, and the amount of lane changing at the intersection.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/business-industry/partners-and-suppliers/guidelines/complementary-traffic-material/tsdappendixev1-2.pdf|title=Traffic Signal Design: Appendix E Left Turn on Red|work=NSW Government Roads and Maritime Services|date=14 July 2016}}</ref> There are conflicting views on the policy of left turns on red, with supporters pointing to lower vehicle emission and time savings, while opponents cite safety concerns.<ref name=\"ABCau\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/wa/a/23004026/turn-left-on-red-possible-solution/#page1|title=Turn left on red possible solution|first=Kent|last=Acott|work=The West Australian|date=27 April 2014|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[New Zealand]], which drives on the left, left turns on red are not permitted. However, there is usually a fork before the traffic lights with a giveway sign on busy intersections.\n\nIn [[Samoa]], which drives on the left, left turns on red are permitted<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.samoa.travel/travel-info/driving-in-samoa/road-rules/|title=Samoa Road Rules}}</ref>. Samoa used to drive on the right and basically follow the US rules of American Samoa, and this rule remained after switching to driving on the left on 7 September 2009.\n\n==Pedestrian and bicyclist safety==\nA 1981 US Department of Transportation study determined that the frequency of motor vehicle collisions with bicyclists and pedestrians when the vehicle was turning right increased significantly after the adoption of \"Western RTOR\". According to that study \"Estimates of the magnitude of the increases ranged from 43% to 107% for pedestrian accidents and 72% to 123% for bicyclist accidents.\"<ref>{{cite report |authors=D. F. Preusser, W. A. Leaf, K. B. DeBartolo, R. D. Blomberg |date=October 1981 |title=The Effect of Right-Turn-On-Red on Pedestrian and Bicyclist Accidents |url=https://rosap.ntl.bts.gov/view/dot/1322/dot_1322_DS1.pdf? |publisher=US.Department of Transportation National Highway Traffic Safety Administration |page=vii |accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> A 1984 study found that where RTOR was allowed \"all right-turning crashes increase by about 23%, pedestrian crashes by about 60%, and bicyclist crashes by about 100%.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zador |first1=Paul |date=August 1984 |title=Right-turn-on-red laws and motor vehicle crashes: A review of the literature |journal=Accident Analysis & Prevention |volume= 16|issue=4 |pages=241\u2013245 |doi= 10.1016/0001-4575(84)90019-8}}</ref> A 1993 study also concluded that RTOR increased crashes for pedestrians and cyclists, by 44% and 59% respectively.<ref>{{cite conference|title=Safety Effects of Right Turn on Red: A Meta Analysis |last1=Dussault |first1=Claude |date=14\u201316 June 1993 |location=Saskatoon, Saskatchewan |conference=Proceedings of the Canadian Multidisciplinary Road Safety Conference VIIII}}</ref> However, a 2002 study brought those results into question, while agreeing that \"No-Turn-on-Red restrictions are desirable where high volumes of pedestrian and conflicting vehicular traffic exist.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleck |first1=Jack |last2=Yee |first2=Bond |title=Safety Evaluation of Right Turn on Red |url=https://archives.sfmta.com/cms/rhomepd/documents/DPT_right_turn_on_red.pdf |accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Vienna Convention on Road Signs and Signals]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov/people/outreach/traftech/1995/TT086.htm The Safety Impact Of Right Turn On Red: Report To Congress], [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration]] ''Traffic Tech''\n* Sarkar, van Houten, and Moffatt, [http://trrjournalonline.trb.org/doi/10.3141/1674-07 Using License Manuals To Increase Awareness About Pedestrian Hazards at Intersections]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sarkar|first=Sheila|last2=Van Houten|first2=Ron|last3=Moffatt|first3=John|date=1 January 1999|title=Using License Manuals To Increase Awareness About Pedestrian Hazards at Intersections. Missed Opportunity for Educating Drivers|url=|journal=Transportation Research Record: Journal of the Transportation Research Board|volume=1674|pages=49\u201356|doi=10.3141/1674-07|issn=0361-1981}}</ref>, ''Transportation Research Record'' 1674.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091027100909/http://geocities.com/jusjih/trafficlightsignals.html Traffic Light Signals and Red Light Cameras: Turning on Red Light (US)], by Justin JIH.\n\n{{Traffic law}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Right Turn On Red}}\n[[Category:Traffic law]]\n[[Category:Traffic signals]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turn_on_red"}
{"title_page": "Wyn Harness", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Wyn Harness\n|birth_date=1 February 1960\n|birth_place=[[Boston, Lincolnshire]]\n|death_date=3 October 2007 (aged 47)\n|death_place=[[Hove, Sussex|Hove]]\n|spouse=Sue Royal\n|years_active=1978\u20132006\n}}\n'''Wyn Harness''' (1960\u20132007)<ref name=pressGazetteObit /> was a journalist at [[The Independent]] from the newspaper's creation in 1986.<ref name=indyObit />\n\n==Life==\nHarness was born in 1960 in [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], where he attended [[Boston Grammar School]].<ref name=indyObit /> He was the youngest child of Ray and Freda Harness.\n\nWyn married Sue Royal in 1998; with whom he had two children.<ref name=argusObit />\n\nHe died aged 47 of a brain tumour.<ref name=guardianObit />\n\n==Career==\nAt the age of 18 he began his career as a journalist, working at the [[Lincolnshire Standard]] from 1978.<ref name=pressGazetteObit />\nFrom there he joined ''[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Brighton Argus]]'' in 1982, where he stayed until 1986.<ref name=argusObit />\nHarness joined ''The Independent'' before it was launched, and was the first layout sub-editor. During his time at ''The Independent'' he took several sub-editorial roles until he became the chief sub-editor.<ref name=guardianObit /> He later became the assistant editor of ''The Independent'' and the [[Independent on Sunday]],<ref name=indyObit /> where he remained until he left the paper due to ill health in 2006.<ref name=pressGazetteRun />\n\n==The Wyn Harness prize== <!-- concerned about using this term -->\nThe annual Wyn Harness prize for young journalists was created by The Independent in his memory.<ref name=theIndependentPrizeinfo />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=pressGazetteObit>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=39160|title=Wyn Harness|publisher=[[Press Gazette]]|author=Louis Jebb|date=24 October 2007|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=theIndependentPrizeinfo>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/press/the-wyn-harness-prize-for-young-journalists-2096259.html?origin=internalSearch|title=The Wyn Harness Prize for Young Journalists|date=3 October 2010|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=guardianObit>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/nov/01/guardianobituaries.obituaries?INTCMP=SRCH|title=Obituary: Wyn Harness|author=Martin Farrer|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=1 November 2007|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=argusObit>{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/1745635.Top_journalist_dies_aged_47/|title=Top journalist dies aged 47|date=9 October 2007|author=Richard Gurner|publisher=The Brighton Argus|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=indyObit>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/wyn-harness-396136.html|title=Wyn Harness - Obituaries|date=6 October 2007|author=Louis Jebb|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=pressGazetteRun>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=7&storycode=40858|title=Mullin to run London Marathon|date=11 April 2007|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harness, Wyn}}\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Boston Grammar School]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Wyn Harness\n|birth_date=1 February 1960\n|birth_place=[[Boston, Lincolnshire]]\n|death_date=3 October 2007 (aged 47)\n|death_place=[[Hove, Sussex|Hove]]\n|spouse=Sue Royal\n|years_active=1978\u20132006\n}}\n'''Wyn Harness''' (1960\u20132007)<ref name=pressGazetteObit /> was a journalist at [[The Independent]] from the newspaper's creation in 1986.<ref name=indyObit />\n\n==Life==\nHarness was born in 1960 in [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], where he attended [[Boston Grammar School]].<ref name=indyObit /> He was the youngest child of Ray and Freda Harness.\n\nWyn married Sue Royal in 1998; with whom he had two children.<ref name=argusObit />\n\nHe died aged 47 of a brain tumour.<ref name=guardianObit />\n\n==Career==\nAt the age of 18 he began his career as a journalist, working at the [[Lincolnshire Standard]] from 1978.<ref name=pressGazetteObit />\nFrom there he joined ''[[The Argus (Brighton)|The Brighton Argus]]'' in 1982, where he stayed until 1986.<ref name=argusObit />\nHarness joined ''The Independent'' before it was launched, and was the first layout sub-editor. During his time at ''The Independent'' he took several sub-editorial roles until he became the chief sub-editor.<ref name=guardianObit /> He later became the assistant editor of ''The Independent'' and the [[Independent on Sunday]],<ref name=indyObit /> where he remained until he left the paper due to ill health in 2006.<ref name=pressGazetteRun />\n\n==The Wyn Harness prize== <!-- concerned about using this term -->\nThe annual Wyn Harness prize for young journalists was created by The Independent in his memory.<ref name=theIndependentPrizeinfo />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=pressGazetteObit>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=39160|title=Wyn Harness|publisher=[[Press Gazette]]|author=Louis Jebb|date=24 October 2007|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=theIndependentPrizeinfo>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/press/the-wyn-harness-prize-for-young-journalists-2096259.html?origin=internalSearch|title=The Wyn Harness Prize for Young Journalists|date=3 October 2010|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=guardianObit>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/nov/01/guardianobituaries.obituaries?INTCMP=SRCH|title=Obituary: Wyn Harness|author=Martin Farrer|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=1 November 2007|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=argusObit>{{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/1745635.Top_journalist_dies_aged_47/|title=Top journalist dies aged 47|date=9 October 2007|author=Richard Gurner|publisher=The Brighton Argus|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=indyObit>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/wyn-harness-396136.html|title=Wyn Harness - Obituaries|date=6 October 2007|author=Louis Jebb|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=pressGazetteRun>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=7&storycode=40858|title=Mullin to run London Marathon|date=11 April 2007|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harness, Wyn}}\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:People educated at Boston Grammar School]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wyn_Harness"}
{"title_page": "Turlough O'Carolan", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=November 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Maurice O'Connor.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Turlough Carolan.]]\n\n'''Turlough O'Carolan''',<ref>According to the 5th edition of [[Grove's Dictionary of Music and Musicians]], the version \"O'Carolan\" is ''\"modern and lacks authority\"''</ref> ({{lang-ga|Toirdhealbhach \u00d3 Cearbhall\u00e1in}}; {{IPA-ga|\u02c8t\u032a\u02e0\u027e\u02e0e\u02d0l\u032a\u02e0\u0259x o\u02d0 \u02c8caru\u02d0l\u032a\u02e0a\u02d0n\u02b2}}) (1670{{spaced ndash}}25 March 1738) was a blind [[Celtic harp]]er, composer and singer in Ireland whose great fame is due to his gift for melodic composition.\n\nAlthough not a composer in the classical sense, Carolan is considered by many to be Ireland's national composer. Harpers in the old Irish tradition were still living as late as 1792, and ten, including [[Arthur O'Neill (harpist)|Arthur O'Neill]], [[Patrick Quin]] and [[Donnchadh \u00d3 H\u00e1msaigh]], attended the [[Belfast Harp Festival]]. \u00d3 H\u00e1msaigh did play some of Carolan's music but disliked it for being too modern. Some of Carolan's own compositions show influences of the style of continental classical music, whereas others such as Carolan's ''Farewell to Music'' reflect a much older style of \"Gaelic Harping\".\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Turlough Carolan memorial - Dublin, Ireland.jpg|thumb|left|Carolan's memorial in [[St Patrick's Cathedral, Dublin|St Patrick's Cathedral]] was the gift of [[Sydney, Lady Morgan]].]]\n\nCarolan was born in 1670 in [[Nobber]], [[County Meath]], where his father was a blacksmith. The family moved from Meath to [[Ballyfarnon]], [[County Roscommon]] in 1684. In Roscommon, his father took a job with the [[MacDermotRoe|MacDermott Roe]] family of Alderford House. Mrs. MacDermott Roe gave Turlough an education, and he showed talent in poetry. After being blinded by [[smallpox]] at the age of eighteen, Carolan was apprenticed by Mrs. MacDermott Roe to a good harper. At the age of twenty-one, being given a horse and a guide, he set out to travel Ireland and compose songs for patrons.<ref>White, Harry: \"Carolan, Turlough (\u00d3 Cearbhall\u00e1in, Toirdhealbhach)\", in: ''[[Dictionary of Irish Biography]]'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2009).</ref>\n\nFor almost fifty years, Carolan journeyed from one end of Ireland to the other, composing and performing his tunes. One of his earliest compositions was about Brigid Cruise, with whom he was infatuated. Brigid was the teenage daughter of the schoolmaster at the school for the blind attended by Carolan in Cruisetown, Ireland.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hardiman|first=James|title=Irish Minstrelsy, or, Bardic Remains of Ireland: with English poetical translations|url=https://archive.org/details/irishminstrelsy00currgoog|year=1831|publisher=J. Robins|location=London|page=xlix}}</ref> In 1720, Carolan married Mary Maguire. He was then 50 years of age. Their first family home was a cottage on a parcel of land near the town of Manachain (now [[Mohill]]) in County Leitrim, where they settled. They had seven children, six daughters and one son. In 1733 Mary died.\n\nTurlough O'Carolan died on 25 March 1738. He is buried in the MacDermott Roe family crypt in Kilronan Burial Ground near [[Ballyfarnon]], County Roscommon. The annual O'Carolan Harp Festival and Summer School commemorates his life and work in [[Keadue]], County Roscommon.\n\nA bronze monument by sculptor [[Oisin Kelly]] depicting Turlough O'Carolan playing his harp was erected on a plinth at the Market Square, Mohill, on 10 August 1986, and was unveiled by [[Patrick Hillery]], [[President of Ireland]].\n\nA statue was erected to him at his place of birth (Nobber, Co Meath) in 2002, during the Annual O'Carolan Harp Festival, the first of which was held in Nobber in 1988.\n\n==Music and style==\nCarolan composed both songs and instrumental harp music, reflecting various styles of composition. About a third of Carolan's surviving music have associated Irish lyrics that survive to this day. Largely these lyrics are unknown to the musicians of today, who have for the most part adapted Carolan's repertoire to the currently popular Irish fare of jigs and reels.\n\nCarolan's activities during his career are only partially documented historically. This has led to a lack of accurate information about Carolan and his music, even among Irish musicians. Sometimes, alternate titles or incorrect titles have been applied to songs, creating confusion as to whether the song is Carolan's or someone else's. Also, some of those who have written about Carolan and his music have made up facts or repeated unfounded stories. For instance, Edward Bunting, who began the work of collecting Carolan's pieces, referred to a \"very ancient air\" the Fairy Queen, saying it \"seems to have been the original of Carolan's ''Fairy Queen''.\" He also reported that \"the ''Fairy Queen'' of Carolan was not intended by him for words, but as a piece of music for the harp.\" While it is true that Carolan did not write the traditional ''Fairy Queen'' words, which indeed do exist, the words are not ancient (nor is the entirely different traditional Irish air ''The Fairy Queen'')<ref>{{cite book |author=O'Sullivan, Donal |year=1958 |title=Carolan: The life, times, and music of an Irish harper |location=London, UK |publisher=Routledge and Kegan Paul |at=vol.&nbsp;2, p.&nbsp;116}}</ref>, and the words do in fact fit perfectly the original music which Carolan composed for them.<ref>As heard on Track&nbsp;8 of ''Le Concert de l'Hostel Dieu'', by Garlic Bread, 2013</ref>\n\nIrish was the majority language in Ireland during Carolan's time. As Carolan did not speak English very well, he composed only one song in English, \"Carolan's Devotion\". Most of his songs were dedicated to and written about specific individual patrons. Many of his tunes are widely performed and appreciated today, and a handful of his Irish songs have been recorded by various artists. He typically composed the tune first, as he rode from place to place, then added words later. Many of his songs are designated as \"''[[wiktionary:planxty|planxties]]''\", [[wiktionary:planxty|an obscure word]] that Carolan apparently invented or popularized to signify a tribute to a merry host. In return for writing songs in honour of wealthy patrons, Carolan was often welcomed as an honoured guest to stay on their estates.<ref>{{cite book |author=O'Sullivan, Donal |year=1958 |title=Carolan: The life, times, and music of an Irish harper |location=London, UK |publisher=Routledge and Kegan Paul}} in 2&nbsp;volumes; new edition in 1&nbsp;volume: {{cite book |author=O'Sullivan, Donal |year=2001 |title=Carolan: The life, times, and music of an Irish harper |location=Cork, EI |publisher=Ossian Publications |ISBN=1-900428-76-8 |edition=hardback}}; paperback 2001 edition {{ISBN|1-900428-71-7}}.</ref> It is said that weddings and funerals were sometimes delayed until he could arrive to perform.\n\n==Publication==\nMost of Carolan's compositions were not published or even written down in his lifetime. They survived in the repertoires of fiddlers, pipers, and the last of the old Irish harper/singers. They were collected and published during the late 18th century and beyond, largely beginning with the work of Edward Bunting and his assistants in 1792.<ref>Bunting, Edward ''The Ancient Music of Ireland / Bunting's Collections'' (Waltons' Piano and Musical Instrument Galleries, Dublin, 1969)</ref>\n\nA small sampling of Carolan's music was published during his lifetime. One of the first such publications was in Neale's ''A Collection of the Most Celebrated Irish Tunes ...'', Dublin, 1724.<ref>''A Colection [sic!] of the most Celebrated Irish Tunes proper for the Violin German Flute or Hautboy'' (Dublin: John and William Neale, undated [1724]; facsimile edition by Nicholas Carolan (Dublin: Folk Music Society of Ireland, 1986), {{ISBN|0-905733-01-0}}.</ref>\n\nThe definitive work containing all 214 of Carolan's tunes as identified by Donal O'Sullivan (1893\u20131973) is the 1958 edition (2001 reprint) of ''Carolan: The Life Times and Music of an Irish Harper''.<ref>O'Sullivan, Donal ''Carolan'' (as above).</ref> Partial lyrics (and all known sources of lyrics) are mentioned in the text description of each piece, but are not matched to the written music. O'Sullivan does not include any of the handful of alleged Carolan songs that he considers to be erroneous, such as: \"Dermott O'Doud\", \"Planxty Miss Burke\", and \"The Snowy-Breasted Pearl\".<ref>Bunting, Edward: ''A General Collection of the Ancient Irish Music'' (Dublin: W. Power & Co., 1796), p. 17.</ref>\n\nA comprehensive edition of Carolan's Songs & Airs containing new arrangements for harp of all 214 airs, along with an additional 12 airs from the Appendix of the 2001 edition<ref>O'Sullivan, Donal: ''Carolan'' (as above), p. 334 ff.</ref> was published by Caitr\u00edona Rowsome in 2011.<ref name=\":0\">Rowsome, Caitr\u00edona: ''The Complete Carolan Songs & Airs'' (Dublin: Waltons Publishing, 2011), {{ISBN|9781857202182}}.</ref> This book includes an instance of each of Carolan's undisputed surviving lyrics and metrically sets the lyrics note-for-note to the sheet music airs. Each of the 226 harp settings in this book are played by the author on a neo-Irish harp (book and 4-CD set). This is the first time that all of Carolan's lyrics have been set to the airs and has been welcomed as \"a task that has needed doing for many years\".<ref>''An P\u00edobaire'' 9 (2013) 1 (Feabhra / February).</ref> The 4-CD recording is of harp music without vocals, but the book includes the sheet music for interested singers. The book also includes an English interpretation for each of Carolan's 72 Irish song lyrics. Five of these interpretations take the form of new English lyrics set metrically to the sheet music of 'Hewlett', 'Colonel John Irwin', 'John O'Connor', 'Kean O'Hara (3rd Air)' and 'Sheebeg and Sheemore'.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Performances==\nSince 1967, when Se\u00e1n O\u2019Riada and the Ceolt\u00f3ir\u00ed Chualann released ''Carolan\u2019s Concerto'' and 2 other Carolan compositions,<ref>O\u2019Riada, Se\u00e1n ''Ceol Na nUasal'' (Gael Linn records, Ireland, 1967)</ref> there have been hundreds of recordings of Carolan songs released by dozens of artists. Many of these recordings are by such well-known performers as [[The Chieftains]], [[Planxty]], Patrick Ball, and Joemy Wilson, others by less well known artists. Occasionally, an artist who is popular in another area will record a single Carolan song for variety, such as Steeleye Span's ''Sheebeg and Sheemore'', [[John Renbourn]]'s ''[[Lament for Owen Roe O'Neill]]'', [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]]'s ''Morgan Mawgan'' [sic], Stefan Grossman's ''Blind Mary'', John Williams' ''Mrs. Maxwell'', and many others. Several popular collections by multiple artists have also been issued, including ''The Music of O\u2019Carolan'' (1993), ''Deluxe Anthology of Carolan'' (1995), ''Celtic Treasure'' (1996), and ''Celtic Treasure II'' (2001). The sheer quantity of these recordings has greatly expanded the number of Carolan pieces known to the public, but the performers do tend to come back to certain songs again and again. Among the most frequently recorded pieces are the following:\n\n''Carolan\u2019s Concerto'' (at least 35), ''Blind Mary'' (at least 23), ''[[S\u00ed Bheag, S\u00ed Mh\u00f3r|Sheebeg and Sheemore]]'' (at least 22), ''Planxty George Brabazon'' (at least 21), ''Planxty Col. Irwin'' (at least 19), ''Fanny Power'' (at least 19), ''Eleanor Plunkett'' (at least 18), ''Carolan\u2019s Farewell to Music'' (at least 18), ''Carolan\u2019s Draught'' (at least 17), ''Hewlett'' (at least 16), ''The Princess Royal'' (at least 16), and ''Stafford's Receipt'' (at least 16). In addition, innumerable musicians have performed many of Carolan's tunes learned from such books as ''The Fiddler's Fakebook'',<ref>Brody, David ''[[The Fiddler's Fakebook]]'' (New York: Oak Publications, 1983).</ref> which contains some of the above tunes plus ''Morgan Magan'' and ''Planxty Drury''. Also, ''O'Neill\u2019s Music of Ireland'' (1903)<ref>http://trillian.mit.edu/~jc/music/book/oneills/</ref> is still in print and contains over 60 of Carolan's tunes, of which far too many to list have made their way into the repertoire of musicians around the world.\n\nIn addition, ''Carolan's Concerto'' has been used as a neutral slow march by the [[Foot Guards]] of the [[British Army]] during the ceremony of [[Trooping the Colour]]. Also, some of Carolan's compositions have appeared in the role-playing game ''[[Fate (video game)|FATE]]''.\n\nCarolan's music has frequently been adapted for fingerstyle guitar (primarily steel string acoustic), often by altering the tuning from standard (EADGBE) to DADGBE (drop D), DADGAD, and CGDGAD, among others. This allows strings to ring out and results in a more harp-like sound. Duck Baker has recorded many Carolan songs in drop D tuning. El McMeen performs almost exclusively in CGDGAD, and has recorded many Carolan songs.\n\n==Compositions==\nThe complete list of the 214 Carolan compositions identified by Donal O'Sullivan (see References) are, in alphabetical order, as follows:\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*All Alive\n*Baptist Johnston\n*Betty MacNeill\n*Betty O'Brien\n*Blind Mary\n*Brian Maguire\n*Bridget Cruise, 1st Air\n*Bridget Cruise, 2nd Air\n*Bridget Cruise, 3rd Air\n*Bridget Cruise, 4th Air\n*Bumper Squire Jones\n*Captain Higgins\n*Captain Magan\n*Captain O'Kane\n*Captain O'Neill, (no. 214)\n*Captain Sudley (Carolan's Dowry)\n*Carolan's Cap\n*Carolan's Cottage\n*Carolan's Cup\n*Carolan's Draught\n*Carolan's Dream\n*Carolan's Farewell to Music\n*Carolan's Frolic\n*Carolan's Maggot\n*Carolan's Quarrel with the Landlady\n*Carolan's Ramble to Cashel\n*[[Carolan's Welcome]], (no. 171)\n*Catherine Martin\n*Catherine O'More\n*Charles O'Conor\n*The Clergy's Lamentation\n*Colonel Irwin\n*Colonel Manus O'Donnell\n*Colonel O'Hara\n*Conor O'Reilly\n*Constantine Maguire\n*Counsellor Dillon\n*Cremonea\n*Daniel Kelly\n*The Dark, Plaintive Youth\n*David Power\n*Denis O'Conor, 1st Air\n*Denis O'Conor, 2nd Air\n*Dolly MacDonough (The Morning Star)\n*Donal O'Brien\n*Dr. John Hart\n*Dr. John Stafford (Stafford's Receipt)\n*Dr. MacMahon, Bishop of Clogher\n*Dr. Delany\n*Dr. John Hart, Bishop of Achonry\n*Dr. O'Connor\n*Edmond MacDermott Roe\n*Edward Corcoran\n*Edward Dodwell\n*Eleanor Plunkett\n*The Elevation\n*Elizabeth MacDermott Roe\n*Elizabeth Nugent\n*The Fairy Queen\n*Fanny Dillon\n*Fanny Power\n*Father Brian MacDermott Roe\n*Frank Palmer\n*General Wynne\n*George Brabazon, 1st Air\n*(\"Planxty\") George Brabazon, 2nd Air\n*George Reynolds\n*Gerald Dillon\n*Grace Nugent\n*Henry MacDermott Roe, 1st Air\n*Henry MacDermott Roe, 2nd Air\n*Henry MacDermott Roe, 3rd Air\n*The Honourable Thomas Burke\n*Hugh Kelly\n*Hugh O'Donnell\n*Isabella Burke\n*James Betagh\n*James Crofton\n*James Daly\n*James Plunkett\n*John Drury, 1st Air\n*John Drury, 2nd Air\n*John Jameson\n*John Jones\n*John Kelly\n*John MacDermott\n*John Moore\n*John Nugent\n*John O'Connor\n*John O'Reilly, 1st Air\n*John O'Reilly, 2nd Air\n*John Peyton\n*Katherine O'More (The Hawk of the Erne)\n*Kean O'Hara, 1st Air (O'Hara's Cup)\n*Kean O'Hara, 2nd Air\n*Kean O'Hara, 3rd Air\n*Kitty Magennis\n*Lady Athenry\n*Lady Blaney\n*Lady Dillon\n*Lady Gethin\n*Lady Laetitia Burke\n*Lady St. John\n*Lady Wrixon\n*Lament for Charles MacCabe\n*Lament for Owen O'Rourke\n*[[Lament for Owen Roe O'Neill]]\n*Lament for Sir Ulick Burke\n*Lament for Terence MacDonough\n*The Landlady\n*Loftus Jones\n*Lord Dillon\n*Lord Galway's Lamentation\n*Lord Inchiquin\n*Lord Louth\n*Lord Massereene\n*Lord Mayo\n*Luke Dillon\n*Mabel Kelly\n*Major Shanly\n*Margaret Malone\n*Mary O'Neill\n*Maurice O'Connor, 1st Air\n*Maurice O'Connor, 2nd Air\n*Maurice O'Connor, 3rd Air\n*Mervyn Pratt\n*Michael O'Connor, 1st Air\n*Michael O'Connor, 2nd Air\n*Miss Crofton\n*Miss Fetherston (Carolan's Devotion)\n*Miss Goulding\n*[[The Saucy Arethusa|Miss MacDermott]] ([[Prince of Coolavin#The Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]])\n*Miss MacMurray\n*Miss Murphy\n*Miss Noble\n*Morgan Magan\n*Mr. Malone\n*Mr. O'Connor\n*Mr. Waller\n*Mrs. Anne MacDermott Roe\n*Mrs. Bermingham, 1st Air\n*Mrs. Bermingham, 2nd Air\n*Mrs. Cole\n*Mrs. Costello\n*Mrs. Crofton\n*Mrs. Delany\n*Mrs. Edwards\n*Mrs. Fallon\n*Mrs. Farrell\n*Mrs. Garvey, 1st Air\n*Mrs. Garvey, 2nd Air\n*Mrs. Harwood\n*Mrs. Judge\n*Mrs. Keel\n*Mrs. MacDermott Roe\n*Mrs. Maxwell, 1st Air\n*Mrs. Maxwell, 2nd Air\n*Mrs. Nugent\n*Mrs. O'Connor\n*Mrs. O'Conor\n*Mrs. O'Neill of Carlane\n*Mrs. O'Neill (Carolan's Favourite)\n*Mrs. O'Rourke\n*Mrs. Power (Carolan's Concerto)\n*Mrs. Sterling\n*Mrs. Waller\n*Nancy Cooper, 1st Air\n*Nancy Cooper, 2nd Air\n*O'Flinn\n*O'Reilly of Athcarne\n*The O'Rourkes' Feast\n*Ode to Whiskey\n*One Bottle More\n*Owen O'Rourke\n*Patrick Kelly\n*Peggy Morton\n*Planxty Browne, (no. 180)\n*Planxty Burke\n*Planxty Crilly\n*Planxty Drew\n*Planxty Hewlett\n*Planxty John Irwin\n*Planxty Kelly\n*Planxty O'Rourke, 1st Air\n*Planxty O'Rourke, 2nd Air\n*Planxty Plunkett\n*Planxty Sweeney\n*Planxty Wilkinson\n*Richard Cusack\n*Robert Hawkes\n*Robert Jordan\n*The Seas are Deep\n*Separation of Soul and Body\n*[[S\u00ed Bheag, S\u00ed Mh\u00f3r|Sheebeg and Sheemore]]\n*Sir Arthur Shaen\n*Sir Charles Coote\n*Sir Edward Crofton\n*Sir Festus Burke\n*Sir Ulick Burke\n*Squire Parsons\n*[[William Wood (Mintmaster)|Squire Wood]]'s Lamentation on the Refusal of his Halfpence\n*Susanna Kelly\n*Thomas Burke\n*Thomas Judge (Carolan's Frolic)\n*Tobias Peyton\n*The Two William Davises\n*(unnamed) - 8 pieces, (nos. 172-179)\n*Variations on the Scottish Air<BR>\"[[Cock Up Your Beaver]]\"\n*Variations on the Scottish Air<BR>\"When She Cam Ben\"\n*William Eccles\n*William Ward\n{{div col end}}\n\nMany of these pieces have alternative titles, as fully documented by Donal O'Sullivan. O'Sullivan's preferred titles are the ones generally accepted as standard, though quite a few of these titles were devised by O'Sullivan himself after exhaustive research into the identities of the patrons for whom each song was written.\n\nAdditionally, a manuscript compiled in Scotland in 1816 by the MacLean-Clephane sisters was discovered in 1983 and includes at least five other pieces credited to Carolan and other annotated pieces that were \"improved by Carolan\" or \"consistent with Carolan's writing to warrant consideration\". These airs are included in the Appendix of the 2001 edition of ''Carolan: The Life Times and Music of an Irish Harper'' along with detailed research notes. These pieces came to light a decade after the death of Donal O'Sullivan in 1973, so he never had an opportunity to subject them to the same analysis that he used on the original 214 airs that he originally compiled in 1958. However, to date, no one has disputed the attributions presented in this manuscript. Newly composed harp arrangements for each of these and all the other airs (as well as new Carolan repertoire numbers 215 to 226 for each of the MacLean-Clephane tunes) are included in ''The Complete Carolan Songs & Airs'' by Caitr\u00edona Rowsome.<ref>Rowsome, Caitr\u00edona (as above), pp. 238-251.</ref> The five pieces that are said to be composed by Carolan rather than simply \"improved\" are:\n*\"Athlone\" (215)\n*\"Banks of the Shannon\" (216)\n*\"Farewell to Lough Neaghe\" (219)\n*\"Irish Galloway Tom\" (220)\n*\"The Lamentation of Ireland\" (221)\n\n==Other==\n\n\n*O'Carolan Road in the Tenters area of [[The Liberties|Dublin 8]] is named in his honour.\n*Carolan Road and \"Carolan Corner\" shop are named in his honour in the [[Ballynafeigh]] area of south [[Belfast]].\n*The [[meteorite]] [[Impact_crater|crater]] Carolan on [[Mercury_(planet)|Mercury]] was named in his honour in 2015.<ref>Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature, IAU, [https://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/15321 Map of crater Carolan]</ref>\n*Polish bands: [[2 plus 1]] in 1979 and [[Myslovitz]] in 1996 recorded songs entitled \"Peggy Brown\", said to be a translation of an obscure O'Carolan lyric by Polish lyricist Ernest Bryll, with different tunes and arrangements: folk and alternative rock, respectively. Neither of these tunes use an O'Carolan composition. Both songs were very popular in Poland.\n*O'Carolan is depicted on the \u00a350 note, [[Series B Banknotes (Ireland)|Series B Banknote]] of Ireland.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people on the postage stamps of Ireland]]\n*[[Music of Ireland]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Donal O'Sullivan: ''Carolan: The Life Times and Music of an Irish Harper'', 2 volumes (London: Routledge and Kegan Paul, 1958); new edition in 1 volume: Cork: Ossian Publications, 2001; {{ISBN|1-900428-76-8}} (hardback), 1-900428-71-7 (paperback).\n*Donal O'Sullivan: ''Songs of the Irish'' (Dublin: Brown & Nolan, 1960).\n*The Complete Works of O'Carolan: Irish Harper & Composer (1670-1738), published by Ossian Publications, Ireland, 1984, {{ISBN|0 946005 16 8}}.\n*Art Edelstein: \"Fair Melodies: Turlough Carolan, An Irish Harper\" (East Calais, Vermont: Noble Stone Press, 2001), {{ISBN|978-0971169302}}.\n*The first commercial recording of Carolan's complete works was ''The Complete Works of Turlough O\u2019Carolan (1670-1738)'' [2006, 8-cd set, Trigon, 214 tracks] arranged and performed by Irish pianist [[J.J. Sheridan]].\n*The first commercial recording on an Irish harp of the ''Complete Carolan: Songs & Airs'' has been recorded and arranged by Irish harpist Caitr\u00edona Rowsome (Dublin: Waltons Publishing, 2011). This is packaged with a 254-page book of sheet music, with the same name.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.myspace.com/carolansdream Recording of O'Carolan's tunes by \"Garlic Bread\" and French baroque ensemble \"Le concert de l'Hostel Dieu\" ]\n*[http://www.docsworkshop.co.uk The Complete Carolan: many of Carolan's tunes, arranged in open tunings for the guitar]\n*[http://www.earlygaelicharp.info/carolan O'Carolan: pages on his life, his tunes, his songs, his harp, with audio files]\n*[[Nikolaus Newerkla]], Playford Dances & Carolan Tunes, Moeck-Verlag Celle, 2007, tunes arranged for recorders and basso continuo, The Music of an Irish Harper, B\u00e4renreiter-Verlag Kassel, 2012, tunes arranged for recorders and harpsichord (piano).\n*[http://www.contemplator.com/carolan/ Turlough O'Carolan: Irish Harper]\n*[http://english.glendale.cc.ca.us/carolan.html Turlough O'Carolan 1670-1738]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060218200307/http://www.oldmusicproject.com/OCC.html Complete Works of Turlough O'Carolan] (musical scores)\n*[http://www.earlygaelicharp.info/sources/carolan.htm Carolan Fragment: one of the early sources described]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070518155910/http://www.calumcille.com/modhan/iuchraichean/priomh.html Gaelic harp keys] (web article with suggested original keys of all O'Carolan's tunes)\n*{{CathEncy|wstitle=Torlogh O'Carolan}}\n*The first complete recording of the Complete Works of O'Carolan has been recorded and arranged by Irish pianist, J.J. Sheridan\n*{{IMSLP|id=Carolan, Turlough}}\n*The first complete recording on an Irish Harp of the Complete Carolan: Songs & Airs has been recorded and arranged by Irish Harpist, Caitr\u00edona Rowsome, 2011\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:OCarolan, Turlough}}\n[[Category:1670 births]]\n[[Category:1738 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:18th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:Irish Baroque composers]]\n[[Category:Composers for harp]]\n[[Category:Irish composers]]\n[[Category:Irish harpists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from County Meath]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=November 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Maurice O'Connor.jpg|thumb|Portrait of Turlough Carolan.]]\n\n'''Turlough O'Carolan''',<ref>According to the 5th edition of [[Grove's Dictionary of Music and Musicians]], the version \"O'Carolan\" is ''\"modern and lacks authority\"''</ref> ({{lang-ga|Toirdhealbhach \u00d3 Cearbhall\u00e1in}}; {{IPA-ga|\u02c8t\u032a\u02e0\u027e\u02e0e\u02d0l\u032a\u02e0\u0259x o\u02d0 \u02c8caru\u02d0l\u032a\u02e0a\u02d0n\u02b2}}) (1670{{spaced ndash}}25 March 1738) was a blind [[Celtic harp]]er, composer and singer in Ireland whose great fame is due to his gift for melodic composition.\n\nAlthough not a composer in the classical sense, Carolan is considered by many to be Ireland's national composer. Harpers in the old Irish tradition were still living as late as 1792, and ten, including [[Arthur O'Neill (harpist)|Arthur O'Neill]], [[Patrick Quin]] and [[Donnchadh \u00d3 H\u00e1msaigh]], attended the [[Belfast Harp Festival]]. \u00d3 H\u00e1msaigh did play some of Carolan's music but disliked it for being too modern. Some of Carolan's own compositions show influences of the style of continental classical music, whereas others such as Carolan's ''Farewell to Music'' reflect a much older style of \"Gaelic Harping\".\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Turlough Carolan memorial - Dublin, Ireland.jpg|thumb|left|Carolan's memorial in [[St Patrick's Cathedral, Dublin|St Patrick's Cathedral]] was the gift of [[Sydney, Lady Morgan]].]]\n\nCarolan was born in 1670 in [[Nobber]], [[County Meath]], where his father was a blacksmith. The family moved from Meath to [[Ballyfarnon]], [[County Roscommon]] in 1684. In Roscommon, his father took a job with the [[MacDermotRoe|MacDermott Roe]] family of Alderford House. Mrs. MacDermott Roe gave Turlough an education, and he showed talent in poetry. After being blinded by [[smallpox]] at the age of eighteen, Carolan was apprenticed by Mrs. MacDermott Roe to a good harper. At the age of twenty-one, being given a horse and a guide, he set out to travel Ireland and compose songs for patrons.<ref>White, Harry: \"Carolan, Turlough (\u00d3 Cearbhall\u00e1in, Toirdhealbhach)\", in: ''[[Dictionary of Irish Biography]]'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2009).</ref>\n\nFor almost fifty years, Carolan journeyed from one end of Ireland to the other, composing and performing his tunes. One of his earliest compositions was about Brigid Cruise, with whom he was infatuated. Brigid was the teenage daughter of the schoolmaster at the school for the blind attended by Carolan in Cruisetown, Ireland.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hardiman|first=James|title=Irish Minstrelsy, or, Bardic Remains of Ireland: with English poetical translations|url=https://archive.org/details/irishminstrelsy00currgoog|year=1831|publisher=J. Robins|location=London|page=xlix}}</ref> In 1720, Carolan married Mary Maguire. He was then 50 years of age. Their first family home was a cottage on a parcel of land near the town of Manachain (now [[Mohill]]) in County Leitrim, where they settled. They had seven children, six daughters and one son. In 1733 Mary died.\n\nTurlough O'Carolan died on 25 March 1738. He is buried in the MacDermott Roe family crypt in Kilronan Burial Ground near [[Ballyfarnon]], County Roscommon. The annual O'Carolan Harp Festival and Summer School commemorates his life and work in [[Keadue]], County Roscommon.\n\nA bronze monument by sculptor [[Oisin Kelly]] depicting Turlough O'Carolan playing his harp was erected on a plinth at the Market Square, Mohill, on 10 August 1986, and was unveiled by [[Patrick Hillery]], [[President of Ireland]].\n\nA statue was erected to him at his place of birth (Nobber, Co Meath) in 2002, during the Annual O'Carolan Harp Festival, the first of which was held in Nobber in 1988.\n\n==Music and style==\nCarolan composed both songs and instrumental harp music, reflecting various styles of composition. About a third of Carolan's surviving music have associated Irish lyrics that survive to this day. Largely these lyrics are unknown to the musicians of today, who have for the most part adapted Carolan's repertoire to the currently popular Irish fare of jigs and reels.\n\nCarolan's activities during his career are only partially documented historically. This has led to a lack of accurate information about Carolan and his music, even among Irish musicians. Sometimes, alternate titles or incorrect titles have been applied to songs, creating confusion as to whether the song is Carolan's or someone else's. Also, some of those who have written about Carolan and his music have made up facts or repeated unfounded stories. For instance, Edward Bunting, who began the work of collecting Carolan's pieces, referred to a \"very ancient air\" the Fairy Queen, saying it \"seems to have been the original of Carolan's ''Fairy Queen''.\" He also reported that \"the ''Fairy Queen'' of Carolan was not intended by him for words, but as a piece of music for the harp.\" While it is true that Carolan did not write the traditional ''Fairy Queen'' words, which indeed do exist, the words are not ancient (nor is the entirely different traditional Irish air ''The Fairy Queen'')<ref>{{cite book |author=O'Sullivan, Donal |year=1958 |title=Carolan: The life, times, and music of an Irish harper |location=London, UK |publisher=Routledge and Kegan Paul |at=vol.&nbsp;2, p.&nbsp;116}}</ref>, and the words do in fact fit perfectly the original music which Carolan composed for them<ref>As heard on Track&nbsp;8 of ''Le Concert de l'Hostel Dieu'', by Garlic Bread, 2013</ref>.\n\nIrish was the majority language in Ireland during Carolan's time. As Carolan did not speak English very well, he composed only one song in English, \"Carolan's Devotion\". Most of his songs were dedicated to and written about specific individual patrons. Many of his tunes are widely performed and appreciated today, and a handful of his Irish songs have been recorded by various artists. He typically composed the tune first, as he rode from place to place, then added words later. Many of his songs are designated as \"''[[wiktionary:planxty|planxties]]''\", [[wiktionary:planxty|an obscure word]] that Carolan apparently invented or popularized to signify a tribute to a merry host. In return for writing songs in honour of wealthy patrons, Carolan was often welcomed as an honoured guest to stay on their estates.<ref>{{cite book |author=O'Sullivan, Donal |year=1958 |title=Carolan: The life, times, and music of an Irish harper |location=London, UK |publisher=Routledge and Kegan Paul}} in 2&nbsp;volumes; new edition in 1&nbsp;volume: {{cite book |author=O'Sullivan, Donal |year=2001 |title=Carolan: The life, times, and music of an Irish harper |location=Cork, EI |publisher=Ossian Publications |ISBN=1-900428-76-8 |edition=hardback}}; paperback 2001 edition {{ISBN|1-900428-71-7}}.</ref> It is said that weddings and funerals were sometimes delayed until he could arrive to perform.\n\n==Publication==\nMost of Carolan's compositions were not published or even written down in his lifetime. They survived in the repertoires of fiddlers, pipers, and the last of the old Irish harper/singers. They were collected and published during the late 18th century and beyond, largely beginning with the work of Edward Bunting and his assistants in 1792.<ref>Bunting, Edward ''The Ancient Music of Ireland / Bunting's Collections'' (Waltons' Piano and Musical Instrument Galleries, Dublin, 1969)</ref>\n\nA small sampling of Carolan's music was published during his lifetime. One of the first such publications was in Neale's ''A Collection of the Most Celebrated Irish Tunes ...'', Dublin, 1724.<ref>''A Colection [sic!] of the most Celebrated Irish Tunes proper for the Violin German Flute or Hautboy'' (Dublin: John and William Neale, undated [1724]; facsimile edition by Nicholas Carolan (Dublin: Folk Music Society of Ireland, 1986), {{ISBN|0-905733-01-0}}.</ref>\n\nThe definitive work containing all 214 of Carolan's tunes as identified by Donal O'Sullivan (1893\u20131973) is the 1958 edition (2001 reprint) of ''Carolan: The Life Times and Music of an Irish Harper''.<ref>O'Sullivan, Donal ''Carolan'' (as above).</ref> Partial lyrics (and all known sources of lyrics) are mentioned in the text description of each piece, but are not matched to the written music. O'Sullivan does not include any of the handful of alleged Carolan songs that he considers to be erroneous, such as: \"Dermott O'Doud\", \"Planxty Miss Burke\", and \"The Snowy-Breasted Pearl\".<ref>Bunting, Edward: ''A General Collection of the Ancient Irish Music'' (Dublin: W. Power & Co., 1796), p. 17.</ref>\n\nA comprehensive edition of Carolan's Songs & Airs containing new arrangements for harp of all 214 airs, along with an additional 12 airs from the Appendix of the 2001 edition<ref>O'Sullivan, Donal: ''Carolan'' (as above), p. 334 ff.</ref> was published by Caitr\u00edona Rowsome in 2011.<ref name=\":0\">Rowsome, Caitr\u00edona: ''The Complete Carolan Songs & Airs'' (Dublin: Waltons Publishing, 2011), {{ISBN|9781857202182}}.</ref> This book includes an instance of each of Carolan's undisputed surviving lyrics and metrically sets the lyrics note-for-note to the sheet music airs. Each of the 226 harp settings in this book are played by the author on a neo-Irish harp (book and 4-CD set). This is the first time that all of Carolan's lyrics have been set to the airs and has been welcomed as \"a task that has needed doing for many years\".<ref>''An P\u00edobaire'' 9 (2013) 1 (Feabhra / February).</ref> The 4-CD recording is of harp music without vocals, but the book includes the sheet music for interested singers. The book also includes an English interpretation for each of Carolan's 72 Irish song lyrics. Five of these interpretations take the form of new English lyrics set metrically to the sheet music of 'Hewlett', 'Colonel John Irwin', 'John O'Connor', 'Kean O'Hara (3rd Air)' and 'Sheebeg and Sheemore'.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Performances==\nSince 1967, when Se\u00e1n O\u2019Riada and the Ceolt\u00f3ir\u00ed Chualann released ''Carolan\u2019s Concerto'' and 2 other Carolan compositions,<ref>O\u2019Riada, Se\u00e1n ''Ceol Na nUasal'' (Gael Linn records, Ireland, 1967)</ref> there have been hundreds of recordings of Carolan songs released by dozens of artists. Many of these recordings are by such well-known performers as [[The Chieftains]], [[Planxty]], Patrick Ball, and Joemy Wilson, others by less well known artists. Occasionally, an artist who is popular in another area will record a single Carolan song for variety, such as Steeleye Span's ''Sheebeg and Sheemore'', [[John Renbourn]]'s ''[[Lament for Owen Roe O'Neill]]'', [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]]'s ''Morgan Mawgan'' [sic], Stefan Grossman's ''Blind Mary'', John Williams' ''Mrs. Maxwell'', and many others. Several popular collections by multiple artists have also been issued, including ''The Music of O\u2019Carolan'' (1993), ''Deluxe Anthology of Carolan'' (1995), ''Celtic Treasure'' (1996), and ''Celtic Treasure II'' (2001). The sheer quantity of these recordings has greatly expanded the number of Carolan pieces known to the public, but the performers do tend to come back to certain songs again and again. Among the most frequently recorded pieces are the following:\n\n''Carolan\u2019s Concerto'' (at least 35), ''Blind Mary'' (at least 23), ''[[S\u00ed Bheag, S\u00ed Mh\u00f3r|Sheebeg and Sheemore]]'' (at least 22), ''Planxty George Brabazon'' (at least 21), ''Planxty Col. Irwin'' (at least 19), ''Fanny Power'' (at least 19), ''Eleanor Plunkett'' (at least 18), ''Carolan\u2019s Farewell to Music'' (at least 18), ''Carolan\u2019s Draught'' (at least 17), ''Hewlett'' (at least 16), ''The Princess Royal'' (at least 16), and ''Stafford's Receipt'' (at least 16). In addition, innumerable musicians have performed many of Carolan's tunes learned from such books as ''The Fiddler's Fakebook'',<ref>Brody, David ''[[The Fiddler's Fakebook]]'' (New York: Oak Publications, 1983).</ref> which contains some of the above tunes plus ''Morgan Magan'' and ''Planxty Drury''. Also, ''O'Neill\u2019s Music of Ireland'' (1903)<ref>http://trillian.mit.edu/~jc/music/book/oneills/</ref> is still in print and contains over 60 of Carolan's tunes, of which far too many to list have made their way into the repertoire of musicians around the world.\n\nIn addition, ''Carolan's Concerto'' has been used as a neutral slow march by the [[Foot Guards]] of the [[British Army]] during the ceremony of [[Trooping the Colour]]. Also, some of Carolan's compositions have appeared in the role-playing game ''[[Fate (video game)|FATE]]''.\n\nCarolan's music has frequently been adapted for fingerstyle guitar (primarily steel string acoustic), often by altering the tuning from standard (EADGBE) to DADGBE (drop D), DADGAD, and CGDGAD, among others. This allows strings to ring out and results in a more harp-like sound. Duck Baker has recorded many Carolan songs in drop D tuning. El McMeen performs almost exclusively in CGDGAD, and has recorded many Carolan songs.\n\n==Compositions==\nThe complete list of the 214 Carolan compositions identified by Donal O'Sullivan (see References) are, in alphabetical order, as follows:\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n*All Alive\n*Baptist Johnston\n*Betty MacNeill\n*Betty O'Brien\n*Blind Mary\n*Brian Maguire\n*Bridget Cruise, 1st Air\n*Bridget Cruise, 2nd Air\n*Bridget Cruise, 3rd Air\n*Bridget Cruise, 4th Air\n*Bumper Squire Jones\n*Captain Higgins\n*Captain Magan\n*Captain O'Kane\n*Captain O'Neill, (no. 214)\n*Captain Sudley (Carolan's Dowry)\n*Carolan's Cap\n*Carolan's Cottage\n*Carolan's Cup\n*Carolan's Draught\n*Carolan's Dream\n*Carolan's Farewell to Music\n*Carolan's Frolic\n*Carolan's Maggot\n*Carolan's Quarrel with the Landlady\n*Carolan's Ramble to Cashel\n*[[Carolan's Welcome]], (no. 171)\n*Catherine Martin\n*Catherine O'More\n*Charles O'Conor\n*The Clergy's Lamentation\n*Colonel Irwin\n*Colonel Manus O'Donnell\n*Colonel O'Hara\n*Conor O'Reilly\n*Constantine Maguire\n*Counsellor Dillon\n*Cremonea\n*Daniel Kelly\n*The Dark, Plaintive Youth\n*David Power\n*Denis O'Conor, 1st Air\n*Denis O'Conor, 2nd Air\n*Dolly MacDonough (The Morning Star)\n*Donal O'Brien\n*Dr. John Hart\n*Dr. John Stafford (Stafford's Receipt)\n*Dr. MacMahon, Bishop of Clogher\n*Dr. Delany\n*Dr. John Hart, Bishop of Achonry\n*Dr. O'Connor\n*Edmond MacDermott Roe\n*Edward Corcoran\n*Edward Dodwell\n*Eleanor Plunkett\n*The Elevation\n*Elizabeth MacDermott Roe\n*Elizabeth Nugent\n*The Fairy Queen\n*Fanny Dillon\n*Fanny Power\n*Father Brian MacDermott Roe\n*Frank Palmer\n*General Wynne\n*George Brabazon, 1st Air\n*(\"Planxty\") George Brabazon, 2nd Air\n*George Reynolds\n*Gerald Dillon\n*Grace Nugent\n*Henry MacDermott Roe, 1st Air\n*Henry MacDermott Roe, 2nd Air\n*Henry MacDermott Roe, 3rd Air\n*The Honourable Thomas Burke\n*Hugh Kelly\n*Hugh O'Donnell\n*Isabella Burke\n*James Betagh\n*James Crofton\n*James Daly\n*James Plunkett\n*John Drury, 1st Air\n*John Drury, 2nd Air\n*John Jameson\n*John Jones\n*John Kelly\n*John MacDermott\n*John Moore\n*John Nugent\n*John O'Connor\n*John O'Reilly, 1st Air\n*John O'Reilly, 2nd Air\n*John Peyton\n*Katherine O'More (The Hawk of the Erne)\n*Kean O'Hara, 1st Air (O'Hara's Cup)\n*Kean O'Hara, 2nd Air\n*Kean O'Hara, 3rd Air\n*Kitty Magennis\n*Lady Athenry\n*Lady Blaney\n*Lady Dillon\n*Lady Gethin\n*Lady Laetitia Burke\n*Lady St. John\n*Lady Wrixon\n*Lament for Charles MacCabe\n*Lament for Owen O'Rourke\n*[[Lament for Owen Roe O'Neill]]\n*Lament for Sir Ulick Burke\n*Lament for Terence MacDonough\n*The Landlady\n*Loftus Jones\n*Lord Dillon\n*Lord Galway's Lamentation\n*Lord Inchiquin\n*Lord Louth\n*Lord Massereene\n*Lord Mayo\n*Luke Dillon\n*Mabel Kelly\n*Major Shanly\n*Margaret Malone\n*Mary O'Neill\n*Maurice O'Connor, 1st Air\n*Maurice O'Connor, 2nd Air\n*Maurice O'Connor, 3rd Air\n*Mervyn Pratt\n*Michael O'Connor, 1st Air\n*Michael O'Connor, 2nd Air\n*Miss Crofton\n*Miss Fetherston (Carolan's Devotion)\n*Miss Goulding\n*[[The Saucy Arethusa|Miss MacDermott]] ([[Prince of Coolavin#The Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]])\n*Miss MacMurray\n*Miss Murphy\n*Miss Noble\n*Morgan Magan\n*Mr. Malone\n*Mr. O'Connor\n*Mr. Waller\n*Mrs. Anne MacDermott Roe\n*Mrs. Bermingham, 1st Air\n*Mrs. Bermingham, 2nd Air\n*Mrs. Cole\n*Mrs. Costello\n*Mrs. Crofton\n*Mrs. Delany\n*Mrs. Edwards\n*Mrs. Fallon\n*Mrs. Farrell\n*Mrs. Garvey, 1st Air\n*Mrs. Garvey, 2nd Air\n*Mrs. Harwood\n*Mrs. Judge\n*Mrs. Keel\n*Mrs. MacDermott Roe\n*Mrs. Maxwell, 1st Air\n*Mrs. Maxwell, 2nd Air\n*Mrs. Nugent\n*Mrs. O'Connor\n*Mrs. O'Conor\n*Mrs. O'Neill of Carlane\n*Mrs. O'Neill (Carolan's Favourite)\n*Mrs. O'Rourke\n*Mrs. Power (Carolan's Concerto)\n*Mrs. Sterling\n*Mrs. Waller\n*Nancy Cooper, 1st Air\n*Nancy Cooper, 2nd Air\n*O'Flinn\n*O'Reilly of Athcarne\n*The O'Rourkes' Feast\n*Ode to Whiskey\n*One Bottle More\n*Owen O'Rourke\n*Patrick Kelly\n*Peggy Morton\n*Planxty Browne, (no. 180)\n*Planxty Burke\n*Planxty Crilly\n*Planxty Drew\n*Planxty Hewlett\n*Planxty John Irwin\n*Planxty Kelly\n*Planxty O'Rourke, 1st Air\n*Planxty O'Rourke, 2nd Air\n*Planxty Plunkett\n*Planxty Sweeney\n*Planxty Wilkinson\n*Richard Cusack\n*Robert Hawkes\n*Robert Jordan\n*The Seas are Deep\n*Separation of Soul and Body\n*[[S\u00ed Bheag, S\u00ed Mh\u00f3r|Sheebeg and Sheemore]]\n*Sir Arthur Shaen\n*Sir Charles Coote\n*Sir Edward Crofton\n*Sir Festus Burke\n*Sir Ulick Burke\n*Squire Parsons\n*[[William Wood (Mintmaster)|Squire Wood]]'s Lamentation on the Refusal of his Halfpence\n*Susanna Kelly\n*Thomas Burke\n*Thomas Judge (Carolan's Frolic)\n*Tobias Peyton\n*The Two William Davises\n*(unnamed) - 8 pieces, (nos. 172-179)\n*Variations on the Scottish Air<BR>\"[[Cock Up Your Beaver]]\"\n*Variations on the Scottish Air<BR>\"When She Cam Ben\"\n*William Eccles\n*William Ward\n{{div col end}}\n\nMany of these pieces have alternative titles, as fully documented by Donal O'Sullivan. O'Sullivan's preferred titles are the ones generally accepted as standard, though quite a few of these titles were devised by O'Sullivan himself after exhaustive research into the identities of the patrons for whom each song was written.\n\nAdditionally, a manuscript compiled in Scotland in 1816 by the MacLean-Clephane sisters was discovered in 1983 and includes at least five other pieces credited to Carolan and other annotated pieces that were \"improved by Carolan\" or \"consistent with Carolan's writing to warrant consideration\". These airs are included in the Appendix of the 2001 edition of ''Carolan: The Life Times and Music of an Irish Harper'' along with detailed research notes. These pieces came to light a decade after the death of Donal O'Sullivan in 1973, so he never had an opportunity to subject them to the same analysis that he used on the original 214 airs that he originally compiled in 1958. However, to date, no one has disputed the attributions presented in this manuscript. Newly composed harp arrangements for each of these and all the other airs (as well as new Carolan repertoire numbers 215 to 226 for each of the MacLean-Clephane tunes) are included in ''The Complete Carolan Songs & Airs'' by Caitr\u00edona Rowsome.<ref>Rowsome, Caitr\u00edona (as above), pp. 238-251.</ref> The five pieces that are said to be composed by Carolan rather than simply \"improved\" are:\n*\"Athlone\" (215)\n*\"Banks of the Shannon\" (216)\n*\"Farewell to Lough Neaghe\" (219)\n*\"Irish Galloway Tom\" (220)\n*\"The Lamentation of Ireland\" (221)\n\n==Other==\n\n\n*O'Carolan Road in the Tenters area of [[The Liberties|Dublin 8]] is named in his honour.\n*Carolan Road and \"Carolan Corner\" shop are named in his honour in the [[Ballynafeigh]] area of south [[Belfast]].\n*The [[meteorite]] [[Impact_crater|crater]] Carolan on [[Mercury_(planet)|Mercury]] was named in his honour in 2015.<ref>Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature, IAU, [https://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/15321 Map of crater Carolan]</ref>\n*Polish bands: [[2 plus 1]] in 1979 and [[Myslovitz]] in 1996 recorded songs entitled \"Peggy Brown\", said to be a translation of an obscure O'Carolan lyric by Polish lyricist Ernest Bryll, with different tunes and arrangements: folk and alternative rock, respectively. Neither of these tunes use an O'Carolan composition. Both songs were very popular in Poland.\n*O'Carolan is depicted on the \u00a350 note, [[Series B Banknotes (Ireland)|Series B Banknote]] of Ireland.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people on the postage stamps of Ireland]]\n*[[Music of Ireland]]\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Donal O'Sullivan: ''Carolan: The Life Times and Music of an Irish Harper'', 2 volumes (London: Routledge and Kegan Paul, 1958); new edition in 1 volume: Cork: Ossian Publications, 2001; {{ISBN|1-900428-76-8}} (hardback), 1-900428-71-7 (paperback).\n*Donal O'Sullivan: ''Songs of the Irish'' (Dublin: Brown & Nolan, 1960).\n*The Complete Works of O'Carolan: Irish Harper & Composer (1670-1738), published by Ossian Publications, Ireland, 1984, {{ISBN|0 946005 16 8}}.\n*Art Edelstein: \"Fair Melodies: Turlough Carolan, An Irish Harper\" (East Calais, Vermont: Noble Stone Press, 2001), {{ISBN|978-0971169302}}.\n*The first commercial recording of Carolan's complete works was ''The Complete Works of Turlough O\u2019Carolan (1670-1738)'' [2006, 8-cd set, Trigon, 214 tracks] arranged and performed by Irish pianist [[J.J. Sheridan]].\n*The first commercial recording on an Irish harp of the ''Complete Carolan: Songs & Airs'' has been recorded and arranged by Irish harpist Caitr\u00edona Rowsome (Dublin: Waltons Publishing, 2011). This is packaged with a 254-page book of sheet music, with the same name.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.myspace.com/carolansdream Recording of O'Carolan's tunes by \"Garlic Bread\" and French baroque ensemble \"Le concert de l'Hostel Dieu\" ]\n*[http://www.docsworkshop.co.uk The Complete Carolan: many of Carolan's tunes, arranged in open tunings for the guitar]\n*[http://www.earlygaelicharp.info/carolan O'Carolan: pages on his life, his tunes, his songs, his harp, with audio files]\n*[[Nikolaus Newerkla]], Playford Dances & Carolan Tunes, Moeck-Verlag Celle, 2007, tunes arranged for recorders and basso continuo, The Music of an Irish Harper, B\u00e4renreiter-Verlag Kassel, 2012, tunes arranged for recorders and harpsichord (piano).\n*[http://www.contemplator.com/carolan/ Turlough O'Carolan: Irish Harper]\n*[http://english.glendale.cc.ca.us/carolan.html Turlough O'Carolan 1670-1738]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060218200307/http://www.oldmusicproject.com/OCC.html Complete Works of Turlough O'Carolan] (musical scores)\n*[http://www.earlygaelicharp.info/sources/carolan.htm Carolan Fragment: one of the early sources described]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070518155910/http://www.calumcille.com/modhan/iuchraichean/priomh.html Gaelic harp keys] (web article with suggested original keys of all O'Carolan's tunes)\n*{{CathEncy|wstitle=Torlogh O'Carolan}}\n*The first complete recording of the Complete Works of O'Carolan has been recorded and arranged by Irish pianist, J.J. Sheridan\n*{{IMSLP|id=Carolan, Turlough}}\n*The first complete recording on an Irish Harp of the Complete Carolan: Songs & Airs has been recorded and arranged by Irish Harpist, Caitr\u00edona Rowsome, 2011\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:OCarolan, Turlough}}\n[[Category:1670 births]]\n[[Category:1738 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:18th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:Irish Baroque composers]]\n[[Category:Composers for harp]]\n[[Category:Irish composers]]\n[[Category:Irish harpists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from County Meath]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turlough_O%27Carolan"}
{"title_page": "Turkmenistan\u2013Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan\u2013India Pipeline", "text_new": "{{Short description|Infrastructure project in Asia}}{{Infobox pipeline\n| name        = Turkmenistan\u2013Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan\u2013India Pipeline (TAPI)\n| type        = [[Natural gas]]\n| map         =\n| map_caption = Location of Trans-Indian Pipeline\n| country     = {{flagicon|Turkmenistan}} [[Turkmenistan]] <br/>{{flagicon|Afghanistan}} [[Afghanistan]] <br/>{{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]] <br/>{{flagicon|India}} [[India]]\n| coordinates =\n| photo       = File:TAPI-EIA.png\n| caption     = A map of the TAPI route\n| partners    = [[T\u00fcrkmengaz]]\n| length_km   = 1814\n| discharge   = {{convert|33|e9m3/a|abbr=off}}\n| direction   = North\u2013South\n| start       = [[Galkynysh gas field]], [[Turkmenistan]]\n| finish      = [[Fazilka]], [[India]]\n| est         = \n| through     = [[Herat]]<br/>[[Kandahar]]<br/>[[Quetta]]<br/>[[Multan]]\n| par         = [[Kandahar\u2013Herat Highway]]\n}}\nThe '''Turkmenistan\u2013Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan\u2013India Pipeline''' ('''TAPI'''), also known as '''Trans-Afghanistan Pipeline''', is a [[natural gas]] [[pipeline transport|pipeline]] being developed by the Galkynysh \u2013 TAPI Pipeline Company Limited <ref name=nebit>{{cite web| url=http://www.oilgas.gov.tm/en/blog/124/the-office-of-consortium-galkynysh--tapi-pipeline-company-limited-will-be-opened-in-dubai|title=The office of consortium \"Galkynysh \u2013 TAPI Pipeline Company Limited\" will be opened in Dubai|date=18 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=hron>{{cite web | title=TAPI CJSC office to appear in Dubai|url=https://en.hronikatm.com/2016/01/tapi-cjsc-office-to-appear-in-dubai/|date=20 January 2016}}</ref> with participation of the [[Asian Development Bank]].<ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\"/> The pipeline will transport natural gas from the [[Galkynysh Gas Field]] in [[Turkmenistan]] through [[Afghanistan]] into [[Pakistan]] and then to [[India]].<ref name=\"Is Turkmenistan's gas line a pipe dream?\">\n{{cite news\n |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-32981469\n |title= Is Turkmenistan's gas line a pipe dream?\n |editor= Abdujalil Abdurasulov\n |date= 2015-07-16\n |publisher= BBC\n |accessdate=2015-07-17}}\n</ref> Construction on the project started in Turkmenistan on 13 December 2015,<ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\">{{cite news | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/turkmenistan-gas-pipeline-idUKKBN0TW05Q20151213 | title = Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India | agency = Reuters | date = 13 December 2015 | accessdate = 13 December 2015}}</ref>; work on the Afghan section began in February 2018, and work on the Pakistani section was planned to commence in December 2018.<ref name=\"Pakistan to start work on TAPI by December\">{{cite news | url = https://pakobserver.net/pakistan-to-start-work-on-tapi-by-december/ | title = Pakistan to start work on TAPI by December | agency = Pakistan Observer | date = 10 October 2018 | accessdate = 10 October 2018}}</ref>\nThe abbreviation TAPI comes from the first letters of those countries. Proponents of the project see it as a modern continuation of the [[Silk Road]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = TAPI project will be the new Silk Route, says Deora\n| first = Sujay | last = Mehdudia\n| url = http://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/article946191.ece\n| newspaper = [[The Hindu]]\n| date  = 2010-12-11\n| accessdate = 2011-06-28\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = U.S. brings Silk Road to India\n| first = M. K. | last= Bhadrakumar\n| url = http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/article972541.ece\n| newspaper = The Hindu\n| publisher = Kasturi & Sons Ltd. / The Hindu Group\n| date  = 2010-12-24\n| accessdate = 2011-06-28\n}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe roots of this project lie in the involvement of international oil companies in [[Kazakhstan]] and Turkmenistan beginning of 1990s.  As [[Russia]], who controlled all export pipelines of these countries, consistently refusing to allow the use of its pipeline network, these companies needed an independent export route avoiding both [[Iran]] and Russia.<ref>{{cite book |last1= Brisard |first1= Jean-Charles |first2= Guillaume |last2= Dasquie |title= Forbidden Truth \u2013 U.S. Taliban Secret Oil Diplomacy and the Failed Hunt for bin Laden |publisher= [[Nation Books]] |year= 2002 |isbn= 978-1-56025-414-0 |pages= ? |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/forbiddentruthus00bris }}</ref><ref name=LeVine>{{cite book | last=LeVine | first=Steve | title=The Oil and the Glory: The Pursuit of Empire and Fortune on the Caspian Sea | url=https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_w0b1 | url-access=registration | publisher=Random House | year = 2007 | isbn = 9781588366467 | page=[https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_w0b1/page/291 291]}}</ref>\n\nThe original project started on 15 March 1995 when an inaugural memorandum of understanding between the governments of Turkmenistan and Pakistan for a pipeline project was signed. This project was promoted by [[Argentina|Argentinian]] company [[Bridas Corporation]]. The U.S. company [[Unocal]], in conjunction with the [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] oil company Delta, promoted an alternative project without Bridas' involvement. On 21 October 1995, these two companies signed a separate agreement with Turkmenistan's president [[Saparmurat Niyazov]]. In August 1996, the [[CentGas|Central Asia Gas Pipeline, Ltd. (CentGas)]] [[consortium]] for construction of a pipeline, led by Unocal, was formed. On 27 October 1997, CentGas was incorporated in formal signing ceremonies in [[Ashgabat]], Turkmenistan, by several international oil companies along with the [[Government of Turkmenistan]].<ref name=eiu>{{cite book | title = Country Report: Turkmenistan | publisher = [[Economist Intelligence Unit]] | year = 1998 | page = 24}}</ref>\n\nSince the pipeline was to pass through Afghanistan, it was necessary to work with the Taliban. The U.S. ambassador to Pakistan, [[Robert B. Oakley|Robert Oakley]], moved into CentGas in 1997. In January 1998, the [[Taliban]], selecting CentGas over Argentinian competitor [[Bridas Corporation]], signed an agreement that allowed the proposed project to proceed. In June 1998, Russian [[Gazprom]] relinquished its 10% stake in the project. On 7 August 1998, [[1998 United States embassy bombings|American embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam were bombed]]. The United States alleged that [[Osama bin Laden]] was behind those attacks, and all pipeline negotiations halted, as the Taliban's then leader, [[Mohammed Omar|Mullah Omar]], announced that bin Laden had the Taliban's support. Unocal withdrew from the consortium on 8 December 1998, and soon after closed its offices in Afghanistan and Pakistan.<ref name=croissant>\n{{cite book\n | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3lyCPmitLkQC&pg=PA87\n | title = Oil and Geopolitics in the Caspian Sea Region\n | first1 = Michael P. | last1 = Croissant\n | first2 = B\u00fclent | last2 = Aras\n | publisher = [[Greenwood Publishing Group]]\n | page = 87\n | year = 1999\n | isbn = 9780275963958\n}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[September 11 attacks]] some people came to believe that a possible motivation for the attacks included justifying the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|invasions of Afghanistan]] as well as [[geostrategy|geostrategic]] interests such as the Trans-Afghanistan Pipeline project.<ref name=\"Knight\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1215/0094033X-2007-024 |title=Outrageous Conspiracy Theories: Popular and Official Responses to 9/11 in Germany and the United States |year=2008 |last1=Knight |first1=Peter |journal=New German Critique |volume=35 |pages=165\u201393{{clarify|date=October 2012}}}}</ref>  The new deal on the pipeline was signed on 27 December 2002 by the leaders of Turkmenistan, Afghanistan and Pakistan.<ref name=bbc1>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2608713.stm\n | title = Central Asia pipeline deal signed\n | first = Ian | last = McWilliam\n | agency= [[BBC]]\n | date = 2002-12-27\n | accessdate = 2008-05-18}}\n</ref> In 2005, the Asian Development Bank submitted the final version of a feasibility study designed by British company [[Penspen]]. The project has drawn strong US support as it would allow the Central Asian republics to export energy to Western markets \"without relying on Russian routes\". Then-US Ambassador to Turkmenistan [[Tracey Ann Jacobson]] noted, \"We are seriously looking at the project, and it is quite possible that American companies will join it\".<ref name=newint>\n{{cite web\n |url= http://www.newint.org/features/2009/10/01/blowback-extended-version/\n |title=Our Terrorists\n |author= [[Nafeez Mosaddeq Ahmed]]\n |date=October 2009\n |work=\n |publisher=[[New Internationalist]]\n |accessdate=2009-12-07}}\n</ref> Due to increasing instability, the project has essentially stalled; construction of the Turkmen part was supposed to start in 2006, but the overall feasibility is questionable since the southern part of the Afghan section runs through territory which continues to be under ''[[de facto]]'' Taliban control.<ref name=newint/>\n\nOn 24 April 2008, Pakistan, India and Afghanistan signed a framework agreement to buy natural gas from Turkmenistan.<ref name=upstream1>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.upstreamonline.com/live/article153168.ece\n | title = Trio sign up for Turkmen gas\n | newspaper = [[Upstream (newspaper)|Upstream Online]]\n | publisher = NHST Media Group\n | date = 2008-04-25\n | accessdate = 2008-05-18}}\n</ref> The intergovernmental agreement on the pipeline was signed on 11 December 2010 in [[Ashgabat]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n |url        = http://classic.cnbc.com/id/40617007\n |title      = Agreement sought on Afghan-Pakistan gas pipeline\n |agency     = [[Associated Press]]\n |publisher  = CNBC\n |date       = 2010-12-11\n |accessdate = 2010-12-11\n}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}\n</ref> However, in April 2012, India and Afghanistan have failed to agree on transit fee for gas passing through Afghan territory. Consequently, Islamabad and New Delhi too could not agree on the transit fee for the segment of the pipeline passing through Pakistan, which has linked its fee structure to any India-Afghanistan agreement.<ref>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.satrapia.com/news/article/tapi-india-afghanistan-fail-to-agree-on-transit-fee/\n | title = TAPI: India, Afghanistan Fail to Agree on Transit Fee\n | newspaper = The Gazette of Central Asia\n | publisher = Satrapia\n | date = 2012-04-18\n | accessdate = 2012-05-06}}\n</ref> On 16 May 2012, the [[National Assembly of Afghanistan|Afghan Parliament]], approved the agreement on a gas pipeline and the day after, the Indian Cabinet allowed state-run gas-firm [[GAIL]] to sign the Gas Sale and Purchase Agreement (GSPA) with [[T\u00fcrkmengaz]], Turkmenistan's national oil company.<ref>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.satrapia.com/news/article/india-authorizes-to-sign-tapi-gas-sales-and-purchase-pact/\n | title = India Authorizes to Sign TAPI Gas Sales and Purchase Pact\n | newspaper = The Gazette of Central Asia\n | publisher = Satrapia\n | date = 2012-05-18\n | accessdate = 2012-05-18}}\n</ref>\n\nConstruction on the project started in Turkmenistan on 13 December 2015 <ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\"/> and was completed by mid-2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2019/07/08/508207/pakistan-turkmenistan-to-discuss-tapi-gas-pipeline-groundbreaking-in-august|title=Pakistan and Turkmenistan to discuss TAPI gas pipeline|date=8 July 2019 |website=voanews.com|accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref> Construction on the Afghan side started on February 24, 2018, while construction on the Pakistan side is planned to start by October 2019 and be completed in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2019/07/08/508207/pakistan-turkmenistan-to-discuss-tapi-gas-pipeline-groundbreaking-in-august|title=Pakistan and Turkmenistan to discuss TAPI gas pipeline|date=8 July 2019 |website=voanews.com|accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref> The Taliban have vowed to cooperate and not disrupt the project in areas they control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/taliban-to-protect-tapi-gas-pipeline-project/4268767.html|title=Taliban Vows to Protect TAPI Gas Pipeline Project|first=Hasib Danish|last=Alikozai|date=|website=voanews.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/02/tapi-moves-into-afghanistan-taliban-promise-to-protect-the-project/|title=TAPI Moves Into Afghanistan, Taliban Promise to Protect the Project|first=Catherine Putz, The|last=Diplomat|date=|website=thediplomat.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Technical features==\nThe pipeline will be {{convert|1420|mm|in}} in diameter with a working pressure of {{convert|100|atm}}.<ref name=alex2>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.gasandoil.com/goc/news/ntc64919.htm\n | title = Gas pipeline project Turkmenistan-Afghanistan-Pakistan-India approved\n | publisher = Alexander's Gas & Oil Connections\n | date = 2006-11-21\n | accessdate = 2008-05-18}}\n</ref>  The capacity will be {{convert|33|e9m3|abbr=off}} of natural gas per year of which {{convert|5|e9m3|abbr=off}} will be provided to Afghanistan and {{convert|14|e9m3|abbr=off}} to each Pakistan and India.<ref name=diplomat031215>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://thediplomat.com/2015/12/a-fillip-for-the-tapi-pipeline/\n | title = A Fillip for the TAPI Pipeline\n | newspaper = The Diplomat\n | first =  Micha'el | last = Tanchum\n | date = 2015-12-03\n | accessdate = 2015-12-13}}\n</ref>  Six compressor stations would be constructed along the pipeline.<ref name=alex2/> The pipeline was intended to be operational by 2019.<ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\"/>\n\nOriginally, the cost of the pipeline project was reportedly estimated at US$7.6&nbsp;billion, but a more recent estimate was $10&nbsp;billion.<ref name=upi031214>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.upi.com/Business_News/Energy-Resources/2014/12/03/Kazakhstan-keen-on-TAPI-gas-pipeline/1741417604335/\n | title = Kazakhstan keen on TAPI gas pipeline\n | first = Daniel J. | last=Graeber\n | agency = [[United Press International|UPI]]\n | date = 2014-12-03\n | accessdate = 2015-02-25}}\n</ref>  The leading partner of the project is [[T\u00fcrkmengaz]].<ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\"/>\n\n==Route==\nThe {{convert|1814|km|adj=on}} pipeline will run from gas fields in Turkmenistan through Afghanistan and Pakistan to India. It start from the [[Galkynysh gas field]].<ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\"/> In Afghanistan, TAPI pipeline will be constructed alongside the [[Kandahar\u2013Herat Highway]] in western Afghanistan, and then via [[Quetta]] and [[Multan]] in Pakistan.<ref name=dailytimes220203>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_22-2-2003_pg1_5\n | title = Alternate route for pipeline to be discussed today\n | first1 = Khalid | last1 = Mustafa\n | newspaper = [[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]]\n | date = 2003-02-22\n | accessdate = 2012-01-27}}\n</ref> The final destination of the pipeline will be the Indian town of [[Fazilka]], near the border between Pakistan and India.<ref name=alex2/>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Afghanistan Oil Pipeline]]\n* [[Transport in Afghanistan]]\n* [[Baku-Tbilisi-Ceyhan pipeline]] (BTC)\n* [[Enron]]'s [[Dabhol Power Company]]\n* [[Trans-Caspian Gas Pipeline]]\n* [[South Caucasus Pipeline]]\n* [[CentGas]]\n* [[Port of Chabahar]]\n* [[Ashgabat agreement]]\n{{col div end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turkmenistan-Afghanistan-Pakistan-India Pipeline}}\n[[Category:Natural gas pipelines in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Natural gas pipelines in Turkmenistan]]\n[[Category:Natural gas pipelines in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Natural gas pipelines in India]]\n[[Category:Proposed pipelines in Asia]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013India relations]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013Turkmenistan relations]]\n[[Category:India\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n[[Category:Pakistan\u2013Turkmenistan relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Infrastructure project in Asia}}{{Infobox pipeline\n| name        = Turkmenistan\u2013Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan\u2013India Pipeline (TAPI)\n| type        = [[Natural gas]]\n| map         =\n| map_caption = Location of Trans-Indian Pipeline\n| country     = {{flagicon|Turkmenistan}} [[Turkmenistan]] <br/>{{flagicon|Afghanistan}} [[Afghanistan]] <br/>{{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]] <br/>{{flagicon|India}} [[India]]\n| coordinates =\n| photo       = File:TAPI-EIA.png\n| caption     = A map of the TAPI route\n| partners    = [[T\u00fcrkmengaz]]\n| length_km   = 1814\n| discharge   = {{convert|33|e9m3/a|abbr=off}}\n| direction   = North\u2013South\n| start       = [[Galkynysh gas field]], [[Turkmenistan]]\n| finish      = [[Fazilka]], [[India]]\n| est         = \n| through     = [[Herat]]<br/>[[Kandahar]]<br/>[[Quetta]]<br/>[[Multan]]\n| par         = [[Kandahar\u2013Herat Highway]]\n}}\nThe '''Turkmenistan\u2013Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan\u2013India Pipeline''' ('''TAPI'''), also known as '''Trans-Afghanistan Pipeline''', is a [[natural gas]] [[pipeline transport|pipeline]] being developed by the Galkynysh \u2013 TAPI Pipeline Company Limited <ref name=nebit>{{cite web| url=http://www.oilgas.gov.tm/en/blog/124/the-office-of-consortium-galkynysh--tapi-pipeline-company-limited-will-be-opened-in-dubai|title=The office of consortium \"Galkynysh \u2013 TAPI Pipeline Company Limited\" will be opened in Dubai|date=18 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=hron>{{cite web | title=TAPI CJSC office to appear in Dubai|url=https://en.hronikatm.com/2016/01/tapi-cjsc-office-to-appear-in-dubai/|date=20 January 2016}}</ref> with participation of the [[Asian Development Bank]].<ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\"/> The pipeline will transport natural gas from the [[Galkynysh Gas Field]] in [[Turkmenistan]] through [[Afghanistan]] into [[Pakistan]] and then to [[India]].<ref name=\"Is Turkmenistan's gas line a pipe dream?\">\n{{cite news\n |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-32981469\n |title= Is Turkmenistan's gas line a pipe dream?\n |editor= Abdujalil Abdurasulov\n |date= 2015-07-16\n |publisher= BBC\n |accessdate=2015-07-17}}\n</ref> Construction on the project started in Turkmenistan on 13 December 2015,<ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\">{{cite news | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/turkmenistan-gas-pipeline-idUKKBN0TW05Q20151213 | title = Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India | agency = Reuters | date = 13 December 2015 | accessdate = 13 December 2015}}</ref>; work on the Afghan section began in February 2018, and work on the Pakistani section was planned to commence in December 2018.<ref name=\"Pakistan to start work on TAPI by December\">{{cite news | url = https://pakobserver.net/pakistan-to-start-work-on-tapi-by-december/ | title = Pakistan to start work on TAPI by December | agency = Pakistan Observer | date = 10 October 2018 | accessdate = 10 October 2018}}</ref>\nThe abbreviation TAPI comes from the first letters of those countries. Proponents of the project see it as a modern continuation of the [[Silk Road]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = TAPI project will be the new Silk Route, says Deora\n| first = Sujay | last = Mehdudia\n| url = http://www.thehindu.com/business/Economy/article946191.ece\n| newspaper = [[The Hindu]]\n| date  = 2010-12-11\n| accessdate = 2011-06-28\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = U.S. brings Silk Road to India\n| first = M. K. | last= Bhadrakumar\n| url = http://www.thehindu.com/opinion/lead/article972541.ece\n| newspaper = The Hindu\n| publisher = Kasturi & Sons Ltd. / The Hindu Group\n| date  = 2010-12-24\n| accessdate = 2011-06-28\n}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe roots of this project lie in the involvement of international oil companies in [[Kazakhstan]] and Turkmenistan beginning of 1990s.  As [[Russia]], who controlled all export pipelines of these countries, consistently refusing to allow the use of its pipeline network, these companies needed an independent export route avoiding both [[Iran]] and Russia.<ref>{{cite book |last1= Brisard |first1= Jean-Charles |first2= Guillaume |last2= Dasquie |title= Forbidden Truth \u2013 U.S. Taliban Secret Oil Diplomacy and the Failed Hunt for bin Laden |publisher= [[Nation Books]] |year= 2002 |isbn= 978-1-56025-414-0 |pages= ? |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/forbiddentruthus00bris }}</ref><ref name=LeVine>{{cite book | last=LeVine | first=Steve | title=The Oil and the Glory: The Pursuit of Empire and Fortune on the Caspian Sea | url=https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_w0b1 | url-access=registration | publisher=Random House | year = 2007 | isbn = 9781588366467 | page=[https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_w0b1/page/291 291]}}</ref>\n\nThe original project started on 15 March 1995 when an inaugural memorandum of understanding between the governments of Turkmenistan and Pakistan for a pipeline project was signed. This project was promoted by [[Argentina|Argentinian]] company [[Bridas Corporation]]. The U.S. company [[Unocal]], in conjunction with the [[Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] oil company Delta, promoted an alternative project without Bridas' involvement. On 21 October 1995, these two companies signed a separate agreement with Turkmenistan's president [[Saparmurat Niyazov]]. In August 1996, the [[CentGas|Central Asia Gas Pipeline, Ltd. (CentGas)]] [[consortium]] for construction of a pipeline, led by Unocal, was formed. On 27 October 1997, CentGas was incorporated in formal signing ceremonies in [[Ashgabat]], Turkmenistan, by several international oil companies along with the [[Government of Turkmenistan]].<ref name=eiu>{{cite book | title = Country Report: Turkmenistan | publisher = [[Economist Intelligence Unit]] | year = 1998 | page = 24}}</ref>\n\nSince the pipeline was to pass through Afghanistan, it was necessary to work with the Taliban. The U.S. ambassador to Pakistan, [[Robert B. Oakley|Robert Oakley]], moved into CentGas in 1997. In January 1998, the [[Taliban]], selecting CentGas over Argentinian competitor [[Bridas Corporation]], signed an agreement that allowed the proposed project to proceed. In June 1998, Russian [[Gazprom]] relinquished its 10% stake in the project. On 7 August 1998, [[1998 United States embassy bombings|American embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam were bombed]]. The United States alleged that [[Osama bin Laden]] was behind those attacks, and all pipeline negotiations halted, as the Taliban's then leader, [[Mohammed Omar|Mullah Omar]], announced that bin Laden had the Taliban's support. Unocal withdrew from the consortium on 8 December 1998, and soon after closed its offices in Afghanistan and Pakistan.<ref name=croissant>\n{{cite book\n | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3lyCPmitLkQC&pg=PA87\n | title = Oil and Geopolitics in the Caspian Sea Region\n | first1 = Michael P. | last1 = Croissant\n | first2 = B\u00fclent | last2 = Aras\n | publisher = [[Greenwood Publishing Group]]\n | page = 87\n | year = 1999\n | isbn = 9780275963958\n}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[September 11 attacks]] some people came to believe that a possible motivation for the attacks included justifying the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|invasions of Afghanistan]] as well as [[geostrategy|geostrategic]] interests such as the Trans-Afghanistan Pipeline project.<ref name=\"Knight\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1215/0094033X-2007-024 |title=Outrageous Conspiracy Theories: Popular and Official Responses to 9/11 in Germany and the United States |year=2008 |last1=Knight |first1=Peter |journal=New German Critique |volume=35 |pages=165\u201393{{clarify|date=October 2012}}}}</ref>  The new deal on the pipeline was signed on 27 December 2002 by the leaders of Turkmenistan, Afghanistan and Pakistan.<ref name=bbc1>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2608713.stm\n | title = Central Asia pipeline deal signed\n | first = Ian | last = McWilliam\n | agency= [[BBC]]\n | date = 2002-12-27\n | accessdate = 2008-05-18}}\n</ref> In 2005, the Asian Development Bank submitted the final version of a feasibility study designed by British company [[Penspen]]. The project has drawn strong US support as it would allow the Central Asian republics to export energy to Western markets \"without relying on Russian routes\". Then-US Ambassador to Turkmenistan [[Tracey Ann Jacobson]] noted, \"We are seriously looking at the project, and it is quite possible that American companies will join it\".<ref name=newint>\n{{cite web\n |url= http://www.newint.org/features/2009/10/01/blowback-extended-version/\n |title=Our Terrorists\n |author= [[Nafeez Mosaddeq Ahmed]]\n |date=October 2009\n |work=\n |publisher=[[New Internationalist]]\n |accessdate=2009-12-07}}\n</ref> Due to increasing instability, the project has essentially stalled; construction of the Turkmen part was supposed to start in 2006, but the overall feasibility is questionable since the southern part of the Afghan section runs through territory which continues to be under ''[[de facto]]'' Taliban control.<ref name=newint/>\n\nOn 24 April 2008, Pakistan, India and Afghanistan signed a framework agreement to buy natural gas from Turkmenistan.<ref name=upstream1>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.upstreamonline.com/live/article153168.ece\n | title = Trio sign up for Turkmen gas\n | newspaper = [[Upstream (newspaper)|Upstream Online]]\n | publisher = NHST Media Group\n | date = 2008-04-25\n | accessdate = 2008-05-18}}\n</ref> The intergovernmental agreement on the pipeline was signed on 11 December 2010 in [[Ashgabat]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n |url        = http://classic.cnbc.com/id/40617007\n |title      = Agreement sought on Afghan-Pakistan gas pipeline\n |agency     = [[Associated Press]]\n |publisher  = CNBC\n |date       = 2010-12-11\n |accessdate = 2010-12-11\n}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}\n</ref> However, in April 2012, India and Afghanistan have failed to agree on transit fee for gas passing through Afghan territory. Consequently, Islamabad and New Delhi too could not agree on the transit fee for the segment of the pipeline passing through Pakistan, which has linked its fee structure to any India-Afghanistan agreement.<ref>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.satrapia.com/news/article/tapi-india-afghanistan-fail-to-agree-on-transit-fee/\n | title = TAPI: India, Afghanistan Fail to Agree on Transit Fee\n | newspaper = The Gazette of Central Asia\n | publisher = Satrapia\n | date = 2012-04-18\n | accessdate = 2012-05-06}}\n</ref> On 16 May 2012, the [[National Assembly of Afghanistan|Afghan Parliament]], approved the agreement on a gas pipeline and the day after, the Indian Cabinet allowed state-run gas-firm [[GAIL]] to sign the Gas Sale and Purchase Agreement (GSPA) with [[T\u00fcrkmengaz]], Turkmenistan's national oil company.<ref>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.satrapia.com/news/article/india-authorizes-to-sign-tapi-gas-sales-and-purchase-pact/\n | title = India Authorizes to Sign TAPI Gas Sales and Purchase Pact\n | newspaper = The Gazette of Central Asia\n | publisher = Satrapia\n | date = 2012-05-18\n | accessdate = 2012-05-18}}\n</ref>\n\nConstruction on the project started in Turkmenistan on 13 December 2015 <ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\"/> and was completed by mid-2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2019/07/08/508207/pakistan-turkmenistan-to-discuss-tapi-gas-pipeline-groundbreaking-in-august|title=Pakistan and Turkmenistan to discuss TAPI gas pipeline|date=8 July 2019 |website=voanews.com|accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref>. Construction on the Afghan side started on February 24, 2018, while construction on the Pakistan side is planned to start by October 2019 and be completed in 2020<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brecorder.com/2019/07/08/508207/pakistan-turkmenistan-to-discuss-tapi-gas-pipeline-groundbreaking-in-august|title=Pakistan and Turkmenistan to discuss TAPI gas pipeline|date=8 July 2019 |website=voanews.com|accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref>. The Taliban have vowed to cooperate and not disrupt the project in areas they control.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/taliban-to-protect-tapi-gas-pipeline-project/4268767.html|title=Taliban Vows to Protect TAPI Gas Pipeline Project|first=Hasib Danish|last=Alikozai|date=|website=voanews.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thediplomat.com/2018/02/tapi-moves-into-afghanistan-taliban-promise-to-protect-the-project/|title=TAPI Moves Into Afghanistan, Taliban Promise to Protect the Project|first=Catherine Putz, The|last=Diplomat|date=|website=thediplomat.com|accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Technical features==\nThe pipeline will be {{convert|1420|mm|in}} in diameter with a working pressure of {{convert|100|atm}}.<ref name=alex2>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.gasandoil.com/goc/news/ntc64919.htm\n | title = Gas pipeline project Turkmenistan-Afghanistan-Pakistan-India approved\n | publisher = Alexander's Gas & Oil Connections\n | date = 2006-11-21\n | accessdate = 2008-05-18}}\n</ref>  The capacity will be {{convert|33|e9m3|abbr=off}} of natural gas per year of which {{convert|5|e9m3|abbr=off}} will be provided to Afghanistan and {{convert|14|e9m3|abbr=off}} to each Pakistan and India.<ref name=diplomat031215>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://thediplomat.com/2015/12/a-fillip-for-the-tapi-pipeline/\n | title = A Fillip for the TAPI Pipeline\n | newspaper = The Diplomat\n | first =  Micha'el | last = Tanchum\n | date = 2015-12-03\n | accessdate = 2015-12-13}}\n</ref>  Six compressor stations would be constructed along the pipeline.<ref name=alex2/> The pipeline was intended to be operational by 2019.<ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\"/>\n\nOriginally, the cost of the pipeline project was reportedly estimated at US$7.6&nbsp;billion, but a more recent estimate was $10&nbsp;billion.<ref name=upi031214>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.upi.com/Business_News/Energy-Resources/2014/12/03/Kazakhstan-keen-on-TAPI-gas-pipeline/1741417604335/\n | title = Kazakhstan keen on TAPI gas pipeline\n | first = Daniel J. | last=Graeber\n | agency = [[United Press International|UPI]]\n | date = 2014-12-03\n | accessdate = 2015-02-25}}\n</ref>  The leading partner of the project is [[T\u00fcrkmengaz]].<ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\"/>\n\n==Route==\nThe {{convert|1814|km|adj=on}} pipeline will run from gas fields in Turkmenistan through Afghanistan and Pakistan to India. It start from the [[Galkynysh gas field]].<ref name=\"Turkmenistan starts work on gas link to Afghanistan, Pakistan, India\"/> In Afghanistan, TAPI pipeline will be constructed alongside the [[Kandahar\u2013Herat Highway]] in western Afghanistan, and then via [[Quetta]] and [[Multan]] in Pakistan.<ref name=dailytimes220203>\n{{cite news\n | url = http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=story_22-2-2003_pg1_5\n | title = Alternate route for pipeline to be discussed today\n | first1 = Khalid | last1 = Mustafa\n | newspaper = [[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]]\n | date = 2003-02-22\n | accessdate = 2012-01-27}}\n</ref> The final destination of the pipeline will be the Indian town of [[Fazilka]], near the border between Pakistan and India.<ref name=alex2/>\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Afghanistan Oil Pipeline]]\n* [[Transport in Afghanistan]]\n* [[Baku-Tbilisi-Ceyhan pipeline]] (BTC)\n* [[Enron]]'s [[Dabhol Power Company]]\n* [[Trans-Caspian Gas Pipeline]]\n* [[South Caucasus Pipeline]]\n* [[CentGas]]\n* [[Port of Chabahar]]\n* [[Ashgabat agreement]]\n{{col div end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turkmenistan-Afghanistan-Pakistan-India Pipeline}}\n[[Category:Natural gas pipelines in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Natural gas pipelines in Turkmenistan]]\n[[Category:Natural gas pipelines in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Natural gas pipelines in India]]\n[[Category:Proposed pipelines in Asia]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013India relations]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013Turkmenistan relations]]\n[[Category:India\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n[[Category:Pakistan\u2013Turkmenistan relations]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkmenistan%E2%80%93Afghanistan%E2%80%93Pakistan%E2%80%93India_Pipeline"}
{"title_page": "Turkey in the Straw", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Turkey in the Straw\n| cover      = File:Turkey in the straw (NYPL Hades-609605-1998230).jpg\n| cover_size = 300px\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Sheet music\n| type       =\n| written    =\n| published  =\n| writer     =\n| composer   =\n| lyricist   =\n}}\n{{listen\n|filename=Turkey in the Straw.ogg\n|title=\"Turkey in the Straw\"\n|description=\"[[Chicken Reel]]/Turkey in the Straw medley\" performed by the [[United States Air Force Band]]\n}}\n\"'''Turkey in the Straw'''\" is an American folk song that first gained popularity in the early 19th century.\n\n== History ==\nThe first part of the song is a [[contrafactum]] of the ballad \"My Grandmother Lived on Yonder Little Green,\" ''aka'' \"My Grandma Lived on Yonder Little Green,\" ''aka'' \"My Grandma's Advice,\" published in 1857 by [[Horace Waters]], 333 Broadway, [[New York City|New York]], which is a [[contrafactum]] of the Irish ballad \"The Old Rose Tree.\"<ref name=\"Linscott 1939\" />\n\n\"Turkey in the Straw\" was initially a popular tune for [[fiddle]] players. In the late 1820s and early 1830s, \"Turkey in the Straw\" was performed in [[minstrel shows]] by [[blackface]] actors and musicians, notably [[George Washington Dixon]]<ref name=\"Studwell 1997\" />\n\n==Lyrics==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\n: '''1st verse'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in de straw, turkey in de hay\nTurkey in de straw, turkey in de hay\nRoll 'em up an' twist 'em up a high tuc-ka-haw\nAn' twist 'em up a tune called Turkey in the Straw\n}}\n\n: '''Traditional chorus'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the hay, in the hay, in the hay.\nTurkey in the straw, in the straw, in the straw,\nPick up your fiddle and [[rosin]] your bow,\nAnd put on a tune called Turkey in the Straw.\n}}\n\n: '''1st verse of another version'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the straw \u2014 Ha ha ha\nTurkey in the hay \u2014 Hey hey hey\nThe Reubens are dancing to Turkey in the Straw\nHey highdy heydy, and a haw haw haw}}\n\n: '''1st verse of another version'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the straw, turkey in the hay\nTune up the fiddle, doodle de day\nWith a rump and riddle and a high tuc-ka-haw\nStrike up that tune called \"Turkey in the Straw\"}}\n\n: '''The Full Lyrics'''\n{{poemquote|As I was a-gwine down the road,\nTired team and a heavy load,\nCrack my whip and the leader sprung,\nl seys day-day to the wagon tongue.\n\nTurkey in the straw, turkey in the hay,\nTurkey in the straw, turkey in the hay\nRoll 'em up and twist 'em up a high tuckahaw\nAnd twist 'em up a tune called Turkey in the Straw.\n\nWent out to milk, and I didn't know how,\nI milked the goat instead of the cow.\nA monkey sittin' on a pile of straw,\nA-winkin' at his mother-in-law.\n\nMet Mr. Catfish comin' down stream.\nSays Mr. Catfish, \"What does you mean?\"\nCaught Mr. Catfish by the snout,\nAnd turned Mr. Catfish wrong side out.\n\nCame to a river and I couldn't get across,\nPaid five dollars for a blind old hoss;\nWouldn't go ahead, nor he wouldn't stand still,\nSo he went up and down like an old saw mill.\n\nAs I came down the new cut road,\nMet Mr. Bullfrog, met Miss Toad\nAnd every time Miss Toad would sing,\nOld Bullfrog cut a pigeon wing.\n\nOh I jumped in the seat and I gave a little yell\nThe horses ran away, broke the wagon all to hell\nSugar in the gourd and honey in the horn\nI never been so happy since the day I was born.\"}}\n\n{{ref begin|100em}}\n:: {{Font color|#A9A9A9|{{loop|20|\u2013}}}}\n:: Tuckahoe (''[[Peltandra virginica]]'', also called green arrow arum) = an edible wetland plant with long [[Petiole (botany)|petioles]]\n:: Reubens = farmers\n{{ref end}}\n\nThere are versions from the [[American Civil War]], versions about fishing and one with [[nonsense]] verses. Folklorists have documented folk versions with obscene lyrics from the [[19th century]].\n\n: '''''Lyrics of [[The Wiggles]]'' and [[Sharon Lois and Bram]]'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the straw\u2014Haw haw haw\nTurkey in the hay\u2014Hey hey hey\nAnd the old folks danced with their mother-in-law\nAs they danced to a tune we call \"Turkey in the Straw\"}}\n\nAnother version is called \"[[Natchez people|Natchez]] Under the Hill\". The lyrics are thought to have been added to an earlier tune by Bob Farrell who first performed them in a blackface act on August 11, 1834.\n\n: '''1st verse of another version'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the straw, turkey in the hay,\nTurkey in the straw what do you say.\nFunnest thing I ever saw.\nIt's a little tune called Turkey in the Straw.}}\n\nIn 1942, a [[soundie]] titled, \"Turkey in the Straw\" was created by [[Freddie Fisher (musician)|Freddie Fisher]] and [[The Schnickelfritz Band]]. (Directed by Sam Coslow and Produced by Josef Berne). There are two versions to the chorus that are sung. The first goes:\n\n: '''Chorus; 1st version'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the Straw, A' Turkey in the hay,\nA' Turkey in the Straw, \"What did you say?\"\nHay! Roll 'em, twist 'em up a high tuc-ka-haw,\nHittin' up a tune called \"Turkey in the Straw.\"}}\n\n: '''Chorus; 2nd version'''\n{{poemquote|A' Turkey in the Straw, A' Turkey in the grass,\nA' Turkey in the Straw, \"I get a kick outta this..\"\nRoll 'em, twist 'em up a high tuc-ka-haw,\nHittin' up a tune called \"Turkey in the Straw.\"}}\n\nIn [[Barney & Friends]] they used these lyrics:\n\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the Straw (whistles)\nTurkey in the Straw (whistles)\nHats on, boots on Yee Hah\nSing a little song called \"Turkey in the Straw.\"}}\n\nMickey's Fun Songs and [[Sesame Street]] use these lyrics\n\n{{poemquote| I was a-going down a dusty road,\nWith a team of horses and a great big load,\nIt was oh such a warm and lazy afternoon,\nSo I tapped my toe and started singing a tune.\n\nDancing tonight,\nDancing tonight,\nHappiest people you ever saw\nWill be Dancing Together with the Turkey in the Straw}}\n\n=== Racist versions ===\n[[Harry C. Browne]] recorded a version in 1916 called \"Nigger Love a Watermelon Ha! Ha! Ha!\".<ref name=\"Authentic History 2015\" /> This version relied heavily on the offensive and widespread [[Coon song|coon]] stereotype.\n\n==== {{anchor|Zip Coon}} \"Zip Coon\" ====\nAnother [[contrafactum]], \"Zip Coon\", sung to the same tune as \"Turkey in the Straw\",<ref name=Doo-dah!>{{cite book |last=Emerson |first=Ken |title=Doo-dah!: Stephen Foster and the Rise of American Popular Culture |year=1997 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=New York |isbn=978-0684810102 |page=[https://archive.org/details/doodahstephenfos0000unse/page/60 60] |url=https://archive.org/details/doodahstephenfos0000unse/page/60 }}</ref> was popularized by Dixon and flourished during the [[Andrew Jackson]] administration. This version was first published between 1829 and 1834 in either New York or [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]]. All of the above performers claimed to have written the song, and the dispute is not resolved. [[Ohio]] songwriter [[Daniel Decatur Emmett]] is sometimes erroneously credited as the song's author.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nativeground.com/danemmett.asp |title=Dan Emmett \u2013 The Man Who Wrote \"Dixie\" by Wayne Erbsen |publisher=NativeGround.com |accessdate=June 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317140833/http://www.nativeground.com/danemmett.asp |archivedate=March 17, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n\"Zip Coon\" has a vocal range of an octave and a minor sixth. Both the verse and the chorus end on the tonic, and both begin a major third above the tonic. In the verse, the highest note is a fifth above the tonic and the lowest is a minor sixth below. In the chorus, the highest note is an octave above the last note, and the lowest is the last note itself. The song stays in key throughout.\n\nThe song gave rise to the blackface minstrel show character [[Minstrel show#Zip Coon|Zip Coon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://black-face.com/|title=Blackface!|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===== More versions =====\n\"Zip Coon\" has many different lyrical versions. Thomas Birch published a version in 1834,<ref name=\"Zip Coon\">{{cite web |last=Birch |first=Thomas |title=Zip Coon |url=http://utc.iath.virginia.edu/minstrel/zipcoonfr.html |publisher=University of Virginia |accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref> while George Washington Dixon published a version called \"Ole Zip Coon\" with different lyrics circa 1835.<ref name=\"OLE ZIP COON\">{{cite web |last=Dixon |first=G.W. |title=OLE ZIP COON |url=http://lyricsplayground.com/alpha/songs/o/olezipcoon.shtml |publisher=International Lyrics Playground |accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref> Both Birch's and Dixon's versions keep the same chorus and the first four stanzas:\n\n{{poemquote|(3\u00d7) O ole Zip Coon he is a larned skoler,\nSings posum up a gum tree an conny in a holler.\n(3\u00d7) Posum up a gum tree, coonny on a stump,\nDen over dubble trubble, Zip coon will jump.}}\n\n: '''Chorus'''\n{{poemquote|O Zip a duden duden duden zip a duden day.\nO Zip a duden duden duden duden duden day.\nO Zip a duden duden duden zip a duden day.\nZip a duden duden duden zip a duden day.}}\n\n{{poemquote|O ist old Suky blue skin, she is in lub wid me\nI went the udder arter noon to take a dish ob tea;\nWhat do you tink now, Suky hab for supper,\nWhy chicken foot an posum heel, widout any butter.}}\n\n: '''Chorus'''\n{{poemquote|Did you eber see the wild goose, sailing on de ocean,\nO de wild goose motion is a berry pretty notion;\nEbry time de wild goose, beckens to de swaller,\nYou hear him google google google google gollar.}}\n\n: '''Chorus'''\n{{poemquote|I went down to Sandy Hollar t other arternoon\nAnd the first man I chanced to meet war ole Zip Coon;\nOle Zip Coon he is a natty scholar,\nFor he plays upon de Banjo \"Cooney in de hollar\".}}\n\nIn subsequent stanzas, both lyricists talk about events in the life of [[Andrew Jackson]], Birth of President Jackson's battle with the [[Second Bank of the United States]]<ref name=\"Zip Coon\" /> and Dixon of General Jackson at the [[Battle of New Orleans]].<ref name=\"OLE ZIP COON\" /> When the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] began, Dixon published a new version of \"Zip Coon\" with updated lyrics pertaining to the war:\n\n{{poemquote|And spite of any rumors\nWe'll vanquish all the Montezumas!<ref name=Doo-dah! />}}\n\nThe chorus \"Zip a duden duden duden zip a duden day\" influenced the song \"[[Zip-A-Dee-Doo-Dah]]\" in [[Walt Disney]]'s 1946 adaptation of [[Joel Chandler Harris]]' [[Uncle Remus]] tales, ''[[Song of the South]]''.<ref name=Doo-dah! />\n\nAnother version of \"Old Zip Coon\" with new self-referencing lyrics by David K. Stevens (1860\u20131946) was published in the ''Boy Scout Song Book'' (1920).<ref>{{cite book |title=Boy Scout Song Book |date=1920 |publisher=C.C. Birchard and Co. |location=Boston, Mass. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/boyscout00boys/page/48 48]-49 |quote=Old American tune.|url=https://archive.org/details/boyscout00boys |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stevens |first1=D. K. |last2=Repper |first2=Charles |title=Old Zip Coon |url=http://link.lib.byu.edu/portal/Old-zip-coon--S.A.T.B.-text-by-David-Stevens/gu35Nmh5Apk/ |website=Brigham Young University |accessdate=23 January 2019 }}</ref> Stevens' lyrics contain no direct racial references other than the title of the song itself:\n{{poemquote|\nThere once was a man with a double chin,\nWho played with skill on a violin:\nAnd he played in time and he played in tune,\nBut he never played anything but 'Old Zip Coon'.}}\n\n==Performance history==\n[[File:Decca 9-27306 - TurkeyInTheStraw-OldHenCackle-Fiddler'sDream.jpg|thumb|[[Phonograph record]] version by [[Clayton McMichen]].]]\nArtistic and popular use of \"Turkey in the Straw\" through the years has established the song as an item of [[Americana]]. \n* \"Turkey in the Straw\" was [[Billy the Kid]]'s favorite song.<ref>\"Billy the Kid:  The Endless Ride\", by Michael Wallis.</ref>\n* In 1909 the composer [[Charles Ives]] incorporated the tune, along with other [[popular song|vernacular American melodies]], into his orchestral [[Symphony No. 2 (Ives)|Symphony No. 2]].<ref>https://performingarts.georgetown.edu/Charles-Ives-America Georgetown University:\"Charles Ives's America\"</ref><ref>J. Peter Burkholder, '[https://www.jstor.org/stable/746629 \"Quotation\" and Paraphrase in Ives' Second Symphony'], ''19th Century Music, ''Vol. 11, No. 1, pp. 3-25. [accessed 26 July 2013]</ref> \n* According to survivors, \"Turkey in the Straw\" was among songs played by the [[Musicians of the RMS Titanic|band]] of the [[RMS Titanic|RMS ''Titanic'']] at one point during the [[Sinking of the RMS Titanic|sinking]] on April 14 and April 15, 1912.<ref>Fitch, Tad and J. Kent Layton, Bill Wormstedt (2012) ''On a Sea of Glass: The Life and Loss of the RMS Titanic''. Gloucestershire: Amberly. p. 303</ref>\n*\"Nigger Loves a Watermelon\" (1916) parody recorded by [[Harry C. Browne]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=97nqGtuNJmw</ref>\n* In 1920, American composer [[Leo Wood]] wrote the lyrics to Otto Bonnell's version of \"Turkey In The Straw, A Rag-Time Fantasy\" which was published by Leo Feist Inc., New York.\n* In 1925, American composer [[Joseph W. Clokey]] (stepfather of [[Gumby]] creator [[Art Clokey]]) wrote the choral ballad \"The Musical Trust,\" which incorporated \"Turkey in the Straw\" (with a reference to \"Zip Coon\") and other traditional American tunes.\n* In 1926, \"Turkey in the Straw\" was recorded by the [[old-time music|old-time]] band [[Gid Tanner]] & His [[Skillet Lickers]] with [[Riley Puckett]].<ref>http://countrydiscography.blogspot.no/2009/07/gid-tanner.html</ref>\n* In 1928, this was used as the base melody in the famous early [[Mickey Mouse]] cartoon ''[[Steamboat Willie]]''.<ref>[[Rimgaila Salys]], {{Google books |id=cDk8d2UMRLwC |page=86 |title=The Musical Comedy Films of Grigorii Aleksandrov: Laughing Matters}}</ref><ref>{{Google books |id=8-EEANKOC6kC |page=832 |title=New Scientist 7 Jun 1979}}</ref><ref>{{Google books |id=iOGW56Q5uToC |page=9 |title=The New Illustrated Treasury of Disney Songs}}</ref> The rendering of the tune in the cartoon is noted for being one of the first instances of successful synchronization in animated films.<ref>{{Google books |id=xt5k08yuAXIC |page=55 |title=Hollywood Cartoons: American Animation in Its Golden Age |first=Michael |last=Barrier}}</ref> The tune became prominent in Mickey's animated series and was used in many subsequent cartoons in the 1920s and '30s, most notably the first Mickey Mouse cartoon in color, ''[[The Band Concert]]'', in which [[Donald Duck]] annoys an orchestra by repeatedly playing the tune over their efforts at [[The William Tell Overture]]''.\n* In 1942 [[Carson Robison]] performed an anti-Axis Powers version of Turkey in the Straw. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.historyonthenet.com/authentichistory/1939-1945/3-music/08-Axis-Allies/19420100_1942_Turkey_In_The_Straw-Carson_Robison-lyrics.html |title=1942 Turkey In The Straw Lyrics |last=Robison|first=Carson |date=January 1942 |website=History on the Net |access-date=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n* In the video game ''[[Bubsy in Claws Encounters of the Furred Kind]]'', the music used in chapters 10-12 contains a sample of ''Turkey in the Straw''.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Bubsy in Claws Encounters of the Furred Kind| developer = Accolade| publisher = Accolade, Retroism| date = May 1993| platform = Super NES| level = Beavery Careful, Rock around the Croc, Claws for Alarm| language = English}}</ref>\n* The song is the base to \"Wakko's America\" on the hit children's TV show ''[[Animaniacs]]''.\n* A looped segment of the song is used during the Astro Chicken minigame in [[Space Quest III]], and used in later Space Quest games as easter eggs or whenever Astro Chicken is shown.\n* The song is one of the selectable songs in ''[[Wii Music]]''.\n* The animated adaptation of ''Rosie's Walk'' uses \"Turkey in the Straw\" as incidental music.\n* [[Ern\u0151 Dohn\u00e1nyi|Erno Dohnanyi]] used the tune (and also two other traditional American folktunes) in his composition ''American Rhapsody'' (1953).\n* The melody is played by many [[ice cream trucks]];<ref>[http://www.sandiegoreader.com/news/1998/aug/20/how-did-tune-turkey-straw-become-song-ice-cream-tr/ San Diego Reader]</ref> in 1942 [[Raymond Chandler]]'s novel ''[[The High Window]]'', the protagonist recounts \"The Good Humor man went by in his little blue and white wagon, playing 'Turkey in the Straw' on his music box\".\n* The song is played in the [[MSX]] game Mouser (1983).\n* The theme music of short-lived [[WWE|WWF]] character [[H\u00e9ctor Guerrero|The Gobbeldy Gooker]] was an instrumental rock version of the song. This version has many titles on BMI and the Uncaged X Download & Stream CD. Turkey in the Straw, Gooker, Gobblely Gooker, Gobbledy Gooker and Break an Egg upon release WWE went with Break an Egg for the release version out on Friday 10/04/2019 - 04/10/2019 at 12am UK time.\n* In the episode of ''Sonic Boom'' entitled \"Don't Judge Me\", during Stick's time on the witness stand during Sonic's trial, she stated that Dr. Eggman got songs stuck in people's heads.  Afterwards, she sings \"Well, if frogs had wings and snakes had hair, And automobiles went flyin' thro' the air...\".\n* It was also heard in the children's television show ''Barney & Friends''.\n* The song \"Verishuvi\" of the Japanese Idol group [[Sakura Gakuin]] use this melody as opening and interlude.\n* The instrumental \"Hoedown\" from [[Emerson Lake and Palmer]]'s album ''[[Trilogy (Emerson, Lake & Palmer album)|Trilogy]]'' quotes the melody.\n* In 2015 Japanese singer [[Ai (singer)|Ai]] had a surprise hit with her version of the song, done for a phone commercial, called \"Everyone Is a Hero\" (\"\u307f\u3093\u306a\u304c\u307f\u3093\u306a\u82f1\u96c4\"). <ref>https://www.gooume-jp.com/works/528</ref>\n* \"Why Don't You Love Me\" by Hank Williams is based around this melody.\n* In [[Sesame Street]], an animated segment featured a spoof of the song, which involves counting 13 turkeys.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coon song]]\n*[[Do Your Ears Hang Low?]]\n*[[Unsquare Dance]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Linscott 1939\">''Folk Songs of Old New England,'' by [[Eloise Hubbard Linscott]] ''(n\u00e9e'' Eloise Barrett Hubbard; 1897\u20131978), [[Macmillan Publishers]] (1939; reprinted 2011 by [[Dover Publications]]), pps. 101, 102, & 244; {{OCLC|30827924}}; {{ISBN|978-0-4862-7827-8}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Studwell 1997\">{{cite book |title=The Americana Song Reader |first=William E. |last=Studwell |year=1997 |publisher=Haworth Press |isbn=0-7890-0150-0 |page=58}}</ref> and [[Bob Farrell (minstrel singer)|Bob Farrell]].</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Authentic History 2015\">{{cite web |url=http://www.authentichistory.com/diversity/african/3-coon/5-chickwatermelon/19160300_Nigger_Love_A_Watermelon-Harry_C_Browne.html |title=Nigger Love a Watermelon Ha! Ha! Ha! |last=Browne |first=Harry C. |website=AuthenticHistory.com |accessdate=19 March 2015 |others=Recorded March 1916}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Fuld, James (1966). ''The Book of World Famous Music, Classical, Popular and Folk''.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.contemplator.com/america/turkeyis.html Turkey in the Straw]\n* [http://www.csufresno.edu/folklore/ballads/RJ19258.html Old Zip Coon]\n* {{YouTube |id=CZB6WXDuM1g |title=The Ice Cream Truck Song}}\n* [https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2014/05/11/310708342/recall-that-ice-cream-truck-song-we-have-unpleasant-news-for-you NPR: Recall That Ice Cream Truck Song? We Have Unpleasant News For You]\n* [https://newrepublic.com/article/117792/racist-ice-cream-song-story-nprcom-wrong The New Republic: That Viral Story About the Racist Ice Cream Song Is Wrong]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turkey In The Straw}}\n[[Category:American folk songs]]\n[[Category:American country music songs]]\n[[Category:Blackface minstrel songs]]\n[[Category:English children's songs]]\n[[Category:Traditional children's songs]]\n[[Category:English-language songs]]\n[[Category:19th-century songs]]\n[[Category:Songs of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Year of song unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Turkey in the Straw\n| cover      = File:Turkey in the straw (NYPL Hades-609605-1998230).jpg\n| cover_size = 300px\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Sheet music\n| type       =\n| written    =\n| published  =\n| writer     =\n| composer   =\n| lyricist   =\n}}\n{{listen\n|filename=Turkey in the Straw.ogg\n|title=\"Turkey in the Straw\"\n|description=\"[[Chicken Reel]]/Turkey in the Straw medley\" performed by the [[United States Air Force Band]]\n}}\n\"'''Turkey in the Straw'''\" is an American folk song that first gained popularity in the early 19th century.\n\n== History ==\nThe first part of the song is a [[contrafactum]] of the ballad \"My Grandmother Lived on Yonder Little Green,\" ''aka'' \"My Grandma Lived on Yonder Little Green,\" ''aka'' \"My Grandma's Advice,\" published in 1857 by [[Horace Waters]], 333 Broadway, [[New York City|New York]], which is a [[contrafactum]] of the Irish ballad \"The Old Rose Tree.\"<ref name=\"Linscott 1939\" />\n\n\"Turkey in the Straw\" was initially a popular tune for [[fiddle]] players. In the late 1820s and early 1830s, \"Turkey in the Straw\" was performed in [[minstrel shows]] by [[blackface]] actors and musicians, notably [[George Washington Dixon]]<ref name=\"Studwell 1997\" />\n\n==Lyrics==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2018}}\n: '''1st verse'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in de straw, turkey in de hay\nTurkey in de straw, turkey in de hay\nRoll 'em up an' twist 'em up a high tuc-ka-haw\nAn' twist 'em up a tune called Turkey in the Straw\n}}\n\n: '''Traditional chorus'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the hay, in the hay, in the hay.\nTurkey in the straw, in the straw, in the straw,\nPick up your fiddle and [[rosin]] your bow,\nAnd put on a tune called Turkey in the Straw.\n}}\n\n: '''1st verse of another version'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the straw \u2014 Ha ha ha\nTurkey in the hay \u2014 Hey hey hey\nThe Reubens are dancing to Turkey in the Straw\nHey highdy heydy, and a haw haw haw}}\n\n: '''1st verse of another version'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the straw, turkey in the hay\nTune up the fiddle, doodle de day\nWith a rump and riddle and a high tuc-ka-haw\nStrike up that tune called \"Turkey in the Straw\"}}\n\n: '''The Full Lyrics'''\n{{poemquote|As I was a-gwine down the road,\nTired team and a heavy load,\nCrack my whip and the leader sprung,\nl seys day-day to the wagon tongue.\n\nTurkey in the straw, turkey in the hay,\nTurkey in the straw, turkey in the hay\nRoll 'em up and twist 'em up a high tuckahaw\nAnd twist 'em up a tune called Turkey in the Straw.\n\nWent out to milk, and I didn't know how,\nI milked the goat instead of the cow.\nA monkey sittin' on a pile of straw,\nA-winkin' at his mother-in-law.\n\nMet Mr. Catfish comin' down stream.\nSays Mr. Catfish, \"What does you mean?\"\nCaught Mr. Catfish by the snout,\nAnd turned Mr. Catfish wrong side out.\n\nCame to a river and I couldn't get across,\nPaid five dollars for a blind old hoss;\nWouldn't go ahead, nor he wouldn't stand still,\nSo he went up and down like an old saw mill.\n\nAs I came down the new cut road,\nMet Mr. Bullfrog, met Miss Toad\nAnd every time Miss Toad would sing,\nOld Bullfrog cut a pigeon wing.\n\nOh I jumped in the seat and I gave a little yell\nThe horses ran away, broke the wagon all to hell\nSugar in the gourd and honey in the horn\nI never been so happy since the day I was born.\"}}\n\n{{ref begin|100em}}\n:: {{Font color|#A9A9A9|{{loop|20|\u2013}}}}\n:: Tuckahoe (''[[Peltandra virginica]]'', also called green arrow arum) = an edible wetland plant with long [[Petiole (botany)|petioles]]\n:: Reubens = farmers\n{{ref end}}\n\nThere are versions from the [[American Civil War]], versions about fishing and one with [[nonsense]] verses. Folklorists have documented folk versions with obscene lyrics from the [[19th century]].\n\n: '''''Lyrics of [[The Wiggles]]'' and [[Sharon Lois and Bram]]'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the straw\u2014Haw haw haw\nTurkey in the hay\u2014Hey hey hey\nAnd the old folks danced with their mother-in-law\nAs they danced to a tune we call \"Turkey in the Straw\"}}\n\nAnother version is called \"[[Natchez people|Natchez]] Under the Hill\". The lyrics are thought to have been added to an earlier tune by Bob Farrell who first performed them in a blackface act on August 11, 1834.\n\n: '''1st verse of another version'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the straw, turkey in the hay,\nTurkey in the straw what do you say.\nFunnest thing I ever saw.\nIt's a little tune called Turkey in the Straw.}}\n\nIn 1942, a [[soundie]] titled, \"Turkey in the Straw\" was created by [[Freddie Fisher (musician)|Freddie Fisher]] and [[The Schnickelfritz Band]]. (Directed by Sam Coslow and Produced by Josef Berne). There are two versions to the chorus that are sung. The first goes:\n\n: '''Chorus; 1st version'''\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the Straw, A' Turkey in the hay,\nA' Turkey in the Straw, \"What did you say?\"\nHay! Roll 'em, twist 'em up a high tuc-ka-haw,\nHittin' up a tune called \"Turkey in the Straw.\"}}\n\n: '''Chorus; 2nd version'''\n{{poemquote|A' Turkey in the Straw, A' Turkey in the grass,\nA' Turkey in the Straw, \"I get a kick outta this..\"\nRoll 'em, twist 'em up a high tuc-ka-haw,\nHittin' up a tune called \"Turkey in the Straw.\"}}\n\nIn [[Barney & Friends]] they used these lyrics:\n\n{{poemquote|Turkey in the Straw (whistles)\nTurkey in the Straw (whistles)\nHats on, boots on Yee Hah\nSing a little song called \"Turkey in the Straw.\"}}\n\nMickey's Fun Songs and [[Sesame Street]] use these lyrics\n\n{{poemquote| I was a-going down a dusty road,\nWith a team of horses and a great big load,\nIt was oh such a warm and lazy afternoon,\nSo I tapped my toe and started singing a tune.\n\nDancing tonight,\nDancing tonight,\nHappiest people you ever saw\nWill be Dancing Together with the Turkey in the Straw}}\n\n=== Racist versions ===\n[[Harry C. Browne]] recorded a version in 1916 called \"Nigger Love a Watermelon Ha! Ha! Ha!\".<ref name=\"Authentic History 2015\" /> This version relied heavily on the offensive and widespread [[Coon song|coon]] stereotype.\n\n==== {{anchor|Zip Coon}} \"Zip Coon\" ====\nAnother [[contrafactum]], \"Zip Coon\", sung to the same tune as \"Turkey in the Straw\",<ref name=Doo-dah!>{{cite book |last=Emerson |first=Ken |title=Doo-dah!: Stephen Foster and the Rise of American Popular Culture |year=1997 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=New York |isbn=978-0684810102 |page=[https://archive.org/details/doodahstephenfos0000unse/page/60 60] |url=https://archive.org/details/doodahstephenfos0000unse/page/60 }}</ref> was popularized by Dixon and flourished during the [[Andrew Jackson]] administration. This version was first published between 1829 and 1834 in either New York or [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]]. All of the above performers claimed to have written the song, and the dispute is not resolved. [[Ohio]] songwriter [[Daniel Decatur Emmett]] is sometimes erroneously credited as the song's author.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nativeground.com/danemmett.asp |title=Dan Emmett \u2013 The Man Who Wrote \"Dixie\" by Wayne Erbsen |publisher=NativeGround.com |accessdate=June 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317140833/http://www.nativeground.com/danemmett.asp |archivedate=March 17, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n\"Zip Coon\" has a vocal range of an octave and a minor sixth. Both the verse and the chorus end on the tonic, and both begin a major third above the tonic. In the verse, the highest note is a fifth above the tonic and the lowest is a minor sixth below. In the chorus, the highest note is an octave above the last note, and the lowest is the last note itself. The song stays in key throughout.\n\nThe song gave rise to the blackface minstrel show character [[Minstrel show#Zip Coon|Zip Coon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://black-face.com/|title=Blackface!|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===== More versions =====\n\"Zip Coon\" has many different lyrical versions. Thomas Birch published a version in 1834,<ref name=\"Zip Coon\">{{cite web |last=Birch |first=Thomas |title=Zip Coon |url=http://utc.iath.virginia.edu/minstrel/zipcoonfr.html |publisher=University of Virginia |accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref> while George Washington Dixon published a version called \"Ole Zip Coon\" with different lyrics circa 1835.<ref name=\"OLE ZIP COON\">{{cite web |last=Dixon |first=G.W. |title=OLE ZIP COON |url=http://lyricsplayground.com/alpha/songs/o/olezipcoon.shtml |publisher=International Lyrics Playground |accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref> Both Birch's and Dixon's versions keep the same chorus and the first four stanzas:\n\n{{poemquote|(3\u00d7) O ole Zip Coon he is a larned skoler,\nSings posum up a gum tree an conny in a holler.\n(3\u00d7) Posum up a gum tree, coonny on a stump,\nDen over dubble trubble, Zip coon will jump.}}\n\n: '''Chorus'''\n{{poemquote|O Zip a duden duden duden zip a duden day.\nO Zip a duden duden duden duden duden day.\nO Zip a duden duden duden zip a duden day.\nZip a duden duden duden zip a duden day.}}\n\n{{poemquote|O ist old Suky blue skin, she is in lub wid me\nI went the udder arter noon to take a dish ob tea;\nWhat do you tink now, Suky hab for supper,\nWhy chicken foot an posum heel, widout any butter.}}\n\n: '''Chorus'''\n{{poemquote|Did you eber see the wild goose, sailing on de ocean,\nO de wild goose motion is a berry pretty notion;\nEbry time de wild goose, beckens to de swaller,\nYou hear him google google google google gollar.}}\n\n: '''Chorus'''\n{{poemquote|I went down to Sandy Hollar t other arternoon\nAnd the first man I chanced to meet war ole Zip Coon;\nOle Zip Coon he is a natty scholar,\nFor he plays upon de Banjo \"Cooney in de hollar\".}}\n\nIn subsequent stanzas, both lyricists talk about events in the life of [[Andrew Jackson]], Birth of President Jackson's battle with the [[Second Bank of the United States]]<ref name=\"Zip Coon\" /> and Dixon of General Jackson at the [[Battle of New Orleans]].<ref name=\"OLE ZIP COON\" /> When the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] began, Dixon published a new version of \"Zip Coon\" with updated lyrics pertaining to the war:\n\n{{poemquote|And spite of any rumors\nWe'll vanquish all the Montezumas!<ref name=Doo-dah! />}}\n\nThe chorus \"Zip a duden duden duden zip a duden day\" influenced the song \"[[Zip-A-Dee-Doo-Dah]]\" in [[Walt Disney]]'s 1946 adaptation of [[Joel Chandler Harris]]' [[Uncle Remus]] tales, ''[[Song of the South]]''.<ref name=Doo-dah! />\n\nAnother version of \"Old Zip Coon\" with new self-referencing lyrics by David K. Stevens (1860\u20131946) was published in the ''Boy Scout Song Book'' (1920).<ref>{{cite book |title=Boy Scout Song Book |date=1920 |publisher=C.C. Birchard and Co. |location=Boston, Mass. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/boyscout00boys/page/48 48]-49 |quote=Old American tune.|url=https://archive.org/details/boyscout00boys |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stevens |first1=D. K. |last2=Repper |first2=Charles |title=Old Zip Coon |url=http://link.lib.byu.edu/portal/Old-zip-coon--S.A.T.B.-text-by-David-Stevens/gu35Nmh5Apk/ |website=Brigham Young University |accessdate=23 January 2019 }}</ref> Stevens' lyrics contain no direct racial references other than the title of the song itself:\n{{poemquote|\nThere once was a man with a double chin,\nWho played with skill on a violin:\nAnd he played in time and he played in tune,\nBut he never played anything but 'Old Zip Coon'.}}\n\n==Performance history==\n[[File:Decca 9-27306 - TurkeyInTheStraw-OldHenCackle-Fiddler'sDream.jpg|thumb|[[Phonograph record]] version by [[Clayton McMichen]].]]\nArtistic and popular use of \"Turkey in the Straw\" through the years has established the song as an item of [[Americana]]. \n* \"Turkey in the Straw\" was [[Billy the Kid]]'s favorite song.<ref>\"Billy the Kid:  The Endless Ride\", by Michael Wallis.</ref>\n* In 1909 the composer [[Charles Ives]] incorporated the tune, along with other [[popular song|vernacular American melodies]], into his orchestral [[Symphony No. 2 (Ives)|Symphony No. 2]].<ref>https://performingarts.georgetown.edu/Charles-Ives-America Georgetown University:\"Charles Ives's America\"</ref><ref>J. Peter Burkholder, '[https://www.jstor.org/stable/746629 \"Quotation\" and Paraphrase in Ives' Second Symphony'], ''19th Century Music, ''Vol. 11, No. 1, pp. 3-25. [accessed 26 July 2013]</ref> \n* According to survivors, \"Turkey in the Straw\" was among songs played by the [[Musicians of the RMS Titanic|band]] of the [[RMS Titanic|RMS ''Titanic'']] at one point during the [[Sinking of the RMS Titanic|sinking]] on April 14 and April 15, 1912.<ref>Fitch, Tad and J. Kent Layton, Bill Wormstedt (2012) ''On a Sea of Glass: The Life and Loss of the RMS Titanic''. Gloucestershire: Amberly. p. 303</ref>\n*\"Nigger Loves a Watermelon\" (1916) parody recorded by [[Harry C. Browne]]<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=97nqGtuNJmw</ref>\n* In 1920, American composer [[Leo Wood]] wrote the lyrics to Otto Bonnell's version of \"Turkey In The Straw, A Rag-Time Fantasy\" which was published by Leo Feist Inc., New York.\n* In 1925, American composer [[Joseph W. Clokey]] (stepfather of [[Gumby]] creator [[Art Clokey]]) wrote the choral ballad \"The Musical Trust,\" which incorporated \"Turkey in the Straw\" (with a reference to \"Zip Coon\") and other traditional American tunes.\n* In 1926, \"Turkey in the Straw\" was recorded by the [[old-time music|old-time]] band [[Gid Tanner]] & His [[Skillet Lickers]] with [[Riley Puckett]]<ref>http://countrydiscography.blogspot.no/2009/07/gid-tanner.html</ref>.\n* In 1928, this was used as the base melody in the famous early [[Mickey Mouse]] cartoon ''[[Steamboat Willie]]''.<ref>[[Rimgaila Salys]], {{Google books |id=cDk8d2UMRLwC |page=86 |title=The Musical Comedy Films of Grigorii Aleksandrov: Laughing Matters}}</ref><ref>{{Google books |id=8-EEANKOC6kC |page=832 |title=New Scientist 7 Jun 1979}}</ref><ref>{{Google books |id=iOGW56Q5uToC |page=9 |title=The New Illustrated Treasury of Disney Songs}}</ref> The rendering of the tune in the cartoon is noted for being one of the first instances of successful synchronization in animated films.<ref>{{Google books |id=xt5k08yuAXIC |page=55 |title=Hollywood Cartoons: American Animation in Its Golden Age |first=Michael |last=Barrier}}</ref> The tune became prominent in Mickey's animated series and was used in many subsequent cartoons in the 1920s and '30s, most notably the first Mickey Mouse cartoon in color, ''[[The Band Concert]]'', in which [[Donald Duck]] annoys an orchestra by repeatedly playing the tune over their efforts at [[The William Tell Overture]]''.\n* In 1942 [[Carson Robison]] performed an anti-Axis Powers version of Turkey in the Straw. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.historyonthenet.com/authentichistory/1939-1945/3-music/08-Axis-Allies/19420100_1942_Turkey_In_The_Straw-Carson_Robison-lyrics.html |title=1942 Turkey In The Straw Lyrics |last=Robison|first=Carson |date=January 1942 |website=History on the Net |access-date=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n* In the video game ''[[Bubsy in Claws Encounters of the Furred Kind]]'', the music used in chapters 10-12 contains a sample of ''Turkey in the Straw''.<ref>{{cite video game| title = Bubsy in Claws Encounters of the Furred Kind| developer = Accolade| publisher = Accolade, Retroism| date = May 1993| platform = Super NES| level = Beavery Careful, Rock around the Croc, Claws for Alarm| language = English}}</ref>\n* The song is the base to \"Wakko's America\" on the hit children's TV show ''[[Animaniacs]]''.\n* A looped segment of the song is used during the Astro Chicken minigame in [[Space Quest III]], and used in later Space Quest games as easter eggs or whenever Astro Chicken is shown.\n* The song is one of the selectable songs in ''[[Wii Music]]''.\n* The animated adaptation of ''Rosie's Walk'' uses \"Turkey in the Straw\" as incidental music.\n* [[Ern\u0151 Dohn\u00e1nyi|Erno Dohnanyi]] used the tune (and also two other traditional American folktunes) in his composition ''American Rhapsody'' (1953).\n* The melody is played by many [[ice cream trucks]];<ref>[http://www.sandiegoreader.com/news/1998/aug/20/how-did-tune-turkey-straw-become-song-ice-cream-tr/ San Diego Reader]</ref> in 1942 [[Raymond Chandler]]'s novel ''[[The High Window]]'', the protagonist recounts \"The Good Humor man went by in his little blue and white wagon, playing 'Turkey in the Straw' on his music box\".\n* The song is played in the [[MSX]] game Mouser (1983).\n* The theme music of short-lived [[WWE|WWF]] character [[H\u00e9ctor Guerrero|The Gobbeldy Gooker]] was an instrumental rock version of the song. This version has many titles on BMI and the Uncaged X Download & Stream CD. Turkey in the Straw, Gooker, Gobblely Gooker, Gobbledy Gooker and Break an Egg upon release WWE went with Break an Egg for the release version out on Friday 10/04/2019 - 04/10/2019 at 12am UK time.\n* In the episode of ''Sonic Boom'' entitled \"Don't Judge Me\", during Stick's time on the witness stand during Sonic's trial, she stated that Dr. Eggman got songs stuck in people's heads.  Afterwards, she sings \"Well, if frogs had wings and snakes had hair, And automobiles went flyin' thro' the air...\".\n* It was also heard in the children's television show ''Barney & Friends''.\n* The song \"Verishuvi\" of the Japanese Idol group [[Sakura Gakuin]] use this melody as opening and interlude.\n* The instrumental \"Hoedown\" from [[Emerson Lake and Palmer]]'s album ''[[Trilogy (Emerson, Lake & Palmer album)|Trilogy]]'' quotes the melody.\n* In 2015 Japanese singer [[Ai (singer)|Ai]] had a surprise hit with her version of the song, done for a phone commercial, called \"Everyone Is a Hero\" (\"\u307f\u3093\u306a\u304c\u307f\u3093\u306a\u82f1\u96c4\"). <ref>https://www.gooume-jp.com/works/528</ref>\n* \"Why Don't You Love Me\" by Hank Williams is based around this melody.\n* In [[Sesame Street]], an animated segment featured a spoof of the song, which involves counting 13 turkeys.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Coon song]]\n*[[Do Your Ears Hang Low?]]\n*[[Unsquare Dance]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Linscott 1939\">''Folk Songs of Old New England,'' by [[Eloise Hubbard Linscott]] ''(n\u00e9e'' Eloise Barrett Hubbard; 1897\u20131978), [[Macmillan Publishers]] (1939; reprinted 2011 by [[Dover Publications]]), pps. 101, 102, & 244; {{OCLC|30827924}}; {{ISBN|978-0-4862-7827-8}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Studwell 1997\">{{cite book |title=The Americana Song Reader |first=William E. |last=Studwell |year=1997 |publisher=Haworth Press |isbn=0-7890-0150-0 |page=58}}</ref> and [[Bob Farrell (minstrel singer)|Bob Farrell]].</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Authentic History 2015\">{{cite web |url=http://www.authentichistory.com/diversity/african/3-coon/5-chickwatermelon/19160300_Nigger_Love_A_Watermelon-Harry_C_Browne.html |title=Nigger Love a Watermelon Ha! Ha! Ha! |last=Browne |first=Harry C. |website=AuthenticHistory.com |accessdate=19 March 2015 |others=Recorded March 1916}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Fuld, James (1966). ''The Book of World Famous Music, Classical, Popular and Folk''.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.contemplator.com/america/turkeyis.html Turkey in the Straw]\n* [http://www.csufresno.edu/folklore/ballads/RJ19258.html Old Zip Coon]\n* {{YouTube |id=CZB6WXDuM1g |title=The Ice Cream Truck Song}}\n* [https://www.npr.org/sections/codeswitch/2014/05/11/310708342/recall-that-ice-cream-truck-song-we-have-unpleasant-news-for-you NPR: Recall That Ice Cream Truck Song? We Have Unpleasant News For You]\n* [https://newrepublic.com/article/117792/racist-ice-cream-song-story-nprcom-wrong The New Republic: That Viral Story About the Racist Ice Cream Song Is Wrong]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turkey In The Straw}}\n[[Category:American folk songs]]\n[[Category:American country music songs]]\n[[Category:Blackface minstrel songs]]\n[[Category:English children's songs]]\n[[Category:Traditional children's songs]]\n[[Category:English-language songs]]\n[[Category:19th-century songs]]\n[[Category:Songs of the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Year of song unknown]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turkey_in_the_Straw"}
{"title_page": "Tuolumne River", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n| name               = Tuolumne River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Glen Aulin.jpg\n| image_size         = 260\n| image_caption      = The Tuolumne River at [[Glen Aulin]] valley, below Tuolumne Meadows\n| map                = Tuolumnemap-01.png\n| map_size           = 260\n| map_caption        = The Tuolumne River watershed\n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type2  = State\n| subdivision_name2  = [[California]]\n| subdivision_type3  = \n| subdivision_name3  = \n| subdivision_type4  = \n| subdivision_name4  = \n| subdivision_type5  = \n| subdivision_name5  = \n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|148.7|mi|km|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= above [[La Grange Dam]]<ref name=\"Abvlagrange\">{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/monthly/?referred_module=sw&amp;site_no=11288000&amp;por_11288000_1=2208871,00060,1,1911-10,1970-10&amp;format=html_table&amp;date_format=YYYY-MM-DD&amp;rdb_compression=file&amp;submitted_form=parameter_selection_list|title=USGS Gage #11288000 on the Tuolumne River above La Grange Dam near La Grange, CA|publisher=U.S. Geological Survey|work=National Water Information System|date=1911\u20131970|accessdate=2014-09-13}}</ref>\n| discharge1_min     = {{convert|57|cuft/s|m3/s|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_avg     = {{convert|2343|cuft/s|m3/s|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Abvlagrange\">{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/monthly/?referred_module=sw&amp;site_no=11288000&amp;por_11288000_1=2208871,00060,1,1911-10,1970-10&amp;format=html_table&amp;date_format=YYYY-MM-DD&amp;rdb_compression=file&amp;submitted_form=parameter_selection_list|title=USGS Gage #11288000 on the Tuolumne River above La Grange Dam near La Grange, CA|publisher=U.S. Geological Survey|work=National Water Information System|date=1911\u20131970|accessdate=2014-09-13}}</ref>\n| discharge1_max     = {{convert|130000|cuft/s|m3/s|abbr=on}}\n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = Confluence of Lyell and Dana Forks\n| source1_location   = [[Tuolumne Meadows]], [[Yosemite National Park]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|37|52|31|N|119|21|08|W|display=inline}}<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|id=255171|name=Tuolumne River|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2014-09-13}}</ref>\n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|8589|ft|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = [[San Joaquin River]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Grayson, California|Grayson]], [[Stanislaus County, California|Stanislaus County]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|37|36|21|N|121|10|25|W|display=inline,title}}<ref name=\"gnis\"/>\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|26|ft|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = {{convert|1958|sqmi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"river-system\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.sf-planning.org/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentid=7941\n|title=Chapter 5.3 Tuolumne River System and Downstream Water Bodies\n|publisher=City & County of San Francisco Planning Department\n|work=Preliminary Environmental Impact Report on SFPUC Water System Improvement Program\n|year=2005\n|accessdate=2015-03-21}}</ref>\n| tributaries_left   = South Fork Tuolumne River\n| tributaries_right  = [[Cherry Creek (Tuolumne River)|Cherry Creek]], [[Clavey River]], [[North Fork Tuolumne River]]\n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = {{Designation list\n| embed                   = yes\n| designation1            = nwsr\n| designation1_type       = Wild, Scenic, Recreational\n| designation1_date       = September 28, 1984\n| designation1_number     =\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Tuolumne River''' ({{IPAc-en|t|u|\u02c8|\u0252|l|\u0259m|i}}; [[Yokutsan language|Yokutsan]]: ''Tawalimnu'')<ref name=tawalimnu>{{cite book | last=Swanton | first=J.R. | title=The Indian Tribes of North America | publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company | series=Bulletin (Smithsonian Institution. Bureau of American Ethnology) | year=1952 | isbn=978-0-8063-1730-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xpx6WoPz7xIC&pg=PA505 | page=505}}</ref> flows for {{convert|149|mi|km}} through [[Central California]], from the high [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] to join the [[San Joaquin River]] in the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]]. Originating at over {{convert|8000|ft|m}} above sea level in [[Yosemite National Park]], the Tuolumne drains a rugged watershed of {{convert|1958|mi2|km2}}, carving a series of canyons through the western slope of the Sierra. While the upper Tuolumne is a fast-flowing mountain stream, the lower river crosses a broad, fertile and extensively cultivated [[alluvial plain]]. Like most other central California rivers, the Tuolumne is dammed multiple times for irrigation and the generation of [[hydroelectricity]].\n\nHumans have inhabited the Tuolumne River area for up to 10,000 years. Prior to the arrival of Europeans, the river canyon provided an important summer hunting ground and a trade route between [[Indigenous peoples of North America|Native Americans]] in the Central Valley to the west and the [[Great Basin]] to the east. First named in 1806 by a Spanish explorer after a nearby indigenous village, the Tuolumne was heavily prospected during the [[California Gold Rush]] in the 1850s, and the lower valley was cultivated by American settlers over the next few decades. The city of [[Modesto, California|Modesto]] grew up on the Tuolumne as a railroad hub, absorbing most of the population of the Tuolumne valley around the turn of the century. As agricultural production rose, farmers along the Tuolumne formed California's first two [[irrigation district]]s to better control and develop the river.\n\nFrom the 1900s to the 1930s, the river was dammed at [[Don Pedro Dam|Don Pedro]] and [[Hetch Hetchy]] to provide water for Central Valley farmers and the city of [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], respectively. The Hetch Hetchy project, located inside Yosemite National Park, incited national controversy, and has been described as having forged the modern [[environmental movement]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earthisland.org/journal/index.php/elist/eListRead/a_century_later_the_battle_for_hetch_hetchy_continues/|title=A Century Later, the Battle for Hetch Hetchy Continues|publisher=Earth Island Institute|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> As the mid-20th century progressed, demands on the Tuolumne continued to increase, culminating in the completion of [[New Don Pedro Dam]] in the early 1970s. These projects halved the amount of water flowing from the Tuolumne into the San Joaquin, greatly reducing the once-abundant runs of salmon and steelhead in both rivers.\n\n==Course==\n{{multiple image\n|align=right\n|direction=vertical\n|width=180\n|image1=California Falls, Tuolumne River, California (1921).jpg\n|image2=Waterwheel Falls in Yosemite.jpg\n|caption2=Top: California Falls. Bottom: Waterwheel Falls, the tallest of several waterfalls along the Tuolumne River.}}\n\nThe Tuolumne originates in Yosemite National Park, high in the Sierra Nevada, as two streams. The {{convert|7|mi|km|adj=on}}<ref name=\"Streamer\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://nationalmap.gov/streamer/webApp/streamer.html#\n |title       = Streamer\n |publisher   = United States Geological Survey\n |work        = The National Map\n |date        = 2014-04-14\n |accessdate  = 2014-03-21\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140907031400/http://nationalmap.gov/streamer/webApp/streamer.html\n |archivedate = 2014-09-07\n}}</ref> Lyell Fork rises at the [[Lyell Glacier]] below {{convert|13114|ft|m|adj=on}} [[Mount Lyell (California)|Mount Lyell]], the highest peak in Yosemite National Park,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.summitpost.org/mount-lyell/150494|title=Mount Lyell|publisher=Summitpost|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> and flows north through [[Lyell Canyon]]. The {{convert|5|mi|km|adj=on}}<ref name=\"Streamer\"/> Dana Fork originates between [[Mount Dana]] ({{convert|13044|ft|m|adj=on}}<ref>{{cite gnis|id=1655123|name=Mount Dana|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2014-09-11}}</ref>) and [[Mount Gibbs]] ({{convert|12772|ft|m|adj=on}}<ref>{{cite gnis|id=260547|name=Mount Gibbs|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2014-09-11}}</ref>) and flows west.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tid.org/water/projects/tuolumne-river|title=Tuolumne River|publisher=Turlock Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the confluence of the forks in [[Tuolumne Meadows]], the river meanders northwest, passing under [[Tioga Road]]. Although calm for the first few miles, this quickly changes as the river drops over Tuolumne Falls and White Cascades. After briefly passing through [[Glen Aulin]], the river enters the spectacular {{convert|20|mi|km|adj=on}} [[Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne]], where it forms three more major waterfalls \u2013 California, LeConte and [[Waterwheel Falls]]. Return and Piute Creeks join the river from the north within the Tuolumne Canyon. At the end of the canyon the river widens into Hetch Hetchy Reservoir, formed by a dam built in 1923 to provide water to the city of [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], in the scenic [[Hetch Hetchy Valley]].<ref name=\"HetchHetchyProject\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.tchistory.org/tchistory/Wonders_10.htm\n|title=Hetch Hetchy Water and Power System\n|publisher=Tuolumne County Historical Society\n|date=\n|accessdate=2015-03-21}}</ref> [[Falls Creek (California)|Falls Creek]] forms [[Wapama Falls]] and [[Tueeulala Falls]], two of the highest in Yosemite, as it enters the reservoir from the north. From its source at {{convert|8589|ft|m}} above sea level in Tuolumne Meadows, the river drops nearly a mile (1.6&nbsp;km) to the Hetch Hetchy reservoir at {{convert|3800|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite book\n|author1=Hoover, Mildred Brooke |author2=Kyle, Douglas E. |title=Historic Spots in California\n|publisher=Stanford University Press\n|year=1990\n|isbn=0-80471-734-6\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p2WrAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA518}}</ref>\n\nBelow the [[O'Shaughnessy Dam (California)|O'Shaughnessy Dam]] the Tuolumne passes Poopenaut Valley and enters a series of continuous canyons as it flows through the Sierra foothills, leaving the western boundary of Yosemite National Park and entering the [[Stanislaus National Forest]]. Most of the Tuolumne's main tributaries join within this reach, beginning with [[Cherry Creek (Tuolumne River)|Cherry Creek]] from the north just below the intake of the [[Hetch Hetchy Aqueduct]], which delivers water to San Francisco. The South Fork of the Tuolumne joins from the south a few miles downstream, near [[Groveland-Big Oak Flat, California|Groveland-Big Oak Flat]], followed by the [[Clavey River]] from the north a few miles after that.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/tributaries |publisher=Tuolumne River Trust |work=The Watershed |title=Tributaries |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151023013312/http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/tributaries |archivedate=23 October 2015 }}</ref> The North Fork of the Tuolumne joins from the north near the upper end of [[Don Pedro Reservoir|Lake Don Pedro]], which was formed in 1971 when the [[New Don Pedro Dam]] was built to provide hydroelectricity and irrigation water storage. Directly below Don Pedro Dam is the [[La Grange Dam]], where about half the river's natural flow is diverted into the Turlock and Modesto Main Canals to irrigate over {{convert|200000|acre|ha}} in the Central Valley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.org/about/fastfacts.html|title=MID Fast Facts|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"tid.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tid.org/water/irrigation|title=Irrigation|publisher=Turlock Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Don-Pedro-Lake-Panorama-2005-11-24.jpg|thumb|left|400px|Lake Don Pedro, in the foothills east of [[La Grange, California|La Grange]], is the Tuolumne's largest reservoir.]]\nLeaving the foothills, the Tuolumne flows approximately {{convert|50|mi|km}} west across the Central Valley to its confluence with the San Joaquin River, passing [[Waterford, California|Waterford]], [[Hughson, California|Hughson]], [[Empire, California|Empire]], [[Ceres, California|Ceres]] and [[Modesto, California|Modesto]]. The lower Tuolumne is wide and slow-flowing, dropping just {{convert|230|ft|m}} from the base of La Grange Dam to its mouth at {{convert|26|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"ACME\">{{cite map\n|publisher=ACME Mapper\n|title=USGS Topo Maps for United States\n|year=\n|cartography=[[United States Geological Survey]]\n|accessdate=2009-10-29\n|url=http://mapper.acme.com/}}</ref> [[California State Route 99|Highway 99]] and the [[Southern Pacific Railroad]] tracks both cross the river in Modesto, and the [[Modesto Airport]] is located adjacent to the river shortly upstream. [[Dry Creek (Tuolumne River)|Dry Creek]] joins the Tuolumne from the north between the airport and the railroad. The confluence of the Tuolumne and San Joaquin is located in the [[San Joaquin River National Wildlife Refuge]], about {{convert|2|mi|km}} north of [[Grayson, California|Grayson]] in [[Stanislaus County, California|Stanislaus County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuolumne.org/content/fmd/files/DosRios_Background%20%282%29.pdf|title=Dos Rios Ranch|publisher=Tuolumne River Trust|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref>\n\n===Discharge===\n[[Image:O\u2019Shaughnessy Dam looking downstream towards the Poopenaut Valley - panoramio.jpg|thumb|right|Flood water is released from Hetch Hetchy Reservoir into the Tuolumne River]]\nBy volume, the Tuolumne is the largest river draining the southern Sierra, with an estimated virgin flow of {{convert|1850000|acre feet|km3}} per year \u2013 over {{convert|2550|cuft/s|m3/s}}.<ref name=\"river-system\"/> Near the river's mouth, the highest recorded annual volume was {{convert|3995000|acre feet|km3}} or {{convert|5518|cuft/s|m3/s}} in 1983, and the lowest was {{convert|134000|acre feet|km3}} or {{convert|185|cuft/s|m3/s}} in 1977 \u2013 a 30:1 difference.<ref name=\"modesto\">{{cite web|url=http://wdr.water.usgs.gov/wy2013/pdfs/11290000.2013.pdf|work=Water Data Report 2013|title=Tuolumne River at Modesto, CA|publisher=USGS|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Although most of the flow in the river originates from summer snowmelt, massive floods can occur following heavy winter storms.<ref name=\"river-system\"/> The natural flow of the Tuolumne at the mouth is greatly reduced by diversions to both San Francisco's Hetch Hetchy municipal water system and the canals of the Modesto and Turlock irrigation districts.\n\nThe [[United States Geological Survey]] (USGS) operates, or has operated, several stream gages along the Tuolumne River. Today, average annual river flows reach a maximum in the short stretch between Don Pedro Dam and La Grange Dam, about {{convert|50|mi|km}} above the mouth, before the start of large irrigation diversions. A USGS gage recorded an average annual flow of {{convert|2343|cuft/s|m3/s}} here between 1911 and 1970, with a maximum peak of {{convert|60300|cuft/s|m3/s}} on January 31, 1911, and a minimum monthly mean of {{convert|57.5|cuft/s|m3/s}} in October 1912.<ref name=\"Abvlagrange\"/> During the [[Great Flood of 1862]], the river reached an estimated peak of {{convert|130000|cuft/s|m3/s}}<ref name=\"modestopeak\"/> here, after a record {{convert|72|in|mm}} of rain fell in the Tuolumne River basin between November 11, 1861 and January 14, 1862, as recorded at [[Sonora, California|Sonora]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redlandsfortnightly.org/papers/Taylor06.htm|publisher=Fortnightly Club of Redlands|title=The Great California Flood Of 1862|first1=WL|last1=Taylor|first2=RW|last2=Taylor|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The gage was not in place during this time.<ref name=\"modestopeak\">{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/peak?site_no=11288000&agency_cd=USGS&format=html|publisher=USGS|work=Surface Water for USA|title=Peak Streamflow|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nFurther downstream, the USGS gage at Modesto \u2013 about {{convert|10|mi|km}} above the mouth \u2013 recorded an annual mean of {{convert|1326|cuft/s|m3/s}} between 1940 and 2013. The highest peak was {{convert|57000|cuft/s|m3/s}} on December 9, 1950, and the lowest daily mean was {{convert|56|cuft/s|m3/s}} on August 6, 1977.<ref name=\"modesto\"/>\n\n==Watershed==\n\n===Physiography===\nThe Tuolumne River watershed can be divided into three distinct physiographic regions. From the headwaters to below Hetch Hetchy Reservoir, the river drains the Sierra highlands, which are characterized by solid, [[glacier]]-carved granitic bedrock, thin poor soils and areas of heavy forestation. Most of the snowpack that feeds the Tuolumne accumulates in this region.{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=7}} Streams are generally high-gradient, clear and rocky, but large [[alpine meadow]]s provide riparian and wetland habitat, which contribute sediment to the watershed's runoff. There are also a large number of natural lakes and tarns in the upper watershed. The Sierra crest harbors a number of glaciers, including Lyell and Maclure Glaciers, the largest in Yosemite National Park. Melting ice feeds the upper reaches of the Tuolumne River, maintaining water flow in the late summer when many other streams in the region are dry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/yose/blogs/Lyell-Glacier.htm|title=Lyell Glacier|publisher=National Park Service|work=Yosemite National Park|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The Lyell Glacier is the second largest in the Sierra Nevada, after [[Palisade Glacier]] at the headwaters of [[Big Pine Creek (California)|Big Pine Creek]] a tributary of the [[Owens River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5195705.pdf|title=Wilderness Hiking, Big Pine Canyon, Inyo National Forest|publisher=USFS|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Both Lyell and Maclure glaciers have shrunk significantly since the late 1800s when measurements were first made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/yose/parknews/lyellglacier.htm|title=Yosemite National Park's Largest Glacier Stagnant|work=Yosemite National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nBetween Hetch Hetchy Reservoir and the upper end of Lake Don Pedro the Tuolumne flows through the Sierra foothills, where it has a lower gradient but continues to maintain a fast current. Stream pools and gravel bars figure more prominently in the channel, allowing the growth of riparian habitat. By the time the river reaches Lake Don Pedro it has accumulated almost 90 percent of its total flow as precipitation run-off, [[snowmelt]] and [[groundwater]] [[Baseflow|base flow]].{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|pp=4-10}} Below Don Pedro Dam the river flows across the large [[alluvial plain]] of the San Joaquin Valley, formed by millions of years of sediment deposits eroded from the Sierra. Historically this section of the river was subject to frequent course changes and formed thousands of acres of seasonal wetlands during the spring floods. Since the introduction of large-scale agriculture the Tuolumne River course has been fixed between an extensive system of levees. More than {{convert|300000|acre|ha}} in the San Joaquin Valley are irrigated using Tuolumne water.{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=8}}\n\nAbout {{convert|669|mi2|km2}}, or 34&nbsp;percent, of the Tuolumne River watershed is inside Yosemite National Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.us-parks.com/yosemite-national-park/watersheds.html|work=Yosemite National Park|title=Watersheds|publisher=us-parks.com|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The rivers whose watersheds border that of the Tuolumne are the [[Stanislaus River]] and [[West Walker River]] in the north, the [[Merced River]] in the south, the [[East Walker River]] to the northeast, the [[Mono Lake]] basin ([[Mill Creek (Mono Lake)|Mill Creek]], [[Lee Vining Creek]] and [[Rush Creek (Mono County, California)|Rush Creek]]) to the east, and the headwaters of the San Joaquin River proper to the southeast.\n\n====Tributaries====\nMajor tributaries of the Tuolumne and pertinent data are listed in the below table. Order is from the headwaters downstream.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Coordinates\n!Elevation\n!Distance<br>from mouth<ref name=\"ACME\"/>\n!Length<ref name=\"Streamer\"/>\n!Watershed\n!Discharge\n!Bank{{#tag:ref|R stands for right bank, L for left bank}}\n!Image\n|-\n|[[Dana Fork Tuolumne River]]\n|{{coord|37|52|31|N|119|21|08|W}}<ref name=\"DanaGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=253658|name=Dana Fork|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|8,589}} ft<br>(2,618 m)<ref name=\"DanaGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|149}} mi<br>(240&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|5}} mi<br>(8&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|[[Image:Dana Meadows Yosemite.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Lyell Fork Tuolumne River]]\n|{{coord|37|52|31|N|119|21|08|W}}<ref name=\"LyellGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=253533|name=Lyell Fork|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|8,589}} ft<br>(2,618 m)<ref name=\"LyellGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|149}} mi<br>(240&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|7}} mi<br>(11&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|L\n|[[Image:Lyell Canyon.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Return Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|55|55|N|119|27|58|W}}<ref name=\"ReturnGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=265379|name=Return Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|6,204}} ft<br>(1,891 m)<ref name=\"ReturnGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|139}} mi<br>(224&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|14}} mi<br>(23&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|\n|-\n|[[Piute Creek (Tuolumne River)|Piute Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|55|48|N|119|36|03|W}}<ref name=\"PiuteGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id253760|name=Piute Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|4344}} ft<br>(1,324 m)\n|{{nts|130}} mi<br>(209&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|20}} mi<br>(32&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|\n|-\n|[[Rancheria Creek (Tuolumne County, California)|Rancheria Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|57|12|N|119|43|41|W}}<ref name=\"RancheriaGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=265177|name=Rancheria Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|3,796}} ft<br>(1,157 m)<ref name=\"RancheriaGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|121}} mi<br>(195&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|24}} mi<br>(39&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|[[Image:Rapids_below_Rancheria_Falls_-_panoramio.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Falls Creek (California)|Falls Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|57|47|N|119|45|55|W}}<ref name=\"FallsGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=260042|name=Falls Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|3783}} ft<br>(1,153 m)<ref name=\"FallsGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|119}} mi<br>(192&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|23}} mi<br>(37&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|[[Image:Wapama Falls in Yosemite NP.JPG|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Cherry Creek (California)|Cherry Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|53|19|N|119|58|19|W}}<ref name=\"CherryGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=258242|name=Cherry Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|2,162}} ft<br>(659 m)<ref name=\"CherryGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|104}} mi<br>(167&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|42}} mi<br>(68&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|234}} mi<sup>2</sup><br>(607&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>)<ref name=\"Cherryflow\">{{cite web|url=http://wdr.water.usgs.gov/wy2013/pdfs/11278400.2013.pdf|work=Water Data Report 2013|publisher=USGS|title=Cherry Creek below Dion R. Holm Powerplant, near Mather, CA}}</ref>\n|{{nts|694}} cfs<br>(19.7 m<sup>3</sup>/s)<ref name=\"Cherryflow\"/>\n|R\n|[[Image:Cherry Lake Stanislaus National Forest.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[South Fork Tuolumne River]]\n|{{coord|37|50|25|N|120|02|52|W}}<ref name=\"SfGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=267514|name=South Fork Tuolumne River|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|1,447}} ft<br>(441 m)<ref name=\"SfGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|96}} mi<br>(155&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|31}} mi<br>(50&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|164}} mi<sup>2</sup><br>(425&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>)<ref name=\"SFflow\">{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/monthly/?referred_module=sw&amp;site_no=11282500&amp;por_11282500_1=2208852,00060,1,1911-10,1921-09&amp;format=html_table&amp;date_format=YYYY-MM-DD&amp;rdb_compression=file&amp;submitted_form=parameter_selection_list|publisher=USGS|work=Surface Water data for USA|title=Surface-Water Monthly Statistics|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n|{{nts|167}} cfs<br>(4.7 m<sup>3</sup>/s)<ref name=\"SFflow\"/>\n|L\n|[[Image:Rainbow Pools on the South Fork of the Tuolumne River.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Clavey River]]\n|{{coord|37|51|50|N|120|06|59|W}}<ref name=\"ClaveyGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=266572|name=Clavey River|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|1,178}} ft<br>(359 m)<ref name=\"ClaveyGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|91}} mi<br>(147&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|42}} mi<br>(68&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|157}} mi<sup>2</sup><br>(407&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calwater.ca.gov/Admin_Record/I-006319.pdf|title=Clavey River Watershed Analysis|publisher=USFS|year=1997|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref>\n|{{nts|255}} cfs<br>(7.2 m<sup>3</sup>/s)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/monthly/?referred_module=sw&amp;site_no=11283500&amp;por_11283500_1=2208860,00060,1,1959-10,1995-06&amp;format=html_table&amp;date_format=YYYY-MM-DD&amp;rdb_compression=file&amp;submitted_form=parameter_selection_list|publisher=USGS|work=Surface Water data for USA|title=Surface-Water Monthly Statistics|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n|R\n|\n|-\n|[[North Fork Tuolumne River]]\n|{{coord|37|53|49|N|120|15|14|W}}<ref name=\"NfGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=234378|name=North Fork Tuolumne River|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|853}} ft<br>(260 m)<ref name=\"NfGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|81}} mi<br>(130&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|36}} mi<br>(58&nbsp;km)\n|\n|{{nts|54}} cfs<br>(1.5 m<sup>3</sup>/s)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/monthly/?referred_module=sw&amp;site_no=11285000&amp;por_11285000_1=2208865,00060,1,1958-10,1966-09&amp;format=html_table&amp;date_format=YYYY-MM-DD&amp;rdb_compression=file&amp;submitted_form=parameter_selection_list|publisher=USGS|work=Surface Water data for USA|title=Surface-Water Monthly Statistics|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n|R\n|\n|-\n|[[Woods Creek (Tuolumne River)|Woods Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|50|45|N|120|22|41|W}}<ref name=\"WoodsGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=274569|name=Woods Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|791}} ft<br>(241 m)<ref name=\"WoodsGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|68}} mi<br>(109&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|28}} mi<br>(45&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|\n|-\n|[[Dry Creek (Tuolumne River)|Dry Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|53|49|N|120|15|14|W}}<ref name=\"DryGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=\t259548|name=Dry Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|46}} ft<br>(14 m)<ref name=\"DryGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|10}} mi<br>(16&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|63}} mi<br>(101&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|\n|}\n\n===Land use===\n{{expand section|date=May 2015}}\nAlmost 80&nbsp;percent of the Tuolumne River watershed lies above [[New Don Pedro Dam]] and is primarily forested with some alpine, meadow and grassland zones.<ref>http://www.tudwater.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Sec2_T-S-RegionDescription_021313_w-TRK.pdf</ref> The primary land use in the lower Tuolumne River watershed is agriculture, but there are also significant urbanized areas.<ref>http://www.sjrg.org/EIR/supplemental/sup_chpt8.htm</ref> Although only about {{convert|68000|acre|ha}} (5.4&nbsp;percent) of the watershed itself are farmed, river water is used to irrigate almost five times that area outside the watershed boundaries. About {{convert|16500|acre|ha}} (1.3&nbsp;percent) of the watershed are urbanized, mostly in the Greater Modesto area. About 550,000 people inhabit the Tuolumne River watershed as a whole, with approximately 210,000 living in Modesto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.modestogov.com/ed/demographics/population.asp |title=Population |publisher=City of Modesto |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150902033730/http://www.modestogov.com/ed/demographics/population.asp |archivedate=2 September 2015 }}</ref>{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=4}}\n\n===Engineering and flood control===\nLike most other Sierra Nevada rivers, the Tuolumne has been extensively dammed to provide flood control, water supply, and hydroelectric power.<ref name=\"tldownstream\">http://sf-planning.org/sites/default/files/FileCenter/Documents/7941-2005.0159E_vol3_sec5-3_wsip_finalpeir.pdf</ref> The uppermost dam is the O'Shaughnessy, which impounds the {{convert|360000|acre feet|m3|adj=on}} Hetch Hetchy Reservoir, providing water and power to the City of San Francisco. The Hetch Hetchy hydroelectric system diverts large volumes of water into tunnels that feed two hydroelectric plants, the Kirkwood and the Moccasin. The power system is efficient because of the Tuolumne's great drop, over {{convert|2750|ft|m}}, between Hetch Hetchy and the outlet of Moccasin Powerhouse. However, it also causes dewatering of significant portions of the Tuolumne River, especially during low water summers when all but a minimal fish release is diverted through the power plants. Not all of the flow used by the power plants is returned to the river. About {{convert|244000|acre feet|m3}} per year flows through the gravity fed Hetch Hetchy Aqueduct to serve San Francisco and its customer municipalities.<ref name=\"tldownstream\"/> Due to the pristine quality of the water, the Hetch Hetchy system is one of only a few serving major cities in the United States that does not require filtration.\n\n[[Image:Hetchhetchyprojmap.jpg|thumb|right|360px|The Hetch Hetchy Project provides Tuolumne water to the city of San Francisco.]]\nCherry Creek, the Tuolumne's biggest tributary, is also part of the San Francisco hydroelectric system. Cherry Creek is dammed at the Cherry Valley Dam, which creates {{convert|274000|acre feet|m3|adj=on}} [[Cherry Lake]]. A major tributary, Eleanor Creek, is dammed to form [[Lake Eleanor]], and diverted into Cherry Lake through a tunnel. The combined flow is channeled into a penstock and returns to the river at the Holm Powerhouse. Unlike the Hetch Hetchy system, the Cherry Creek system is used exclusively for hydropower, not water supply, because the water quality is not quite as good. However, there is a connecting aqueduct that allows Cherry Lake to be tapped to supply the Hetch Hetchy system during severe droughts. This backup water supply was last used during late 2015, as a test to ensure its functionality should drought conditions become worse.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/sf-water-to-be-mixed-with-filtered-water-as-city-tests-drought-preparedness/|title=SF water to be mixed with filtered water as city tests drought preparedness|publisher=The San Francisco Examiner|first=Michael|last=Barba|date=October 9, 2015}}</ref> The previous time it was used was 1988.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/science/article/California-drought-2-reservoirs-near-Hetch-5321213.php|title=California drought: 2 reservoirs near Hetch Hetchy tapped|publisher=SFGate|first=Marisa|last=Lagos|date=March 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Tuolumne River Modesto.jpg|thumb|right|Tuolumne River in Modesto]]\nBelow the confluence with the North Fork of the Tuolumne the river flows into Lake Don Pedro, the largest in the Tuolumne River system and the sixth-largest man made lake in California at {{convert|2030000|acre feet|m3}}. The earth-filled New Don Pedro Dam, {{convert|585|ft|m}} high, is the 10th tallest dam in the United States and was constructed as a multipurpose project, serving irrigation, municipal water supply, hydropower and flood control. It replaced an earlier concrete dam built on approximately the same site. The Turlock and Modesto Irrigation Districts control the lion's share of water in the reservoir, although the City of San Francisco also has storage rights, which it uses mainly to offset the effects of water diverted upstream at Hetch Hetchy. Because of the desire to increase water storage for other uses, only {{convert|340000|acre feet|m3}} of the reservoir is designated flood control, which is relatively small compared to other reservoirs in California. As a result, Don Pedro frequently fills and spills during winter storms, causing damage downstream.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe La Grange Dam, a much smaller masonry diversion dam, is the last one on the Tuolumne before it joins with the San Joaquin. Modesto Canal, on the north side of the river, and Turlock Canal, on the south side, are both large irrigation diversions. The Modesto Canal feeds the {{convert|29000|acre feet|m3|adj=on}} off-stream Modesto Reservoir, which regulates the water for distribution to farmers. The Turlock Lake is regulated by the similar but much larger Turlock Lake, which has a capacity of {{convert|49000|acre feet|m3|adj=on}}. The estimated annual diversion for irrigation is {{convert|867000|acre feet|m3}}, about half of the Tuolumne River's natural flow.<ref name=\"tldownstream\"/>\n\nBelow La Grange, the Tuolumne \u2013 much reduced due to irrigation diversions \u2013 flows through a fixed channel with a highly restricted [[floodplain]]. Before agriculture, the river inundated large areas of seasonal marshland and was free to change course during its frequent floods. Today farms and communities are protected by a [[levee]] system with a channel capacity of roughly {{convert|9000|cuft/s|m3/s}} at the 9th St. Bridge in Modesto \u2013 significantly smaller than the river's maximum flood potential. The valley is dependent on flood control storage at Lake Don Pedro to prevent flows from exceeding the channel capacity. However, this has happened many times, most infamously during the [[New Year's Flood of 1997]], during which inflows to Don Pedro hit {{convert|120000|cuft/s|m3/s}}, the largest recorded since the [[Great Flood of 1862]]. Water releases from Don Pedro Dam peaked at {{convert|60000|cuft/s|m3/s}}; while this vastly reduced potential damage from the flood, it still exceeded the channel capacity by six times, causing extensive property damage along the river.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.water.ca.gov/historicaldocs/irwm/feat-1997/fcsia2.html|title=Final Report of the Flood Emergency Action Team|year=1997|publisher=State of California|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Fish, plants and wildlife===\nThe Tuolumne once supported large spring and fall runs of [[chinook salmon]] (king salmon, ''Oncorhynchus tshawytscha'') and [[Rainbow trout|steelhead trout]] (''Oncorhynchus mykiss''). In its native state the fall Chinook run alone may have numbered as high as 130,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://water4fish.org/other-rivers/|title=Other Rivers|publisher=water4fish.org|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> With the exception of the [[Merced River]] immediately south, this is the southernmost existing population of Chinook salmon in North America.<ref>http://www.westcoast.fisheries.noaa.gov/publications/recovery_planning/salmon_steelhead/domains/california_central_valley/appendix_a_watershed_profiles_7102014.pdf</ref> Massive irrigation diversions and river channelization projects have led to the extinction of the spring Chinook run and greatly reduced the fall run. Dams have blocked more than half of the original {{convert|99|mi|km}} of migratory fish spawning habitat in the Tuolumne River watershed. The San Joaquin River and the [[Sacramento\u2013San Joaquin River Delta]], which link the Tuolumne salmon runs to the Pacific, have also been affected by flow reduction and pollution. In addition, introduced species such as [[striped bass]] prey on juvenile salmon, consuming as much as 93&nbsp;percent of smolt before they can migrate to the sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://westernfarmpress.com/government/tuolumne-river-93-percent-juvenile-salmon-consumed-predators|title=Tuolumne River: 93 percent of juvenile salmon consumed by predators|publisher=Western Farm Press|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> A controversial proposal by the State Water Resources Control Board from around 2013 would require increased spring and summer flows on the Tuolumne River which would benefit native [[Fish migration|anadromous]] fish populations, but greatly reduce the water supply available for farms and cities. This has been countered by irrigation districts who maintain that the aforementioned predation, not low flows, are the primary cause of salmon smolt deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.turlockcitynews.com/news/item/199-fish-predation-not-flows-causing-salmon-death-on-tuolumne|title=Fish Predation, Not Flows, Causing Salmon Death on Tuolumne|last=|first=|date=2013-02-19|website=|publisher=Turlock City News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nForests in the watershed are divided between several distinct zones. The foothill region is characterized by trees and plants adapted to a hot, dry climate, including [[Adenostoma fasciculatum|chamise]] (greasewood), [[Ceanothus|California lilac]], [[manzanita]], [[Quercus douglasii|blue oak]], [[Quercus wislizeni|interior live oak]] (Sierra live oak), and [[Pinus sabiniana|gray pine]]. Further east and higher in elevation are the lower and upper montane forests, which lie between {{convert|3000|to|6000|ft|m}} and {{convert|6000|to|8000|ft|m}} elevation, respectively. The lower montane forests include [[Quercus kelloggii|black oak]], [[Pinus ponderosa|ponderosa pine]], [[Calocedrus|incense cedar]] and [[Abies concolor|white fir]]; higher up [[Jeffrey pine]] and [[Juniperus occidentalis|western juniper]] appear. Higher still is the subalpine forest zone between {{convert|8000|to|9500|ft|m}}, which is dominated by [[Western white pine]], [[Tsuga mertensiana|mountain hemlock]] and [[Pinus contorta|lodgepole pine]]. Above 9500 feet, only small shrubs, flowering plants and occasional [[Pinus albicaulis|whitebark pine]]{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=56}} populate the alpine zone, which is limited to the peaks around Tuolumne Meadows and along the Sierra Crest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/ecosystems |publisher=Tuolumne River Trust |work=The Watershed |title=Ecosystems |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151023024138/http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/ecosystems |archivedate=23 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\nHumans have influenced natural conditions in the Tuolumne River watershed for centuries. Native Americans set [[Controlled burn|controlled fires]] in grassland to clear out dead foliage, providing room for new growth which in turn attracted game animals to forage. They also periodically burned out oak woodland areas in the foothills to control pests, which otherwise would have affected their main food supply, acorns. During the Spanish and Mexican periods, the Central Valley was used for cattle ranching, which quickly decimated natural range grasses. During the 1880s American sheep ranchers brought their herds into the upper Tuolumne River watershed for summer pasture, which further damaged the range in the foothills and Sierras. Hetch Hetchy Valley was one of the main summer grazing areas for sheep. The decline of native [[perennial plant|perennial]] grasses caused invasive [[annual plant|annual]] species to flourish, and also increased the susceptibility of the watershed to [[wildfire]]s. In order to protect property and watershed quality, intensive fire suppression began in the early 20th century. However, this led to overgrowth and a disruption of the natural [[Forest dynamics|forest succession]] process that was previously driven by wildfires.{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=69\u201370}}\n\n==Geology==\n{{expand section|date=May 2015}}\n\n==Early history==\nEstimates of the first human habitation along the Tuolumne River range from 3000\u20137000 BC.<ref name=\"earlyhist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/humans |publisher=Tuolumne River Trust |work=The Watershed |title=Early Humans |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151023013316/http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/humans |archivedate=23 October 2015 }}</ref> The [[Plains and Sierra Miwok]], who were the largest regional Native American group immediately prior to European contact, first established themselves in the area around 1200 CE.<ref name=\"earlyhist\"/> The Miwok lived in the Sierra foothills and Central Valley lowlands during winter and traveled into the upper Tuolumne River in summer to hunt, as well as seek refuge from the summer heat. The [[Northern Paiute|Paiute]], who inhabited the Great Basin on the east side of the Sierra, also ventured into the Tuolumne River basin during the summer.<ref name=\"HetchHetchyBattle\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/battleoverhetchh00righ|url-access=registration|title=The Battle over Hetch Hetchy : America's Most Controversial Dam and the Birth of Modern Environmentalism|page=[https://archive.org/details/battleoverhetchh00righ/page/14 14]|first=Robert W.|last=Righter|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2005|isbn=978-0-19-803410-0}}</ref> The [[Yokuts people|Yokuts]] lived along the lower Tuolumne River and were not known to venture up into the Sierra during summer.\n\n[[Image:117.TuolumneRiver.JPG|thumb|left|Tuolumne River in West Meadow, Tuolumne Meadows]]\nThe chief meeting point of the Paiute and Miwok was the Hetch Hetchy Valley, rich in edible plants and game. The origin of the name \"Hetch Hetchy\" may have been a type of edible grass that grew in the valley, which native peoples made into grain and ground in stone mortars for meal.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N3Rs7E7_J_IC&pg=PA63|title=Yosemite Place Names|first=Peter|last=Browning|publisher=Great West Books|year=2005|page=63|isbn=978-0-944220-19-1}}</ref>\nThey set controlled fires to clear out old vegetation in their gathering areas, allowing for more efficient harvesting of new growth.<ref name=\"earlyhist\"/> This would also increase the prevalence of grasses and ferns, attracting game animals such as deer, and made the landscape more easily navigable. Many of the landscapes in the Tuolumne River area encountered by the first European explorers were thus not pristine but the result of hundreds of years of management; indeed, the famous meadows of Hetch Hetchy Valley prior to its damming only existed because of the annual burn.<ref name=\"HetchHetchyBattle\"/>\n\nThe origin of the Tuolumne River's name is unclear. The first recorded use of the name \"Tuolumne\" was by the Spanish explorer [[Gabriel Moraga]] in 1806, who may have named the river for the nearby Native American village of ''Tualamne'' or ''Tautamne''. This may in turn refer to the native word ''talmalamne'', or \"a group of stone huts or caves\". Father Pedro Mu\u00f1oz, a member of the 1806 expedition, noted in his diary that \"we came upon a village called Tautamne. This village is situated on some steep precipices, inaccessible on account of their rough rocks. The Indians live in their s\u00f3tanos [cellars or caves]\".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_ZWjAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA500&lpg=PA500|title=Historic Spots In California: Valley and Sierra Counties|first1=HE|last1=Rensch|first2=EG|last2=Rensch|first3=MB|last3=Hoover|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1932|page=500|isbn=978-0-8047-1615-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Gudde | first=E.G. | title=California Place Names: A Geographical Dictionary | publisher=University of California Press | year=1949 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-22djGNuhwC&pg=SL3-PA240 | page=240}}</ref> At this time, the Native American population along the lower Tuolumne and Stanislaus Rivers is believed to have been approximately two thousand.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D8jzdPSQAzcC&pg=PA7|title=Sonora|first=Michael|last=Gahagan|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2007|page=7|isbn=978-0-7385-4783-1}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:GrandCanyonTuolumneRiver.jpg|thumb|right|Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne, circa 1914]]\nAnother possible origin of the name ''Tuolumne'' is the Central Sierra Miwok word ''taawal\u00efmi'', meaning \"squirrel place\", referring to a Native American village on the nearby Stanislaus River.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tcMnAy6m5doC&pg=PA159|title=1500 California Place Names|first=William|last=Bright|publisher=University of California Press|year=1998|edition=3rd|page=159|isbn=978-0-520-92054-5}}</ref> The suffix ''-umne'', which appears in the names of two other California rivers, the [[Mokelumne River|Mokelumne]] and [[Cosumnes River|Cosumnes]], is thought to have meant \"place of\" or \"people of\" in the native language.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/naturalworldof00heiz|url-access=registration|title=The Natural World of the California Indians|first1=RF|last1=Heizer|first2=AB|last2=Elsasser|publisher=University of California Press|year=1980|page=[https://archive.org/details/naturalworldof00heiz/page/15 15]|isbn=978-0-520-03896-7}}</ref>\n\nThe Tuolumne River was the scene of significant gold mining activity during the [[California Gold Rush]]. The first known discovery of gold in the area was made by Benjamin Wood, a prospector from Oregon, in the summer of 1848. During the latter part of that year and early 1849, mining camps were established along the Tuolumne, including Jamestown, Tuttletown, Melones, Don Pedros Bar, and Shaws Flat.<ref name=\"gold\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tchistory.org/TCHISTORY/Gold_Tuolumne.htm|title=Gold in Tuolumne County|publisher=Tuolumne County Historical Society|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The following spring a party of Mexican miners from [[Sonora]] discovered an even richer deposit farther upstream, establishing Sonoranian Camp, predecessor of the present-day town of [[Sonora, California]].<!--<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.examiner.com/article/sonora-california-and-the-start-of-mining-along-the-tuolumne-river|title=Sonora, California and the start of mining along the Tuolumne River|publisher=San Francisco Examiner|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>--> By the end of 1849, there were over 10,000 miners in the Tuolumne River area, half of them in Sonora, which became the Tuolumne County seat in 1850.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O0Ypj5Te8DIC&pg=PA197&lpg=PA198|title=A Self-governing Dominion, California, 1849-1860|first=William Henry|last=Ellison|publisher=University of California Press|year=1978|page=197|isbn=978-0-520-03713-7}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:VIEW OF WEST FACE AND TUOLUMNE RIVER. - Tuolumne Meadows Bridge, Spanning Tuolumne River on Tioga Road, Mather, Tuolumne County, CA HAER CAL,55-TOULM,2-6.tif|thumb|right|[[Tioga Road]], originally a Gold Rush-era pack trail, crosses the Tuolumne at Tuolumne Meadows.]]\nMining activity increased dramatically in the early 1850s, with prospectors pushing up into the foothills beyond [[Soulsbyville, California|Soulsbyville]].<ref name=\"gold\"/> In March 1850, an \"enormously rich\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oISiKnZz-HcC&pg=106|title=Gold: The California Story|first=Mary|last=Hill|publisher=University of California Press|year=1999|page=106|isbn=978-0-520-21547-4}}</ref> deposit was discovered at Columbia. The same year, the Bonanza Mine near Sonora yielded a 1500-ounce nugget, the fourth largest ever discovered in California.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oISiKnZz-HcC&pg=258|title=Gold: The California Story|first=Mary|last=Hill|publisher=University of California Press|year=1999|page=258|isbn=978-0-520-21547-4}}</ref> (The largest was found in [[Carson Hill, California|Carson Hill]] in Calaveras County, just north of the Tuolumne River watershed along the [[Stanislaus River]], in 1854.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museumca.org/goldrush/dist-carsonhill.html|title=Carson Hill|work=Gold Districts of California|publisher=Oakland Museum of California|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>) The prosperity in the region prompted a search for a new crossing of the Sierra Nevada that would provide more direct access to the camps from the east. The Clark-Skidmore Party made this crossing in 1852 via the upper Stanislaus River and the north fork of the Tuolumne.<ref name=\"earlyhist\"/> Parts of the route they established eventually formed the Walker River Trail, regarded as one of the more difficult of the main Sierra crossings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sonorapasspioneers.com/1852.html|work=Sonora Pass Emigrants and Tuolumne County California Pioneers|title=The Clark-Skidmore Party, 1852|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor a brief period the lower Tuolumne became a major [[steamboat]] route, ferrying prospectors and supplies from [[Stockton, California|Stockton]].<ref name=\"earlyhist\"/> Depending on water level, approximately {{convert|35|mi|km}} of the lower river were navigable, from the mouth to above [[Waterford, California|Waterford]].<ref name=\"waterford\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l2CKNfLDt5MC&pg=PA7|title=Waterford|first=Jeff|last=Benziger|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2011|page=7|isbn=978-1-4396-3926-9}}</ref> The unpredictable nature of the river made both navigating and crossing difficult, so starting in the Gold Rush era many ferries were established, one of the first at Dickenson's Ferry in the early 1850s. This particular location was the crossing of Fort Miller Road (Millerton Road), a major land trade route that connected Stockton with [[Millerton, Madera County, California|Millerton]] near present-day Fresno (today the site of the [[Millerton Lake]] reservoir).<ref name=\"ferries\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/historicspotsinc00rens|url-access=registration|title=Historic Spots in California|first1=MB|last1=Hoover|first2=HE|last2=Rensch|first3=EG|last3=Rensch|editor-first=WN|editor-last=Abeloe|edition=Third|year=1966|publisher=Stanford University Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/historicspotsinc00rens/page/542 542]|isbn=978-0-8047-4020-3}}</ref>\n\nBy 1853, most of the easily mined gold had been exhausted, and [[hydraulic mining]] operations became the dominant extraction method.<ref name=\"gold\"/> The Tuolumne County Water Company, first organized in 1851 to divert water from the Tuolumne River basin to the Stanislaus River, constructed a network of reservoirs, ditches and flumes initially used for mining and later for irrigation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tudwater.com/pdf/2012_pdf/Engineering/rpt_hrer_public_web_2012.pdf|publisher=Tuolumne Utilities District|work=Ditch Sustainability Project|title=Historic Resource Evaluation Report|accessdate=2015-10-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409043043/http://www.tudwater.com/pdf/2012_pdf/Engineering/rpt_hrer_public_web_2012.pdf|archivedate=2016-04-09}}</ref> The Golden Rock Water Company, incorporated in 1855, diverted the South Fork of the Tuolumne to supply the diggings at [[Groveland, California|Groveland]] and [[Big Oak Flat, California|Big Oak Flat]]; their most notable achievement was the construction of a {{convert|2200|ft|m|adj=on}} long, {{convert|265|ft|m|adj=on}} high aqueduct (the Big Gap Flume) over [[Buck Meadows, California|Buck Meadows]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinemountainlake.com/Page/21389~335627/Mountain-Lifeline-Golden-Rock-Flume-System|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128031440/http://pinemountainlake.com/?pg=mountainlifelinegoldenrocksystem|archivedate=2010-11-28|title=Mountain Lifeline Golden Rock System Flowed With New Hope|first=Jean|last=McClish}}</ref> The first dam on the Tuolumne River proper, near [[La Grange, California|La Grange]], was built in 1852 to divert water for hydraulic mining. Sediment and rocks washed down by hydraulic mining and sluicing operations accumulated along the lower Tuolumne, destroying native floodplain habitat<ref name=\"restoration\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fws.gov/lodi/afrp/documents/tuolplan.pdf|title=Habitat Restoration Plan for the Lower Tuolumne River Corridor|publisher=US Fish and Wildlife Service|year=1999|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> and making much of the river unnavigable.<ref name=\"earlyhist\"/>\n\n==Irrigation, power and water supply==\n\n===La Grange and Old Don Pedro Dams===\nAfter the gold rush many miners settled along the lower Tuolumne River as farmers. Ferry sites grew into lively towns, such as at Waterford, where a crossing had been established in 1866.<ref name=\"waterford\"/> The town of [[Tuolumne City, California|Tuolumne City]] was founded near the mouth of the Tuolumne as a port, but it soon became apparent that mining debris had made the river unsuitable for navigation, and the area was abandoned. In the mid-1860s Tuolumne City and Paradise (located about {{convert|5|mi|km}} further up the river) were reestablished as farming communities. The founding of [[Modesto, California|Modesto]] in 1870, along a new railroad through the San Joaquin Valley, drew most of the population away from these towns and others along the Tuolumne.<ref name=\"ferries\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.modestogov.com/localInfo/cityHistory/ |title=Modesto Historical Information |author=city staff |publisher=City of Modesto |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929024023/http://www.modestogov.com/localinfo/cityhistory/ |archivedate=29 September 2015 }}</ref> By the early 1900s Modesto's population numbered more than four thousand.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bggjmhXp6xsC&pg=PA9&lpg=PA9|title=Modesto|first=Wayne A.|last=Mathes|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2011|page=9|isbn=978-0-7385-7485-1}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:OldDonPedroDam.jpg|thumb|right|The original [[Don Pedro Dam]] was completed in 1923 to provide long-term storage for irrigation.]]\nAs it became apparent that the Central Valley's seasonal rainfall patterns made it unsuitable for [[dryland farming]], farmers organized to build irrigation infrastructure along the Tuolumne River. Turlock Irrigation District (TID), established in 1887, was the first irrigation district in California,<ref name=\"TIDhist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tid.org/about-tid/history|title=History|publisher=Turlock Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> and the Modesto Irrigation District (MID) was established soon after in the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.org/about/history/chpt_03.html|work=Greening of Paradise Valley|title=Chapter 3|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The two districts serve the south and north sides of the river, respectively. The present-day [[La Grange Dam]], completed in 1893, replaced the older mining dam at the same site; at {{convert|122|ft|m}}, it was the highest overflow dam in the United States. The dam diverted the river into canals that water most of the lower valley.<ref name=\"restoration\"/> The first TID farmers received water in 1900.<ref name=\"TIDhist\"/> The MID canal took a total of thirteen years to complete, with the first water deliveries on June 27, 1903.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.org/about/history/chpt_05.html|work=Greening of Paradise Valley|title=Chapter 5|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.org/about/history/chpt_06.html|work=Greening of Paradise Valley|title=Chapter 6|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs the population of the area grew, the Tuolumne River districts soon began to experience seasonal water shortages. The Dallas-Warner Reservoir (today's Modesto Reservoir) was completed in 1912 on the north side of the river, but was only considered a temporary solution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.org/about/history/chpt_09.html|work=Greening of Paradise Valley|title=Chapter 9|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> Construction on the first [[Don Pedro Dam]] began in 1921 to store floodwaters of the Tuolumne proper, allowing for the extension of the irrigation season and to provide water during dry years.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pLXmAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA290|title=Construction of Don Pedro Dam|journal=Engineering World|volume=20-21|page=290|year=1922}}</ref> A secondary purpose for the construction of the dam was that TID and MID were aware that the city of San Francisco, {{convert|160|mi|km}} west of the river, coveted water from the Tuolumne. Although the irrigation districts had the primary rights to the Tuolumne under the [[Prior-appropriation water rights|doctrine of prior appropriation]], those rights could be relinquished under the \"use it or lose it\" rule, so storage had to be developed to enable the full beneficial use of river water.{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010}} Named for the Gold Rush mining camp its reservoir submerged, the Don Pedro dam was completed in 1923, holding back {{convert|289000|acre feet|km3}} of water. In 1923 and 1924 both Don Pedro and La Grange dams were fitted for hydroelectric generation.<ref name=\"TIDhist\"/>\n\n===Hetch Hetchy Project===\nSan Francisco did not move forward with plans to divert the Tuolumne until the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake]] and subsequent fires devastated the city, proving the inadequacy of the existing water system. After exploring fourteen sites throughout Central California, San Francisco had settled on the Tuolumne's Hetch Hetchy Valley as the ideal location to develop storage and hydroelectric power.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/hetchhetchydams00housgoog|title=Hetch Hetchy dam site|author=United States Congressional House Committee on Public Lands|publisher=Govt. Printing Office|year=1913|page=[https://archive.org/details/hetchhetchydams00housgoog/page/n135 131]}}</ref> Because the area had been located inside Yosemite National Park since 1890, the city petitioned for Congress to pass the [[Raker Act]]. Signed in 1913 by President [[Woodrow Wilson]], the Act allowed San Francisco to dam the Tuolumne River, as long as the water and power provided would be reserved exclusively for public utility, not private sale.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/sanfrancisco/100-years-later-sf-water-war-rages-on/Content?oid=2653490|title=100 years after Raker Act was signed, the fight over Hetch Hetchy dam continues|work=The San Francisco Examiner|first=Jonah Owen|last=Lamb|date=December 19, 2013|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfmuseum.org/hetch/hetchy10.html|title=Hetch Hetchy Reservoir Site|publisher=Virtual Museum of the City of San Francisco}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:HTHspillway.jpg|thumb|left|Hetch Hetchy Reservoir and spillway]]\nThe Hetch Hetchy Valley became the center of the first major environmental controversy in the United States. [[John Muir]], the leader of the [[Sierra Club]], spearheaded a legal battle against the proposed [[O'Shaughnessy Dam (California)|O'Shaughnessy Dam]], famously stating \u2013 \"Dam Hetch Hetchy! As well dam for water-tanks the peoples' cathedrals and churches, for no holier temple has ever been consecrated by the heart of man.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vault.sierraclub.org/ca/hetchhetchy/|title=Hetch Hetchy|publisher=Sierra Club|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The Hetch Hetchy debacle is often credited with birthing modern environmentalism, sharply dividing the [[Conservation in the United States#Early American conservation movement|conservation movement]] \u2013 which favored the development of natural resources for public benefit \u2013 and the preservationists, who believed that sites of scenic value like Hetch Hetchy were better left for public recreation and enjoyment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://foundsf.org/index.php?title=The_Hetch_Hetchy_Story,_Part_I:_John_Muir,_Preservationists_vs._Conservationists|title=The Hetch Hetchy Story, Part I: John Muir, Preservationists vs. Conservationists|work=San Francisco Digital Archive|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nDespite the controversy, the city of San Francisco pushed through, beginning construction in early 1914 and filling the reservoir for the first time in May 1923. The [[Hetch Hetchy Railroad]] was built along {{convert|68|mi|km}} of the Tuolumne River Canyon to provide access to the remote construction site. Hydroelectric power reached San Francisco by 1925, but the first water was not delivered until 1934.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://bawsca.org/water-supply/hetch-hetchy-water-system/\n|title=Hetch Hetchy Water System\n|publisher=Bay Area Water Supply & Conservation Agency\n|website=\n|date=\n|accessdate=2014-09-13}}</ref> Today, San Francisco diverts about 33&nbsp;percent of the flow of the Tuolumne at Hetch Hetchy, or 14&nbsp;percent of the river's total flow.\n\n===New Don Pedro Dam and modern development===\nBy the mid 20th century it was clear that storage capacity in Tuolumne River reservoirs was insufficient to meet growing water demands. The irrigation dam at Don Pedro could only store enough water for a single growing season, allowing little carryover for drought years, and on the other hand providing very little flood control.<ref name=\"tid.org\"/> In the late 1950s TID and MID began planning for a high dam on the Tuolumne River several miles below the existing Don Pedro Dam. In 1961 voters approved revenue bonds to fund the project. However, it took until 1966 for the Federal Power Commission (now [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission|FERC]]) to greenlight the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donpedro-relicensing.com/Lists/Announcements/Attachments/16/DP%20Newsletter_Issue1_110502.pdf|title=Don Pedro|volume=1|number=1|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District and Turlock Irrigation District|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Concerns that the new dam would impact [[king salmon]] populations were the primary cause of the delay.<ref>{{cite news\n|author=Cummerow, David\n|title=Growing Storm Wrecked '66 Target Date \u2013 Fish Issue Cost Five Years In Planning New Don Pedro Dam\n|work=The Modesto Bee\n|date=1966-02-17\n}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the dam began in 1967 and the river was diverted in September 1968. The embankment was topped out on May 28, 1970 and the project was formally dedicated on May 22, 1971, after four years of construction and a total cost of over $110 million. It would be eleven years before the new reservoir of {{convert|2030000|acre feet|km3}} \u2013 ten times the size of Old Don Pedro \u2013 filled completely in June 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdec.water.ca.gov/jspplot/jspPlotServlet.jsp?sensor_no=4818&end=03%2F21%2F2015+16%3A35&geom=huge&interval=25000&cookies=cdec01|title=CDEC - Data Application|work=State of California|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The reservoir submerged {{convert|25|mi|km}} of the middle Tuolumne River and {{convert|12000|acre|ha}} of surrounding land, including the historic Gold Rush town of Jacksonville.\n\n===Dam proposals===\n<!--Red Mountain Bar<ref>http://large.stanford.edu/publications/coal/references/docs/tidweb_red_mountain_fact_sheet.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.nwcouncil.org/media/10846/AmyPetersen.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cserc.org/main/news/news_briefs/Don_pedro_plan.html|title=Don Pedro Plans Raise Concerns|publisher=Central Sierra Environmental Research Center|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>-->\nSince the 1970s, the Turlock Irrigation District has proposed damming the Clavey River, a free-flowing tributary of the Tuolumne, to produce hydroelectricity. The dam would have been {{convert|413|ft|m}} high and dried up most of the lower Clavey, a popular whitewater run. In 1994 the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]] studied the project and determined that the benefits would not justify the financial and environmental costs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-01-25/news/mn-24212_1_dam-project|date=January 25, 1995|first=Richard C.|last=Paddock|title=Power Company Shelves Plans to Build Dam Near Yosemite|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-07-30/local/me-21650_1_clavey-river|title=Study Throws Cold Water on Dam Plan|date=July 30, 1994|first=Richard C.|last=Paddock|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Recreation==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2015}}\nThe Tuolumne River watershed receives over a million recreational visits each year, primarily to the protected wilderness areas of Yosemite National Park and to the difficult but popular [[whitewater]] on the Main Tuolumne and Cherry Creek.{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=4}}\n\nThe Tuolumne is considered a classic California whitewater run, and has been used recreationally since the 1960s. Most rafters put in at Meral's Pool, located about {{convert|2|mi|km}} below Cherry Creek, for the {{convert|18|mi|km|adj=on}} run to Lake Don Pedro. Several rafting companies serve the main Tuolumne, a [[International Scale of River Difficulty|Class IV+]] (advanced) river with many rapids changing to Class V when the flow exceeds {{convert|4000|cuft/s|m3/s}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuolumne-river.com/tuolumne.htm|title=Whitewater Rafting on the Tuolumne River|publisher=tuolumne-river.com|accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> The most difficult single rapids is Clavey Falls, located just above the Clavey River; the longest is Grey's Grindstone, at nearly a mile (1.6&nbsp;km). Between these two rapids the swimming holes of the Clavey are a popular camping spot during the summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-w-r.com/rivers/tuolumne-river.html|title=Rafting on Tuolumne River in California|publisher=California Whitewater Rafting|accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> The Cherry Creek is also run by commercial trips. It is considered one of the most difficult whitewater rivers in the entire United States, with fifteen Class V rapids.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aorafting.com/river/cherry-creek/welcome.htm|title=Cherry Creek / Upper Tuolumne River - Whitewater Rafting (Advanced)|work=All-Outdoors California Whitewater Rafting|accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> Both runs are dam controlled, which usually extends the rafting season through the dry late summer and fall.\n\nIn Yosemite National Park, the Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne (from Tuolumne Meadows to Hetch Hetchy Reservoir) was first kayaked in 1983. This {{convert|32|mi|km|adj=on}} segment is rated Class IV-V+, with many waterfalls requiring a portage. In addition to being extremely difficult (if not borderline impossible at the aforementioned waterfalls) the water flow depends entirely on rain and snow melt, and the whitewater season can be extremely short during dry years. The general consensus is \"that the best paddling in is the upper miles while the middle section is better for hikers and canyoneers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/324/|title=Tuolumne Meadows to Hetch Hetchy Reservoir (Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne River)|publisher=American Whitewater|date=2009-03-12|accessdate=2015-10-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Clavey River, not being located in the national park, is open to public access, but due to its remoteness and difficulty (Class V+), and the short window of boatable spring runoff, it is only run by a handful of kayakers each year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.friendsoftheriver.org/site/PageServer?pagename=FORCalRiversClaveyRiver |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-05-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708085201/http://www.friendsoftheriver.org/site/PageServer?pagename=FORCalRiversClaveyRiver |archivedate=2007-07-08 }}</ref>\n\nTo protect the river, the [[U.S. Forest Service]] requires private trips to obtain a permit before floating the Tuolumne.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/stanislaus/recarea/?recid=14975|work=Stanislaus National Forest|title=Tuolumne Wild & Scenic River|publisher=USFS|accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> Running the Tuolumne within Yosemite National Park was also in a legal gray zone until 2015, when the park opened the Tuolumne and [[Merced River|Merced]] Rivers to limited paddling and rafting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canoekayak.com/whitewater-kayak/yosemite-rivers-now-open-paddling/|title=Yosemite Rivers Now Open to Paddling: Management plan for Merced River means more paddling opportunities in the park|author=Buchanan, Eugene|publisher=CanoeKayak.com|date=2015-04-26|accessdate=2015-10-18}}</ref>\n\n== Wildfire ==\nIn 2013, the [[Rim Fire]] burned 257,314 acres.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprd3808811.pdf|title=Rim Fire Recovery Update|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This megafire was, at the time, California's third largest wildfire on record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildfiretoday.com/tag/rim-fire/|title=Rim Fire Archives|website=Wildfire Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref> This wildfire devistated habitat for many native and/or endangered species, and has impacted recreational opportunities, communities and economies alike. \n\n==See also==\n*[[List of rivers of California]]\n*[[Roderick Nash]]\n*[[Tuolumne River Regional Park]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book|editor-last1=Mount|editor-first1=J|editor-first2=S|editor-last2=Purdy|first1=G|last1=Epke|first2=M|last2=Finger|first3=R|last3=Lusardi|first4=N|last4=Marks|first5=A|last5=Nichols|first6=S|last6=Null|first7=T|last7=O\u2019Rear|first8=A|last8=Senter|first9=J|last9=Viers|year=2010|title=Confluence: A Natural and Human History of the Tuolumne River Watershed|publisher=Department of Geology and Center for Watershed Sciences. UC Davis|url=https://watershed.ucdavis.edu/tuolumne/resources/ConfluenceTuolumneV1.pdf|accessdate=2014-09-12|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons+cat}}\n* [http://www.tuolumne-river.com/ Informational Site about rafting on the Tuolumne River]\n* [http://www.caliriver.com/tuolumne/ News and information about rafting the Tuolumne River]\n* [https://www.blm.gov/programs/national-conservation-lands/california/tuolumne-wsr Tuolumne Wild and Scenic River] - BLM page\n\n{{Central Valley Rivers|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tuolumne River| ]]\n[[Category:Rivers of the Sierra Nevada (U.S.)]]\n[[Category:Tributaries of the San Joaquin River]]\n[[Category:Wild and Scenic Rivers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Mariposa County, California]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Stanislaus County, California]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Tuolumne County, California]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Yosemite National Park]]\n[[Category:Geography of Modesto, California]]\n[[Category:Hetch Hetchy Project]]\n[[Category:Geography of the San Joaquin Valley]]\n[[Category:Stanislaus National Forest]]\n[[Category:Biosphere reserves of the United States]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Northern California]]\n[[Category:Rivers of the Sierra Nevada in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n| name               = Tuolumne River\n| name_native        = \n| name_native_lang   = \n| name_other         = \n| name_etymology     = \n<!---------------------- IMAGE & MAP -->\n| image              = Glen Aulin.jpg\n| image_size         = 260\n| image_caption      = The Tuolumne River at [[Glen Aulin]] valley, below Tuolumne Meadows\n| map                = Tuolumnemap-01.png\n| map_size           = 260\n| map_caption        = The Tuolumne River watershed\n| pushpin_map        = \n| pushpin_map_size   = \n| pushpin_map_caption= \n<!---------------------- LOCATION -->\n| subdivision_type1  = Country\n| subdivision_name1  = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type2  = State\n| subdivision_name2  = [[California]]\n| subdivision_type3  = \n| subdivision_name3  = \n| subdivision_type4  = \n| subdivision_name4  = \n| subdivision_type5  = \n| subdivision_name5  = \n<!---------------------- PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS -->\n| length             = {{convert|148.7|mi|km|abbr=on}} \n| width_min          = \n| width_avg          = \n| width_max          = \n| depth_min          = \n| depth_avg          = \n| depth_max          = \n| discharge1_location= above [[La Grange Dam]]<ref name=\"Abvlagrange\">{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/monthly/?referred_module=sw&amp;site_no=11288000&amp;por_11288000_1=2208871,00060,1,1911-10,1970-10&amp;format=html_table&amp;date_format=YYYY-MM-DD&amp;rdb_compression=file&amp;submitted_form=parameter_selection_list|title=USGS Gage #11288000 on the Tuolumne River above La Grange Dam near La Grange, CA|publisher=U.S. Geological Survey|work=National Water Information System|date=1911\u20131970|accessdate=2014-09-13}}</ref>\n| discharge1_min     = {{convert|57|cuft/s|m3/s|abbr=on}}\n| discharge1_avg     = {{convert|2343|cuft/s|m3/s|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Abvlagrange\">{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/monthly/?referred_module=sw&amp;site_no=11288000&amp;por_11288000_1=2208871,00060,1,1911-10,1970-10&amp;format=html_table&amp;date_format=YYYY-MM-DD&amp;rdb_compression=file&amp;submitted_form=parameter_selection_list|title=USGS Gage #11288000 on the Tuolumne River above La Grange Dam near La Grange, CA|publisher=U.S. Geological Survey|work=National Water Information System|date=1911\u20131970|accessdate=2014-09-13}}</ref>\n| discharge1_max     = {{convert|130000|cuft/s|m3/s|abbr=on}}\n<!---------------------- BASIN FEATURES -->\n| source1            = Confluence of Lyell and Dana Forks\n| source1_location   = [[Tuolumne Meadows]], [[Yosemite National Park]]\n| source1_coordinates= {{coord|37|52|31|N|119|21|08|W|display=inline}}<ref name=\"gnis\">{{cite gnis|id=255171|name=Tuolumne River|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2014-09-13}}</ref>\n| source1_elevation  = {{convert|8589|ft|abbr=on}}\n| mouth              = [[San Joaquin River]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Grayson, California|Grayson]], [[Stanislaus County, California|Stanislaus County]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|37|36|21|N|121|10|25|W|display=inline,title}}<ref name=\"gnis\"/>\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|26|ft|abbr=on}}\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = {{convert|1958|sqmi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"river-system\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.sf-planning.org/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentid=7941\n|title=Chapter 5.3 Tuolumne River System and Downstream Water Bodies\n|publisher=City & County of San Francisco Planning Department\n|work=Preliminary Environmental Impact Report on SFPUC Water System Improvement Program\n|year=2005\n|accessdate=2015-03-21}}</ref>\n| tributaries_left   = South Fork Tuolumne River\n| tributaries_right  = [[Cherry Creek (Tuolumne River)|Cherry Creek]], [[Clavey River]], [[North Fork Tuolumne River]]\n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = {{Designation list\n| embed                   = yes\n| designation1            = nwsr\n| designation1_type       = Wild, Scenic, Recreational\n| designation1_date       = September 28, 1984\n| designation1_number     =\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Tuolumne River''' ({{IPAc-en|t|u|\u02c8|\u0252|l|\u0259m|i}}; [[Yokutsan language|Yokutsan]]: ''Tawalimnu'')<ref name=tawalimnu>{{cite book | last=Swanton | first=J.R. | title=The Indian Tribes of North America | publisher=Genealogical Publishing Company | series=Bulletin (Smithsonian Institution. Bureau of American Ethnology) | year=1952 | isbn=978-0-8063-1730-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xpx6WoPz7xIC&pg=PA505 | page=505}}</ref> flows for {{convert|149|mi|km}} through [[Central California]], from the high [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] to join the [[San Joaquin River]] in the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]]. Originating at over {{convert|8000|ft|m}} above sea level in [[Yosemite National Park]], the Tuolumne drains a rugged watershed of {{convert|1958|mi2|km2}}, carving a series of canyons through the western slope of the Sierra. While the upper Tuolumne is a fast-flowing mountain stream, the lower river crosses a broad, fertile and extensively cultivated [[alluvial plain]]. Like most other central California rivers, the Tuolumne is dammed multiple times for irrigation and the generation of [[hydroelectricity]].\n\nHumans have inhabited the Tuolumne River area for up to 10,000 years. Prior to the arrival of Europeans, the river canyon provided an important summer hunting ground and a trade route between [[Indigenous peoples of North America|Native Americans]] in the Central Valley to the west and the [[Great Basin]] to the east. First named in 1806 by a Spanish explorer after a nearby indigenous village, the Tuolumne was heavily prospected during the [[California Gold Rush]] in the 1850s, and the lower valley was cultivated by American settlers over the next few decades. The city of [[Modesto, California|Modesto]] grew up on the Tuolumne as a railroad hub, absorbing most of the population of the Tuolumne valley around the turn of the century. As agricultural production rose, farmers along the Tuolumne formed California's first two [[irrigation district]]s to better control and develop the river.\n\nFrom the 1900s to the 1930s, the river was dammed at [[Don Pedro Dam|Don Pedro]] and [[Hetch Hetchy]] to provide water for Central Valley farmers and the city of [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], respectively. The Hetch Hetchy project, located inside Yosemite National Park, incited national controversy, and has been described as having forged the modern [[environmental movement]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earthisland.org/journal/index.php/elist/eListRead/a_century_later_the_battle_for_hetch_hetchy_continues/|title=A Century Later, the Battle for Hetch Hetchy Continues|publisher=Earth Island Institute|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> As the mid-20th century progressed, demands on the Tuolumne continued to increase, culminating in the completion of [[New Don Pedro Dam]] in the early 1970s. These projects halved the amount of water flowing from the Tuolumne into the San Joaquin, greatly reducing the once-abundant runs of salmon and steelhead in both rivers.\n\n==Course==\n{{multiple image\n|align=right\n|direction=vertical\n|width=180\n|image1=California Falls, Tuolumne River, California (1921).jpg\n|image2=Waterwheel Falls in Yosemite.jpg\n|caption2=Top: California Falls. Bottom: Waterwheel Falls, the tallest of several waterfalls along the Tuolumne River.}}\n\nThe Tuolumne originates in Yosemite National Park, high in the Sierra Nevada, as two streams. The {{convert|7|mi|km|adj=on}}<ref name=\"Streamer\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://nationalmap.gov/streamer/webApp/streamer.html#\n |title       = Streamer\n |publisher   = United States Geological Survey\n |work        = The National Map\n |date        = 2014-04-14\n |accessdate  = 2014-03-21\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140907031400/http://nationalmap.gov/streamer/webApp/streamer.html\n |archivedate = 2014-09-07\n}}</ref> Lyell Fork rises at the [[Lyell Glacier]] below {{convert|13114|ft|m|adj=on}} [[Mount Lyell (California)|Mount Lyell]], the highest peak in Yosemite National Park,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.summitpost.org/mount-lyell/150494|title=Mount Lyell|publisher=Summitpost|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> and flows north through [[Lyell Canyon]]. The {{convert|5|mi|km|adj=on}}<ref name=\"Streamer\"/> Dana Fork originates between [[Mount Dana]] ({{convert|13044|ft|m|adj=on}}<ref>{{cite gnis|id=1655123|name=Mount Dana|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2014-09-11}}</ref>) and [[Mount Gibbs]] ({{convert|12772|ft|m|adj=on}}<ref>{{cite gnis|id=260547|name=Mount Gibbs|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2014-09-11}}</ref>) and flows west.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tid.org/water/projects/tuolumne-river|title=Tuolumne River|publisher=Turlock Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the confluence of the forks in [[Tuolumne Meadows]], the river meanders northwest, passing under [[Tioga Road]]. Although calm for the first few miles, this quickly changes as the river drops over Tuolumne Falls and White Cascades. After briefly passing through [[Glen Aulin]], the river enters the spectacular {{convert|20|mi|km|adj=on}} [[Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne]], where it forms three more major waterfalls \u2013 California, LeConte and [[Waterwheel Falls]]. Return and Piute Creeks join the river from the north within the Tuolumne Canyon. At the end of the canyon the river widens into Hetch Hetchy Reservoir, formed by a dam built in 1923 to provide water to the city of [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], in the scenic [[Hetch Hetchy Valley]].<ref name=\"HetchHetchyProject\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.tchistory.org/tchistory/Wonders_10.htm\n|title=Hetch Hetchy Water and Power System\n|publisher=Tuolumne County Historical Society\n|date=\n|accessdate=2015-03-21}}</ref> [[Falls Creek (California)|Falls Creek]] forms [[Wapama Falls]] and [[Tueeulala Falls]], two of the highest in Yosemite, as it enters the reservoir from the north. From its source at {{convert|8589|ft|m}} above sea level in Tuolumne Meadows, the river drops nearly a mile (1.6&nbsp;km) to the Hetch Hetchy reservoir at {{convert|3800|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite book\n|author1=Hoover, Mildred Brooke |author2=Kyle, Douglas E. |title=Historic Spots in California\n|publisher=Stanford University Press\n|year=1990\n|isbn=0-80471-734-6\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p2WrAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA518}}</ref>\n\nBelow the [[O'Shaughnessy Dam (California)|O'Shaughnessy Dam]] the Tuolumne passes Poopenaut Valley and enters a series of continuous canyons as it flows through the Sierra foothills, leaving the western boundary of Yosemite National Park and entering the [[Stanislaus National Forest]]. Most of the Tuolumne's main tributaries join within this reach, beginning with [[Cherry Creek (Tuolumne River)|Cherry Creek]] from the north just below the intake of the [[Hetch Hetchy Aqueduct]], which delivers water to San Francisco. The South Fork of the Tuolumne joins from the south a few miles downstream, near [[Groveland-Big Oak Flat, California|Groveland-Big Oak Flat]], followed by the [[Clavey River]] from the north a few miles after that.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/tributaries |publisher=Tuolumne River Trust |work=The Watershed |title=Tributaries |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151023013312/http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/tributaries |archivedate=23 October 2015 }}</ref> The North Fork of the Tuolumne joins from the north near the upper end of [[Don Pedro Reservoir|Lake Don Pedro]], which was formed in 1971 when the [[New Don Pedro Dam]] was built to provide hydroelectricity and irrigation water storage. Directly below Don Pedro Dam is the [[La Grange Dam]], where about half the river's natural flow is diverted into the Turlock and Modesto Main Canals to irrigate over {{convert|200000|acre|ha}} in the Central Valley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.org/about/fastfacts.html|title=MID Fast Facts|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"tid.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tid.org/water/irrigation|title=Irrigation|publisher=Turlock Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Don-Pedro-Lake-Panorama-2005-11-24.jpg|thumb|left|400px|Lake Don Pedro, in the foothills east of [[La Grange, California|La Grange]], is the Tuolumne's largest reservoir.]]\nLeaving the foothills, the Tuolumne flows approximately {{convert|50|mi|km}} west across the Central Valley to its confluence with the San Joaquin River, passing [[Waterford, California|Waterford]], [[Hughson, California|Hughson]], [[Empire, California|Empire]], [[Ceres, California|Ceres]] and [[Modesto, California|Modesto]]. The lower Tuolumne is wide and slow-flowing, dropping just {{convert|230|ft|m}} from the base of La Grange Dam to its mouth at {{convert|26|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"ACME\">{{cite map\n|publisher=ACME Mapper\n|title=USGS Topo Maps for United States\n|year=\n|cartography=[[United States Geological Survey]]\n|accessdate=2009-10-29\n|url=http://mapper.acme.com/}}</ref> [[California State Route 99|Highway 99]] and the [[Southern Pacific Railroad]] tracks both cross the river in Modesto, and the [[Modesto Airport]] is located adjacent to the river shortly upstream. [[Dry Creek (Tuolumne River)|Dry Creek]] joins the Tuolumne from the north between the airport and the railroad. The confluence of the Tuolumne and San Joaquin is located in the [[San Joaquin River National Wildlife Refuge]], about {{convert|2|mi|km}} north of [[Grayson, California|Grayson]] in [[Stanislaus County, California|Stanislaus County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuolumne.org/content/fmd/files/DosRios_Background%20%282%29.pdf|title=Dos Rios Ranch|publisher=Tuolumne River Trust|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref>\n\n===Discharge===\n[[Image:O\u2019Shaughnessy Dam looking downstream towards the Poopenaut Valley - panoramio.jpg|thumb|right|Flood water is released from Hetch Hetchy Reservoir into the Tuolumne River]]\nBy volume, the Tuolumne is the largest river draining the southern Sierra, with an estimated virgin flow of {{convert|1850000|acre feet|km3}} per year \u2013 over {{convert|2550|cuft/s|m3/s}}.<ref name=\"river-system\"/> Near the river's mouth, the highest recorded annual volume was {{convert|3995000|acre feet|km3}} or {{convert|5518|cuft/s|m3/s}} in 1983, and the lowest was {{convert|134000|acre feet|km3}} or {{convert|185|cuft/s|m3/s}} in 1977 \u2013 a 30:1 difference.<ref name=\"modesto\">{{cite web|url=http://wdr.water.usgs.gov/wy2013/pdfs/11290000.2013.pdf|work=Water Data Report 2013|title=Tuolumne River at Modesto, CA|publisher=USGS|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Although most of the flow in the river originates from summer snowmelt, massive floods can occur following heavy winter storms.<ref name=\"river-system\"/> The natural flow of the Tuolumne at the mouth is greatly reduced by diversions to both San Francisco's Hetch Hetchy municipal water system and the canals of the Modesto and Turlock irrigation districts.\n\nThe [[United States Geological Survey]] (USGS) operates, or has operated, several stream gages along the Tuolumne River. Today, average annual river flows reach a maximum in the short stretch between Don Pedro Dam and La Grange Dam, about {{convert|50|mi|km}} above the mouth, before the start of large irrigation diversions. A USGS gage recorded an average annual flow of {{convert|2343|cuft/s|m3/s}} here between 1911 and 1970, with a maximum peak of {{convert|60300|cuft/s|m3/s}} on January 31, 1911, and a minimum monthly mean of {{convert|57.5|cuft/s|m3/s}} in October 1912.<ref name=\"Abvlagrange\"/> During the [[Great Flood of 1862]], the river reached an estimated peak of {{convert|130000|cuft/s|m3/s}}<ref name=\"modestopeak\"/> here, after a record {{convert|72|in|mm}} of rain fell in the Tuolumne River basin between November 11, 1861 and January 14, 1862, as recorded at [[Sonora, California|Sonora]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redlandsfortnightly.org/papers/Taylor06.htm|publisher=Fortnightly Club of Redlands|title=The Great California Flood Of 1862|first1=WL|last1=Taylor|first2=RW|last2=Taylor|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The gage was not in place during this time.<ref name=\"modestopeak\">{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/peak?site_no=11288000&agency_cd=USGS&format=html|publisher=USGS|work=Surface Water for USA|title=Peak Streamflow|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nFurther downstream, the USGS gage at Modesto \u2013 about {{convert|10|mi|km}} above the mouth \u2013 recorded an annual mean of {{convert|1326|cuft/s|m3/s}} between 1940 and 2013. The highest peak was {{convert|57000|cuft/s|m3/s}} on December 9, 1950, and the lowest daily mean was {{convert|56|cuft/s|m3/s}} on August 6, 1977.<ref name=\"modesto\"/>\n\n==Watershed==\n\n===Physiography===\nThe Tuolumne River watershed can be divided into three distinct physiographic regions. From the headwaters to below Hetch Hetchy Reservoir, the river drains the Sierra highlands, which are characterized by solid, [[glacier]]-carved granitic bedrock, thin poor soils and areas of heavy forestation. Most of the snowpack that feeds the Tuolumne accumulates in this region.{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=7}} Streams are generally high-gradient, clear and rocky, but large [[alpine meadow]]s provide riparian and wetland habitat, which contribute sediment to the watershed's runoff. There are also a large number of natural lakes and tarns in the upper watershed. The Sierra crest harbors a number of glaciers, including Lyell and Maclure Glaciers, the largest in Yosemite National Park. Melting ice feeds the upper reaches of the Tuolumne River, maintaining water flow in the late summer when many other streams in the region are dry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/yose/blogs/Lyell-Glacier.htm|title=Lyell Glacier|publisher=National Park Service|work=Yosemite National Park|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The Lyell Glacier is the second largest in the Sierra Nevada, after [[Palisade Glacier]] at the headwaters of [[Big Pine Creek (California)|Big Pine Creek]] a tributary of the [[Owens River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprdb5195705.pdf|title=Wilderness Hiking, Big Pine Canyon, Inyo National Forest|publisher=USFS|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Both Lyell and Maclure glaciers have shrunk significantly since the late 1800s when measurements were first made.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/yose/parknews/lyellglacier.htm|title=Yosemite National Park's Largest Glacier Stagnant|work=Yosemite National Park|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nBetween Hetch Hetchy Reservoir and the upper end of Lake Don Pedro the Tuolumne flows through the Sierra foothills, where it has a lower gradient but continues to maintain a fast current. Stream pools and gravel bars figure more prominently in the channel, allowing the growth of riparian habitat. By the time the river reaches Lake Don Pedro it has accumulated almost 90 percent of its total flow as precipitation run-off, [[snowmelt]] and [[groundwater]] [[Baseflow|base flow]].{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|pp=4-10}} Below Don Pedro Dam the river flows across the large [[alluvial plain]] of the San Joaquin Valley, formed by millions of years of sediment deposits eroded from the Sierra. Historically this section of the river was subject to frequent course changes and formed thousands of acres of seasonal wetlands during the spring floods. Since the introduction of large-scale agriculture the Tuolumne River course has been fixed between an extensive system of levees. More than {{convert|300000|acre|ha}} in the San Joaquin Valley are irrigated using Tuolumne water.{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=8}}\n\nAbout {{convert|669|mi2|km2}}, or 34&nbsp;percent, of the Tuolumne River watershed is inside Yosemite National Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.us-parks.com/yosemite-national-park/watersheds.html|work=Yosemite National Park|title=Watersheds|publisher=us-parks.com|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The rivers whose watersheds border that of the Tuolumne are the [[Stanislaus River]] and [[West Walker River]] in the north, the [[Merced River]] in the south, the [[East Walker River]] to the northeast, the [[Mono Lake]] basin ([[Mill Creek (Mono Lake)|Mill Creek]], [[Lee Vining Creek]] and [[Rush Creek (Mono County, California)|Rush Creek]]) to the east, and the headwaters of the San Joaquin River proper to the southeast.\n\n====Tributaries====\nMajor tributaries of the Tuolumne and pertinent data are listed in the below table. Order is from the headwaters downstream.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Coordinates\n!Elevation\n!Distance<br>from mouth<ref name=\"ACME\"/>\n!Length<ref name=\"Streamer\"/>\n!Watershed\n!Discharge\n!Bank{{#tag:ref|R stands for right bank, L for left bank}}\n!Image\n|-\n|[[Dana Fork Tuolumne River]]\n|{{coord|37|52|31|N|119|21|08|W}}<ref name=\"DanaGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=253658|name=Dana Fork|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|8,589}} ft<br>(2,618 m)<ref name=\"DanaGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|149}} mi<br>(240&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|5}} mi<br>(8&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|[[Image:Dana Meadows Yosemite.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Lyell Fork Tuolumne River]]\n|{{coord|37|52|31|N|119|21|08|W}}<ref name=\"LyellGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=253533|name=Lyell Fork|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|8,589}} ft<br>(2,618 m)<ref name=\"LyellGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|149}} mi<br>(240&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|7}} mi<br>(11&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|L\n|[[Image:Lyell Canyon.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Return Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|55|55|N|119|27|58|W}}<ref name=\"ReturnGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=265379|name=Return Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|6,204}} ft<br>(1,891 m)<ref name=\"ReturnGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|139}} mi<br>(224&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|14}} mi<br>(23&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|\n|-\n|[[Piute Creek (Tuolumne River)|Piute Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|55|48|N|119|36|03|W}}<ref name=\"PiuteGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id253760|name=Piute Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|4344}} ft<br>(1,324 m)\n|{{nts|130}} mi<br>(209&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|20}} mi<br>(32&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|\n|-\n|[[Rancheria Creek (Tuolumne County, California)|Rancheria Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|57|12|N|119|43|41|W}}<ref name=\"RancheriaGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=265177|name=Rancheria Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|3,796}} ft<br>(1,157 m)<ref name=\"RancheriaGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|121}} mi<br>(195&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|24}} mi<br>(39&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|[[Image:Rapids_below_Rancheria_Falls_-_panoramio.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Falls Creek (California)|Falls Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|57|47|N|119|45|55|W}}<ref name=\"FallsGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=260042|name=Falls Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|3783}} ft<br>(1,153 m)<ref name=\"FallsGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|119}} mi<br>(192&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|23}} mi<br>(37&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|[[Image:Wapama Falls in Yosemite NP.JPG|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Cherry Creek (California)|Cherry Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|53|19|N|119|58|19|W}}<ref name=\"CherryGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=258242|name=Cherry Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|2,162}} ft<br>(659 m)<ref name=\"CherryGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|104}} mi<br>(167&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|42}} mi<br>(68&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|234}} mi<sup>2</sup><br>(607&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>)<ref name=\"Cherryflow\">{{cite web|url=http://wdr.water.usgs.gov/wy2013/pdfs/11278400.2013.pdf|work=Water Data Report 2013|publisher=USGS|title=Cherry Creek below Dion R. Holm Powerplant, near Mather, CA}}</ref>\n|{{nts|694}} cfs<br>(19.7 m<sup>3</sup>/s)<ref name=\"Cherryflow\"/>\n|R\n|[[Image:Cherry Lake Stanislaus National Forest.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[South Fork Tuolumne River]]\n|{{coord|37|50|25|N|120|02|52|W}}<ref name=\"SfGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=267514|name=South Fork Tuolumne River|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|1,447}} ft<br>(441 m)<ref name=\"SfGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|96}} mi<br>(155&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|31}} mi<br>(50&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|164}} mi<sup>2</sup><br>(425&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>)<ref name=\"SFflow\">{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/monthly/?referred_module=sw&amp;site_no=11282500&amp;por_11282500_1=2208852,00060,1,1911-10,1921-09&amp;format=html_table&amp;date_format=YYYY-MM-DD&amp;rdb_compression=file&amp;submitted_form=parameter_selection_list|publisher=USGS|work=Surface Water data for USA|title=Surface-Water Monthly Statistics|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n|{{nts|167}} cfs<br>(4.7 m<sup>3</sup>/s)<ref name=\"SFflow\"/>\n|L\n|[[Image:Rainbow Pools on the South Fork of the Tuolumne River.jpg|120px]]\n|-\n|[[Clavey River]]\n|{{coord|37|51|50|N|120|06|59|W}}<ref name=\"ClaveyGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=266572|name=Clavey River|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|1,178}} ft<br>(359 m)<ref name=\"ClaveyGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|91}} mi<br>(147&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|42}} mi<br>(68&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|157}} mi<sup>2</sup><br>(407&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calwater.ca.gov/Admin_Record/I-006319.pdf|title=Clavey River Watershed Analysis|publisher=USFS|year=1997|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref>\n|{{nts|255}} cfs<br>(7.2 m<sup>3</sup>/s)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/monthly/?referred_module=sw&amp;site_no=11283500&amp;por_11283500_1=2208860,00060,1,1959-10,1995-06&amp;format=html_table&amp;date_format=YYYY-MM-DD&amp;rdb_compression=file&amp;submitted_form=parameter_selection_list|publisher=USGS|work=Surface Water data for USA|title=Surface-Water Monthly Statistics|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n|R\n|\n|-\n|[[North Fork Tuolumne River]]\n|{{coord|37|53|49|N|120|15|14|W}}<ref name=\"NfGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=234378|name=North Fork Tuolumne River|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|853}} ft<br>(260 m)<ref name=\"NfGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|81}} mi<br>(130&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|36}} mi<br>(58&nbsp;km)\n|\n|{{nts|54}} cfs<br>(1.5 m<sup>3</sup>/s)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/monthly/?referred_module=sw&amp;site_no=11285000&amp;por_11285000_1=2208865,00060,1,1958-10,1966-09&amp;format=html_table&amp;date_format=YYYY-MM-DD&amp;rdb_compression=file&amp;submitted_form=parameter_selection_list|publisher=USGS|work=Surface Water data for USA|title=Surface-Water Monthly Statistics|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n|R\n|\n|-\n|[[Woods Creek (Tuolumne River)|Woods Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|50|45|N|120|22|41|W}}<ref name=\"WoodsGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=274569|name=Woods Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|791}} ft<br>(241 m)<ref name=\"WoodsGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|68}} mi<br>(109&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|28}} mi<br>(45&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|\n|-\n|[[Dry Creek (Tuolumne River)|Dry Creek]]\n|{{coord|37|53|49|N|120|15|14|W}}<ref name=\"DryGNIS\">{{cite gnis|id=\t259548|name=Dry Creek|entrydate=1981-01-19|accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref>\n|{{nts|46}} ft<br>(14 m)<ref name=\"DryGNIS\"/>\n|{{nts|10}} mi<br>(16&nbsp;km)\n|{{nts|63}} mi<br>(101&nbsp;km)\n|\n|\n|R\n|\n|}\n\n===Land use===\n{{expand section|date=May 2015}}\nAlmost 80&nbsp;percent of the Tuolumne River watershed lies above [[New Don Pedro Dam]] and is primarily forested with some alpine, meadow and grassland zones.<ref>http://www.tudwater.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Sec2_T-S-RegionDescription_021313_w-TRK.pdf</ref> The primary land use in the lower Tuolumne River watershed is agriculture, but there are also significant urbanized areas.<ref>http://www.sjrg.org/EIR/supplemental/sup_chpt8.htm</ref> Although only about {{convert|68000|acre|ha}} (5.4&nbsp;percent) of the watershed itself are farmed, river water is used to irrigate almost five times that area outside the watershed boundaries. About {{convert|16500|acre|ha}} (1.3&nbsp;percent) of the watershed are urbanized, mostly in the Greater Modesto area. About 550,000 people inhabit the Tuolumne River watershed as a whole, with approximately 210,000 living in Modesto.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.modestogov.com/ed/demographics/population.asp |title=Population |publisher=City of Modesto |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150902033730/http://www.modestogov.com/ed/demographics/population.asp |archivedate=2 September 2015 }}</ref>{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=4}}\n\n===Engineering and flood control===\nLike most other Sierra Nevada rivers, the Tuolumne has been extensively dammed to provide flood control, water supply, and hydroelectric power.<ref name=\"tldownstream\">http://sf-planning.org/sites/default/files/FileCenter/Documents/7941-2005.0159E_vol3_sec5-3_wsip_finalpeir.pdf</ref> The uppermost dam is the O'Shaughnessy, which impounds the {{convert|360000|acre feet|m3|adj=on}} Hetch Hetchy Reservoir, providing water and power to the City of San Francisco. The Hetch Hetchy hydroelectric system diverts large volumes of water into tunnels that feed two hydroelectric plants, the Kirkwood and the Moccasin. The power system is efficient because of the Tuolumne's great drop, over {{convert|2750|ft|m}}, between Hetch Hetchy and the outlet of Moccasin Powerhouse. However, it also causes dewatering of significant portions of the Tuolumne River, especially during low water summers when all but a minimal fish release is diverted through the power plants. Not all of the flow used by the power plants is returned to the river. About {{convert|244000|acre feet|m3}} per year flows through the gravity fed Hetch Hetchy Aqueduct to serve San Francisco and its customer municipalities.<ref name=\"tldownstream\"/> Due to the pristine quality of the water, the Hetch Hetchy system is one of only a few serving major cities in the United States that does not require filtration.\n\n[[Image:Hetchhetchyprojmap.jpg|thumb|right|360px|The Hetch Hetchy Project provides Tuolumne water to the city of San Francisco.]]\nCherry Creek, the Tuolumne's biggest tributary, is also part of the San Francisco hydroelectric system. Cherry Creek is dammed at the Cherry Valley Dam, which creates {{convert|274000|acre feet|m3|adj=on}} [[Cherry Lake]]. A major tributary, Eleanor Creek, is dammed to form [[Lake Eleanor]], and diverted into Cherry Lake through a tunnel. The combined flow is channeled into a penstock and returns to the river at the Holm Powerhouse. Unlike the Hetch Hetchy system, the Cherry Creek system is used exclusively for hydropower, not water supply, because the water quality is not quite as good. However, there is a connecting aqueduct that allows Cherry Lake to be tapped to supply the Hetch Hetchy system during severe droughts. This backup water supply was last used during late 2015, as a test to ensure its functionality should drought conditions become worse.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/sf-water-to-be-mixed-with-filtered-water-as-city-tests-drought-preparedness/|title=SF water to be mixed with filtered water as city tests drought preparedness|publisher=The San Francisco Examiner|first=Michael|last=Barba|date=October 9, 2015}}</ref> The previous time it was used was 1988.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/science/article/California-drought-2-reservoirs-near-Hetch-5321213.php|title=California drought: 2 reservoirs near Hetch Hetchy tapped|publisher=SFGate|first=Marisa|last=Lagos|date=March 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Tuolumne River Modesto.jpg|thumb|right|Tuolumne River in Modesto]]\nBelow the confluence with the North Fork of the Tuolumne the river flows into Lake Don Pedro, the largest in the Tuolumne River system and the sixth-largest man made lake in California at {{convert|2030000|acre feet|m3}}. The earth-filled New Don Pedro Dam, {{convert|585|ft|m}} high, is the 10th tallest dam in the United States and was constructed as a multipurpose project, serving irrigation, municipal water supply, hydropower and flood control. It replaced an earlier concrete dam built on approximately the same site. The Turlock and Modesto Irrigation Districts control the lion's share of water in the reservoir, although the City of San Francisco also has storage rights, which it uses mainly to offset the effects of water diverted upstream at Hetch Hetchy. Because of the desire to increase water storage for other uses, only {{convert|340000|acre feet|m3}} of the reservoir is designated flood control, which is relatively small compared to other reservoirs in California. As a result, Don Pedro frequently fills and spills during winter storms, causing damage downstream.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nThe La Grange Dam, a much smaller masonry diversion dam, is the last one on the Tuolumne before it joins with the San Joaquin. Modesto Canal, on the north side of the river, and Turlock Canal, on the south side, are both large irrigation diversions. The Modesto Canal feeds the {{convert|29000|acre feet|m3|adj=on}} off-stream Modesto Reservoir, which regulates the water for distribution to farmers. The Turlock Lake is regulated by the similar but much larger Turlock Lake, which has a capacity of {{convert|49000|acre feet|m3|adj=on}}. The estimated annual diversion for irrigation is {{convert|867000|acre feet|m3}}, about half of the Tuolumne River's natural flow.<ref name=\"tldownstream\"/>\n\nBelow La Grange, the Tuolumne \u2013 much reduced due to irrigation diversions \u2013 flows through a fixed channel with a highly restricted [[floodplain]]. Before agriculture, the river inundated large areas of seasonal marshland and was free to change course during its frequent floods. Today farms and communities are protected by a [[levee]] system with a channel capacity of roughly {{convert|9000|cuft/s|m3/s}} at the 9th St. Bridge in Modesto \u2013 significantly smaller than the river's maximum flood potential. The valley is dependent on flood control storage at Lake Don Pedro to prevent flows from exceeding the channel capacity. However, this has happened many times, most infamously during the [[New Year's Flood of 1997]], during which inflows to Don Pedro hit {{convert|120000|cuft/s|m3/s}}, the largest recorded since the [[Great Flood of 1862]]. Water releases from Don Pedro Dam peaked at {{convert|60000|cuft/s|m3/s}}; while this vastly reduced potential damage from the flood, it still exceeded the channel capacity by six times, causing extensive property damage along the river.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.water.ca.gov/historicaldocs/irwm/feat-1997/fcsia2.html|title=Final Report of the Flood Emergency Action Team|year=1997|publisher=State of California|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Fish, plants and wildlife===\nThe Tuolumne once supported large spring and fall runs of [[chinook salmon]] (king salmon, ''Oncorhynchus tshawytscha'') and [[Rainbow trout|steelhead trout]] (''Oncorhynchus mykiss''). In its native state the fall Chinook run alone may have numbered as high as 130,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://water4fish.org/other-rivers/|title=Other Rivers|publisher=water4fish.org|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> With the exception of the [[Merced River]] immediately south, this is the southernmost existing population of Chinook salmon in North America.<ref>http://www.westcoast.fisheries.noaa.gov/publications/recovery_planning/salmon_steelhead/domains/california_central_valley/appendix_a_watershed_profiles_7102014.pdf</ref> Massive irrigation diversions and river channelization projects have led to the extinction of the spring Chinook run and greatly reduced the fall run. Dams have blocked more than half of the original {{convert|99|mi|km}} of migratory fish spawning habitat in the Tuolumne River watershed. The San Joaquin River and the [[Sacramento\u2013San Joaquin River Delta]], which link the Tuolumne salmon runs to the Pacific, have also been affected by flow reduction and pollution. In addition, introduced species such as [[striped bass]] prey on juvenile salmon, consuming as much as 93&nbsp;percent of smolt before they can migrate to the sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://westernfarmpress.com/government/tuolumne-river-93-percent-juvenile-salmon-consumed-predators|title=Tuolumne River: 93 percent of juvenile salmon consumed by predators|publisher=Western Farm Press|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> A controversial proposal by the State Water Resources Control Board from around 2013 would require increased spring and summer flows on the Tuolumne River which would benefit native [[Fish migration|anadromous]] fish populations, but greatly reduce the water supply available for farms and cities. This has been countered by irrigation districts who maintain that the aforementioned predation, not low flows, are the primary cause of salmon smolt deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.turlockcitynews.com/news/item/199-fish-predation-not-flows-causing-salmon-death-on-tuolumne|title=Fish Predation, Not Flows, Causing Salmon Death on Tuolumne|last=|first=|date=2013-02-19|website=|publisher=Turlock City News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nForests in the watershed are divided between several distinct zones. The foothill region is characterized by trees and plants adapted to a hot, dry climate, including [[Adenostoma fasciculatum|chamise]] (greasewood), [[Ceanothus|California lilac]], [[manzanita]], [[Quercus douglasii|blue oak]], [[Quercus wislizeni|interior live oak]] (Sierra live oak), and [[Pinus sabiniana|gray pine]]. Further east and higher in elevation are the lower and upper montane forests, which lie between {{convert|3000|to|6000|ft|m}} and {{convert|6000|to|8000|ft|m}} elevation, respectively. The lower montane forests include [[Quercus kelloggii|black oak]], [[Pinus ponderosa|ponderosa pine]], [[Calocedrus|incense cedar]] and [[Abies concolor|white fir]]; higher up [[Jeffrey pine]] and [[Juniperus occidentalis|western juniper]] appear. Higher still is the subalpine forest zone between {{convert|8000|to|9500|ft|m}}, which is dominated by [[Western white pine]], [[Tsuga mertensiana|mountain hemlock]] and [[Pinus contorta|lodgepole pine]]. Above 9500 feet, only small shrubs, flowering plants and occasional [[Pinus albicaulis|whitebark pine]]{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=56}} populate the alpine zone, which is limited to the peaks around Tuolumne Meadows and along the Sierra Crest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/ecosystems |publisher=Tuolumne River Trust |work=The Watershed |title=Ecosystems |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151023024138/http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/ecosystems |archivedate=23 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\nHumans have influenced natural conditions in the Tuolumne River watershed for centuries. Native Americans set [[Controlled burn|controlled fires]] in grassland to clear out dead foliage, providing room for new growth which in turn attracted game animals to forage. They also periodically burned out oak woodland areas in the foothills to control pests, which otherwise would have affected their main food supply, acorns. During the Spanish and Mexican periods, the Central Valley was used for cattle ranching, which quickly decimated natural range grasses. During the 1880s American sheep ranchers brought their herds into the upper Tuolumne River watershed for summer pasture, which further damaged the range in the foothills and Sierras. Hetch Hetchy Valley was one of the main summer grazing areas for sheep. The decline of native [[perennial plant|perennial]] grasses caused invasive [[annual plant|annual]] species to flourish, and also increased the susceptibility of the watershed to [[wildfire]]s. In order to protect property and watershed quality, intensive fire suppression began in the early 20th century. However, this led to overgrowth and a disruption of the natural [[Forest dynamics|forest succession]] process that was previously driven by wildfires.{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=69\u201370}}\n\n==Geology==\n{{expand section|date=May 2015}}\n\n==Early history==\nEstimates of the first human habitation along the Tuolumne River range from 3000\u20137000 BC.<ref name=\"earlyhist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/humans |publisher=Tuolumne River Trust |work=The Watershed |title=Early Humans |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151023013316/http://www.tuolumne.org/content/article.php/humans |archivedate=23 October 2015 }}</ref> The [[Plains and Sierra Miwok]], who were the largest regional Native American group immediately prior to European contact, first established themselves in the area around 1200 CE.<ref name=\"earlyhist\"/> The Miwok lived in the Sierra foothills and Central Valley lowlands during winter and traveled into the upper Tuolumne River in summer to hunt, as well as seek refuge from the summer heat. The [[Northern Paiute|Paiute]], who inhabited the Great Basin on the east side of the Sierra, also ventured into the Tuolumne River basin during the summer.<ref name=\"HetchHetchyBattle\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/battleoverhetchh00righ|url-access=registration|title=The Battle over Hetch Hetchy : America's Most Controversial Dam and the Birth of Modern Environmentalism|page=[https://archive.org/details/battleoverhetchh00righ/page/14 14]|first=Robert W.|last=Righter|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2005|isbn=978-0-19-803410-0}}</ref> The [[Yokuts people|Yokuts]] lived along the lower Tuolumne River and were not known to venture up into the Sierra during summer.\n\n[[Image:117.TuolumneRiver.JPG|thumb|left|Tuolumne River in West Meadow, Tuolumne Meadows]]\nThe chief meeting point of the Paiute and Miwok was the Hetch Hetchy Valley, rich in edible plants and game. The origin of the name \"Hetch Hetchy\" may have been a type of edible grass that grew in the valley, which native peoples made into grain and ground in stone mortars for meal.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N3Rs7E7_J_IC&pg=PA63|title=Yosemite Place Names|first=Peter|last=Browning|publisher=Great West Books|year=2005|page=63|isbn=978-0-944220-19-1}}</ref>\nThey set controlled fires to clear out old vegetation in their gathering areas, allowing for more efficient harvesting of new growth.<ref name=\"earlyhist\"/> This would also increase the prevalence of grasses and ferns, attracting game animals such as deer, and made the landscape more easily navigable. Many of the landscapes in the Tuolumne River area encountered by the first European explorers were thus not pristine but the result of hundreds of years of management; indeed, the famous meadows of Hetch Hetchy Valley prior to its damming only existed because of the annual burn.<ref name=\"HetchHetchyBattle\"/>\n\nThe origin of the Tuolumne River's name is unclear. The first recorded use of the name \"Tuolumne\" was by the Spanish explorer [[Gabriel Moraga]] in 1806, who may have named the river for the nearby Native American village of ''Tualamne'' or ''Tautamne''. This may in turn refer to the native word ''talmalamne'', or \"a group of stone huts or caves\". Father Pedro Mu\u00f1oz, a member of the 1806 expedition, noted in his diary that \"we came upon a village called Tautamne. This village is situated on some steep precipices, inaccessible on account of their rough rocks. The Indians live in their s\u00f3tanos [cellars or caves]\".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_ZWjAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA500&lpg=PA500|title=Historic Spots In California: Valley and Sierra Counties|first1=HE|last1=Rensch|first2=EG|last2=Rensch|first3=MB|last3=Hoover|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1932|page=500|isbn=978-0-8047-1615-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Gudde | first=E.G. | title=California Place Names: A Geographical Dictionary | publisher=University of California Press | year=1949 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-22djGNuhwC&pg=SL3-PA240 | page=240}}</ref> At this time, the Native American population along the lower Tuolumne and Stanislaus Rivers is believed to have been approximately two thousand.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D8jzdPSQAzcC&pg=PA7|title=Sonora|first=Michael|last=Gahagan|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2007|page=7|isbn=978-0-7385-4783-1}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:GrandCanyonTuolumneRiver.jpg|thumb|right|Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne, circa 1914]]\nAnother possible origin of the name ''Tuolumne'' is the Central Sierra Miwok word ''taawal\u00efmi'', meaning \"squirrel place\", referring to a Native American village on the nearby Stanislaus River.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tcMnAy6m5doC&pg=PA159|title=1500 California Place Names|first=William|last=Bright|publisher=University of California Press|year=1998|edition=3rd|page=159|isbn=978-0-520-92054-5}}</ref> The suffix ''-umne'', which appears in the names of two other California rivers, the [[Mokelumne River|Mokelumne]] and [[Cosumnes River|Cosumnes]], is thought to have meant \"place of\" or \"people of\" in the native language.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/naturalworldof00heiz|url-access=registration|title=The Natural World of the California Indians|first1=RF|last1=Heizer|first2=AB|last2=Elsasser|publisher=University of California Press|year=1980|page=[https://archive.org/details/naturalworldof00heiz/page/15 15]|isbn=978-0-520-03896-7}}</ref>\n\nThe Tuolumne River was the scene of significant gold mining activity during the [[California Gold Rush]]. The first known discovery of gold in the area was made by Benjamin Wood, a prospector from Oregon, in the summer of 1848. During the latter part of that year and early 1849, mining camps were established along the Tuolumne, including Jamestown, Tuttletown, Melones, Don Pedros Bar, and Shaws Flat.<ref name=\"gold\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tchistory.org/TCHISTORY/Gold_Tuolumne.htm|title=Gold in Tuolumne County|publisher=Tuolumne County Historical Society|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The following spring a party of Mexican miners from [[Sonora]] discovered an even richer deposit farther upstream, establishing Sonoranian Camp, predecessor of the present-day town of [[Sonora, California]].<!--<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.examiner.com/article/sonora-california-and-the-start-of-mining-along-the-tuolumne-river|title=Sonora, California and the start of mining along the Tuolumne River|publisher=San Francisco Examiner|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>--> By the end of 1849, there were over 10,000 miners in the Tuolumne River area, half of them in Sonora, which became the Tuolumne County seat in 1850.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O0Ypj5Te8DIC&pg=PA197&lpg=PA198|title=A Self-governing Dominion, California, 1849-1860|first=William Henry|last=Ellison|publisher=University of California Press|year=1978|page=197|isbn=978-0-520-03713-7}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:VIEW OF WEST FACE AND TUOLUMNE RIVER. - Tuolumne Meadows Bridge, Spanning Tuolumne River on Tioga Road, Mather, Tuolumne County, CA HAER CAL,55-TOULM,2-6.tif|thumb|right|[[Tioga Road]], originally a Gold Rush-era pack trail, crosses the Tuolumne at Tuolumne Meadows.]]\nMining activity increased dramatically in the early 1850s, with prospectors pushing up into the foothills beyond [[Soulsbyville, California|Soulsbyville]].<ref name=\"gold\"/> In March 1850, an \"enormously rich\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oISiKnZz-HcC&pg=106|title=Gold: The California Story|first=Mary|last=Hill|publisher=University of California Press|year=1999|page=106|isbn=978-0-520-21547-4}}</ref> deposit was discovered at Columbia. The same year, the Bonanza Mine near Sonora yielded a 1500-ounce nugget, the fourth largest ever discovered in California.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oISiKnZz-HcC&pg=258|title=Gold: The California Story|first=Mary|last=Hill|publisher=University of California Press|year=1999|page=258|isbn=978-0-520-21547-4}}</ref> (The largest was found in [[Carson Hill, California|Carson Hill]] in Calaveras County, just north of the Tuolumne River watershed along the [[Stanislaus River]], in 1854.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museumca.org/goldrush/dist-carsonhill.html|title=Carson Hill|work=Gold Districts of California|publisher=Oakland Museum of California|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>) The prosperity in the region prompted a search for a new crossing of the Sierra Nevada that would provide more direct access to the camps from the east. The Clark-Skidmore Party made this crossing in 1852 via the upper Stanislaus River and the north fork of the Tuolumne.<ref name=\"earlyhist\"/> Parts of the route they established eventually formed the Walker River Trail, regarded as one of the more difficult of the main Sierra crossings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sonorapasspioneers.com/1852.html|work=Sonora Pass Emigrants and Tuolumne County California Pioneers|title=The Clark-Skidmore Party, 1852|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nFor a brief period the lower Tuolumne became a major [[steamboat]] route, ferrying prospectors and supplies from [[Stockton, California|Stockton]].<ref name=\"earlyhist\"/> Depending on water level, approximately {{convert|35|mi|km}} of the lower river were navigable, from the mouth to above [[Waterford, California|Waterford]].<ref name=\"waterford\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l2CKNfLDt5MC&pg=PA7|title=Waterford|first=Jeff|last=Benziger|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2011|page=7|isbn=978-1-4396-3926-9}}</ref> The unpredictable nature of the river made both navigating and crossing difficult, so starting in the Gold Rush era many ferries were established, one of the first at Dickenson's Ferry in the early 1850s. This particular location was the crossing of Fort Miller Road (Millerton Road), a major land trade route that connected Stockton with [[Millerton, Madera County, California|Millerton]] near present-day Fresno (today the site of the [[Millerton Lake]] reservoir).<ref name=\"ferries\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/historicspotsinc00rens|url-access=registration|title=Historic Spots in California|first1=MB|last1=Hoover|first2=HE|last2=Rensch|first3=EG|last3=Rensch|editor-first=WN|editor-last=Abeloe|edition=Third|year=1966|publisher=Stanford University Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/historicspotsinc00rens/page/542 542]|isbn=978-0-8047-4020-3}}</ref>\n\nBy 1853, most of the easily mined gold had been exhausted, and [[hydraulic mining]] operations became the dominant extraction method.<ref name=\"gold\"/> The Tuolumne County Water Company, first organized in 1851 to divert water from the Tuolumne River basin to the Stanislaus River, constructed a network of reservoirs, ditches and flumes initially used for mining and later for irrigation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tudwater.com/pdf/2012_pdf/Engineering/rpt_hrer_public_web_2012.pdf|publisher=Tuolumne Utilities District|work=Ditch Sustainability Project|title=Historic Resource Evaluation Report|accessdate=2015-10-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409043043/http://www.tudwater.com/pdf/2012_pdf/Engineering/rpt_hrer_public_web_2012.pdf|archivedate=2016-04-09}}</ref> The Golden Rock Water Company, incorporated in 1855, diverted the South Fork of the Tuolumne to supply the diggings at [[Groveland, California|Groveland]] and [[Big Oak Flat, California|Big Oak Flat]]; their most notable achievement was the construction of a {{convert|2200|ft|m|adj=on}} long, {{convert|265|ft|m|adj=on}} high aqueduct (the Big Gap Flume) over [[Buck Meadows, California|Buck Meadows]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinemountainlake.com/Page/21389~335627/Mountain-Lifeline-Golden-Rock-Flume-System|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128031440/http://pinemountainlake.com/?pg=mountainlifelinegoldenrocksystem|archivedate=2010-11-28|title=Mountain Lifeline Golden Rock System Flowed With New Hope|first=Jean|last=McClish}}</ref> The first dam on the Tuolumne River proper, near [[La Grange, California|La Grange]], was built in 1852 to divert water for hydraulic mining. Sediment and rocks washed down by hydraulic mining and sluicing operations accumulated along the lower Tuolumne, destroying native floodplain habitat<ref name=\"restoration\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fws.gov/lodi/afrp/documents/tuolplan.pdf|title=Habitat Restoration Plan for the Lower Tuolumne River Corridor|publisher=US Fish and Wildlife Service|year=1999|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> and making much of the river unnavigable.<ref name=\"earlyhist\"/>\n\n==Irrigation, power and water supply==\n\n===La Grange and Old Don Pedro Dams===\nAfter the gold rush many miners settled along the lower Tuolumne River as farmers. Ferry sites grew into lively towns, such as at Waterford, where a crossing had been established in 1866.<ref name=\"waterford\"/> The town of [[Tuolumne City, California|Tuolumne City]] was founded near the mouth of the Tuolumne as a port, but it soon became apparent that mining debris had made the river unsuitable for navigation, and the area was abandoned. In the mid-1860s Tuolumne City and Paradise (located about {{convert|5|mi|km}} further up the river) were reestablished as farming communities. The founding of [[Modesto, California|Modesto]] in 1870, along a new railroad through the San Joaquin Valley, drew most of the population away from these towns and others along the Tuolumne.<ref name=\"ferries\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.modestogov.com/localInfo/cityHistory/ |title=Modesto Historical Information |author=city staff |publisher=City of Modesto |accessdate=12 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929024023/http://www.modestogov.com/localinfo/cityhistory/ |archivedate=29 September 2015 }}</ref> By the early 1900s Modesto's population numbered more than four thousand.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bggjmhXp6xsC&pg=PA9&lpg=PA9|title=Modesto|first=Wayne A.|last=Mathes|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2011|page=9|isbn=978-0-7385-7485-1}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:OldDonPedroDam.jpg|thumb|right|The original [[Don Pedro Dam]] was completed in 1923 to provide long-term storage for irrigation.]]\nAs it became apparent that the Central Valley's seasonal rainfall patterns made it unsuitable for [[dryland farming]], farmers organized to build irrigation infrastructure along the Tuolumne River. Turlock Irrigation District (TID), established in 1887, was the first irrigation district in California,<ref name=\"TIDhist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tid.org/about-tid/history|title=History|publisher=Turlock Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> and the Modesto Irrigation District (MID) was established soon after in the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.org/about/history/chpt_03.html|work=Greening of Paradise Valley|title=Chapter 3|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The two districts serve the south and north sides of the river, respectively. The present-day [[La Grange Dam]], completed in 1893, replaced the older mining dam at the same site; at {{convert|122|ft|m}}, it was the highest overflow dam in the United States. The dam diverted the river into canals that water most of the lower valley.<ref name=\"restoration\"/> The first TID farmers received water in 1900.<ref name=\"TIDhist\"/> The MID canal took a total of thirteen years to complete, with the first water deliveries on June 27, 1903.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.org/about/history/chpt_05.html|work=Greening of Paradise Valley|title=Chapter 5|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.org/about/history/chpt_06.html|work=Greening of Paradise Valley|title=Chapter 6|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs the population of the area grew, the Tuolumne River districts soon began to experience seasonal water shortages. The Dallas-Warner Reservoir (today's Modesto Reservoir) was completed in 1912 on the north side of the river, but was only considered a temporary solution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid.org/about/history/chpt_09.html|work=Greening of Paradise Valley|title=Chapter 9|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> Construction on the first [[Don Pedro Dam]] began in 1921 to store floodwaters of the Tuolumne proper, allowing for the extension of the irrigation season and to provide water during dry years.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pLXmAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA290|title=Construction of Don Pedro Dam|journal=Engineering World|volume=20-21|page=290|year=1922}}</ref> A secondary purpose for the construction of the dam was that TID and MID were aware that the city of San Francisco, {{convert|160|mi|km}} west of the river, coveted water from the Tuolumne. Although the irrigation districts had the primary rights to the Tuolumne under the [[Prior-appropriation water rights|doctrine of prior appropriation]], those rights could be relinquished under the \"use it or lose it\" rule, so storage had to be developed to enable the full beneficial use of river water.{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010}} Named for the Gold Rush mining camp its reservoir submerged, the Don Pedro dam was completed in 1923, holding back {{convert|289000|acre feet|km3}} of water. In 1923 and 1924 both Don Pedro and La Grange dams were fitted for hydroelectric generation.<ref name=\"TIDhist\"/>\n\n===Hetch Hetchy Project===\nSan Francisco did not move forward with plans to divert the Tuolumne until the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake]] and subsequent fires devastated the city, proving the inadequacy of the existing water system. After exploring fourteen sites throughout Central California, San Francisco had settled on the Tuolumne's Hetch Hetchy Valley as the ideal location to develop storage and hydroelectric power.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/hetchhetchydams00housgoog|title=Hetch Hetchy dam site|author=United States Congressional House Committee on Public Lands|publisher=Govt. Printing Office|year=1913|page=[https://archive.org/details/hetchhetchydams00housgoog/page/n135 131]}}</ref> Because the area had been located inside Yosemite National Park since 1890, the city petitioned for Congress to pass the [[Raker Act]]. Signed in 1913 by President [[Woodrow Wilson]], the Act allowed San Francisco to dam the Tuolumne River, as long as the water and power provided would be reserved exclusively for public utility, not private sale.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/sanfrancisco/100-years-later-sf-water-war-rages-on/Content?oid=2653490|title=100 years after Raker Act was signed, the fight over Hetch Hetchy dam continues|work=The San Francisco Examiner|first=Jonah Owen|last=Lamb|date=December 19, 2013|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfmuseum.org/hetch/hetchy10.html|title=Hetch Hetchy Reservoir Site|publisher=Virtual Museum of the City of San Francisco}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:HTHspillway.jpg|thumb|left|Hetch Hetchy Reservoir and spillway]]\nThe Hetch Hetchy Valley became the center of the first major environmental controversy in the United States. [[John Muir]], the leader of the [[Sierra Club]], spearheaded a legal battle against the proposed [[O'Shaughnessy Dam (California)|O'Shaughnessy Dam]], famously stating \u2013 \"Dam Hetch Hetchy! As well dam for water-tanks the peoples' cathedrals and churches, for no holier temple has ever been consecrated by the heart of man.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vault.sierraclub.org/ca/hetchhetchy/|title=Hetch Hetchy|publisher=Sierra Club|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The Hetch Hetchy debacle is often credited with birthing modern environmentalism, sharply dividing the [[Conservation in the United States#Early American conservation movement|conservation movement]] \u2013 which favored the development of natural resources for public benefit \u2013 and the preservationists, who believed that sites of scenic value like Hetch Hetchy were better left for public recreation and enjoyment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://foundsf.org/index.php?title=The_Hetch_Hetchy_Story,_Part_I:_John_Muir,_Preservationists_vs._Conservationists|title=The Hetch Hetchy Story, Part I: John Muir, Preservationists vs. Conservationists|work=San Francisco Digital Archive|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nDespite the controversy, the city of San Francisco pushed through, beginning construction in early 1914 and filling the reservoir for the first time in May 1923. The [[Hetch Hetchy Railroad]] was built along {{convert|68|mi|km}} of the Tuolumne River Canyon to provide access to the remote construction site. Hydroelectric power reached San Francisco by 1925, but the first water was not delivered until 1934.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://bawsca.org/water-supply/hetch-hetchy-water-system/\n|title=Hetch Hetchy Water System\n|publisher=Bay Area Water Supply & Conservation Agency\n|website=\n|date=\n|accessdate=2014-09-13}}</ref> Today, San Francisco diverts about 33&nbsp;percent of the flow of the Tuolumne at Hetch Hetchy, or 14&nbsp;percent of the river's total flow.\n\n===New Don Pedro Dam and modern development===\nBy the mid 20th century it was clear that storage capacity in Tuolumne River reservoirs was insufficient to meet growing water demands. The irrigation dam at Don Pedro could only store enough water for a single growing season, allowing little carryover for drought years, and on the other hand providing very little flood control.<ref name=\"tid.org\"/> In the late 1950s TID and MID began planning for a high dam on the Tuolumne River several miles below the existing Don Pedro Dam. In 1961 voters approved revenue bonds to fund the project. However, it took until 1966 for the Federal Power Commission (now [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission|FERC]]) to greenlight the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.donpedro-relicensing.com/Lists/Announcements/Attachments/16/DP%20Newsletter_Issue1_110502.pdf|title=Don Pedro|volume=1|number=1|publisher=Modesto Irrigation District and Turlock Irrigation District|accessdate=2015-10-11}}</ref> Concerns that the new dam would impact [[king salmon]] populations were the primary cause of the delay.<ref>{{cite news\n|author=Cummerow, David\n|title=Growing Storm Wrecked '66 Target Date \u2013 Fish Issue Cost Five Years In Planning New Don Pedro Dam\n|work=The Modesto Bee\n|date=1966-02-17\n}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the dam began in 1967 and the river was diverted in September 1968. The embankment was topped out on May 28, 1970 and the project was formally dedicated on May 22, 1971, after four years of construction and a total cost of over $110 million. It would be eleven years before the new reservoir of {{convert|2030000|acre feet|km3}} \u2013 ten times the size of Old Don Pedro \u2013 filled completely in June 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdec.water.ca.gov/jspplot/jspPlotServlet.jsp?sensor_no=4818&end=03%2F21%2F2015+16%3A35&geom=huge&interval=25000&cookies=cdec01|title=CDEC - Data Application|work=State of California|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> The reservoir submerged {{convert|25|mi|km}} of the middle Tuolumne River and {{convert|12000|acre|ha}} of surrounding land, including the historic Gold Rush town of Jacksonville.\n\n===Dam proposals===\n<!--Red Mountain Bar<ref>http://large.stanford.edu/publications/coal/references/docs/tidweb_red_mountain_fact_sheet.pdf</ref><ref>http://www.nwcouncil.org/media/10846/AmyPetersen.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cserc.org/main/news/news_briefs/Don_pedro_plan.html|title=Don Pedro Plans Raise Concerns|publisher=Central Sierra Environmental Research Center|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>-->\nSince the 1970s, the Turlock Irrigation District has proposed damming the Clavey River, a free-flowing tributary of the Tuolumne, to produce hydroelectricity. The dam would have been {{convert|413|ft|m}} high and dried up most of the lower Clavey, a popular whitewater run. In 1994 the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]] studied the project and determined that the benefits would not justify the financial and environmental costs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-01-25/news/mn-24212_1_dam-project|date=January 25, 1995|first=Richard C.|last=Paddock|title=Power Company Shelves Plans to Build Dam Near Yosemite|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-07-30/local/me-21650_1_clavey-river|title=Study Throws Cold Water on Dam Plan|date=July 30, 1994|first=Richard C.|last=Paddock|publisher=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Recreation==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2015}}\nThe Tuolumne River watershed receives over a million recreational visits each year, primarily to the protected wilderness areas of Yosemite National Park and to the difficult but popular [[whitewater]] on the Main Tuolumne and Cherry Creek.{{sfn|Epke|Finger|Lusardi|Marks|2010|p=4}}\n\nThe Tuolumne is considered a classic California whitewater run, and has been used recreationally since the 1960s. Most rafters put in at Meral's Pool, located about {{convert|2|mi|km}} below Cherry Creek, for the {{convert|18|mi|km|adj=on}} run to Lake Don Pedro. Several rafting companies serve the main Tuolumne, a [[International Scale of River Difficulty|Class IV+]] (advanced) river with many rapids changing to Class V when the flow exceeds {{convert|4000|cuft/s|m3/s}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuolumne-river.com/tuolumne.htm|title=Whitewater Rafting on the Tuolumne River|publisher=tuolumne-river.com|accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> The most difficult single rapids is Clavey Falls, located just above the Clavey River; the longest is Grey's Grindstone, at nearly a mile (1.6&nbsp;km). Between these two rapids the swimming holes of the Clavey are a popular camping spot during the summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-w-r.com/rivers/tuolumne-river.html|title=Rafting on Tuolumne River in California|publisher=California Whitewater Rafting|accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> The Cherry Creek is also run by commercial trips. It is considered one of the most difficult whitewater rivers in the entire United States, with fifteen Class V rapids.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aorafting.com/river/cherry-creek/welcome.htm|title=Cherry Creek / Upper Tuolumne River - Whitewater Rafting (Advanced)|work=All-Outdoors California Whitewater Rafting|accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> Both runs are dam controlled, which usually extends the rafting season through the dry late summer and fall.\n\nIn Yosemite National Park, the Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne (from Tuolumne Meadows to Hetch Hetchy Reservoir) was first kayaked in 1983. This {{convert|32|mi|km|adj=on}} segment is rated Class IV-V+, with many waterfalls requiring a portage. In addition to being extremely difficult (if not borderline impossible at the aforementioned waterfalls) the water flow depends entirely on rain and snow melt, and the whitewater season can be extremely short during dry years. The general consensus is \"that the best paddling in is the upper miles while the middle section is better for hikers and canyoneers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/324/|title=Tuolumne Meadows to Hetch Hetchy Reservoir (Grand Canyon of the Tuolumne River)|publisher=American Whitewater|date=2009-03-12|accessdate=2015-10-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Clavey River, not being located in the national park, is open to public access, but due to its remoteness and difficulty (Class V+), and the short window of boatable spring runoff, it is only run by a handful of kayakers each year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.friendsoftheriver.org/site/PageServer?pagename=FORCalRiversClaveyRiver |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-05-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708085201/http://www.friendsoftheriver.org/site/PageServer?pagename=FORCalRiversClaveyRiver |archivedate=2007-07-08 }}</ref>\n\nTo protect the river, the [[U.S. Forest Service]] requires private trips to obtain a permit before floating the Tuolumne.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/stanislaus/recarea/?recid=14975|work=Stanislaus National Forest|title=Tuolumne Wild & Scenic River|publisher=USFS|accessdate=2015-10-17}}</ref> Running the Tuolumne within Yosemite National Park was also in a legal gray zone until 2015, when the park opened the Tuolumne and [[Merced River|Merced]] Rivers to limited paddling and rafting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canoekayak.com/whitewater-kayak/yosemite-rivers-now-open-paddling/|title=Yosemite Rivers Now Open to Paddling: Management plan for Merced River means more paddling opportunities in the park|author=Buchanan, Eugene|publisher=CanoeKayak.com|date=2015-04-26|accessdate=2015-10-18}}</ref>\n\n== Wildfire ==\nIn 2013, the [[Rim Fire]] burned 257,314 acres<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fs.usda.gov/Internet/FSE_DOCUMENTS/stelprd3808811.pdf|title=Rim Fire Recovery Update|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. This megafire was, at the time, California's third largest wildfire on record<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wildfiretoday.com/tag/rim-fire/|title=Rim Fire Archives|website=Wildfire Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>. This wildfire devistated habitat for many native and/or endangered species, and has impacted recreational opportunities, communities and economies alike. \n\n==See also==\n*[[List of rivers of California]]\n*[[Roderick Nash]]\n*[[Tuolumne River Regional Park]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book|editor-last1=Mount|editor-first1=J|editor-first2=S|editor-last2=Purdy|first1=G|last1=Epke|first2=M|last2=Finger|first3=R|last3=Lusardi|first4=N|last4=Marks|first5=A|last5=Nichols|first6=S|last6=Null|first7=T|last7=O\u2019Rear|first8=A|last8=Senter|first9=J|last9=Viers|year=2010|title=Confluence: A Natural and Human History of the Tuolumne River Watershed|publisher=Department of Geology and Center for Watershed Sciences. UC Davis|url=https://watershed.ucdavis.edu/tuolumne/resources/ConfluenceTuolumneV1.pdf|accessdate=2014-09-12|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons+cat}}\n* [http://www.tuolumne-river.com/ Informational Site about rafting on the Tuolumne River]\n* [http://www.caliriver.com/tuolumne/ News and information about rafting the Tuolumne River]\n* [https://www.blm.gov/programs/national-conservation-lands/california/tuolumne-wsr Tuolumne Wild and Scenic River] - BLM page\n\n{{Central Valley Rivers|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tuolumne River| ]]\n[[Category:Rivers of the Sierra Nevada (U.S.)]]\n[[Category:Tributaries of the San Joaquin River]]\n[[Category:Wild and Scenic Rivers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Mariposa County, California]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Stanislaus County, California]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Tuolumne County, California]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Yosemite National Park]]\n[[Category:Geography of Modesto, California]]\n[[Category:Hetch Hetchy Project]]\n[[Category:Geography of the San Joaquin Valley]]\n[[Category:Stanislaus National Forest]]\n[[Category:Biosphere reserves of the United States]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Northern California]]\n[[Category:Rivers of the Sierra Nevada in California]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuolumne_River"}
{"title_page": "Tunku Abdul Rahman University College", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman|University System of Tunku Abdul Rahman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Third-party|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Tunku Abdul Rahman University College\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{native name|ms|Kolej Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman}}<br />{{native name|zh-hant|\u62c9\u66fc\u5927\u5b66\u5b66\u9662|italics=off}}<!--end nobold:-->}}\n| motto = Beyond Education\n| established = 1969\n| type = Private\n| chairman = Dato' Sri Liow Tiong Lai\n| president = Prof Ir Dr Lee Sze Wei\n| city = [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|3.215118|101.728345|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = Kuala Lumpur Main Campus <br> Penang Branch Campus <br> Perak Branch Campus <br> Johor Branch Campus <br> Pahang Branch <br> Sabah Branch\n| former_names = Tunku Abdul Rahman College (1969\u20132013)\n| website = {{URL|tarc.edu.my}}\n| image_name = TARUC LOGO (colour).JPG\n| enrollment = About 28,000\n| affiliations = [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants|ACCA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.accaglobal.com/my/en.html|title=ACCA Malaysia|publisher=ACCA Global|date=December 2018}}</ref>, [[Chartered Institute of Management Accountants|CIMA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cimaglobal.com |title=CIMA Global|publisher=CIMA|date=December 2018}}</ref>, MAICSA<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maicsa.org.my/|title=The Malaysian Institute of Chartered Secretaries and Administrators|publisher=MAICSA|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>, FPAM<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fpam.org.my/|title=Financial Planning Association of Malaysia|publisher=FPAM|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>, [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|ICAEW]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icaew.com/|title=Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|publisher=ICAEW|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>, CPA Malaysia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpaaustralia.com.au/about-us/contact-us/malaysia|title=Certified Practising Accountant Malaysia|publisher=CPA Australia|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>, [[CPA Australia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpaaustralia.com.au/|title=Certified Practising Accountant Australia|publisher=CPA Australia|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>, [[Finance Accreditation Agency|FAA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.faa.org.my/|title=Finance Accreditation Agency|publisher=FAA|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, [[Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport|CILTM]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cilt-m.com.my/en/index.php/|title=Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport Malaysia|publisher=CILTM|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, [[Chartered Institute of Marketing|CIM]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cim.co.uk/|title=Chartered Institute of Marketing|publisher=CIM|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, [[Board of Engineers Malaysia|BEM]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bem.org.my/|title=Board of Engineers Malaysia|publisher=BEM|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, RISM<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rism.org.my/|title=Royal Institution of Surveyors Malaysia|publisher=RISM|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, BQSM<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bqsm.gov.my/index.php/en/|title=Board of Quantity Surveyors Malaysia|publisher=BQSM|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, BOVAEP, LAM, IKM\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese|t=\u62c9\u66fc\u5927\u5b78\u5b78\u9662|s=\u62c9\u66fc\u5927\u5b66\u5b66\u9662|p=L\u0101m\u00e0n D\u00e0xu\u00e9 Xu\u00e9yu\u00e0n|order=st}}\n\n'''Tunku Abdul Rahman University College''', abbreviated '''TAR UC''', is a non-profit, private [[university college]] in [[Malaysia]]. Named after the country's first prime minister, [[Tunku Abdul Rahman]], the school was founded in 1969 as Tunku Abdul Rahman College (or TAR College) by the [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] (MCA). On 2 May 2013, it officially became a university college. \n\nTAR UC's main campus covers {{convert|186|acre|ha}} at Jalan Genting Kelang in Malaysia's capital, [[Kuala Lumpur]]. The university college also has five branches across Malaysia, in the states of [[Penang]], [[Perak]], [[Johor]], [[Pahang]] and [[Sabah]]. The first branch campus, in Penang, began at a temporary location in 1994 before moving to Tanjung Bungah five years later. The second and third branch campuses were founded in [[Kampar, Perak]] and Johor in 1998, and the Pahang faculty branch was established in 1999. The Sabah faculty branch was founded in 2002 in Sabah, [[East Malaysia]]. \n\nThe university college has a student population of over 28,000, including international students from 24 countries including [[China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Mauritius]], [[Papua New Guinea]], [[India]], [[Algeria]], [[Brunei]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Somalia]], [[Pakistan]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Syria]] and [[Yemen]] etc. Over 50 years since its inception, TAR UC has produced more than 210,000 alumni.\n\nTAR UC is the only institution in the world to conduct the Internally Assessed [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants|ACCA]] Fundamentals programme<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accaglobal.com/my/en/cam/iwd/inspirational-women/kho-sokkee.html|title=Kho Sok Kee, vice president of administration and facilities development, TAR UC {{!}} ACCA Global|website=www.accaglobal.com|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref>, and the only institution in Malaysia to be granted the Graduate Gateway status by the [[Chartered Institute of Marketing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/02/23/liow-tar-uc-hopeful-of-gaining-university-status/|title=Liow: TAR UC hopeful of gaining university status |website=thestar.com.my |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n[[File:Tunku Abdul Rahman University College.jpg|alt=Main entrance of TAR UC's KL Main Campus.|thumb|260x260px|Main entrance of TAR UC's KL Main Campus.]]{{TOC limit}}\n\n==History==\n{{See also|History of Malaysia}}\nIn the early years of Malaysian independence, there was a lack of opportunity to pursue higher education. An institution of higher learning was suggested by [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] president Tun Tan Siew Sin. Tan initially suggested the Chinese-language Merdeka University, which was rejected by the government. As a compromise, an [[English language|English]]-[[Medium of instruction|medium]] college was proposed. In April 1968, Tan appointed a working team (chaired by Tan Sri Khaw Kai Boh) to make recommendations for an institution of higher learning.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v9QEBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA403#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Southeast Asian Personalities of Chinese Descent: A Biographical Dictionary|editor= Leo Suryadinata|page=403 |publisher=ISEAS Publishing |date=30 December 2012 |isbn= 978-9814345217 }}</ref>\n\nIts blueprint was submitted to the government, and received the support of Minister of Education Mohamed Khir Johari. The working team estimated that it would require [[Malaysian ringgit|RM]] 20 million to set up the college, and the government agreed to provide the financial assistance on a dollar-for-dollar basis. Prime Minister Tunku Abdul Rahman consented to the college being named for him.\n\nTAR College began operations on 24 February 1969 with its School of Pre-University Studies and an initial enrollment of 764 students. A 15 September 1972 [[Instrument of Government]] provided the legal framework for the administration of the college. Minister of Education Tun Hussein Onn presented the instrument to Tan Siew Sin, the first college president. To raise funds for a campus in Kuala Lumpur, the MCA launched a national fundraising campaign in 1972 led by MCA publicity director [[Lee San Choon]].\n\nIn February 1973, the government approved the allocation of land for the main Kuala Lumpur campus in [[Setapak]]. The ground-breaking ceremony was officiated by Rahman in August 1973. Phase one, including an administrative building, a library, two laboratory blocks, one large and eight small lecture theatres and a canteen, was completed in 1976.\n\nFundraising activities in the 1990s, such as the nationwide TAR College Fund-Raising Campaign, Taxithon, Walkathon, TAR College Torch Run and Motorthon, were led by TAR College Council chairman Ling Liong Sik. Expansion continued under the leadership of TAR College Council chairmen [[Ong Ka Ting]] and [[Chua Soi Lek]]. Since its 2013 upgrade to a university college, TAR UC continued its steady development under the leadership of [[Liow Tiong Lai]]. The latest infrastructure development, the new phase of the Penang branch campus which began on 7 December 2015, includes a three-storey library building, two four-storey faculty blocks and a twin lecture-theatre hall.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n==Institutional Awards==\n'''Asia Pacific CSR Awards 2016'''\n\nTAR UC was accorded the Excellence in Education Improvement award in the Asia Pacific CSR Awards 2016 under the award category of Socially Responsible Company in Education Improvement on 27 September 2016. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csrasiapacificforum.org/awards2016.html|title=Welcome to Asia Pacific CSR Awards 2016!|website=www.csrasiapacificforum.org|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref>\n\n'''Premier Digital Technology Institution'''\n\nTAR UC was recognised with the Premier Digital Tech Institution status by the [[Malaysia Digital Economy Corporation|Malaysia Digital Economy Corporation (MDEC)]] and the Ministry of Higher Education in 2017. This status was renewed again in 2019. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.studyinternational.com/news/malaysia-announces-3-new-premier-digital-tech-institutions/|title=Malaysia announces 3 new Premier Digital Tech Institutions|date=2019-06-18|website=Study International|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n==Faculties==\n<mapframe text=\"Location of TARUC Main Campus\" width=300 height=300 zoom=14 latitude=3.2164825 longitude=101.7298803>\n{\n  \"type\": \"ExternalData\",\n  \"service\": \"geoshape\",\n  \"ids\": \"Q7853255\",\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"title\": \"Tunku Abdul Rahman University College\",\n    \"description\": \"Main Campus\",\n  }\n}\n</mapframe>\n\n==={{anchor|Faculty of Accountancy, Finance & Business (FAFB)}} Faculty of Accountancy, Finance and Business (FAFB)===\nProgrammes are offered at diploma, undergraduate and/or postgraduate levels in:\n\n*[[Accounting in Malaysia|Accounting]]\n*Accounting and Finance\n* Banking and Finance \n* Business Administration \n*Business Economics\n*Commerce\n*Corporate Administration\n*Corporate Governance\n*[[E-commerce]] & Marketing\n*Economics\n*E-marketing\n*Entrepreneurship\n*[[Finance]]\n* Finance & Investment\n* Human Resource Management \n* International Business\n*Investment Management\n* Logistics & Supply Chain Management \n*Marketing\n* Retail Management\n\n====Accreditation====\n\nTAR UC is the only institution in the world to be accorded the exclusive privilege to run the Internally Assessed [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants|ACCA]] Applied Knowledge and Applied Skills level examinations where students of the Bachelor of Commerce (Honours) programme are granted exemptions from all 9 papers of this level upon completion of their second year of study. \n\nTAR UC students under the Bachelor of Accounting (Honours) programme are granted conditional exemptions for all the 9 Applied Knowledge and Applied Skills level papers upon graduation.\n\nTAR UC has also been recognised as a CIMA Global Learning Premium Partner where students under the Bachelor of Accounting (Honours) programme are granted the maximum exemption of 11 out of 16 papers of CIMA. \n\nAdditionally, TAR UC is the first and only CIM Graduate Gateway accredited university in Malaysia where students under the Bachelor of Business (Honours) in Marketing programme are given exemption on Accreditation of Prior Learning (APL) basis from one out of three modules of the CIM Diploma in Professional Marketing.\n\nOther accreditations and exemptions secured by relevant FAFB programmes are as follows:\n* ICSA:\u00a0Exemption for 3 out of 7 papers (Bachelor's degree), and full exemption for all papers (Master's degree).\n* ICAEW: \u00a0Exemption for 8 out of 15 papers.\n* MICPA: \u00a0Exemption for 4 out of 9 papers.\n* CPA Australia: Exemption for 6 out of 12 papers.\n* FPAM: Exemption for 1 out of 4 papers.\n\n===Faculty of Engineering and Technology (FOET)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at [[diploma]], undergraduate and/or postgraduate levels in:\n\n* Mechatronics\n* Electrical and Electronics Engineering\n*Engineering Science\n* Mechanical Engineering\n* Mechanical & Manufacturing Engineering\n* Electronic (Communication) Engineering\n*Telecommunication Engineering\n\n====Accreditation====\nTAR UC offers engineering programmes that are accredited by the Engineering Accreditation Council, Board of Engineers Malaysia.    \n\n===Faculty of Built Environment (FOBE)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at diploma and undergraduate levels in:\n\n* Architecture\n* Interior Architecture \n* Building \n* Real Estate Management\n* Construction Management & Economics \n* Quantity Surveying\n\n====Accreditation====\n\nFOBE programmes are designed and delivered in accordance with the requirements of and/or accredited by the respective statutory boards and/or the following professional bodies: \n* Board of [[Quantity surveyor|Quantity Surveyors]] Malaysia (BQSM) \n* Board of Valuers, Appraisers, Estate Agents and Property Managers Malaysia (BoVAEP)\n* Royal Institution of Surveyors Malaysia (RISM)\n* Board of Architects Malaysia (Lembaga Arkitek Malaysia, LAM)\n\n===Faculty of Applied Sciences (FOAS)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at diploma, undergraduate and/or postgraduate levels in:\n\n* Analytical Chemistry\n* Bioscience with Chemistry\n* Chemistry & Biology \n* Food Science\n* Sports & Exercise Science\n* Aquaculture\n* Applied Physics (Instrumentation)\n\n====Accreditation====\n \nRelevant TAR UC programmes are endorsed by [https://www.ikm.org.my Institut Kimia Malaysia] (IKM) and graduates of these programmes may join IKM as a member after gaining two years\u2019 working experience in chemistry-related industries and recognised as \u201cRegistered Chemists\" in Malaysia.\n\nTAR UC is also listed on the list of universities in the [http://faris.moh.gov.my/index.php/anonymous/faris Food Analyst Registration Information System] in Malaysia (FaRIS). Graduates from relevant TAR UC programmes may apply as registered food analysts online with the Ministry of Health under the Food Analyst Act which was passed in 2011. \u00a0\n\n<br />\n===Faculty of Computing and Information Technology (FOCS)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at diploma and undergraduate levels in:\n\n* Computer Science \n* Data Science \n* Business Information Systems\n* Information Security \n* Information Systems Engineering\n* Interactive Software Technology\n* Internet Technology \n* ICT Applications / ICT Support Systems\n* IT Entrepreneurship \n* Management Mathematics with Computing \n* Mobile Application Development \n* Microelectronics\n* Software Engineering \n* Software Systems Development\n\n====Industry Professional Certification ====\nStudents are prepared for Industry Professional Certification in the following focus areas: \n* [[Cisco Certified Network Associate]] (CCNA)\n* [[Cisco Systems|Cisco]] Certified Network Associate Security (CCNA Security)\n* [[CompTIA]] Security+\n* CompTIA [[Linux+]]\n* CompTIA A+\n* [[International Software Testing Qualifications Board|ISTQB]] Certified Tester Foundation Level (CTFL)\n\n===Faculty of Social Science and Humanities (FSSH)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at diploma, undergraduate and/or postgraduate levels in:\n\n* Counselling/psychology\n* English with Drama\n* Hospitality Management\n* Tourism \n* Hospitality & Catering Management\n* Baking & Cake Artistry\n* Culinary Arts\n* Food Service\n* Event Management\n\n<br />\n===Faculty of Communication and Creative Industries (FCCI)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at diploma and undergraduate levels in:\n\n* Advertising \n* Broadcast Communication\n* Journalism \n* Media Studies \n* Public Relations \n* Graphic Design \n* Multimedia Design \n* Fashion Design\n\n<br />\n===Centre for Pre-University Studies (CPUS)===\nThe Centre for Pre-University Studies (CPUS), formerly known as the School of Pre-University Studies) was established in 1969 and offers [[Malaysian Qualifications Agency]] accredited programmes in:\n\n* Foundation in Science\n* Foundation in Arts\n* Foundation in Accounting \n* Foundation in Business \n*Foundation in Computing\n* Foundation in Engineering\n* Cambridge GCE [[GCE Advanced Level|A-Level]] Science\n* Cambridge GCE A-Level Arts\n\nCPUS is recognised as a Cambridge International School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridgeinternational.org/why-choose-us/find-a-cambridge-school/?Country=Malaysia&City=Kuala%20Lumpur|title=Cambridge International Schools in Kuala Lumpur|access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n===Centre for Postgraduate Studies and Research (CPSR)===\nThe CPSR was founded in October 2013 to provide infrastructure and support to TAR UC to conduct postgraduate-level programmes and assist academic staff to pursue scholarly research. The centre is tasked with the admission of the college's postgraduate students (those studying for master's, PhD and other graduate qualifications).\n\nThe centre manages the college's research grants. In 2014, the college secured three Fundamental Research Grant Scheme grants from the [[Ministry of Education (Malaysia)|Ministry of Education]] (totaling RM376,400) for 2014-2016.\n\nCPSR currently offers the following postgraduate and doctorate programmes:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |Master's Degree\n|-\n!By  Coursework \n!By  Research \n|-\n|Master of Accounting and Finance \n|Master of Arts (Psychology)\n|-\n|Master of Architecture \n|Master of Computer Science \n|-\n|Master of Business Administration \n|Master of Engineering Science \n|-\n|Master of Corporate Governance \n|Master of Information Technology \n|-\n|Master of Investment Management \n|Master of Science \n|-\n|\n|Master of Science (Life Science) \n|-\n|\n|Master of Science (Food Science) \n|-\n|\n|Master of Science in Built Environment\n|-\n|\n|Master of Science in Mathematical Sciences\n|-\n|\n|Master of Science in Sport Science\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Doctoral Degree\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Computer Science)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Information Technology)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Life Sciences)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Mathematical Sciences)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Physical Science)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Sports Science)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy in Built Environment \n|}\n<br />\n\n=={{anchor|Facilities at main campus}}Main Campus Facilities==\n==={{anchor|Sports facilities}}Sports===\n[[File:KL Main Campus Sports Complex.jpg|alt=|thumb|TAR UC's Sports Complex]]\nWith 186 acres of land and surrounded by lush and hilly greeneries, the Kuala Lumpur Main Campus promises an inspiring and conducive study environment. Apart from a vibrant learning environment, the Main Campus is also equipped with top-notch recreational and academic facilities that help students excel both in and out of the classroom.  \n\n===== '''Sports Complex''' =====\n* Gymnasium\n* Dancing room \n* Badminton courts\n* Indoor basketball court \n* Roof top tennis court. \n\n===== '''Clubhouse''' =====\n* Olympic-sized swimming pool \n* Squash courts \n* Snooker table\n\n===== '''Outdoor facilities''' =====\n* Football field\n* Futsal courts \n* Handball courts \n* Volleyball courts\n* Basketball courts \n* Jogging track\n\n===== '''Academic Facilities''' =====\n* Integrated Innovation Hub (I<sup>2</sup> Hub)\n* Student Career Development Centre (SCDC) \n* Library\n* Cyber Centre\n* IBM Centre of Excellence \n* Investment share trading room \n* Broadcast laboratories and studios \n* Video and audio lab \n* Photography studio \n* Newsroom\n* Multimedia labs\n* Fashion studios \n* Creative workshops \n* V Gallery\n* Chemistry labs\n* Biotechnology labs\n* Sports and exercise science labs \n* Physics labs \n* Networking lounge \n* Pitching hall \n* Co-working space \u00a0\n\n===Accommodation===\n====On-campus hostel====\n[[File:OffCampusHostel2.jpg|alt=|thumb|Teratai Residency]]\nThe hostel consists of 10 blocks of 5-storey building with 1,000 standard rooms which can accommodate 2,000 students. Each room is on a twin-sharing basis with 300 rooms allocated for male and 700 rooms for female in separate blocks. Each floor has its own common bathrooms, toilets, pantry, water dispenser and drying area.\n\n====Off-campus accommodation - Teratai Residency====\nThe student residence is a 28-storey building which consists of 448 units with 3 air conditioning/non-air conditioning rooms in each unit. It can accommodate at least 1,500 students. Amenities in the student residence include gym room, swimming pool, multipurpose hall, barbeque area, cafeterias, study rooms, convenience and stationery shop, hot/cold water dispensers, self-service laundry machines, and [[Surau]]. Each unit is complete with bathrooms, toilets, pantry, fridge, induction cooker, sofa, flat screen TV, shoes rack and drying areas. Beds, cupboards, study tables, chairs, bookshelves, ceiling fan are provided in every room.\n\n===Transportation===\nTAR UC has a fleet of air-conditioned buses to ferry students between the Kuala Lumpur Main Campus and nearby residential areas and LRT stations.\n\n===Computing facilities===\nIn addition to Internet computers in the library, more are at the Cyber Centre. [[Wi-Fi]] hotspots are across the college, including the library and canteens.\n\n<br />\n\n==Partner Institution==\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|Australia}} Australia\n**[[Griffith University]]\n**[[University of South Australia]]\n*{{flagicon|Ireland}} Ireland\n**[[Athlone Institute of Technology]]\n**[[Cork Institute of Technology]]\n**[[Dublin City University]]\n**[[Dundalk Institute of Technology]]\n**[[Galway-Mayo Institute of Technology]]\n**[[Griffith College]]\n**[[Technological University Dublin]]\n**[[Institute of Technology, Sligo|Institute of Technology Sligo]]\n**[[Letterkenny Institute of Technology]]\n**[[Limerick Institute of Technology]]\n**[[University College Dublin]]\n**[[Waterford Institute of Technology]]\n*{{flagicon|Korea}} Korea\n**[[Dankook University]]\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|Switzerland}} Switzerland\n**[[IMI International Management Institute Switzerland]]\n*{{flagicon|Malaysia}} Malaysia\n**[[Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman]]<ref name=\"UTARUniversityPartners\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.utar.edu.my/dcinternet/index.jsp?fcatid=7819|title=University Partners - Division of Community and International Networking|publisher=Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman(UTAR)|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} United Kingdom\n**[[Birmingham City University]]\n**[[Coventry University]]\n**[[Edinburgh Napier University]]\n**[[Heriot-Watt University]]\n**[[Queen's University Belfast]]\n**[[Sheffield Hallam University]]\n**[[Teesside University]]\n**[[University College Birmingham]]\n**[[University of Brighton]]\n**[[University of Northampton]]\n**[[University of Plymouth]]\n**[[Middlesex University]]\n*{{flagicon|United States}} United States\n**[[Campbell University]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Malaysia}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.tarc.edu.my/}}\n\n{{University System of Tunku Abdul Rahman}}\n{{Universities in Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Architecture schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:CCNA Networking Academy Program]]\n[[Category:Colleges in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Design schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Journalism schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Engineering universities and colleges in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Hospitality schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Information technology schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Private universities in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Information technology institutes]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Chinese Association]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman|University System of Tunku Abdul Rahman}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Third-party|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Tunku Abdul Rahman University College\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{native name|ms|Kolej Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman}}<br />{{native name|zh-hant|\u62c9\u66fc\u5927\u5b66\u5b66\u9662|italics=off}}<!--end nobold:-->}}\n| motto = Beyond Education\n| established = 1969\n| type = Private\n| chairman = Dato' Sri Liow Tiong Lai\n| president = Prof Ir Dr Lee Sze Wei\n| city = [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|3.215118|101.728345|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = Kuala Lumpur Main Campus <br> Penang Branch Campus <br> Perak Branch Campus <br> Johor Branch Campus <br> Pahang Branch <br> Sabah Branch\n| former_names = Tunku Abdul Rahman College (1969\u20132013)\n| website = {{URL|tarc.edu.my}}\n| image_name = TARUC LOGO (colour).JPG\n| enrollment = About 28,000\n| affiliations = [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants|ACCA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.accaglobal.com/my/en.html|title=ACCA Malaysia|publisher=ACCA Global|date=December 2018}}</ref>, [[Chartered Institute of Management Accountants|CIMA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cimaglobal.com |title=CIMA Global|publisher=CIMA|date=December 2018}}</ref>, MAICSA<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maicsa.org.my/|title=The Malaysian Institute of Chartered Secretaries and Administrators|publisher=MAICSA|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>, FPAM<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fpam.org.my/|title=Financial Planning Association of Malaysia|publisher=FPAM|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>, [[Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|ICAEW]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icaew.com/|title=Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales|publisher=ICAEW|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>, CPA Malaysia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpaaustralia.com.au/about-us/contact-us/malaysia|title=Certified Practising Accountant Malaysia|publisher=CPA Australia|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>, [[CPA Australia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpaaustralia.com.au/|title=Certified Practising Accountant Australia|publisher=CPA Australia|accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>, [[Finance Accreditation Agency|FAA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.faa.org.my/|title=Finance Accreditation Agency|publisher=FAA|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, [[Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport|CILTM]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cilt-m.com.my/en/index.php/|title=Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport Malaysia|publisher=CILTM|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, [[Chartered Institute of Marketing|CIM]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cim.co.uk/|title=Chartered Institute of Marketing|publisher=CIM|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, [[Board of Engineers Malaysia|BEM]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bem.org.my/|title=Board of Engineers Malaysia|publisher=BEM|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, RISM<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rism.org.my/|title=Royal Institution of Surveyors Malaysia|publisher=RISM|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, BQSM<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bqsm.gov.my/index.php/en/|title=Board of Quantity Surveyors Malaysia|publisher=BQSM|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>, BOVAEP, LAM, IKM\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese|t=\u62c9\u66fc\u5927\u5b78\u5b78\u9662|s=\u62c9\u66fc\u5927\u5b66\u5b66\u9662|p=L\u0101m\u00e0n D\u00e0xu\u00e9 Xu\u00e9yu\u00e0n|order=st}}\n\n'''Tunku Abdul Rahman University College''', abbreviated '''TAR UC''', is a non-profit, private [[university college]] in [[Malaysia]]. Named after the country's first prime minister, [[Tunku Abdul Rahman]], the school was founded in 1969 as Tunku Abdul Rahman College (or TAR College) by the [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] (MCA). On 2 May 2013, it officially became a university college. \n\nTAR UC's main campus covers {{convert|186|acre|ha}} at Jalan Genting Kelang in Malaysia's capital, [[Kuala Lumpur]]. The university college also has five branches across Malaysia, in the states of [[Penang]], [[Perak]], [[Johor]], [[Pahang]] and [[Sabah]]. The first branch campus, in Penang, began at a temporary location in 1994 before moving to Tanjung Bungah five years later. The second and third branch campuses were founded in [[Kampar, Perak]] and Johor in 1998, and the Pahang faculty branch was established in 1999. The Sabah faculty branch was founded in 2002 in Sabah, [[East Malaysia]]. \n\nThe university college has a student population of over 28,000, including international students from 24 countries including [[China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Mauritius]], [[Papua New Guinea]], [[India]], [[Algeria]], [[Brunei]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Somalia]], [[Pakistan]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Syria]] and [[Yemen]] etc. Over 50 years since its inception, TAR UC has produced more than 210,000 alumni.\n\nTAR UC is the only institution in the world to conduct the Internally Assessed [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants|ACCA]] Fundamentals programme<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.accaglobal.com/my/en/cam/iwd/inspirational-women/kho-sokkee.html|title=Kho Sok Kee, vice president of administration and facilities development, TAR UC {{!}} ACCA Global|website=www.accaglobal.com|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref>, and the only institution in Malaysia to be granted the Graduate Gateway status by the [[Chartered Institute of Marketing]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2019/02/23/liow-tar-uc-hopeful-of-gaining-university-status/|title=Liow: TAR UC hopeful of gaining university status |website=thestar.com.my |access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>.\n\n<br />\n\n[[File:Tunku Abdul Rahman University College.jpg|alt=Main entrance of TAR UC's KL Main Campus.|thumb|260x260px|Main entrance of TAR UC's KL Main Campus.]]{{TOC limit}}\n\n==History==\n{{See also|History of Malaysia}}\nIn the early years of Malaysian independence, there was a lack of opportunity to pursue higher education. An institution of higher learning was suggested by [[Malaysian Chinese Association]] president Tun Tan Siew Sin. Tan initially suggested the Chinese-language Merdeka University, which was rejected by the government. As a compromise, an [[English language|English]]-[[Medium of instruction|medium]] college was proposed. In April 1968, Tan appointed a working team (chaired by Tan Sri Khaw Kai Boh) to make recommendations for an institution of higher learning.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v9QEBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA403#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Southeast Asian Personalities of Chinese Descent: A Biographical Dictionary|editor= Leo Suryadinata|page=403 |publisher=ISEAS Publishing |date=30 December 2012 |isbn= 978-9814345217 }}</ref>\n\nIts blueprint was submitted to the government, and received the support of Minister of Education Mohamed Khir Johari. The working team estimated that it would require [[Malaysian ringgit|RM]] 20 million to set up the college, and the government agreed to provide the financial assistance on a dollar-for-dollar basis. Prime Minister Tunku Abdul Rahman consented to the college being named for him.\n\nTAR College began operations on 24 February 1969 with its School of Pre-University Studies and an initial enrollment of 764 students. A 15 September 1972 [[Instrument of Government]] provided the legal framework for the administration of the college. Minister of Education Tun Hussein Onn presented the instrument to Tan Siew Sin, the first college president. To raise funds for a campus in Kuala Lumpur, the MCA launched a national fundraising campaign in 1972 led by MCA publicity director [[Lee San Choon]].\n\nIn February 1973, the government approved the allocation of land for the main Kuala Lumpur campus in [[Setapak]]. The ground-breaking ceremony was officiated by Rahman in August 1973. Phase one, including an administrative building, a library, two laboratory blocks, one large and eight small lecture theatres and a canteen, was completed in 1976.\n\nFundraising activities in the 1990s, such as the nationwide TAR College Fund-Raising Campaign, Taxithon, Walkathon, TAR College Torch Run and Motorthon, were led by TAR College Council chairman Ling Liong Sik. Expansion continued under the leadership of TAR College Council chairmen [[Ong Ka Ting]] and [[Chua Soi Lek]]. Since its 2013 upgrade to a university college, TAR UC continued its steady development under the leadership of [[Liow Tiong Lai]]. The latest infrastructure development, the new phase of the Penang branch campus which began on 7 December 2015, includes a three-storey library building, two four-storey faculty blocks and a twin lecture-theatre hall.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n==Institutional Awards==\n'''Asia Pacific CSR Awards 2016'''\n\nTAR UC was accorded the Excellence in Education Improvement award in the Asia Pacific CSR Awards 2016 under the award category of Socially Responsible Company in Education Improvement on 27 September 2016. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.csrasiapacificforum.org/awards2016.html|title=Welcome to Asia Pacific CSR Awards 2016!|website=www.csrasiapacificforum.org|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref>\n\n'''Premier Digital Technology Institution'''\n\nTAR UC was recognised with the Premier Digital Tech Institution status by the [[Malaysia Digital Economy Corporation|Malaysia Digital Economy Corporation (MDEC)]] and the Ministry of Higher Education in 2017. This status was renewed again in 2019. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.studyinternational.com/news/malaysia-announces-3-new-premier-digital-tech-institutions/|title=Malaysia announces 3 new Premier Digital Tech Institutions|date=2019-06-18|website=Study International|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n==Faculties==\n<mapframe text=\"Location of TARUC Main Campus\" width=300 height=300 zoom=14 latitude=3.2164825 longitude=101.7298803>\n{\n  \"type\": \"ExternalData\",\n  \"service\": \"geoshape\",\n  \"ids\": \"Q7853255\",\n  \"properties\": {\n    \"title\": \"Tunku Abdul Rahman University College\",\n    \"description\": \"Main Campus\",\n  }\n}\n</mapframe>\n\n==={{anchor|Faculty of Accountancy, Finance & Business (FAFB)}} Faculty of Accountancy, Finance and Business (FAFB)===\nProgrammes are offered at diploma, undergraduate and/or postgraduate levels in:\n\n*[[Accounting in Malaysia|Accounting]]\n*Accounting and Finance\n* Banking and Finance \n* Business Administration \n*Business Economics\n*Commerce\n*Corporate Administration\n*Corporate Governance\n*[[E-commerce]] & Marketing\n*Economics\n*E-marketing\n*Entrepreneurship\n*[[Finance]]\n* Finance & Investment\n* Human Resource Management \n* International Business\n*Investment Management\n* Logistics & Supply Chain Management \n*Marketing\n* Retail Management\n\n====Accreditation====\n\nTAR UC is the only institution in the world to be accorded the exclusive privilege to run the Internally Assessed [[Association of Chartered Certified Accountants|ACCA]] Applied Knowledge and Applied Skills level examinations where students of the Bachelor of Commerce (Honours) programme are granted exemptions from all 9 papers of this level upon completion of their second year of study. \n\nTAR UC students under the Bachelor of Accounting (Honours) programme are granted conditional exemptions for all the 9 Applied Knowledge and Applied Skills level papers upon graduation.\n\nTAR UC has also been recognised as a CIMA Global Learning Premium Partner where students under the Bachelor of Accounting (Honours) programme are granted the maximum exemption of 11 out of 16 papers of CIMA. \n\nAdditionally, TAR UC is the first and only CIM Graduate Gateway accredited university in Malaysia where students under the Bachelor of Business (Honours) in Marketing programme are given exemption on Accreditation of Prior Learning (APL) basis from one out of three modules of the CIM Diploma in Professional Marketing.\n\nOther accreditations and exemptions secured by relevant FAFB programmes are as follows:\n* ICSA:\u00a0Exemption for 3 out of 7 papers (Bachelor's degree), and full exemption for all papers (Master's degree).\n* ICAEW: \u00a0Exemption for 8 out of 15 papers.\n* MICPA: \u00a0Exemption for 4 out of 9 papers.\n* CPA Australia: Exemption for 6 out of 12 papers.\n* FPAM: Exemption for 1 out of 4 papers.\n\n===Faculty of Engineering and Technology (FOET)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at [[diploma]], undergraduate and/or postgraduate levels in:\n\n* Mechatronics\n* Electrical and Electronics Engineering\n*Engineering Science\n* Mechanical Engineering\n* Mechanical & Manufacturing Engineering\n* Electronic (Communication) Engineering\n*Telecommunication Engineering\n\n====Accreditation====\nTAR UC offers engineering programmes that are accredited by the Engineering Accreditation Council, Board of Engineers Malaysia.    \n\n===Faculty of Built Environment (FOBE)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at diploma and undergraduate levels in:\n\n* Architecture\n* Interior Architecture \n* Building \n* Real Estate Management\n* Construction Management & Economics \n* Quantity Surveying\n\n====Accreditation====\n\nFOBE programmes are designed and delivered in accordance with the requirements of and/or accredited by the respective statutory boards and/or the following professional bodies: \n* Board of [[Quantity surveyor|Quantity Surveyors]] Malaysia (BQSM) \n* Board of Valuers, Appraisers, Estate Agents and Property Managers Malaysia (BoVAEP)\n* Royal Institution of Surveyors Malaysia (RISM)\n* Board of Architects Malaysia (Lembaga Arkitek Malaysia, LAM)\n\n===Faculty of Applied Sciences (FOAS)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at diploma, undergraduate and/or postgraduate levels in:\n\n* Analytical Chemistry\n* Bioscience with Chemistry\n* Chemistry & Biology \n* Food Science\n* Sports & Exercise Science\n* Aquaculture\n* Applied Physics (Instrumentation)\n\n====Accreditation====\n \nRelevant TAR UC programmes are endorsed by [https://www.ikm.org.my Institut Kimia Malaysia] (IKM) and graduates of these programmes may join IKM as a member after gaining two years\u2019 working experience in chemistry-related industries and recognised as \u201cRegistered Chemists\" in Malaysia.\n\nTAR UC is also listed on the list of universities in the [http://faris.moh.gov.my/index.php/anonymous/faris Food Analyst Registration Information System] in Malaysia (FaRIS). Graduates from relevant TAR UC programmes may apply as registered food analysts online with the Ministry of Health under the Food Analyst Act which was passed in 2011. \u00a0\n\n<br />\n===Faculty of Computing and Information Technology (FOCS)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at diploma and undergraduate levels in:\n\n* Computer Science \n* Data Science \n* Business Information Systems\n* Information Security \n* Information Systems Engineering\n* Interactive Software Technology\n* Internet Technology \n* ICT Applications / ICT Support Systems\n* IT Entrepreneurship \n* Management Mathematics with Computing \n* Mobile Application Development \n* Microelectronics\n* Software Engineering \n* Software Systems Development\n\n====Industry Professional Certification ====\nStudents are prepared for Industry Professional Certification in the following focus areas: \n* [[Cisco Certified Network Associate]] (CCNA)\n* [[Cisco Systems|Cisco]] Certified Network Associate Security (CCNA Security)\n* [[CompTIA]] Security+\n* CompTIA [[Linux+]]\n* CompTIA A+\n* [[International Software Testing Qualifications Board|ISTQB]] Certified Tester Foundation Level (CTFL)\n\n===Faculty of Social Science and Humanities (FSSH)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at diploma, undergraduate and/or postgraduate levels in:\n\n* Counselling/psychology\n* English with Drama\n* Hospitality Management\n* Tourism \n* Hospitality & Catering Management\n* Baking & Cake Artistry\n* Culinary Arts\n* Food Service\n* Event Management\n\n<br />\n===Faculty of Communication and Creative Industries (FCCI)===\n\nProgrammes are offered at diploma and undergraduate levels in:\n\n* Advertising \n* Broadcast Communication\n* Journalism \n* Media Studies \n* Public Relations \n* Graphic Design \n* Multimedia Design \n* Fashion Design\n\n<br />\n===Centre for Pre-University Studies (CPUS)===\nThe Centre for Pre-University Studies (CPUS), formerly known as the School of Pre-University Studies) was established in 1969 and offers [[Malaysian Qualifications Agency]] accredited programmes in:\n\n* Foundation in Science\n* Foundation in Arts\n* Foundation in Accounting \n* Foundation in Business \n*Foundation in Computing\n* Foundation in Engineering\n* Cambridge GCE [[GCE Advanced Level|A-Level]] Science\n* Cambridge GCE A-Level Arts\n\nCPUS is recognised as a Cambridge International School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridgeinternational.org/why-choose-us/find-a-cambridge-school/?Country=Malaysia&City=Kuala%20Lumpur|title=Cambridge International Schools in Kuala Lumpur|access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n===Centre for Postgraduate Studies and Research (CPSR)===\nThe CPSR was founded in October 2013 to provide infrastructure and support to TAR UC to conduct postgraduate-level programmes and assist academic staff to pursue scholarly research. The centre is tasked with the admission of the college's postgraduate students (those studying for master's, PhD and other graduate qualifications).\n\nThe centre manages the college's research grants. In 2014, the college secured three Fundamental Research Grant Scheme grants from the [[Ministry of Education (Malaysia)|Ministry of Education]] (totaling RM376,400) for 2014-2016.\n\nCPSR currently offers the following postgraduate and doctorate programmes:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |Master's Degree\n|-\n!By  Coursework \n!By  Research \n|-\n|Master of Accounting and Finance \n|Master of Arts (Psychology)\n|-\n|Master of Architecture \n|Master of Computer Science \n|-\n|Master of Business Administration \n|Master of Engineering Science \n|-\n|Master of Corporate Governance \n|Master of Information Technology \n|-\n|Master of Investment Management \n|Master of Science \n|-\n|\n|Master of Science (Life Science) \n|-\n|\n|Master of Science (Food Science) \n|-\n|\n|Master of Science in Built Environment\n|-\n|\n|Master of Science in Mathematical Sciences\n|-\n|\n|Master of Science in Sport Science\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Doctoral Degree\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Computer Science)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Information Technology)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Life Sciences)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Mathematical Sciences)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Physical Science)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy (Sports Science)\n|-\n|\n|Doctor of Philosophy in Built Environment \n|}\n<br />\n\n=={{anchor|Facilities at main campus}}Main Campus Facilities==\n==={{anchor|Sports facilities}}Sports===\n[[File:KL Main Campus Sports Complex.jpg|alt=|thumb|TAR UC's Sports Complex]]\nWith 186 acres of land and surrounded by lush and hilly greeneries, the Kuala Lumpur Main Campus promises an inspiring and conducive study environment. Apart from a vibrant learning environment, the Main Campus is also equipped with top-notch recreational and academic facilities that help students excel both in and out of the classroom.  \n\n===== '''Sports Complex''' =====\n* Gymnasium\n* Dancing room \n* Badminton courts\n* Indoor basketball court \n* Roof top tennis court. \n\n===== '''Clubhouse''' =====\n* Olympic-sized swimming pool \n* Squash courts \n* Snooker table\n\n===== '''Outdoor facilities''' =====\n* Football field\n* Futsal courts \n* Handball courts \n* Volleyball courts\n* Basketball courts \n* Jogging track\n\n===== '''Academic Facilities''' =====\n* Integrated Innovation Hub (I<sup>2</sup> Hub)\n* Student Career Development Centre (SCDC) \n* Library\n* Cyber Centre\n* IBM Centre of Excellence \n* Investment share trading room \n* Broadcast laboratories and studios \n* Video and audio lab \n* Photography studio \n* Newsroom\n* Multimedia labs\n* Fashion studios \n* Creative workshops \n* V Gallery\n* Chemistry labs\n* Biotechnology labs\n* Sports and exercise science labs \n* Physics labs \n* Networking lounge \n* Pitching hall \n* Co-working space \u00a0\n\n===Accommodation===\n====On-campus hostel====\n[[File:OffCampusHostel2.jpg|alt=|thumb|Teratai Residency]]\nThe hostel consists of 10 blocks of 5-storey building with 1,000 standard rooms which can accommodate 2,000 students. Each room is on a twin-sharing basis with 300 rooms allocated for male and 700 rooms for female in separate blocks. Each floor has its own common bathrooms, toilets, pantry, water dispenser and drying area.\n\n====Off-campus accommodation - Teratai Residency====\nThe student residence is a 28-storey building which consists of 448 units with 3 air conditioning/non-air conditioning rooms in each unit. It can accommodate at least 1,500 students. Amenities in the student residence include gym room, swimming pool, multipurpose hall, barbeque area, cafeterias, study rooms, convenience and stationery shop, hot/cold water dispensers, self-service laundry machines, and [[Surau]]. Each unit is complete with bathrooms, toilets, pantry, fridge, induction cooker, sofa, flat screen TV, shoes rack and drying areas. Beds, cupboards, study tables, chairs, bookshelves, ceiling fan are provided in every room.\n\n===Transportation===\nTAR UC has a fleet of air-conditioned buses to ferry students between the Kuala Lumpur Main Campus and nearby residential areas and LRT stations.\n\n===Computing facilities===\nIn addition to Internet computers in the library, more are at the Cyber Centre. [[Wi-Fi]] hotspots are across the college, including the library and canteens.\n\n<br />\n\n==Partner Institution==\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|Australia}} Australia\n**[[Griffith University]]\n**[[University of South Australia]]\n*{{flagicon|Ireland}} Ireland\n**[[Athlone Institute of Technology]]\n**[[Cork Institute of Technology]]\n**[[Dublin City University]]\n**[[Dundalk Institute of Technology]]\n**[[Galway-Mayo Institute of Technology]]\n**[[Griffith College]]\n**[[Technological University Dublin]]\n**[[Institute of Technology, Sligo|Institute of Technology Sligo]]\n**[[Letterkenny Institute of Technology]]\n**[[Limerick Institute of Technology]]\n**[[University College Dublin]]\n**[[Waterford Institute of Technology]]\n*{{flagicon|Korea}} Korea\n**[[Dankook University]]\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|Switzerland}} Switzerland\n**[[IMI International Management Institute Switzerland]]\n*{{flagicon|Malaysia}} Malaysia\n**[[Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman]]<ref name=\"UTARUniversityPartners\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.utar.edu.my/dcinternet/index.jsp?fcatid=7819|title=University Partners - Division of Community and International Networking|publisher=Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman(UTAR)|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} United Kingdom\n**[[Birmingham City University]]\n**[[Coventry University]]\n**[[Edinburgh Napier University]]\n**[[Heriot-Watt University]]\n**[[Queen's University Belfast]]\n**[[Sheffield Hallam University]]\n**[[Teesside University]]\n**[[University College Birmingham]]\n**[[University of Brighton]]\n**[[University of Northampton]]\n**[[University of Plymouth]]\n**[[Middlesex University]]\n*{{flagicon|United States}} United States\n**[[Campbell University]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Malaysia}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.tarc.edu.my/}}\n\n{{University System of Tunku Abdul Rahman}}\n{{Universities in Malaysia}}\n\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Architecture schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Cambridge schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:CCNA Networking Academy Program]]\n[[Category:Colleges in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Design schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Journalism schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Engineering universities and colleges in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Hospitality schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Information technology schools in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Private universities in Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Kuala Lumpur]]\n[[Category:Information technology institutes]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Chinese Association]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tunku_Abdul_Rahman_University_College"}
{"title_page": "Everybody (Backstreet's Back)", "text_new": "{{short description|1997 single by Backstreet Boys}}\n{{About|the Backstreet Boys song|their 1997 album|Backstreet's Back}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n| cover      = Everybodyuscover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Backstreet Boys]]\n| album      = [[Backstreet's Back]] {{noitalic|(int'l),}} [[Backstreet Boys (1997 album)|Backstreet Boys]] {{noitalic|(US)}}\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Boys Will Be Boys\"|\"[[Anywhere for You (Backstreet Boys song)|Anywhere for You]]\"}}\n| released   = {{start date|1997|6|30}}\n| format     = * [[CD single]]\n* [[7\" single|7\"]]\n| recorded   = October 1996\u20131997\n| studio     =[[Cheiron Studios]] {{small|([[Stockholm]])}} \nParc Studios {{small|([[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]])}}\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 4:48 {{small|(album/extended version)}}<br>3:44 {{small|(radio/7\" edit)}}\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| writer     = {{flat list|\n*[[Denniz PoP]]\n*[[Max Martin]]}}\n| producer   = {{flat list|\n*Denniz PoP\n*Max Martin}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Backstreet Boys\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Anywhere for You (Backstreet Boys song)|Anywhere for You]]\n | prev_year  = 1997\n | title      = Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n | year       = 1997\n | next_title = [[As Long as You Love Me (Backstreet Boys song)|As Long as You Love Me]]\n | next_year  = 1997\n}}{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Backstreet Boys US\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[As Long as You Love Me (Backstreet Boys song)|As Long as You Love Me]]\n | prev_year  = 1997\n | title      = Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n | year       = 1998\n | next_title = [[I'll Never Break Your Heart]]\n | next_year  = 1998\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n| header = Alternate cover\n| type = single\n| cover = ebo1.png\n| border = yes\n| caption = European cover\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|6M6samPEMpM|\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Everybody (Backstreet's Back)'''\" is a song by American boy band [[Backstreet Boys]]. It was released as the first [[Single (music)|single]] from their second international album ''[[Backstreet's Back]]'' in June 1997, and the third single from their [[Backstreet Boys (1997 album)|debut US album]] in March 1998. The US debut was originally released without the song, which references the band's return via their second international album. However, once it was decided that the single would be released in the US, the album was re-released with \"Everybody\" included. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' commented that the song has \"a contagious dance/pop beat and catchy hook that perfectly showcases this talented group's voices.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1998/BB-1998-04-04.pdf|title=Single Reviews|work=Billboard magazine|accessdate=9 February 2020|page=65|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[Zomba Label Group|Zomba]] chairman [[Clive Calder]] suggested the song as a single, but [[Jive Records|Jive]] president [[Barry Weiss]] thought it would be weird to have a song called \"Backstreet's Back\" on the band's first US album. The band suggested it could just mean that they were back home. After Canadian markets began playing the song, US markets near the border began picking the song up. The band met with Weiss and asked that the song be added to the US album after the first million units had already been produced.<ref name=\"ew\">Interview with Backstreet Boys, management, and others from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' 10th Anniversary Issue.</ref> Written and produced by [[Max Martin]] and [[Denniz Pop|Denniz PoP]], \"Everybody\" is one of the Backstreet Boys' most successful singles to date, reaching number 4 in the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], running 22 weeks, and number 3 in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Worldwide Charts|url=http://www.backstreetparadise.com/charts.html|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref> It is [[RIAA certification|certified]] platinum in the United States with 2.1 million sales.\n\nThere are two versions of the song. The international album features the album or 7\" version, which is the standard recording. The US album features the extended version of the song which includes an extended breakdown section, but cuts the bridge. The music video for the song was cut to both versions of the song, with the extended video released to the US market, and the standard video released everywhere else. In late August 2012, Backstreet Boys member [[Nick Carter (musician)|Nick Carter]] revealed via Twitter that the group was recording the song in Spanish, and it might be featured in their eighth studio record for Latin markets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nick Carter twitter update|url=https://twitter.com/nickcarter/status/240277086760206336|accessdate=August 29, 2012|date=August 28, 2012|quote=We are recording backstreets back in Spanish. Omg what's going on! Maybe well put it on the new record for Latin markets. En espa\u00f1ol}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n===Background===\nThe music video was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]] and filmed in [[Los Angeles]], California from June 16\u201318, 1997.<ref name=\"Everybody20\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7865195/backstreet-boys-everybody-backstreets-back-video-anniversary-interview|title=How 'Everybody (Backstreet's Back)' Director Joseph Kahn Pushed Racial Boundaries & Brought a Backstreet Boy to Tears|last=Tailor|first=Leena|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 14, 2017|access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> Kahn was contacted by [[Jive Records]] to direct a project with a \"white [[Jodeci]]\". He initially didn't know who the Backstreet Boys were, but was shocked by the group's European sales figures after being given a [[cassette tape]] and publicity release about them.<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/> Kahn initially started out as a grunge and hip-hop director, but wanted to explore the pop genre, since he grew up listening to music from the 1980s.<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/>\n\nThe haunted house treatment of the video was based on a treatment he envisioned for rapper [[Ice Cube]] a few months prior, and was inspired by the music video of [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Michael Jackson's Thriller (music video)|Thriller]]\".<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/> Kahn and the Backstreet Boys wanted [[Antonio Fargas]] to portray the bus driver, as they were fans of ''[[Starsky & Hutch]]''.<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/> The video shoot lasted for 36 hours, with Nick Carter's mummy shot being filmed last.<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/>\n\nThe video premiered outside the United States in July 1997, although viewers with [[Fuse (TV channel)|MuchMusic USA]] were able to see it as at the time it was still mostly a simulcast of the Canadian channel.  Jive did not get behind the concept of the band in costumes or the $1 million requirements, and did not believe MTV would respect the video. The band ultimately had to put up their own money to shoot the video and had to fight with the label to get reimbursed once it was successful.<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/> In a 2017 interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Kahn reflected on the impact of the music video:<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/><blockquote>I was just trying to do something fun and make the pop video I\u2019d always wanted to make,\" he says. \"I love pop, and it just didn\u2019t exist at that point -- so I guess this helped start the whole pop scene in America. It allowed me to help create a new pop scene and, through these videos, create my view of pop culture.</blockquote>\n\n===Synopsis===\n[[File:Everybody Video BSB.jpg|thumb|The group, with [[Howie D.|Howie]] in front, as they prepare to leave the haunted house]]\nThe video is [[Framing device|bookended]] by scenes framing the context: When their bus breaks down, the band's driver ([[Antonio Fargas]]) insists that the group spend a night at a nearby haunted house (the same house used in the 1995 film ''[[Casper (film)|Casper]]'') while he gets help. It then shows Brian preparing to sleep in one of the bedrooms. As he is in bed, he pulls out a scary animal from under his covers, making him scream in horror. The musical portion of the video plays as a dream sequence in which each band member appears as a different [[movie monster]]: [[Brian Littrell|Brian]] as a [[werewolf]]; [[Howie Dorough|Howie]] as [[Dracula]]; [[Nick Carter (musician)|Nick]] as a [[mummy]]; [[A.J. McLean|A.J.]] as [[Erik (The Phantom of the Opera)|Erik, the Phantom of the Opera]]; and [[Kevin Richardson (musician)|Kevin]] as [[Two-Face]]-like [[Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde]]. The boys, as monsters, mainly appear in their own individual vignettes related to their character, while the band as a group appears in the foyer of the house dressed in centuries-old clothing, performing a dance routine with a group of additional dancers. Supermodel [[Josie Maran]] appears as Howie's companion in his vignette. Following the song, the boys meet up in the foyer, each one having dreamed themselves as monsters. They resolve to leave, but are terrified by the sight of their driver standing at the front door with the appearance of [[Frankenstein's monster]]. The boys scream in terror, and the video ends.\n\nThere are two cuts of the video; one for the US market, and one for the international market, each of which features the edit of the song released on the album for that market. The international video cuts from the opening bookend to the first verse. The bridge of the song is intact and the first half of the dance routine, a ballroom dance portion, is intercut with the vignettes under it. This leads into the second half of the dance portion during the final choruses of the song which are not intercut with the vignettes. In the US cut, the ballroom half of the dance routine and the beginning of the second half are used at the start of the song during the first rhythm-only breakdown, and is not intercut with the vignettes. The second breakdown, which replaces the bridge, is accompanied only by shots from the vignettes, along with some shots of Brian's Wolfman character doing some [[Tumbling (gymnastics)|tumbling]] moves in the foyer and in the various vignettes. When the final choruses begin, the second half of the dance routine is shown again from the start, but is intercut with vignette scenes. Most of the remainder of the video is cut identically, other than several minor instances of alternate scenes or takes being used. The dance floor in the video was painted. At the end, Brian wakes up, looks in his bed to see nothing, and realizes that he had a nightmare. As he tells Howie about his dream, he and the other guys tell each other that they had a dream as well and described what they were. Howie and the others get ready to leave, but find that their bus driver is a monster, making the Backstreet Boys scream in terror.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2020}}\n===MTV Video Music Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[1998 MTV Video Music Awards|1998]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\"\n|[[Best Group Video]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Best Dance Video]]\n|{{nom}}\n{{end}}\n\n===Nickelodeon Kids Choice Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[1999 Kids' Choice Awards|1999]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n|Favorite Song\n|{{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n===Grammy Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n||[[41st Grammy Awards|1999]]\n||Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n|[[Best New Artist]]\n|{{nom}}\n{{end}}\n\n===MuchMusic Video Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n||[[MuchMusic Video Awards|1998]]\n||Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n|Peoples Choice Favorite International Group\n|