f>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/5-random-chart-facts-of-the-week-that-will-leave-you-gobsmacked__19798/|title=5 chart facts of the week to leave you gobsmacked (maybe)|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=July 28, 2017|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=Backstreet Boys|title=Everybody(Backstreet%27s Back)<!-- it's in the RIAA database with this title, including the missing space -->|type=single|award=Platinum|relyear=1998|certyear=1998|salesamount=1,200,000|salesref=<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Q0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA75 |title=Best-Selling Records of 1998 |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=BPI Communications Inc.|date=January 30, 1999 |accessdate=May 31, 2015 |page=75 |issn=0006-2510|volume=111|number=5}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true}}\n\n==Release history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Country\n!Release date\n!Format\n|-\n|Europe\n|June 30, 1997\n|Airplay\n|-\n|Europe\n|July 14, 1997\n|CD single\n|-\n|United States\n|February 23, 1998<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djrhythms.com/db/lb/promoonly/m-radio-1998-02.htm |title=Promo Only: Mainstream Radio [1998-02&#93; February 1998 |publisher=Djrhythms.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>\n|Airplay\n|-\n|United States\n|March 31, 1998<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Everybody-Backstreet-Boys/dp/B000005Z0V |title=Backstreet Boys \u2013 Everybody \u2013 Amazon.com Music |accessdate=November 9, 2015}}</ref>\n|CD single\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|backstreet-boys|everybody-backstreets-back}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Backstreet Boys singles}}\n\n[[Category:1997 songs]]\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:1998 singles]]\n[[Category:Backstreet Boys songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Max Martin]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Denniz Pop]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Max Martin]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Denniz Pop]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Joseph Kahn]]\n[[Category:Werewolves in music]]\n[[Category:Songs about dancing]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Romania]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Spain]]\n[[Category:Jive Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1997 single by Backstreet Boys}}\n{{About|the Backstreet Boys song|their 1997 album|Backstreet's Back}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n| cover      = Everybodyuscover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Backstreet Boys]]\n| album      = [[Backstreet's Back]] {{noitalic|(int'l),}} [[Backstreet Boys (1997 album)|Backstreet Boys]] {{noitalic|(US)}}\n| B-side     = {{ubl|\"Boys Will Be Boys\"|\"[[Anywhere for You (Backstreet Boys song)|Anywhere for You]]\"}}\n| released   = {{start date|1997|6|30}}\n| format     = * [[CD single]]\n* [[7\" single|7\"]]\n| recorded   = October 1996\u20131997\n| studio     =[[Cheiron Studios]] {{small|([[Stockholm]])}} \nParc Studios {{small|([[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]])}}\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 4:48 {{small|(album/extended version)}}<br>3:44 {{small|(radio/7\" edit)}}\n| label      = [[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| writer     = {{flat list|\n*[[Denniz PoP]]\n*[[Max Martin]]}}\n| producer   = {{flat list|\n*Denniz PoP\n*Max Martin}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Backstreet Boys\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Anywhere for You (Backstreet Boys song)|Anywhere for You]]\n | prev_year  = 1997\n | title      = Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n | year       = 1997\n | next_title = [[As Long as You Love Me (Backstreet Boys song)|As Long as You Love Me]]\n | next_year  = 1997\n}}{{Extra chronology\n | artist     = Backstreet Boys US\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[As Long as You Love Me (Backstreet Boys song)|As Long as You Love Me]]\n | prev_year  = 1997\n | title      = Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n | year       = 1998\n | next_title = [[I'll Never Break Your Heart]]\n | next_year  = 1998\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n| header = Alternate cover\n| type = single\n| cover = ebo1.png\n| border = yes\n| caption = European cover\n}}\n{{External music video|{{YouTube|6M6samPEMpM|\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Everybody (Backstreet's Back)'''\" is a song by American boy band [[Backstreet Boys]]. It was released as the first [[Single (music)|single]] from their second international album ''[[Backstreet's Back]]'' in June 1997, and the third single from their [[Backstreet Boys (1997 album)|debut US album]] in March 1998. The US debut was originally released without the song, which references the band's return via their second international album. However, once it was decided that the single would be released in the US, the album was re-released with \"Everybody\" included. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' commented that the song has \"a contagious dance/pop beat and catchy hook that perfectly showcases this talented group's voices.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/90s/1998/BB-1998-04-04.pdf|title=Single Reviews|work=Billboard magazine|accessdate=9 February 2020|page=65|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[Zomba Label Group|Zomba]] chairman [[Clive Calder]] suggested the song as a single, but [[Jive Records|Jive]] president [[Barry Weiss]] thought it would be weird to have a song called \"Backstreet's Back\" on the band's first US album. The band suggested it could just mean that they were back home. After Canadian markets began playing the song, US markets near the border began picking the song up. The band met with Weiss and asked that the song be added to the US album after the first million units had already been produced.<ref name=\"ew\">Interview with Backstreet Boys, management, and others from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' 10th Anniversary Issue.</ref> Written and produced by [[Max Martin]] and [[Denniz Pop|Denniz PoP]], \"Everybody\" is one of the Backstreet Boys' most successful singles to date, reaching number 4 in the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], running 22 weeks, and number 3 in the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Worldwide Charts|url=http://www.backstreetparadise.com/charts.html|accessdate=10 June 2012}}</ref> It is [[RIAA certification|certified]] platinum in the United States with 2.1 million sales.\n\nThere are two versions of the song. The international album features the album or 7\" version, which is the standard recording. The US album features the extended version of the song which includes an extended breakdown section, but cuts the bridge. The music video for the song was cut to both versions of the song, with the extended video released to the US market, and the standard video released everywhere else. In late August 2012, Backstreet Boys member [[Nick Carter (musician)|Nick Carter]] revealed via Twitter that the group was recording the song in Spanish, and it might be featured in their eighth studio record for Latin markets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nick Carter twitter update|url=https://twitter.com/nickcarter/status/240277086760206336|accessdate=August 29, 2012|date=August 28, 2012|quote=We are recording backstreets back in Spanish. Omg what's going on! Maybe well put it on the new record for Latin markets. En espa\u00f1ol}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n===Background===\nThe music video was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]] and filmed in [[Los Angeles]], California from June 16\u201318, 1997.<ref name=\"Everybody20\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7865195/backstreet-boys-everybody-backstreets-back-video-anniversary-interview|title=How 'Everybody (Backstreet's Back)' Director Joseph Kahn Pushed Racial Boundaries & Brought a Backstreet Boy to Tears|last=Tailor|first=Leena|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=July 14, 2017|access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> Kahn was contacted by [[Jive Records]] to direct a project with a \"white [[Jodeci]]\". He initially didn't know who the Backstreet Boys were, but was shocked by the group's European sales figures after being given a [[cassette tape]] and publicity release about them.<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/> Kahn initially started out as a grunge and hip-hop director, but wanted to explore the pop genre, since he grew up listening to music from the 1980s.<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/>\n\nThe haunted house treatment of the video was based on a treatment he envisioned for rapper [[Ice Cube]] a few months prior, and was inspired by the music video of [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Michael Jackson's Thriller (music video)|Thriller]]\".<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/> Kahn and the Backstreet Boys wanted [[Antonio Fargas]] to portray the bus driver, as they were fans of ''[[Starsky & Hutch]]''.<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/> The video shoot lasted for 36 hours, with Nick Carter's mummy shot being filmed last.<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/>\n\nThe video premiered outside the United States in July 1997, although viewers with [[Fuse (TV channel)|MuchMusic USA]] were able to see it as at the time it was still mostly a simulcast of the Canadian channel.  Jive did not get behind the concept of the band in costumes or the $1 million requirements, and did not believe MTV would respect the video. The band ultimately had to put up their own money to shoot the video and had to fight with the label to get reimbursed once it was successful.<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/> In a 2017 interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Kahn reflected on the impact of the music video:<ref name=\"Everybody20\"/><blockquote>I was just trying to do something fun and make the pop video I\u2019d always wanted to make,\" he says. \"I love pop, and it just didn\u2019t exist at that point -- so I guess this helped start the whole pop scene in America. It allowed me to help create a new pop scene and, through these videos, create my view of pop culture.</blockquote>\n\n===Synopsis===\n[[File:Everybody Video BSB.jpg|thumb|The group, with [[Howie D.|Howie]] in front, as they prepare to leave the haunted house]]\nThe video is [[Framing device|bookended]] by scenes framing the context: When their bus breaks down, the band's driver ([[Antonio Fargas]]) insists that the group spend a night at a nearby haunted house (the same house used in the 1995 film ''[[Casper (film)|Casper]]'') while he gets help. It then shows Brian preparing to sleep in one of the bedrooms. As he is in bed, he pulls out a scary animal from under his covers, making him scream in horror. The musical portion of the video plays as a dream sequence in which each band member appears as a different [[movie monster]]: [[Brian Littrell|Brian]] as a [[werewolf]]; [[Howie Dorough|Howie]] as [[Dracula]]; [[Nick Carter (musician)|Nick]] as a [[mummy]]; [[A.J. McLean|A.J.]] as [[Erik (The Phantom of the Opera)|Erik, the Phantom of the Opera]]; and [[Kevin Richardson (musician)|Kevin]] as [[Two-Face]]-like [[Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde]]. The boys, as monsters, mainly appear in their own individual vignettes related to their character, while the band as a group appears in the foyer of the house dressed in centuries-old clothing, performing a dance routine with a group of additional dancers. Supermodel [[Josie Maran]] appears as Howie's companion in his vignette. Following the song, the boys meet up in the foyer, each one having dreamed themselves as monsters. They resolve to leave, but are terrified by the sight of their driver standing at the front door with the appearance of [[Frankenstein's monster]]. The boys scream in terror, and the video ends.\n\nThere are two cuts of the video; one for the US market, and one for the international market, each of which features the edit of the song released on the album for that market. The international video cuts from the opening bookend to the first verse. The bridge of the song is intact and the first half of the dance routine, a ballroom dance portion, is intercut with the vignettes under it. This leads into the second half of the dance portion during the final choruses of the song which are not intercut with the vignettes. In the US cut, the ballroom half of the dance routine and the beginning of the second half are used at the start of the song during the first rhythm-only breakdown, and is not intercut with the vignettes. The second breakdown, which replaces the bridge, is accompanied only by shots from the vignettes, along with some shots of Brian's Wolfman character doing some [[Tumbling (gymnastics)|tumbling]] moves in the foyer and in the various vignettes. When the final choruses begin, the second half of the dance routine is shown again from the start, but is intercut with vignette scenes. Most of the remainder of the video is cut identically, other than several minor instances of alternate scenes or takes being used. The dance floor in the video was painted. At the end, Brian wakes up, looks in his bed to see nothing, and realizes that he had a nightmare. As he tells Howie about his dream, he and the other guys tell each other that they had a dream as well and described what they were. Howie and the others get ready to leave, but find that their bus driver is a monster, making the Backstreet Boys scream in terror.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{unreferenced section|date=January 2020}}\n===MTV Video Music Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[1998 MTV Video Music Awards|1998]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\"\n|[[Best Group Video]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Best Dance Video]]\n|{{nom}}\n{{end}}\n\n===Nickelodeon Kids Choice Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[1999 Kids' Choice Awards|1999]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n|Favorite Song\n|{{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n===Grammy Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n||[[41st Grammy Awards|1999]]\n||Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n|[[Best New Artist]]\n|{{nom}}\n{{end}}\n\n===MuchMusic Video Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n||[[MuchMusic Video Awards|1998]]\n||Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\n|Peoples Choice Favorite International Group\n|{{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n===MTV Movie Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n||[[MTV Movie Awards|2014]]\n|''This Is the End'' (Performance)\n|Best Musical Moment<ref>http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2014/best-musical-moment/</ref>\n|{{won}}\n{{end}}\n\n==Track listing==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===America===\n'''CD1'''\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Radio Edit) \u2013 3:44\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Matty's Radio Mix)\n\n'''CD2'''\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Matty's Radio Mix) \u2013 3:57\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Multiman Remix) \u2013 4:09\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Sharp London Vocal Mix) \u2013 8:02\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Radio Edit) \u2013 3:48\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Extended Version) \u2013 4:46\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Video Clip) \u2013 6:03\n\n'''Vinyl'''\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Extended Radio Mix) \u2013 4:48\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Matty's Hip Hop Radio Remix)\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Kano's Undercurrent Dub)\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Sharp London Vocal Remix)\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Sharp Trade Dub)\n{{col-2}}\n===UK===\n'''CD1'''\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (7\" Version) \u2013 3:44\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Extended Version) \u2013 4:45\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Multiman Remix) \u2013 4:09\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Matty's Remix) \u2013 3:55\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Max & Macario Club Mix) \u2013 6:12\n\n'''CD2'''\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (7\" Version) \u2013 3:44\n#\"Everybody (Backstreet's Back)\" (Exte