ics song|backstreet-boys|everybody-backstreets-back}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Backstreet Boys singles}}\n\n[[Category:1997 songs]]\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:1998 singles]]\n[[Category:Backstreet Boys songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Max Martin]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Denniz Pop]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Max Martin]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Denniz Pop]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Joseph Kahn]]\n[[Category:Werewolves in music]]\n[[Category:Songs about dancing]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Romania]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Spain]]\n[[Category:Jive Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "Angryjoe1111", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCertifications:Fixed parameter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Everybody_(Backstreet%27s_Back)"}
{"title_page": "Tucson Mall", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=December 2011}}\n{{infobox shopping mall |\n| shopping_mall_name = Tucson Mall\n| image =\n| caption =\n| location = 4500 North Oracle Road, [[Tucson, Arizona]]\n| opening_date = {{start date and age|March 22, 1982}}\n| developer = [[Forest City Enterprises]]\n| manager = [[Brookfield Properties Retail Group]]\n| owner = [[Brookfield Properties Retail Group]]<ref name=mall>{{cite web | url=https://www.brookfieldpropertiesretail.com/properties/property-details/tucson-mall.html | title=Tucson Mall | publisher=[[Brookfield Properties Retail Group]]}}</ref>\n| number_of_stores = 175<ref name=mall/>\n| number_of_anchors = 6\n| floor_area = {{convert|1,287,206|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}<br> ([[Gross leasable area|GLA]])<ref name=mall/>\n| floors = 2 (3 in Macy's)\n| website = {{URL|https://www.tucsonmall.com/}}\n}}\n'''Tucson Mall''' is the largest [[shopping mall]] in [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], [[Arizona]]. Tucson Mall features over 170 stores and two levels of indoor shopping. It is anchored by [[Forever 21]], [[J. C. Penney]], [[Macy's]] (formerly [[Foley's]] and [[Robinsons-May]]), [[Dillard's]], and [[Sears, Roebuck and Company|Sears]]. Tucson Mall contains a food court containing several fast food restaurants, as well as \"Arizona Avenue,\" an [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]] containing Southwestern-themed items. The mall is located on the north side of Tucson, bounded by Oracle Road ([[Arizona State Route 77]]), Wetmore Road, Stone Avenue, and the Rillito River.\n\n==Anchor stores==\n*[[Dillard's]] (197,958 sq ft.<ref>http://www.propertyshark.com/mason/Property/70402857/4550-N-Oracle-Rd-Tucson-AZ-85705/</ref>)\n*[[Forever 21]] (86,596 sq ft.,<ref>http://www.propertyshark.com/mason/Property/70364186/4510-N-Oracle-Rd-Tucson-AZ-85705/</ref> formerly [[Mervyn's]])\n*[[J. C. Penney]] (136,864 sq ft.<ref>http://www.propertyshark.com/mason/Property/70305567/4530-N-Oracle-Rd-Tucson-AZ-85705/</ref>)\n*[[Macy's]] (139,078 sq ft., formerly occupied in a {{convert|135000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} originally Broadway Southwest.<ref>https://www.pinterest.com/pin/364017582377940027/</ref> Current location originally opened as [[Foley's]] in 1991; chain's Arizona locations rebranded as Robinsons-May February 2, 1997<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/1996/12/09/225137-street-talk/</ref> changed to Macy's in 2006)\n*[[Old Navy]] (19,996 sq ft.)\n*[[Sears, Roebuck and Company|Sears]] (162,816 sq ft., closing in April 2020<ref>http://www.propertyshark.com/mason/Property/70371803/4570-N-Oracle-Rd-Tucson-AZ-85705/</ref>)\n\n==Former anchors==\n*[[Diamond's]] (sold to [[Dillard's]] in 1984)\n*[[Foley's]] (became [[Robinsons-May]] on February 2, 1997, closed sometime shortly after the chain was bought out by Macy's, reopened as Macy's no earlier than May 25, 2006, & no later than December 25, 2006<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2006/05/24/13537-federated-to-sell-macy-s-in-tucson-mall/</ref>)\n*[[The Broadway]] (became Macy's in 1995 or 1996,<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/1995/10/30/89670-street-talk/</ref> closed in 2006, demolished in 2007<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2007/10/30/67220-demolition-begins-at-tucson-mall-s-macy-s/</ref>)\n*[[Mervyns]] (closed in 2008, became [[Forever 21]] in 2009<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2009/03/16/112220-forever-21-takes-over-tucson-mall-mervyn-s-space/</ref>)\n\n==Idea for the Tucson Mall==\nAccording to historian David Leighton, it was Helen Wetmore, whose husband's family had homesteaded the land in the late 1800s, who came up with the idea for the Tucson Mall. During a trip to Chicago in the 1930s, she spotted a shopping center on the Skokie Highway and thought to herself, \"That's what I am going to have on my land.\" She kept the parcel of land together until 1978, and at that point plans for the mall were initiated with Forest City Enterprises.<ref>[http://tucson.com/news/local/wetmores-had-deep-roots-in-north-side-area/article_0915f2f5-1c43-55d7-8da7-8da543f9f53e.html David Leighton, \"Wetmores had deep roots in north-side area,\" Arizona Daily Star, Sept. 18, 2012]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Tucson Mall opened in 1982, with about 100 stores and five department stores, including [[The Broadway|Broadway]], [[J. C. Penney]], [[Mervyn\u2019s]], [[Diamond's]]<ref>https://www.pinterest.com/pin/364017582379180559/</ref> and [[Sears]]. Diamond's was converted to [[Dillard's]] in 1984.\n\nBeginning in 1990, the mall began an extensive expansion project. First, the Dillard's anchor was expanded and a parking garage was added adjacent to Dillard's. On the east side of the mall, an entirely new wing was built; the original mall footprint had stopped just to the east of the center court area.  The area to the southeast of the Mervyn's had been a parking lot. A new wing opened in 1991 and added over 400,000 sq ft to the mall, over 70 new stores, and a sixth anchor, Houston-based [[Foley's]].\n\nIn 1993, the food court was renovated with addition of a carousel and Arizona Avenue.\n\nIn 1996, the Broadway was changed to a [[Macy's]] after [[Federated Department Stores]] acquired Broadway.\n\nIn 1997, all of Foley's locations in Arizona were rebranded as the [[Los Angeles]]-based [[Robinsons-May]].\n\nIn 2001, General Growth Properties purchased Tucson Mall.\n\nIn 2003, the aging mall underwent a $15 million overhaul, which was the first major overhaul since it opened in 1982. The mall was given all new polished tile floors, glass railings on the upper level, new escalators and elevators where stairs had been, a new children\u2019s play area, new and refurbished restrooms, reworked food court and Arizona Avenue, changes to fountains and a new paint scheme.<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/2002/04/12/14660-tucson-mall-getting-new-look/</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the Robinsons-May was changed to a Macy's after Macy's acquired them in a corporate purchase. The existing Macy's on the south side of the mall was vacated.<ref>https://www.insidetucsonbusiness.com/news/vacant-macy-s-store-to-be-demolished-for-something-special/article_702c7d74-dcd2-5cc1-88d0-96cc144b3125.html</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the former Macy's store was demolished in preparation for an extensive remodel and addition on the south side of the mall. The changes include the addition of a grand entrance hall in the location of the old anchor, extension of stores on both the east and west side of the new entrance, addition of multiple water features, complete update of facade from current Macy's to Mall Security Offices, and the addition of [[Recreational Equipment, Inc.|REI]] and [[The Cheesecake Factory]] on the south side of the Tucson Mall. A parking structure was also added adjacent to the current Macy's.\n\nIn 2008, [[GameStop]], formerly an Electronics Boutique, in the bottom floor was relocated to the center as a Software ETC on the top floor, also owned by Gamestop, hyped a bigger, better Gamestop, this larger center one being the result. Mervyn's closed their store with the chain's demise.\n\nIn 2009, [[Forever 21]] opened in the approximately {{convert|80000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} space formerly anchored by Mervyn's as part of its strategy to open larger stores with a more diverse merchandise selection.<ref>http://tucson.com/business/forever-set-to-take-over-tucson-mall-s-mervyns-site/article_f65a1174-3fee-54dc-a799-27a3de800f55.html</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2020, it was announced that Sears would be closing as part of a plan to close 31 stores nationwide. The store will close in April 2020.<ref>https://www.kold.com/2020/02/06/sears-tucson-mall-closing-doors-liquidation-sale-begins-this-week/</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Sun Tran]]'s Tohono Tadai Transit Center, located adjacent to the Mall, was opened in 1994.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Transportation Research Board| isbn = 9780309060578| pages = 71\u201373| title = The Role of Transit in Creating Livable Metropolitan Communities| chapter = Tohono Tadai Transit Center| date = 1997-01-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.ersys.com/usa/04/0477000/mall.htm ErSys: Tucson, AZ - Area Malls - Shopping Experience]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.tucsonmall.com/en.html Tucson Mall Official Site]\n*[https://www.google.com/maps/place/4500+N+Oracle+Rd,+Tucson+Mall,+Tucson,+AZ+85705/@32.2886593,-110.9741615,710m/data=!3m2!1e3!4b1!4m2!3m1!1s0x86d673bfe7a942df:0x37447e247a3c5d86?hl=en Aerial View]\n\n{{coord|32|17|20|N|110|58|25|W|display=title}}\n\n{{Shopping malls in Arizona}}\n{{Brookfield Properties Retail Group}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Economy of Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Pima County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Tucson, Arizona]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=December 2011}}\n{{infobox shopping mall |\n| shopping_mall_name = Tucson Mall\n| image =\n| caption =\n| location = 4500 North Oracle Road, [[Tucson, Arizona]]\n| opening_date = {{start date and age|March 22, 1982}}\n| developer = [[Forest City Enterprises]]\n| manager = [[Brookfield Properties Retail Group]]\n| owner = [[Brookfield Properties Retail Group]]<ref name=mall>{{cite web | url=https://www.brookfieldpropertiesretail.com/properties/property-details/tucson-mall.html | title=Tucson Mall | publisher=[[Brookfield Properties Retail Group]]}}</ref>\n| number_of_stores = 175<ref name=mall/>\n| number_of_anchors = 6\n| floor_area = {{convert|1,287,206|sqft|m2|abbr=on}}<br> ([[Gross leasable area|GLA]])<ref name=mall/>\n| floors = 2 (3 in Macy's)\n| website = {{URL|https://www.tucsonmall.com/}}\n}}\n'''Tucson Mall''' is the largest [[shopping mall]] in [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], [[Arizona]]. Tucson Mall features over 170 stores and two levels of indoor shopping. It is anchored by [[Forever 21]], [[J. C. Penney]], [[Macy's]] (formerly [[Foley's]] and [[Robinsons-May]]), [[Dillard's]], and [[Sears, Roebuck and Company|Sears]]. Tucson Mall contains a food court containing several fast food restaurants, as well as \"Arizona Avenue,\" an [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]] containing Southwestern-themed items. The mall is located on the north side of Tucson, bounded by Oracle Road ([[Arizona State Route 77]]), Wetmore Road, Stone Avenue, and the Rillito River.\n\n==Anchor stores==\n*[[Dillard's]] (197,958 sq ft.<ref>http://www.propertyshark.com/mason/Property/70402857/4550-N-Oracle-Rd-Tucson-AZ-85705/</ref>)\n*[[Forever 21]] (86,596 sq ft.,<ref>http://www.propertyshark.com/mason/Property/70364186/4510-N-Oracle-Rd-Tucson-AZ-85705/</ref> formerly [[Mervyn's]])\n*[[J. C. Penney]] (136,864 sq ft.<ref>http://www.propertyshark.com/mason/Property/70305567/4530-N-Oracle-Rd-Tucson-AZ-85705/</ref>)\n*[[Macy's]] (139,078 sq ft., formerly occupied in a {{convert|135000|sqft|m2|abbr=on}} originally Broadway Southwest<ref>https://www.pinterest.com/pin/364017582377940027/</ref>. Current location originally opened as [[Foley's]] in 1991; chain's Arizona locations rebranded as Robinsons-May February 2, 1997<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/1996/12/09/225137-street-talk/</ref> changed to Macy's in 2006)\n*[[Old Navy]] (19,996 sq ft.)\n*[[Sears, Roebuck and Company|Sears]] (162,816 sq ft., closing in April 2020<ref>http://www.propertyshark.com/mason/Property/70371803/4570-N-Oracle-Rd-Tucson-AZ-85705/</ref>)\n\n==Former anchors==\n*[[Diamond's]] (sold to [[Dillard's]] in 1984)\n*[[Foley's]] (became [[Robinsons-May]] on February 2, 1997, closed sometime shortly after the chain was bought out by Macy's, reopened as Macy's no earlier than May 25, 2006, & no later than December 25, 2006<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2006/05/24/13537-federated-to-sell-macy-s-in-tucson-mall/</ref>)\n*[[The Broadway]] (became Macy's in 1995 or 1996,<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/1995/10/30/89670-street-talk/</ref> closed in 2006, demolished in 2007<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2007/10/30/67220-demolition-begins-at-tucson-mall-s-macy-s/</ref>)\n*[[Mervyns]] (closed in 2008, became [[Forever 21]] in 2009<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2009/03/16/112220-forever-21-takes-over-tucson-mall-mervyn-s-space/</ref>)\n\n==Idea for the Tucson Mall==\nAccording to historian David Leighton, it was Helen Wetmore, whose husband's family had homesteaded the land in the late 1800s, who came up with the idea for the Tucson Mall. During a trip to Chicago in the 1930s, she spotted a shopping center on the Skokie Highway and thought to herself, \"That's what I am going to have on my land.\" She kept the parcel of land together until 1978, and at that point plans for the mall were initiated with Forest City Enterprises.<ref>[http://tucson.com/news/local/wetmores-had-deep-roots-in-north-side-area/article_0915f2f5-1c43-55d7-8da7-8da543f9f53e.html David Leighton, \"Wetmores had deep roots in north-side area,\" Arizona Daily Star, Sept. 18, 2012]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Tucson Mall opened in 1982, with about 100 stores and five department stores, including [[The Broadway|Broadway]], [[J. C. Penney]], [[Mervyn\u2019s]], [[Diamond's]]<ref>https://www.pinterest.com/pin/364017582379180559/</ref> and [[Sears]]. Diamond's was converted to [[Dillard's]] in 1984.\n\nBeginning in 1990, the mall began an extensive expansion project. First, the Dillard's anchor was expanded and a parking garage was added adjacent to Dillard's. On the east side of the mall, an entirely new wing was built; the original mall footprint had stopped just to the east of the center court area.  The area to the southeast of the Mervyn's had been a parking lot. A new wing opened in 1991 and added over 400,000 sq ft to the mall, over 70 new stores, and a sixth anchor, Houston-based [[Foley's]].\n\nIn 1993, the food court was renovated with addition of a carousel and Arizona Avenue.\n\nIn 1996, the Broadway was changed to a [[Macy's]] after [[Federated Department Stores]] acquired Broadway.\n\nIn 1997, all of Foley's locations in Arizona were rebranded as the [[Los Angeles]]-based [[Robinsons-May]].\n\nIn 2001, General Growth Properties purchased Tucson Mall.\n\nIn 2003, the aging mall underwent a $15 million overhaul, which was the first major overhaul since it opened in 1982. The mall was given all new polished tile floors, glass railings on the upper level, new escalators and elevators where stairs had been, a new children\u2019s play area, new and refurbished restrooms, reworked food court and Arizona Avenue, changes to fountains and a new paint scheme.<ref>http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/2002/04/12/14660-tucson-mall-getting-new-look/</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the Robinsons-May was changed to a Macy's after Macy's acquired them in a corporate purchase. The existing Macy's on the south side of the mall was vacated.<ref>https://www.insidetucsonbusiness.com/news/vacant-macy-s-store-to-be-demolished-for-something-special/article_702c7d74-dcd2-5cc1-88d0-96cc144b3125.html</ref>\n\nIn 2007, the former Macy's store was demolished in preparation for an extensive remodel and addition on the south side of the mall. The changes include the addition of a grand entrance hall in the location of the old anchor, extension of stores on both the east and west side of the new entrance, addition of multiple water features, complete update of facade from current Macy's to Mall Security Offices, and the addition of [[Recreational Equipment, Inc.|REI]] and [[The Cheesecake Factory]] on the south side of the Tucson Mall. A parking structure was also added adjacent to the current Macy's.\n\nIn 2008, [[GameStop]], formerly an Electronics Boutique, in the bottom floor was relocated to the center as a Software ETC on the top floor, also owned by Gamestop, hyped a bigger, better Gamestop, this larger center one being the result. Mervyn's closed their store with the chain's demise.\n\nIn 2009, [[Forever 21]] opened in the approximately {{convert|80000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} space formerly anchored by Mervyn's as part of its strategy to open larger stores with a more diverse merchandise selection.<ref>http://tucson.com/business/forever-set-to-take-over-tucson-mall-s-mervyns-site/article_f65a1174-3fee-54dc-a799-27a3de800f55.html</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2020, it was announced that Sears would be closing as part of a plan to close 31 stores nationwide. The store will close in April 2020.<ref>https://www.kold.com/2020/02/06/sears-tucson-mall-closing-doors-liquidation-sale-begins-this-week/</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n[[Sun Tran]]'s Tohono Tadai Transit Center, located adjacent to the Mall, was opened in 1994.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Transportation Research Board| isbn = 9780309060578| pages = 71\u201373| title = The Role of Transit in Creating Livable Metropolitan Communities| chapter = Tohono Tadai Transit Center| date = 1997-01-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.ersys.com/usa/04/0477000/mall.htm ErSys: Tucson, AZ - Area Malls - Shopping Experience]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.tucsonmall.com/en.html Tucson Mall Official Site]\n*[https://www.google.com/maps/place/4500+N+Oracle+Rd,+Tucson+Mall,+Tucson,+AZ+85705/@32.2886593,-110.9741615,710m/data=!3m2!1e3!4b1!4m2!3m1!1s0x86d673bfe7a942df:0x37447e247a3c5d86?hl=en Aerial View]\n\n{{coord|32|17|20|N|110|58|25|W|display=title}}\n\n{{Shopping malls in Arizona}}\n{{Brookfield Properties Retail Group}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Economy of Tucson, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Pima County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Tucson, Arizona]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tucson_Mall"}
